[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to the first part of the Lifetime Repertoire against 1.c4 and 1.Nf3 for Black! My name is Arturs Neiksans and I'm one of the leading Latvian grandmasters, four times Latvian champion, a chess professional, coach, author, and occasionally also a streamer on Twitch. I'm extremely excited about this project and I hope that you will enjoy studying it as much as I did creating it!  English opening with 1...e5 very often is the same as the Sicilian but with colors reversed but White being up a tempo. Thus if you have some experience with the classical Sicilian lines, it will help to understand the positions better. In the course, I'm aiming for a very center-based approach against pretty much any continuation and often not shying away from potential sacrifices. That's the way I treat chess - if you can get an initiative with Black for just a single pawn sacrifice, it's great! Not only will it build for you a complete repertoire against the English opening, but also help you to understand the game of chess better than before!   The course is divided into four parts, starting with rare continuations from White and then moving onto the most principled approaches.   The first part is the shortest one. Chapter 1 andChapter 2are dedicated to rare lines or reversed Sicilian approaches - mostly Najdorf, Scheveningen, and Dragon. At the GM level, this is usually tested at accelerated time controls to surprise the opponents but some strong players are playing them regularly. Nevertheless, I aim to give you a head start and explain, how to always get a good position out of the opening, no matter how popular the line is. There might be some minor sidelines that I might have missed but based on the overall understanding of the course you should have a pretty good idea of how to counter them even if something is missing.   The second part is everything with early 2. g3 which is covered in Chapters 3-9. As a bonus, I made some original analysis for the very rare 4. Qa4 which I believe could be one of the hottest continuations soon, if starting with 2. g3 but practice will tell.   Then comes what I title as two knights variation with 2. Nc3, followed by 3. g3 which marks the third part of the course. In Chapters 10-14 I have built a complete repertoire with 3...Bb4 and Black always feels very comfortable. This must be the reason why the world elite has moved to the four knights variation which starts the fourth and the most critical part of the course.   The fourth part of the course is everything related to the four knights setups where White starts with Nc3 and Nf3 and then decides, which direction to take. This will be found in Chapters 15-22 and you will find that some of the best players in the world, including the world champion Magnus Carlsen, are testing them right now, among them in super-tournaments and World Cup final decisive games. }
1. -- *

