1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. g3
{ White delays any knight development and fianchettos the bishop on g2 instead. The reason Black's popular approach of ...Bb4 to trade the knight on c3. }
2... c6
{ Black immediately takes advantage of the fact that White is slow and fights for a strong pawn center. }
3. Bg2
{ In the early 2. g3 c6 setup White does not always rush with the development of the bishop. }
3... d5 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3 { If   5.d4  then just  5...e4 } 5... Nf6
{ 'White is threatening to win a pawn and there's nothing that Black can do about it. Sacrifice it for initiative!' }
6. Nc3 Nc6 7. Nxd5 Nxd5 { A true improvement over the traditional   7...Nd4 }
8. Qxd5
{ Necessary as after   8.Bxd5  Nd4!  the white queen is overloaded to defend both the bishop on d5 and the incoming fork on c2. Black can continue to distract the queen with a later ...b5. }
8... Bd6
{ My proposed novelty - depending on the situation, Black wants to play either ...Nb4 or ...Nd4 and ruin White's castling option with the ...Qc7-Nc2+ threat. }
9. Nf3 Nb4 { From here the game is almost forced. } 10. Qe4
{ Retreating with the queen to b3 is bad due to   10...Be6  11.Qb1  Rc8  ,  winning the rook with the ...Nc2 and ...Bxa2 threat. }
10... f5 11. Qb1
{ After   11.Qc4  there's  11...Qe7  and ...Be6 to follow. White is losing too many tempi in the process. }
11... Qc7 12. O-O Nc2 { Black wins an exchange for a pawn. } *

