1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. g3
{ White delays any knight development and fianchettos the bishop on g2 instead. The reason Black's popular approach of ...Bb4 to trade the knight on c3. }
2... c6
{ Black immediately takes advantage of the fact that White is slow and fights for a strong pawn center. }
3. Nf3 { White can try to disrupt Black's intentions to take the center. } 3...
e4
{ This is necessary as any other moves will be passive. The position bears direct resemblance to Sicilian Alapin. }
4. Nd4 d5 5. cxd5
{ If White would include   5.d3  ,  then first chase away the knight from the center with  5...Bc5  6.Nb3  Bb4+  and trade-off the bishop. More on this variation here! }
5... Qxd5 6. e3
{ White is planning to play d3 and create a pawn majority on the kingside. There might also be some improvised ideas with either f3 or f4. }
6... Bc5 { Black should push back the white knight while he can. } 7. Nc3 Qe5
8. d3
{ After   8.f4  Black is not obliged to take the pawn en passant and can just reposition with  8...Qe7 }
8... exd3 9. Qxd3 Nf6 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Rd8
{ Black pins the knight on d4 but not necessarily with intentions to win a pawn. }
12. Qc2 Na6 13. a3 Bxd4 14. exd4 Qf5
{ It's possible to take the pawn and White will have strong compensation due to the strong bishops but a simpler choice is to block the light squares and obtain a solid game. }
