1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. g3
{ White delays any knight development and fianchettos the bishop on g2 instead. The reason Black's popular approach of ...Bb4 to trade the knight on c3. }
2... c6
{ Black immediately takes advantage of the fact that White is slow and fights for a strong pawn center. }
3. d4
{ The main move in the position and most of the variations start with this move. }
3... e4
{ Black wants to play ...d5 next to solidify the center so White can either allow it or try to stop it. }
4. d5 { White disrupts the incoming support to the e4 pawn. } 4... Bb4+
{ The point is to go for a quick short castle. } 5. Bd2 Qe7
{ There's no need to rush with the bishop trade - strengthen your center first. }
6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bg2
{ With the black bishop on b4, Black needs to start to pay attention, can White play some tactical tricks with Nxe4. It doesn't work, not yet anyway. }
7... O-O 8. Nh3
{ White can include   8.a3  but then after  8...Bxc3  9.Bxc3  cxd5  10.cxd5  d6  Black feels pretty solid. }
8... cxd5 { Better to include this move sooner than later. } 9. cxd5 d6 10.
Nxe4
{ After   10.O-O  Bf5  ,  followed by ...Na6 Black has a harmonious development. }
10... Bxh3 { Now starts a forced sequence of trades. } 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. Bxh3
Qxb2 { Black wins back the pawn with an equal position. } *

