1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. g3
{ White delays any knight development and fianchettos the bishop on g2 instead. The reason Black's popular approach of ...Bb4 to trade the knight on c3. }
2... c6
{ Black immediately takes advantage of the fact that White is slow and fights for a strong pawn center. }
3. d4
{ The main move in the position and most of the variations start with this move. }
3... e4
{ Black wants to play ...d5 next to solidify the center so White can either allow it or try to stop it. }
4. Qa4
{ White is stopping Black's idea to play the quick d7-d5 as there's a potential pin at the a4-e8 diagonal and intends to target the pawn on e4 very quickly. I wrote a special chapter for this rare move and the arising complications. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Bd7
{ Time for a gambit! White has two major choices here - either take on c6 immediately or play 6. Qb3. }
6. dxc6
{ 6.Qb3  is a serious alternative - now the mainline goes  6...cxd5  7.Qxd5  Bb4+!  This check is quite important so that in some lines the b7 pawn can't be taken. After  8.Bd2  Nf6  now the pawn on b7 can't be taken because of the bishop trade and the incoming ...e3 and the ... Bc6 threat, so after  9.Qb3  Bd6  Black has a long-term initiative, focusing on the kingside. White has the extra pawn but staying behind in development and the weaknesses of the light squares should fully compensate the missing pawn. }
6... Nxc6 7. Nc3 Bb4
{ Threatening ...Nxd4. White has many choices here but perhaps the most human is to retreat to d1. }
8. Qd1 Rc8 9. Bg2
{ If White plays   9.e3  right away then Black can focus on the kingside and the weakened light squares. }
9... Nf6 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 { White can't keep the extra material here! }
12. e3 Nxd4
{ This is one of the core ideas of the variation - Black should be playing aggressively and be aware of the tactical possibilities, otherwise, the pawn will be lost for no compensation. }
13. Qxd4 Qxd4 14. exd4 Rxc3
{ Winning back everything and even slightly more on top. } *

