1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. g3
{ White delays any knight development and fianchettos the bishop on g2 instead. The reason Black's popular approach of ...Bb4 to trade the knight on c3. }
2... c6
{ Black immediately takes advantage of the fact that White is slow and fights for a strong pawn center. }
3. d4
{ The main move in the position and most of the variations start with this move. }
3... e4
{ Black wants to play ...d5 next to solidify the center so White can either allow it or try to stop it. }
4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3
{ White can immediately challenge the central pawn - with the pawns traded now it's important to know the following line. }
6... Nc6
{ A counter-attack but also an important accuracy as the most logical   6...Nf6  would run into  7.Bg5  and Black is struggling to defend the d5 pawn. Any early pawn trades will give Black access to the c6 square so normally White doesn't rush with the trade unless specifically aiming for the following line. }
7. Qxd5 Qxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd4 { Both players are threatening with forks. } 9. Nc7+
Kd8 10. Nxa8 Nc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1
{ Here White has a little choice - either try to rescue the knight from a8, go for the knight on a1, or perhaps do both. }
12. Bf4 Be6 13. b3 { Now it's important to know the following idea. } 13...
Nxb3 14. axb3 Bxb3+ 15. Kc1 Ba3+ 16. Kb1 Ne7
{ Black prepares to play ...Kd7 next and win the trapped knight. It can't escape immediately as after   17.Nc7  there's the very powerful  ...Bc4!  After the best   17.e3  Black plays  17...g5  first and only then ...Kd7. If  18.Be5  there is  18...f6!  More on this variation Here! }
*

