1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. g3
{ White delays any knight development and fianchettos the bishop on g2 instead. The reason Black's popular approach of ...Bb4 to trade the knight on c3. }
2... c6
{ Black immediately takes advantage of the fact that White is slow and fights for a strong pawn center. }
3. d4
{ The main move in the position and most of the variations start with this move. }
3... e4
{ Black wants to play ...d5 next to solidify the center so White can either allow it or try to stop it. }
4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2 Bb4
{ I suggest playing 5...Bb4 instead of the more traditional 5...Nf6 because of the various pin ideas with the white bishop on g5. They can be easily mixed up as White can play out the opening with a different order of the moves and you might meet Bg5 at any given moment. The move that I'm proposing is much simpler and if given a possibility, Black will simply play ...h6 first before playing ...Nf6. }
6. Qb3
{ At some point White might include Qb3 to pressure the center - on most occasions, the bishop will retreat to a5 to keep the pin alive. White can force the trade with   6.Qa4  but now after  6...Bxc3+  7.bxc3  there's the very strong 7...Nd7-b6 idea. }
6... Ba5
{ Black normally doesn't mind taking on c3, but doing this right away after   6...Bxc3  7.bxc3  would result in the black king getting stuck in the center because of White's Ba3 idea. After Black's ...h6, ...Nf6, and short castle Black will happily take on c3 to relieve the pressure against the center. }
7. cxd5
{ Otherwise Black might want to play ... dxc4 himself and the white queen is in an awkward position because of the incoming ...Be6. }
7... cxd5 8. f3 Nf6
{ Black has no time for ...h6 here. Usually, the general rule is not to take on f3 yourself as White will recapture with the knight and the pressure against d5 will build up quickly. Let White take on e4 himself. }
9. Bg5 O-O 10. e3
{ Accepting the free pawn with   10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.Qxd5  is a very risky approach for White. Black can continue with  11...Qb6  and a very powerful initiative at the queenside. It’s not clear how White should protect the b-pawn. }
10... Nbd7
{ The pawn on e4 is taboo as after   11.fxe4?  dxe4  12.Bxe4  there is  12...Qe8!  followed by  13.Bg2  h6  14.Bxf6  Qxe3  intermezzo check. }
11. Ne2 h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. O-O
{ Now after   13.fxe4  Ng4!  White suddenly has some difficulties protecting the e3 pawn. }
13... exf3 14. Rxf3 Be6
{ As soon as the other knight will leave the e2 square, Black will take on c3. }
*

