1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. g3
{ White delays any knight development and fianchettos the bishop on g2 instead. The reason Black's popular approach of ...Bb4 to trade the knight on c3. }
2... c6
{ Black immediately takes advantage of the fact that White is slow and fights for a strong pawn center. }
3. d4
{ The main move in the position and most of the variations start with this move. }
3... e4
{ Black wants to play ...d5 next to solidify the center so White can either allow it or try to stop it. }
4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2 Bb4
{ I suggest playing 5...Bb4 instead of the more traditional 5...Nf6 because of the various pin ideas with the white bishop on g5. They can be easily mixed up as White can play out the opening with a different order of the moves and you might meet Bg5 at any given moment. The move that I'm proposing is much simpler and if given a possibility, Black will simply play ...h6 first before playing ...Nf6. }
6. Nh3
{ Chapter 4 is dedicated for positions if White includes Qb3 while Chapter 3 covers everything with the white queen remaining on d1. }
6... h6
{ Important move before playing ...Nf6 - you don't want to allow Bg5 pin. The only exceptions are when White is rushing with an early f3 with the white knight still on g1 - then you simply don't have the time for the move. }
7. O-O Nf6 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. f3 O-O
{ Quite precise - Black is not rushing to take on f3 as White would recapture with the rook and then pressure the pawn on d5. }
10. fxe4 Bxc3 { 10...dxe4  is the alternative, also analyzed in the course. }
11. bxc3 Bxh3 12. Bxh3 Nxe4
{ Black is looking towards blocking both e4 and c4 squares and should watch out for White opening the center with c4. }
13. Qb3 { Or   13.Qd3  Nc6  14.c4  Re8  15.e3  b6! } 13... Nc6 14. Rf5
{ After   14.Qxb7  Na5!  Black blocks the center and the loss of a pawn is not that significant. }
14... Qb6 { Black is ready to trade the d5 pawn for c3. } *

