1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. d3
{ If White wants to play Nf3 early without committing to Nc3, this is a reasonable choice. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 { The reversed Sicilian Dragon. } 4... d5 5. cxd5
Nxd5 6. Bg2
{ If White would include   6.Nc3  then this transposes to the four knights variations with 6...Bc5. }
6... Be7
{ I don't recommend positioning the bishop on c5 as White has not developed the queenside knight to c3. }
7. O-O O-O
{ White might consider pushing d3-d4 at any given moment to open his bishops. While you should keep an eye on this, d3 has already cost White a tempo, so it shouldn't be too critical. }
8. Nc3 Be6
{ Black has saved two tempi from an alternate English opening line where the knight early retreats to b6, only to be rerouted back to d5 later. }
9. Bd2 Qd7 10. Ne4 f6
{ Black is incredibly solid in the center. Now it's important to know the following idea - if White plays Rc1 and Nc5, we should advance with ...a5, trade the knight, get rid of the rook with ...b6 and after ...Na7 build Maroczy Bind setup with the incoming ...c5 and ...Nc6 for a considerable space advantage. }
*

