1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. d3
{ If White wants to play Nf3 early without committing to Nc3, this is a reasonable choice. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. a3
{ This is how the reversed Sicilian Najdorf or Scheveningen positions normally start - some Sicilian players like to play known setups also from the White's perspective. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3
{ Or   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3np3/8/P2P1N2/1P2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.e4  - Black continues with  6...Nb6  and positions with bishops on e7 and e6, castling short. Any early b4 ideas meet ...a5 and ...Nd4 next, starting a very good gambit. }
6... a5
{ Black's easiest setup is to position the dark-squared bishop on d6 and start attacking at the kingside. If the white knight lands on c3, just trade it and continue with ...Bd6. }
7. b3 Bd6 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Nbd2 Nb6 10. Be2 Qe7 11. O-O f5
{ If White will push d3-d4, close the center with ...e5-e4. White might consider pushing e3-e4 which is a thematic idea in the Scheveningen. It stops Black's active plans with e5-e4 and should Black answer with f5-f4, this now allows White to make the desired breakthrough in the center with d3-d4. Thus just ignore it and offer White to take himself on f5. }
