1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. Nf3
{ This is Sicilian Nimzowitch with colors reversed - if your opponent allows you to charge forward in the center, do it. }
2... e4 3. Nd4 Nc6 4. Nxc6
{ After   4.e3  Black suddenly poses White some problems with  4...Nxd4  5.exd4  Qf6!  White has a reasonable alternative with   4.Nc2  but then Black should just push  ...d5  . }
4... dxc6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e3
{ White is blocking the e-pawn and intends to position the dark-squared bishop on the long a1-h8 diagonal, while the knight is typically rerouted to d4 via e2. The alternative to immediately pressure the e4 pawn tactically doesn't work. }
6... Bf5 7. Qb3 b6
{ Better this than  7...Rb8  , robbing you of an opportunity to castle long. }
8. Qc2 Qd7 9. h3 h5
{ This stops White's intentions to play g4-g5 and Bg2, winning the pawn on e4. }
10. b3 a5 11. Bb2 h4 { Black has a space advantage and can castle both sides. }
