[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. e3
{ This interesting move on most occasions can transpose to some major lines if White would continue with Nc3 and Nf3. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ Again this is some sort of a Sicilian Nimzowitsch, only having e3 already included. After   3.d4  Black gets an easy game with  3...exd4  ,  followed by ... Bb4+, ...O-O and ...d5. }
3... e4 4. Nd4 Nc6
{ Black is threatening to trade on d4 and push forward the d-pawn. } 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Black wants to trade the knight on c3 only if White is unable to recapture with the queen, otherwise White's dark-squared bishop on the long a1-h8 diagonal will be very strong. }
6. Qb3
{ After   6.Qc2  Black has the same approach -  ...Nxd4  7.exd4  c6  and the pawn on e4 can't be taken because of ...Qe7 pin. Don't give up your dark-squared bishop so easily - it can always retreat to a5, and the e4 pawn can be strengthened with ...d5. }
6... Nxd4 7. exd4 Ba5
{ Black keeps the dark-squared bishop alive and prepares ...c6-d5. } 8. Qa3 c6
9. d3 d5
{ White can't exploit the fact that the black king is cut off from castling. }
10. dxe4 Nxe4 11. Be2 Qb6
{ One final accuracy - Black is threatening with ...Bb4 but also win a pawn on c3 in the process. }
12. cxd5 Bb4 13. Qb3 O-O
{ White can't keep the pawn as  14.dxc6  will run into  ...Be6  and White is in a trouble. }
