1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. g3 Bb4
{ Since the black knight doesn't stand on c6 just yet, this is a great maneuver - Black is threatening to take on c3 to double the c-pawns. Now White's   4.Nd5  is not dangerous due to the simple knight trade and Black can continue with ...c6. }
4. Nf3
{ White is exploiting the fact that Black can't play   4...d6  here because of  5.Qa4+  and now after  5...Nc6  there's  6.Nd5 }
4... Bxc3 { Consistent with the strategy. } 5. bxc3
{ White plans to fight for a strong pawn center with d3, e4, move the knight and push f4. After   5.dxc3  Black plays  5...d6  ,  followed by ...Nc6, ...h6, ... Be6, and ...Qd7, with the idea to trade the light-squared bishops via the h3 square and seek counterplay on the kingside with ...f5. }
5... d6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O
{ Here, if White tries   7.e4  ,  a traditional Rossolimo idea, it doesn't work due to  7...Nxe4  when  8.Nxe5  can be met by  8...Re8! }
7... Re8
{ Black is getting ready for White to play e2-e4 at any given moment and wants to play ...e4 himself. }
8. d3
{ The most played move in the position. White can get very tricky with   8.Ne1  but you can do the same with  8...h6  ,  waiting for White to define his setup. }
8... e4 { Disrupting White's plans. } 9. Nd4
{ If   9.Ng5  then Black just trades on d3. The queenside knight is not going to c6 but d7 instead. }
9... h6 10. Rb1 Nbd7 11. Qc2 Nc5
{ It's not clear how White is going to progress here as Black himself is not going to take the pawn on d3 any time soon and can strengthen it with ...b6 and ...Bb7. }
12. Ba3 Qe7 13. Nb3 b6
{ Black has more space and thus is just better - White's bishops are not doing much. }
