1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. g3 Bb4
{ Since the black knight doesn't stand on c6 just yet, this is a great maneuver - Black is threatening to take on c3 to double the c-pawns. Now White's   4.Nd5  is not dangerous due to the simple knight trade and Black can continue with ...c6. }
4. Bg2 O-O 5. e4
{ White is playing for a strong pawn center and wants to play Nge2 next to recapture on c3 with the knight, so take it right away. }
5... Bxc3
{ White has the traditional choice of how to capture the bishop but also Black's responses remain the same. If White takes with the b-pawn, go for ...c6-d5 and open the center. After dxc3 Black should aim for a positional game with ...d6. }
6. dxc3
{ In closed positions you should pay special attention to - where is your counterplay? }
6... d6 7. Qe2 Nbd7
{ Depending on what White will choose, Black should seek something to attack at the queenside with ...a6-b5 or ...f5 on the kingside. }
8. Nf3 Nc5 9. Nh4
{ If White will go for the slightly passive   9.Nd2  ,  this means that White is ready for actions on the queenside. Thus just play  ...a5  and continue with ...Be6, ...Qd7 to trade off the light-squared bishops via the h3 square and seek ways to generate counter-play at the kingside with ...f5. }
9... a6
{ since ...f5 now is impossible as you don't want to trade your light-squared bishop for the knight, the alternate plan works just fine. }
10. O-O Be6
{ This appears to be more precise than the immediate   10...b5  as now White can’t include  11.Be3  and generate some counterplay - the white pawn on e4 will be under attack and the diagonal h1-a8 remains closed. Black’s ...b5 is an incoming threat and since after the push the white pawn on a2 will be under attack, it almost forces White to waste a tempo on b3 }
11. b3 b5 12. cxb5 axb5
{ With the queenside open and the counter-play established, Black has a good game. }
13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxb5 { White wins a pawn but not for long. } 15...
Ra3 { Black regains the sacrificed material pretty quickly. } *

