1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. a3
{ White's avoided any ...Bb4 traditional ideas to keep the queenside knight alive but at a cost of a tempo. }
3... d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Pretty much in almost every setup with the white knight already on c3 and the pawn standing on a3 Black can simply trade the knights and play ...Bd6 next. With the pawn on a2, it will be a concession. }
5. Nf3 { or   5.e4  - Black takes on c3 and plays ...Bd6 next. } 5... Nc6 6. e4
Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 { Black has a healthy position and an easy development. } 8.
Bb5 { White has managed to pin the knight but it's not dangerous. } 8... O-O 9.
d4 Bg4 10. h3 Bh5
{ Now White can't win the pawn due to some tactical tricks -   11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.dxe5  Bxe5!  and if now White would play  13.Qxd8  Raxd8  14.Nxe5  there's  ...Rd1  mate! }
