2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ Start of the four knights variations. } 3... Nc6
{ White has included Nf3 and ...Nc6 so that after Black playing 4...Bb4 White would have 5. Nd5 as a response, and the potential knight trade on d5 would mean Black a loss of valuable time. }
4. e3
{ This is a very popular alternative to 4. g3 - White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center }
4... Bb4
{ Here   4...d5  is not so great due to  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.Bb5  .  Now Black is threatening to take on c3, double the pawns, and play ...d6. }
5. Nd5
{ White is using the opportunity that Black's queenside knight already stands on c6 so that after trading the knights Black loses a critical tempo. }
5... e4 6. Ng1
{ The critical move of the variation - White is trying to bother the e4 pawn. After   6.Nxb4  Nxb4  7.Nd4  Black continues with  ...c5  and is ready to play ...Nd3+, if necessary. Black often plays ...d5 before castling. }
6... O-O 7. a3 Bd6 { Black already wants to take the knight on d5. } 8. Qc2
{ This line is considered to be dangerous for White but it's important to know the correct continuation. Recently some high-level GMs have started to test   8.d3  but after  8...exd3  followed by  (...Ne5 and ...c6)  Black should equalize without too many adventures. }
8... Re8 9. Ne2 b5
{ Since Black is so much ahead in development, opening the position is very logical, even if it means playing a gambit. }
10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. cxb5 Ne5 12. Qxe4 Bb7
{ Black has a very strong attack - you want to open the position and get to the white king. For instance,   13.Qxb7  Nd3+  14.Kd1  Nxf2+  or the computer-esque  @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/pQpp1ppp/3b1q2/1P6/8/P2nP3/1P1PNPPP/R1BK1B1R b - - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...c6  ends the game. }
13. Qd4 a6 14. h4 Qg6 15. Nf4 Qf5
{ White has two extra pawns but the price might be too big. Black is ready to recapture on a6 with the rook. }
