2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ Start of the four knights variations. } 3... Nc6
{ White has included Nf3 and ...Nc6 so that after Black playing 4...Bb4 White would have 5. Nd5 as a response, and the potential knight trade on d5 would mean Black a loss of valuable time. }
4. e3
{ This is a very popular alternative to 4. g3 - White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center }
4... Bb4
{ Here   4...d5  is not so great due to  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.Bb5  .  Now Black is threatening to take on c3, double the pawns, and play ...d6. }
5. Qc2
{ White wants to get a two-bishop advantage by not spoiling his pawn structure or play Nd5 next. }
5... Bxc3 { I recommend giving up the bishop. } 6. bxc3
{ White aims for a strong pawn chain in the center.   6.dxc3  is worse due to  ...e4  and White will have a bad dark-squared bishop. }
6... O-O 7. e4 d6
{ Black should be looking for ways to generate some counterplay. } 8. g3
{ If White plays now   8.Be2  ,  Black should respond with  ...Nh5  with an idea to play either ...Nf4 or push ...f5. After the critical  9.d4  Qf6  improves the ...Nf4 threat to recapture with the queen. }
8... a6
{ Since White's light-squared bishop is about to land on g2, remind White that Black has some ideas at the queenside. }
9. a4 Nd7 10. Nh4 { This stops Black's ...f5 } 10... Nc5 11. d3 Na5
{ You don't want to give up your light-squared bishop after ...f5. Now Black is threatening to win the pawn on a4 with ...Bd7 and ...Qe8. If the pawn is protected, push ...b5. }
