1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ Start of the four knights variations. } 3... Nc6
{ White has included Nf3 and ...Nc6 so that after Black playing 4...Bb4 White would have 5. Nd5 as a response, and the potential knight trade on d5 would mean Black a loss of valuable time. }
4. e3
{ This is a very popular alternative to 4. g3 - White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center }
4... Bb4
{ Here   4...d5  is not so great due to  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.Bb5  .  Now Black is threatening to take on c3, double the pawns, and play ...d6. }
5. Qc2
{ White wants to get a two-bishop advantage by not spoiling his pawn structure or play Nd5 next. }
5... Bxc3 { I recommend giving up the bishop. } 6. Qxc3
{ White's dream position is to get an open position where the dark-squared bishop controls a long diagonal. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and is preparing to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. You can't afford to play this position passively with moves like   6...d6 }
7. Be2 { White is provoking Black into playing ...d5 first. } 7... d5 8. d4
{ Only then White is opening the center. This is quite tricky and here I have prepared for you a fresh novelty! }
8... Bg4 { Time for a gambit! } 9. dxe5
{ 9.Nxe5  is considerably worse due to  9...Bxe2  10.Nxc6  Qe4 } 9... Ne4
{ The critical line - Black sacrifices a pawn for long-term compensation. } 10.
Qc2
{ A serious alternative here is   10.Qa3  - here after  ...  Qxa3  11.bxa3  O-O-O  Black is threatening to continue with ...dxc4 and ...Nc5, exploiting the weakened light squares that White has created. White will have to navigate through a jungle of variations, already being on the defensive. }
10... Nb4 11. Qa4+
{ A practical choice with the idea to remove the active black bishop from g4. }
11... Bd7 12. Qd1 dxc4
{ Depending on the situation, Black is castling either long @@StartBracket@@don't blunder Qd4@@EndBracket@@ or short, but the idea is to continue with ...Bg4 and ...Rd8, often leading to drawish lines, as after ...Bxf3 Black can force a perpetual check with ...Qg5+ and ...Qf5@@StartBracket@@or sometimes h5@@EndBracket@@-f3. }
13. Bxc4 O-O-O 14. O-O Bg4
{ Black is threatening to force a draw with ...Bxf3 and ... Qg5-f5-f3 next.   15.Qe2  is bad because of  ...Ng5 }
15. Qa4 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Nd2
{ First, play this and only then ...Qg5+! Be accurate with executing either ...Qh5 or ...Qf5, pay attention to the difference. Specifically after   17.Bxd2  Qg5+  18.Kh1  Qf5  has to be played as   18...Qh5  is a losing mistake due to  19.Be2  Rxd2  20.Rad1  and Black can't take the bishop on e2 due to the Qd7-d8 mate. The black queen on f5 stops the idea. }
