1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ Start of the four knights variations. } 3... Nc6
{ White has included Nf3 and ...Nc6 so that after Black playing 4...Bb4 White would have 5. Nd5 as a response, and the potential knight trade on d5 would mean Black a loss of valuable time. }
4. e4 { White is fighting for space advantage and intends to play d4 next. }
4... Bc5
{ If allowed, Black wants to play ...d6 next so White's next move is principled. }
5. Nxe5 Nxe5 6. d4 Bb4 7. dxe5 Nxe4
{ White here has three major moves - 8.Qd4, 8.Qd3 and 8.Qf3, while the tempting 8.Qg4 is a mistake. Depending on what White will play, the bishop will have a different retreat square. }
8. Qf3
{ Currently the most contested move. After   8.Qd4  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Black has to retreat with  9...Be7  and go for the quick ...d6. Here a critical line is  10.Qg4  Kf8  and after following Black's ...d6 you should slowly untangle yourself, leaving White with weak c-pawns.  Quite tricky is   8.Qd3  - after  ...Nxc3  9.bxc3  here it's best to play  9...Ba5  The reason is revealed in the following line -  10.Be2  d6  11.Qg3  O-O  12.Bh6  Black has the saving resource  12...Bxc3+  Another critical line here is   10.Ba3  where Black needs to know the idea of  10...Qg5  and sacrifice pawn with ...d6 so that Black can immediately castle short. It's easy to mix them up so I suggest spending some time, figuring the nuances. Chapter 17 }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5
{ It's important to keep the c3 pawn under attack, should White go for   10.Qg3  again. Immediately it's not good for White because Black can play  ...Qe7  If White wants to go for the idea, he should include   10.Be2  first and then after  ...d6  go  11.Qg3 }
10. Bf4
{ The most recent discovery where White is still trying to prove something. }
10... O-O
{ If White doesn't castle long, Black should sacrifice a pawn with ...d6 and seek initiative. }
11. O-O-O
{ White is about to start an attack at the kingside and his pieces are perfectly positioned to stop Black's ...d6. Thus Black has to seek other ways for counter-play. }
11... Qe7 12. Kb2 Rb8
{ Black is about to open the queenside, even if it will cost a pawn. } 13. Bd3
b5 14. cxb5 Bb7 15. Qh3 g6
{ With perfect play, the game should eventually end with a perpetual check. } *

