1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ Start of the four knights variations. } 3... Nc6
{ White has included Nf3 and ...Nc6 so that after Black playing 4...Bb4 White would have 5. Nd5 as a response, and the potential knight trade on d5 would mean Black a loss of valuable time. }
4. d4
{ This move was popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless. White is fighting for the center. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Bg5
{ The main move - interesting alternative here is   6.g3  after which Black should play  ...O-O  7.Bg2  Bxc3+  8.bxc3  Ne5  attacking the c4 pawn. After  9.c5  Qe7  Black either forces White to play a gambit or to protect it with  10.Nb3  Here it's best to continue with  ...Rb8  to prepare ...b6. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Ne5
{ Black's idea is to get rid of the bishop's pin with ... Ng6. If White is going for a slow build-up with 9. e3, followed by f3 and later e4, it's not a problem. You want to castle short, play ...d6, position one of your knights on c5 for a good blockade. Trading the dark-squared bishop on g3 is not an urgent priority. }
9. f4 Ng6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. g3
{ White is going for a strong pawn chain in the center. } 11... Nf8
{ An important idea to know. } 12. Bg2 Ne6 13. O-O O-O 14. e4 d6
{ Black has an easy game - after White's Nb3 Black can even trade the knight, then position the bishop on c6, double the rooks on the e-file, and pressure the e4 pawn. White's Qd4 can be just ignored as Qxf6 is not a big positional threat. Watch out for e4-e5. }
