1. c4 e5
{ Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide!   My goal is to explain to you the most important lines of the course so that you can start to play them right away in about 2 hours! Here are the three most popular setups that White can choose from:   1@@EndBracket@@ Four knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. Nf3, then choosing between 4. g3, 4. e3, or recently popular 4. e4.  2@@EndBracket@@ Two knights variations with 2. Nc3 and 3. g3   3@@EndBracket@@ Early 2. g3 setup, avoiding placing knight on c3 to skip Black's traditional ...Bb4 setup. Everything else is less popular but still, it's important to know how to play against it all. }
2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ Start of the four knights variations. } 3... Nc6
{ White has included Nf3 and ...Nc6 so that after Black playing 4...Bb4 White would have 5. Nd5 as a response, and the potential knight trade on d5 would mean Black a loss of valuable time. }
4. d3
{ With this order of the moves, there's a fair chance that your opponent is hinting for one of the off-beat lines as after   4.g3  White doesn't always rush with d3. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3
{ 6.g3  Bc5  would just transpose to the four knights variations, having White included an early d3.  After   6.e4  it's best to take the knight with  ...Nxc3  7.bxc3  Bc5  and have a solid grip over the center, continuing with ...O-O and ...Qe7  watching out for White's d4. If White doesn't do it immediately, later you can consider challenging the control of the d4 square with the typical ...Bg4xf3 and ...b5-b4. }
6... Be7
{ Black's setup is to position both bishops on e7 and e6, castle short, and be ready to meet White's a3 with ...a5. }
7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Be6 9. a3 a5
{ If White wants to fight for a space advantage at the queenside with b4, stop it. }
10. Qc2 f5
{ Black's setup always remains the same - play ...Kh8, reroute the dark-squared bishop to d6 and consider starting an attack on the kingside. Keep the knight on d5 for as long as possible. }
