2. Nc3 { Start of the two knights variations. } 2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ Start of the four knights variations. } 3... Nc6
{ White has included Nf3 and ...Nc6 so that after Black playing 4...Bb4 White would have 5. Nd5 as a response, and the potential knight trade on d5 would mean Black a loss of valuable time. }
4. g3
{ One of the hottest continuations right now - White is fianchettoing the bishop on g2 and is ready to meet   4...Bb4  with  5.Nd5 }
4... d5 { Black uses the opportunity to fight for the center. } 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6.
Bg2 Bc5
{ Alexander Grischuk brought this idea to the elite level in 2017. Black keeps the knight on d5 due to tactical tricks. }
7. Nxe5
{ A known motif for White, which can be executed several moves in a row but shouldn't keep Black concerned. }
7... Nxc3
{ Unless the knight is protected on d5, this is the standard response. } 8.
Bxc6+
{ This trick with a check works only once for White - on other occasions, White will play bxc3 and after ...Nxe5 White wins back the piece with d4 and an equal position. Everything else is worse. }
8... bxc6 9. bxc3
{ After   9.dxc3  Qe7  Black has a lasting initiative and a great compensation for the pawn. }
9... Qd5 10. Nf3 Bh3
{ Black is about to develop a strong initiative so it makes sense for White to trade queens. }
11. Qb3
{ Nice try to keep the pawn, but Black eventually equalizes. After   11.d4  Bd6  Black keeps the queens on the board and starts to build up an attack against the stranded white king. }
11... Bg2 12. Qxd5 cxd5 { This is the start of a forced sequence. } 13. Rg1
Bxf3 14. exf3 d4
{ Black will castle long and eventually recapture the pawn due to the piece activity. }
