[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. Nf3
{ Do you know the Sicilian Nimzowitsch variation which usually goes @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  This is the same but colors reversed, and a pet line of Russian GM Alexander Rakhmanov who's been playing the system with both colors. Typically it is played to avoid some mainstream theory. }
2... e4
{ Black charges forward to take some space advantage. White hardly has a choice here. }
3. Nd4 Nc6
{ The most direct move - here White has tested a few continuations. } 4. e3
{ This allows Black immediately to get a fine game. } 4... Nxd4 5. exd4 Qf6
{ Unbelievable but this line was first played almost 100 years ago between two chess legends - Savielly Tartakower versus Ernst Gruenfeld! It's still more accurate than the tempting  5...d5  as after  6.Nc3  Black will be missing this tempo of ...Nf6, comparing with a sharp Sicilian Nimzowitsch variation. For starters, Black is just threatening to win the pawn. }
6. Nc3
{ Perhaps this is a more modern approach - White sacrifices a pawn for some lead in development. }
6... Qxd4 { If you say A, be ready to say B as well. } 7. Be2 Nf6 8. O-O
{ White is relying on some advantage in the development thus instead of being greedy, it's best to give up the pawn immediately and focus on a speedy development. }
8... d5 9. cxd5
{ 9.d3  Bd7!  must be the simplest way to end the gambit and finish the development with equal chances. }
9... Nxd5 10. Nb5
{ White might try  10.Qb3  c6  11.Bc4  Bd6  and Black gives up the extra pawn to finish the development. }
10... Qb6 11. Qa4
{ The most dangerous threat is the double-check on c7 so that must be dealt with first. }
11... c6 12. Qxe4+
{ Rakhmanov,A @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@-Ponkratov,P @@StartBracket@@2628@@EndBracket@@ Top 16 GP rapid 2020, here the two GMs quickly agreed for a draw but the game might have continued a few moves. }
12... Be7 13. Nd6+ Kf8 14. Nxc8 Rxc8
{ Even though Black can't castle anymore, White can't exploit it, plus Black has a great outpost for the knight on d5. }
15. Bc4 Rd8 16. d3 Bf6 { The black king will inevitably find a shelter on g7. }
17. Re1 h5 18. Bxd5 cxd5
{ White gets rid of the outpost on d5 otherwise as soon as the black king will get to g7, White risks getting a worse position because playing an isolated pawn structure with no active prospects can very quickly turn into defending the isolated pawn as a terrible weakness. }
19. Qf3 g6 20. Be3 d4 21. Bd2 Kg7
{ Black has achieved complete equality in a symmetrical position. } *

