1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. Nf3
{ Do you know the Sicilian Nimzowitsch variation which usually goes @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  This is the same but colors reversed, and a pet line of Russian GM Alexander Rakhmanov who's been playing the system with both colors. Typically it is played to avoid some mainstream theory. }
2... e4
{ Black charges forward to take some space advantage. White hardly has a choice here. }
3. Nd4 Nc6
{ The most direct move - here White has tested a few continuations. } 4. Nc2
{ With this retreat White wants to challenge the e-pawn and fight for a strong pawn center. Black should proceed with strong action in the center. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5
{ I hope that after studying the entire course, you will have a much better understanding of when it's best to take on d5 with the queen and when do you need to bring out the kingside knight first to recapture it. Here Black doesn't have a lot of choices as you need to take care of the e4 pawn. The black queen will feel very comfortable on e5. }
6. Nc3 Qe5
{ So far this is almost forced and White has to push the d-pawn or he will get into a worse position immediately. }
7. f3
{ Don't try this at home - the f-pawn push against the e4 pawn is a well-known idea, but not so early. It would make sense if White had already castled. }
7... exf3 8. gxf3
{ Probably White already had to play a gambit and forget about the pawn. } 8...
Qf4 { Suddenly White's in big trouble. } 9. e3 Qh4+ 10. Ke2 Be6
{ Vokac,M @@StartBracket@@2412@@EndBracket@@-Deac,B @@StartBracket@@2579@@EndBracket@@ Czech Open A 2017, the wandering of the white king in the middle of the board can't end well. Black should keep queens on the board to keep the attack going. }
