1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. Nf3
{ Do you know the Sicilian Nimzowitsch variation which usually goes @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  This is the same but colors reversed, and a pet line of Russian GM Alexander Rakhmanov who's been playing the system with both colors. Typically it is played to avoid some mainstream theory. }
2... e4
{ Black charges forward to take some space advantage. White hardly has a choice here. }
3. Nd4 Nc6
{ The most direct move - here White has tested a few continuations. } 4. Nxc6
{ Probably the least dangerous of the continuations but this is one of the core ideas for the Sicilian Nimzowitsch defense. White gives up the center and relies on some unorthodox ideas, usually at the queenside. }
4... dxc6
{ Here taking with the d-pawn is best as it opens the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and the d-file for the black queen. If White would ever play either d2-d3 or d2-d4, then Black will just trade the pawns on d3, leaving White with a weak pawn, plus a potential outpost on d4 for a light piece. }
5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Qc2 Bf5 7. f3
{ This maneuver bears some resemblance to a known game between Magnus Carlsen vs Nils Grandelius with colors reversed, where the world champion spectacularly sacrificed a piece. }
7... Qe7
{ Black protects the pawn and now g-pawn's push will lead White to a disaster. }
8. g4 Bg6 9. g5
{ White is trying to win the pawn on e4 but this meets a tactical refutation. }
9... exf3 10. gxf6 f2+
{ White loses the queen because Black can take on f6 with a check. } *

