1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. Nf3
{ Do you know the Sicilian Nimzowitsch variation which usually goes @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  This is the same but colors reversed, and a pet line of Russian GM Alexander Rakhmanov who's been playing the system with both colors. Typically it is played to avoid some mainstream theory. }
2... e4
{ Black charges forward to take some space advantage. White hardly has a choice here. }
3. Nd4 Nc6
{ The most direct move - here White has tested a few continuations. } 4. Nxc6
{ Probably the least dangerous of the continuations but this is one of the core ideas for the Sicilian Nimzowitsch defense. White gives up the center and relies on some unorthodox ideas, usually at the queenside. }
4... dxc6
{ Here taking with the d-pawn is best as it opens the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and the d-file for the black queen. If White would ever play either d2-d3 or d2-d4, then Black will just trade the pawns on d3, leaving White with a weak pawn, plus a potential outpost on d4 for a light piece. }
5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e3
{ White is blocking the e-pawn and intends to position the dark-squared bishop on the long a1-h8 diagonal. The alternative to immediately pressure the e4 pawn doesn't work. }
6... Bf5 7. Qb3
{ White is provoking Black to play either ...b6 or ...Rb8 first before repositioning the queen to c2 so that in a future attack these weaknesses could work against Black. }
7... b6
{ However, there's no real harm in pushing forward the b-pawn. Black would like to keep the option to castle long and thus why the text move feels better than  7...Rb8 }
8. Qc2 Qd7 9. h3 h5
{ This stops White's intentions to play g4-g5 and Bg2, winning the pawn on e4. }
10. b3
{ One of White's ideas here which often works in the Sicilian Nimzowitsch variations with colors reversed is to reposition the knight to d4 and start an improvized queenside attack. The simplest way to meet it is just postponing the need to castle. }
10... a5
{ This move is not mandatory but it's directed against White's plans to reroute the knight to d4 and to play a3 with b4 later. The fact that Black has pushed the a-pawn doesn't mean that long castle is not an option to be chosen some moves later. }
11. Bb2 h4
{ Rakhmanov,A @@StartBracket@@2634@@EndBracket@@-Savchenko,B @@StartBracket@@2562@@EndBracket@@ Russian blitz championship 2018, this is a typical idea to fix the pawn structure at the kingside but it might not be necessary. Either way, Black has managed to take some considerable space advantage and can easily castle both sides. }
