1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. a3
{ This innocent-looking move immediately bears some resemblance with a known trick from the classical Sicilian -   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6  and here  3.d4  is not so great because of  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  followed by Bb4. Because of the lack of a true challenge in the center Black is free to improvise here with whatever setup he chooses. For the sake of simplicity I propose to keep to the same setup - prepare to play ...d5, if necessary then trade knights on c3 and position the dark-squared bishop on d6 for active chances at the kingside. This motif will be very common in many variations throughout the course. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ This would switch to a Sicilian Kan with colors reversed but Black can keep to the already proposed setup. }
3... d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Bd6
{ As soon as the white knight will jump to c3, trade it off. If the knight is attacked, you can move it to b6 and proceed with the standard plan. Perhaps don't rush with the knight's development on c6 to avoid some tricks with the Bb5 pin. On most occasions, the position should transpose to a covered line and in no scenario, Black is experiencing any problems in the opening. }
*

