[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Rare Lines"]
[Black "2.b3: #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. b3
{ This is an interesting sideline which is important to know - even some strong GMs have been misplaying this line for quite some time. }
2... Nc6 { or  2...Nf6  first, it shouldn't matter much. } 3. Bb2 Nf6
{ This position can be reached with the following order of the moves as well @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.b3  e5  2.Bb2  Nc6  3.c4  Nf6  .  Black wants to play as usual - push d5, take on d5 with the knight, and position the dark-squared bishop on d6. }
4. e3 { This allows Black to carry out the traditional setup. } 4... d5 5. cxd5
Nxd5
{ Now ...Ndb4 and ...Bf5 appear to be serious positional threats thus the next move feels to be almost necessary. }
6. Bb5
{ It is very tempting to target the pawn on e5 but it's just a bad move. } 6...
Nb4
{ A very strong shot - now taking the pawn on e5 lands White into immediate trouble. }
7. Nf3 { Strictly speaking, this is the only move. } 7... e4
{ Black pushes away the white knight to play  ...Qg5  next - White has to choose between  e5  and  d4  squares as  8.a3  Nd3+  gives Black a large advantage. }
8. Ne5 Qg5
{ Now White will have to take on  c6  , otherwise, after  9.Kf1   or  9.g3  Black's reply  9...Bd7!  looks good enough so that after  10.Nxd7  Black can play  10...Qxb5! }
9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bf1 h5
{ Black is ahead in development and already attacking - the doubled c-pawns don't play a big role. }
11. Nc3 Bf5 12. a3
{ Here  12.Rg1  might have been the lesser evil but the position remains bad for White. }
12... Nd3+ 13. Bxd3 Qxg2
{ Nice intermezzo move otherwise White is doing just fine. } 14. Bxe4 Bxe4
{ Domenche Redondo,F @@StartBracket@@1952@@EndBracket@@-Llorach Gracia,T @@StartBracket@@2174@@EndBracket@@ ESP-chT10 B email 2016, and White is strategically lost already after 14 moves. }
