[White "1. Rare Lines"]
[Black "2.b3: #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. b3
{ This is an interesting sideline which is important to know - even some strong GMs have been misplaying this line for quite some time. }
2... Nc6 { or  2...Nf6  first, it shouldn't matter much. } 3. Bb2 Nf6
{ This position can be reached with the following order of the moves as well @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.b3  e5  2.Bb2  Nc6  3.c4  Nf6  .  Black wants to play as usual - push d5, take on d5 with the knight, and position the dark-squared bishop on d6. }
4. g3 { This is the wrong moment for White to double fianchetto his bishops. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5
{ One of the moments when capturing a central pawn with the queen is better - because of the previous slow moves White is not ready for immediate action in the center. }
6. Nf3 e4 7. Nc3 Qa5
{ It's a good idea to keep White from playing Ng5 and the a5 square seems to be the best square to place the queen. }
8. Nh4 Be6
{ Here a very energetic play of one of the strongest Croatian GMs led Black to a crushing victory right after the opening. }
9. Bg2 O-O-O
{ A good strategic approach very often goes side by side with an ability to spot tactical motifs along the road. Here White can't play  10.Nxe4  due to  10...Nxe4  11.Bxe4  Rxd2!  and ...Bb4 next, winning the white queen. }
10. O-O Be7
{ Nestorovic,V @@StartBracket@@2285@@EndBracket@@-Kozul,Z @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@ Bled open 1995. It's fair to say that White's opening has been a total disaster since he still can't take the pawn on e4 without serious consequences and Black is about to storm the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Rare Lines"]
[Black "2.b3: #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. b3
{ This is an interesting sideline which is important to know - even some strong GMs have been misplaying this line for quite some time. }
2... Nc6 { or  2...Nf6  first, it shouldn't matter much. } 3. Bb2 Nf6
{ This position can be reached with the following order of the moves as well @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.b3  e5  2.Bb2  Nc6  3.c4  Nf6  .  Black wants to play as usual - push d5, take on d5 with the knight, and position the dark-squared bishop on d6. }
4. Nf3
{ The most critical move - White is challenging Black's center and something must be done about it. }
4... e4
{ Again, Black is going for the most direct approach, the e-pawn is protected by moving it forward with a tempo. }
5. Nd4
{ The alternatives don't look inspiring -   5.Nh4  can be answered with  5...d5  6.cxd5  Qxd5  7.Bxf6  gxf6  8.Nc3  Qg5  followed by ...f5 and the black bishops look powerful,  while the immediate   5.Ne5  can bring only trouble because of  5...Ne7!  and Black is threatening to trap the white knight with ...d6. }
5... Bc5 6. Nxc6
{ I was quite excited when I saw that one of the references in this line is a very famous game between two chess legends Bent Larsen and Boris Spassky! }
6... dxc6 7. e3 Bf5
{ The arising position is pretty much the same as what happens in the most important line of 2. Nf3 but the difference here is that Black has placed the dark-squared bishop on perhaps not the most optimal square on c5, but also White can't provoke any weaknesses with Qb3. }
8. Qc2 Qe7 9. Be2 O-O-O
{ This has to be a dream position for Black after the opening - all of the pieces are developed and Black even enjoys a space advantage. }
10. f4
{ An error in judgment by the Great Dane - now White has no counterplay whatsoever. }
10... Ng4 11. g3 h5 { Black starts to attack immediately. } 12. h3
{ This is the moment when Spassky unleashed one of his immortal combinations. }
12... h4
{ The idea is to open the kingside and penetrate White's defenses at the weakest spot. }
13. hxg4 hxg3 14. Rg1
{ White is protecting the first rank and it seems that he might just hold, and this is when came the cold shower. }
14... Rh1
{ Oh my goodness! Black sacrifices a whole rook just to win a critical tempo. }
15. Rxh1 g2 { Black's ...Qh4+ and back rank mate threats decide the game. } 16.
Rf1 Qh4+ 17. Kd1 gxf1=Q+
{ Larsen,B  @@StartBracket@@2650@@EndBracket@@-Spassky,B @@StartBracket@@2670@@EndBracket@@ Match/Team URS-World 1970, here White resigned. For one of the leading players in the world to be crushed like that with a mate in 20 moves, and with White - that's a very, very rare event. }
