[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. b3
{ This is an interesting sideline which is important to know - even some strong GMs have been misplaying this line for quite some time. }
2... Nc6 { or  2...Nf6  first, it shouldn't matter much. } 3. Bb2 Nf6
{ This position can be reached with the following order of the moves as well @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.b3  e5  2.Bb2  Nc6  3.c4  Nf6  .  Black wants to play as usual - push d5, take on d5 with the knight, and position the dark-squared bishop on d6. }
4. Nf3
{ The most critical move - White is challenging Black's center and something must be done about it. }
4... e4
{ Again, Black is going for the most direct approach, the e-pawn is protected by moving it forward with a tempo. }
5. Nd4
{ The alternatives don't look inspiring -   5.Nh4  can be answered with  5...d5  6.cxd5  Qxd5  7.Bxf6  gxf6  8.Nc3  Qg5  followed by ...f5 and the black bishops look powerful,  while the immediate   5.Ne5  can bring only trouble because of  5...Ne7!  and Black is threatening to trap the white knight with ...d6. }
5... Bc5 6. Nf5
{ This is the latest fashion of the variation - White keeps the white knight alive and will pressure the e4 pawn. }
6... O-O 7. e3
{ White continues the development and this initiates a couple of forced moves. }
7... d5 8. cxd5
{ Retreating with the knight with  8.Ng3  doesn't look great for White due to  8...d4 }
8... Nb4
{ A very nice intermezzo move - Black eyes the d3-square which ideally would be better occupied by a piece, than by a pawn. }
9. Ng3
{ Or  9.Qc1  Bb6  ,  which is just a different order of the moves of what's coming next. }
9... Nfxd5
{ This is much more energetic than recapturing with the knight from b4 - Black is ready to sacrifice the pawn on e4 and develop a very strong initiative. }
10. Qc1
{ The idea of this move is to keep the option of Nxe4 alive as it extra protects the e3 square against various sacrificial motives. Among other peaceful alternatives are   10.a3  which forces Black to play  10...Nd3+  with a good game, mainly because of the weakened White's queenside pawns,   or  10.Nc3  but this comes with a trick. Now after  10...Nxc3  11.dxc3  instead of the tempting 11...Nd3+ Black should first play the strong  11...Qe7!  as White can't take on b4 because of the recapture and ...Rd8 afterward and only after  12.Qc1  play  ...Nd3+  , winning a couple of critical tempos. }
10... Bb6
{ This move has been tested at correspondence chess already several times and the verdict is that it's incredibly risky for White to take the pawn on e4 @@StartBracket@@surprise, surprise@@EndBracket@@. On b6 the dark-squared bishop still participates in an attack, should White gather the courage and take the bait. }
11. Nxe4
{ As I said, this is playing with fire. I can't see White consciously choosing this approach if knowing the critical lines as they balance with a forced loss. If White happened to be here without any prior knowledge, he shouldn't hold for long. }
11... Re8 12. Nbc3
{ White can bail out with  12.a3  Rxe4  13.axb4  Nxb4  but it doesn't make sense to venture there in the first place and then change the mind after a couple of moves. Now comes the true spirit killer move. }
12... Nf4
{ This is a positional piece sacrifice to keep the white king in the center and open more files. White has no choice but to accept it. }
13. exf4 Qh4
{ Black has sacrificed a whole piece for a dangerous attack and the engines love it! I checked the most critical lines - Black is doing great in all of them and the absence of the piece is not even felt. }
14. g3
{ This might be the human choice to stop Black from capturing the pawn on f2 but it weakens the kingside even more. }
14... Qh5 15. h3 Bf5
{ Black is threatening to win back the sacrificed piece and continue the attack. }
16. Qd1 Qg6 17. d3 Rad8 { White can't keep everything together. } 18. Qb1 Bd4
{ Now the ...Nxd3+ threat already is inevitable. } 19. Be2 Nxd3+ 20. Bxd3 Bxc3+
21. Bxc3 Rxe4+
{ The point of the whole combination - Black wins back all of the sacrificed material. Now after  22.Kf1  Black continues with  22...Rxd3!  White can't take the rook due to the ...Re1+ and the queen falls. }
