1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. d4 { This will force the white queen to walk early which is rarely good. }
2... exd4 3. Nf3
{ White might try to play some sort of a gambit, inviting Black to play here the greedy  3...c5  4.e3  dxe3  5.Bxe3  with a considerable compensation, mainly because of the lead in development and an outpost on d5. Black has a vast choice of options here but probably the best is to keep the pawn, but trade bishops first. }
3... Bb4+ 4. Bd2
{ Or  4.Nbd2  c5  5.a3  Bxd2+  ,  followed by ...Nf6 and ... Qe7. } 4... Bxd2+
5. Qxd2 c5 6. e3
{ Murthy,P @@StartBracket@@1940@@EndBracket@@-Atanasov,A @@StartBracket@@2205@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com Titled Tuesday 2020. Black simply is a pawn up. }
6... Qe7 7. Bd3 dxe3 8. fxe3 Nf6
{ White has no compensation for the sacrificed pawn and Black has a healthy development. }
