[White "1. Rare Lines"]
[Black "2.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. e4
{ White is aiming for the so-called Botvinnik setup of c4-d3-e4, followed by g3-Bg2 but this is probably the worst possible moment for White to go for it. The reason is that Black is flexible and can choose how to meet it with the best efficiency. }
2... Nc6 3. Nc3 Bc5
{ Now Black doesn't need to position the kingside knight to f6 but it can directly go to e7 to push the f-pawn. Two things to watch out for - don't miss White's Nxe5 and d2-d4 threat which would demolish Black's solid grip of the center. The second, don't allow White to trade your dark-squared bishop for a knight with Na4 as the bishop here is a pretty strong piece. }
4. Nf3 d6 { This deals with the first trick. } 5. d3 Nge7
{ Thanks to White's order of the moves, here the knight feels a lot better than on f6. }
6. a3
{ Antipov,M @@StartBracket@@2616@@EndBracket@@-Ovetchkin,R @@StartBracket@@2546@@EndBracket@@ Russian championship Higher league 2018 }
6... a5
{ This move not only parries the Na4 positional threat but also takes more space at the queenside. Black already looks better and will be faster to launch an attack at the kingside. }
*

