1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. Qc2
{ On some occasions, this early queen move should transpose to the other sidelines but there are two important moments I'd like to point out. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Nf3
{ This position probably can be reached with other order of the moves, having White just played 4. Qc2 as well - you should be aware of the following tactical trick at White's disposal. }
4... Nd4
{ The most careful move immediately equalizes the game by trading off both knights. This motif is more known if White had played 4.g3 instead of Qc2 - here it works for Black even better as it comes with a tempo. }
5. Nxd4
{ White could play   5.Qd3  as well, then  5...Nxf3+  6.Qxf3  c6  should be good enough for Black, planning for an active game in the center. }
5... exd4 6. Nd5
{ Or   6.Ne4  Be7  and Black wants to push forward the d-pawn. } 6... c6 7.
Nxf6+ Qxf6 8. e3
{ Iturrizaga Bonelli,E @@StartBracket@@2597@@EndBracket@@ -Topalov,V @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ Salamanca Uni 9th 2019, White would like to position the dark-squared bishop on b2 but the immediate   8.b3  meets  8...d3  Here Black has several good moves. }
8... dxe3 9. dxe3 Qg6
{ Black wants to play . ..Be6 next and push the d-pawn at some point later. The black pawn on d6 is a minor weakness. }
