1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. Qc2
{ On some occasions, this early queen move should transpose to the other sidelines but there are two important moments I'd like to point out. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3
{ This is reversed Sicilian Taimanov and because of the missing tempo, Black has a very interesting option here. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nb4
{ Much more energetic than the standard  5...Nxd5  which would lead to some typical Taimanov lines without the tempo. }
6. Qa4+ Bd7 7. Bb5
{ Retreating with the queen to  b3  is not good due to  7.Qb3  Bf5  and Black takes over. With the text move White trades off many pieces with an equal position. }
7... Nbxd5 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qxd7+ Kxd7
{ Black has no weaknesses and has a good development. } *

