1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. e3
{ This interesting move usually transposes to major lines if White continues with Nc3 and Nf3. }
2... Nf6
{ Here White has some choices - either develop one of the knights or transpose to one of the sidelines with  3.a3   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2P5/4P3/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  3.Qc2 }
3. Nc3 Nc6
{ It is possible to go for  3...Bb4  but then White can switch to Rossolimo / Nimzo Indian ideas with  4.Nge2  and continue with a3. It's just fine but the text move is more consistent with the entire approach. }
4. g4
{ It's looking awfully like Grob - it's an interesting idea for some blitz games but I can't imagine this line to be played by serious players in classical time control. White intends to counter Black's ...d5 with g5 @@StartBracket@@which is still playable due to ...d4@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bb4
{ I see no reason to avoid this move. Ever since a blitz game between Magnus Carlsen and Maxime Vachier - Lagrave back in 2017 many GMs have tested this line with other continuations, but I think MVL was doing just fine. }
5. g5 Bxc3 6. gxf6 { This is possible and perhaps a more peaceful approach. }
6... Ba5 7. a3 d6
{ We should inevitably reach the same final position but the order of the moves might change. }
8. b4 Bb6 9. fxg7 Rg8
{ Black wins back the pawn and is simply ahead in development. White has developed exactly zero pieces. }
