1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. e3
{ This interesting move usually transposes to major lines if White continues with Nc3 and Nf3. }
2... Nf6
{ Here White has some choices - either develop one of the knights or transpose to one of the sidelines with  3.a3   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2P5/4P3/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  3.Qc2 }
3. Nc3 Nc6
{ It is possible to go for  3...Bb4  but then White can switch to Rossolimo / Nimzo Indian ideas with  4.Nge2  and continue with a3. It's just fine but the text move is more consistent with the entire approach. }
4. Qb3
{ With this tricky move White is stopping Black's ...d5 for good and the ...Bb4 maneuver doesn't feel so good as the queen already is challenging the bishop. I think it's safe to continue Anish's Giri recommendation, what he played against Magnus Carlsen in one of the super tournaments. }
4... g6
{ One of the rare moments of the course when we will be going for a bishop fianchetto. The white queen on b3 doesn't seem to be ready for strong action in the center and it makes sense to use it to your advantage. }
5. Nf3 Bg7 6. d4
{ There are other continuations as well, but this is White's best bet. } 6...
exd4 7. exd4 O-O 8. Be2 d6
{ White has a little space advantage but nothing more. } 9. O-O Re8 10. h3 Ne4
{ Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2872@@EndBracket@@-Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2768@@EndBracket@@ Tata Steel Chess 2020, and Black easily equalized. }
