1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. e3
{ This interesting move usually transposes to major lines if White continues with Nc3 and Nf3. }
2... Nf6
{ Here White has some choices - either develop one of the knights or transpose to one of the sidelines with  3.a3   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2P5/4P3/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  3.Qc2 }
3. Nc3 Nc6
{ It is possible to go for  3...Bb4  but then White can switch to Rossolimo / Nimzo Indian ideas with  4.Nge2  and continue with a3. It's just fine but the text move is more consistent with the entire approach. }
4. a3
{ this move allows Black without any headache to switch to the setup which works against many sidelines in this and the next chapter - push d5, trade the knight on c3, position the dark-squared bishop on d6, and enjoy a good game. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Qc2
{ There are other moves as well, but they should either transpose to what happened in this game, or one of the other sidelines. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. Nf3 O-O
{ You might see this setup a lot in many lines, with or without White having included Qc2 or Black - Nc6. }
9. d4 Qe7 10. Be2 Bd7
{ Black is thinking about a potential kingside attack with e5-e4 but it doesn't involve the f-pawn as that would close the light-squared bishop. }
11. O-O Rae8 12. Re1 b6 13. c4 exd4
{ Rosen, E @@StartBracket@@2338@@EndBracket@@-Jacobson, A @@StartBracket@@2311@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis Norm IM 2019, White blundered in the game that  14.exd4  is met by simple  14...Bg4  and White is out of good moves because of the ...Bxf3 threat. }
