[Black "2.e3 and 3.d4: #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. e3
{ This interesting move usually transposes to major lines if White continues with Nc3 and Nf3. }
2... Nf6
{ Here White has some choices - either develop one of the knights or transpose to one of the sidelines with  3.a3   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2P5/4P3/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  3.Qc2 }
3. d4
{ White is fighting for a strong pawn center which is pretty easy to challenge. By doing this White is also falling behind in development and will need to be careful. }
3... exd4 4. exd4
{ The arising setup will be very similar to what can be reached with the following order of the moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.c4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  so you might benefit from it on other occasions as well. In general, it's a harmless setup but there are a couple of things that you should know. }
4... Bb4+ 5. Nc3
{ The only reasonable move as on d2 the white knight will feel a lot worse and Black can just castle short and push forward the d-pawn. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3
{ Maybe  6.Be2  is a more careful move, avoiding any early checks on the e-file but it should lead to the same position a couple of moves later. }
6... d5
{ The position now inevitably transposes to an isolated queen's pawn structure as closing the center with  7.c5  is not good due to  7...b6  8.cxb6  Bxc3+  9.bxc3  axb6  ,  and the light-squared bishops will be traded off via the a6 square, leaving White with some serious weaknesses at the queenside. With the isolated queen's pawn, White is relying on his piece activity - Black mostly tries to block the pawn and trade off some pieces to make the pawn on d4 more vulnerable.   Here White has two setups - either position the kingside knight on f3 or e2 and depending on where the knight will go, Black will have a different approach. I'd like to point out that Black doesn't mind trading the bishop on c3, even if it allows White to continue with bxc3 and protect the d4 pawn but this is not something that Black should be aiming for. There might be moments when White could find a way to force the trade with a3, or perhaps Nf4-d3. Just remember - it's fine as long as your other pieces have a decent activity. Those queenside pawns will be weak anyway. }
7. Ne2
{ With the white knight on e2 now nobody is going to control the e5 square so Black can safely go for the d4 pawn block on d5. }
7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Nbd7
{ Black is inevitably rerouting the queenside knight to d5. } 9. O-O Nb6 10.
Bb3
{ the most flexible move - White doesn't allow Black to play ...Be6 just yet and is quietly preparing the queen + bishop battery at the b1-h7 diagonal. Black's goal is to trade off the light-squared bishops. }
10... c6
{ First fixing the formalities so that the d5 square is firmly under Black's control, otherwise White could consider playing d4-d5 at some point. }
11. Bg5 Re8
{ Black is preparing to play ...Be6 next and if the White bishop will retreat to c2 then ...Bc4 could be an annoying problem. Black can play ...h6 at the right moment and there's no need to rush with the move. }
12. Qd3
{ White is building the battery and Black could play  12...Be6  immediately, however, the text move is a little stronger. }
12... h6 { Black should be aware of any tactics. } 13. Bxh6
{ This is very tempting but it doesn't work. } 13... gxh6 14. Qg6+ Kh8
{ White just doesn't have enough pieces in the close vicinity to increase the pressure in time and Black will regroup a little faster. }
15. Bxf7 { or  15.Qxh6+  Nh7  16.Bc2  f5 } 15... Rf8 16. Qxh6+ Nh7 17. Bg6 Qe7
{ Grabowicz,M @@StartBracket@@1852@@EndBracket@@-Praczukowski,S @@StartBracket@@1862@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw YMCA Autumn-B 130th 2013. White's attack is over, Black has a piece for three pawns that haven't started to move yet thus advantage is with Black. }
