[White "1. Rare Lines"]
[Black "2.e3 and 3.Nf3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Before having a look at the most popular continuations, as a warm-up let's check the rare continuations at White's disposal. Some of them can transpose to either some major lines with a different order of the moves or between each other. I'll review all the unique possibilities. }
2. e3
{ This interesting move usually transposes to major lines if White continues with Nc3 and Nf3. }
2... Nf6
{ Here White has some choices - either develop one of the knights or transpose to one of the sidelines with  3.a3   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/2P5/4P3/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  3.Qc2 }
3. Nf3
{ Again, the early kingside knight's jump to f3 reminds me of the Sicilian Nimzowitsch line with colors reversed. Black should charge forward with the e-pawn to win some time and fight for space advantage, even if temporary. }
3... e4 4. Nd4 Nc6
{ Black is threatening to trade on d4 and push forward the d-pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ 5.Nxc6  dxc6  would just transpose to the mainline of 2.Nf3 but here are some differences }
5... Bb4
{ This appears to be the most precise move to neutralize White's ambitions. It's possible to trade the knights first with  5...Nxd4  6.exd4  as well and then either prepare the d-pawn push with  6...c6   or even push the d-pawn immediately with  6...d5  . However, I found that in the arising positions White is still pushing by playing  d3  and a good version of isolated queen's pawn. After the text move, there should be no questions about the future of this line - Black is doing great and easily equalizes. Now White has some choices - either pressure the black e-pawn with  Qc2  , or try to force Black into trading the dark-squared bishop with either  Qb3  or  Qa4  . }
6. Qc2 { White is targeting the e4 pawn. } 6... Nxd4 7. exd4
{ Rakhmanov,A @@StartBracket@@2606@@EndBracket@@ -Sasikiran,K @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@ Spanish Team championships 2019, and here instead of giving up the dark-squared bishop on c3 and a long-term pressure for White. Black can immediately equalize. }
7... c6 { White can't take the pawn on e4 due to ...Qe7 and ...d5. } 8. a3 Ba5
9. d3 d5 { Very accurate - Black has a harmonious game here. } 10. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This is a little more ambitious than  10...cxd5  - Black is seeking a counterplay.  Now   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2p5/b2n4/3Pp3/P1NP4/1PQ2PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.dxe4  meets  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  Qxd4!  and Black should be better because of the pawn structure. }
11. Bd2 exd3 12. Bxd3 Nf6
{ Another nice move, playing for the isolated queen's pawn structure - White has no attack at the kingside. }
13. O-O O-O
{ In the following game, White decided to spice up things but ended up on the wrong side. }
14. d5 cxd5 15. Bg5 Bxc3 16. bxc3
{ 16.Qxc3  has a very powerful reply  16...Ne4! } 16... h6
{ Dreisch,J @@StartBracket@@2106@@EndBracket@@ -Brodt,A @@StartBracket@@2352@@EndBracket@@ VW-Cup9 Gr43 email 2016, Black feels pretty secure and can easily get rid of the pin. }
