{ White offers Black a trade on c3, to relieve the pressure against the e4 pawn. That's strategically a very risky choice for Black - by doing so White could position the dark-squared bishop on the a1-h8 diagonal with terrifying prospects. The pawn on e4 is still safe so there's no need for this. }
6... Nxd4 7. exd4 Ba5
{ Black keeps the dark-squared bishop alive and prepares ...c6-d5. } 8. Qa3
{ If  8.d3  ,  then Black doesn't have to react to that and can continue with  8...O-O  instead. The following move is a nice trick in White's arsenal - the black king temporarily stays in the center, plus White is threatening to capture the dark-squared bishop with b2-b4. }
8... c6 9. d3
{ Or  9.Be2  d5  10.cxd5  and again  10...Nxd5!  with the idea to meet  11.Nxe4  with  11...Bb4  and Black can castle short and eventually win back the d4 pawn. }
9... d5 10. dxe4 Nxe4 11. cxd5
{ This was played in a correspondence game and Black seems to be doing more than okay. }
11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Qxd5 { Black is not allowing White to castle immediately. }
13. f3 Be6 14. Be3
{ Here Black has to solve the problem of his stuck king in the center first to claim a good game. }
14... Bc7 15. Bd3 Bd6
{ Kermer, W. @@StartBracket@@2382@@EndBracket@@-Shapiro, V. @@StartBracket@@2363@@EndBracket@@ EU-ch 2018 sf13 email 2018, because of the better pawn structure Black seems to be slightly better. }
