[White "2. Reversed Sicilian with 2.d3"]
[Black "3.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ Since English opening very often is reversed Sicilian with many copied ideas, many players might find it interesting to play a reversed Sicilian Najdorf, Scheveningen, or Dragon system. Thus I decided to make a separate chapter and explain how to properly counter them. Luckily, Black is not under the pressure to get an advantage after the opening and nobody will complain if the arising position is equal. }
2... Nf6 3. a3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This should transpose to one of the lines of the chapter and if White is particularly slow, Black can immediately set up the Maroczy Bind with ...c5 and ...Nc6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Reversed Sicilian with 2.d3"]
[Black "4.g3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ Since English opening very often is reversed Sicilian with many copied ideas, many players might find it interesting to play a reversed Sicilian Najdorf, Scheveningen, or Dragon system. Thus I decided to make a separate chapter and explain how to properly counter them. Luckily, Black is not under the pressure to get an advantage after the opening and nobody will complain if the arising position is equal. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ White can start with  3.a3  first to avoid any anti reversed Sicilian approaches with ...Bb4+ but that's not what I'm going to recommend here. }
3... Nc6
{ My goal with the course is to build a complete repertoire for Black against 1. c4 so that you can easily switch to familiar positions and can't be tricked with a different order of the moves. For example, if White would now continue with   4.Nc3  ,  that's the two knights variation from the later chapters of the course. You don't need to reinvent a bicycle and play two different systems against the same setup, played in a different order of the moves.   Note that  4.Nc3  will transpose to Chapter 15 and the other reversed Sicilians at White's disposal, having not played a3. }
4. g3
{ Setup No.1 - the reversed Sicilian Dragon. Interestingly, the traditional Sicilian Dragon has a dubious reputation of falling under a direct attack, but here White is protected by the extra tempo, which should mean something. I also imagine that this could be a favorite choice for somebody who plays Sicilian Dragon with Black. However, there's a little drawback to the entire plan. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ If White will ever try to switch to some kind of a reversed Dragodorf and include  6.a3  either now or later, don't hesitate to meet it with  (...a5,)  stopping the b4 push. }
6. a3 a5 7. Bg2 Be7
{ Normally this line should transpose to some of the reversed Dragon lines, but here White having included a3, I'd like to point out a little trick at his disposal. }
8. d4
{ if White didn't have a3 included, now very powerful would be ...Bb4+ which is very difficult to meet. Here, however, Black easily equalizes. }
8... Nf6
{ This is by far the simplest choice - it is possible to play it a little more aggressively with  8...e4  9.Ne5  f5  10.Nxc6  bxc6  but that's a very double-edged position. }
9. Nxe5 Nxe5
{ Initiating a forced sequence, trading off some pieces, and regaining the pawn. }
10. dxe5 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Ng4
{ Because of the fork threat, White has no time to protect the e5 pawn. } 12.
Ke1 Nxe5 { The position is equal - both sides have no visible weaknesses. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Reversed Sicilian with 2.d3"]
[Black "4.g3: #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ Since English opening very often is reversed Sicilian with many copied ideas, many players might find it interesting to play a reversed Sicilian Najdorf, Scheveningen, or Dragon system. Thus I decided to make a separate chapter and explain how to properly counter them. Luckily, Black is not under the pressure to get an advantage after the opening and nobody will complain if the arising position is equal. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ White can start with  3.a3  first to avoid any anti reversed Sicilian approaches with ...Bb4+ but that's not what I'm going to recommend here. }
3... Nc6
{ My goal with the course is to build a complete repertoire for Black against 1. c4 so that you can easily switch to familiar positions and can't be tricked with a different order of the moves. For example, if White would now continue with   4.Nc3  ,  that's the two knights variation from the later chapters of the course. You don't need to reinvent a bicycle and play two different systems against the same setup, played in a different order of the moves.   Note that  4.Nc3  will transpose to Chapter 15 and the other reversed Sicilians at White's disposal, having not played a3. }
4. g3
{ Setup No.1 - the reversed Sicilian Dragon. Interestingly, the traditional Sicilian Dragon has a dubious reputation of falling under a direct attack, but here White is protected by the extra tempo, which should mean something. I also imagine that this could be a favorite choice for somebody who plays Sicilian Dragon with Black. However, there's a little drawback to the entire plan. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ If White will ever try to switch to some kind of a reversed Dragodorf and include  6.a3  either now or later, don't hesitate to meet it with  (...a5,)  stopping the b4 push. }
6. Nc3
{ Characteristic to some accelerated Dragon ideas, this is a very tricky move - White intends to take on d5 very early and Black will have some practical problems to rearrange the pieces for the traditional setup against the reversed Dragon. }
6... Bc5
{ I think it's best to transpose to the main lines of the four knights variation, covered in the final chapter of the course. Because White has already committed to d3, the arising positions with the traditional Be7 here are quite tricky and it's easy to get confused. }
*

