[White "2. Reversed Sicilian with 2.d3"]
[Black "4.g3: #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ Since English opening very often is reversed Sicilian with many copied ideas, many players might find it interesting to play a reversed Sicilian Najdorf, Scheveningen, or Dragon system. Thus I decided to make a separate chapter and explain how to properly counter them. Luckily, Black is not under the pressure to get an advantage after the opening and nobody will complain if the arising position is equal. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ White can start with  3.a3  first to avoid any anti reversed Sicilian approaches with ...Bb4+ but that's not what I'm going to recommend here. }
3... Nc6
{ My goal with the course is to build a complete repertoire for Black against 1. c4 so that you can easily switch to familiar positions and can't be tricked with a different order of the moves. For example, if White would now continue with   4.Nc3  ,  that's the two knights variation from the later chapters of the course. You don't need to reinvent a bicycle and play two different systems against the same setup, played in a different order of the moves.   Note that  4.Nc3  will transpose to Chapter 15 and the other reversed Sicilians at White's disposal, having not played a3. }
4. g3
{ Setup No.1 - the reversed Sicilian Dragon. Interestingly, the traditional Sicilian Dragon has a dubious reputation of falling under a direct attack, but here White is protected by the extra tempo, which should mean something. I also imagine that this could be a favorite choice for somebody who plays Sicilian Dragon with Black. However, there's a little drawback to the entire plan. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ If White will ever try to switch to some kind of a reversed Dragodorf and include  6.a3  either now or later, don't hesitate to meet it with  (...a5,)  stopping the b4 push. }
6. Bg2 Be7
{ I was considering proposing  6...Bc5  but I realized that the arising positions are very tricky, and mainly because White hasn't developed the queenside knight yet as it might go to d2-c4 if necessary. The suggested move is more consistent. }
7. O-O O-O
{ White might consider pushing d4 at any given moment to open his bishops thus this maneuver is not to be missed. If Black is doing everything as recommended, it's not dangerous since White has already committed himself to d3 and this would cost a tempo. }
8. Nc3 Be6
{ Now it's time to make a comparison with a very familiar line of the English opening. I'm talking about @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  e5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  d5  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.Bg2  and here a lot of people play 5... Nb6 as it's not a great idea to try to keep the knight in the center with  5...Be6  because after  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.d4  this advance was achieved in one move. With the retreated knight on b6 Black typically continues with ...Nc6, ...O-O, ...f6, and then at some point reroutes the knight from b6 back to d5.   Here you can see a major difference - the white pawn is already on d3 thus any d3-d4 thrusts pose no trouble for Black who is up a critical tempo. Thus it's not necessary to remove the knight to b6 as it stands just fine on d5, so Black has effectively saved some time! Let's check several options at Black's disposal. }
9. a3
{ Again, the rule remains - in the reversed Dragon, as soon as White plays a3, Black fires back with ...a5 }
9... a5 10. Nxd5
{ White might consider switching to the Qa4 and Be3 system but it can't do both things at the same time - stop the ...a4 threat and play Be3. }
10... Bxd5 11. Qa4 Bc5
{ There are other good moves as well but this is the most active one. Black 'wastes' a tempo for a second bishop movement but on c5 here it stands a little more active and prepares the ...Nd4 move. }
12. Bd2
{ White's  12.Qb5  can be parried with  12...Qd6  and the pawn on b7 can't ever be taken as the queen will be trapped after  13.Qxb7  Nd4 }
12... Nd4 { White has no choice but to accept the trade. } 13. Nxd4 exd4 14.
Bxd5 Qxd5 15. Rac1 Bb6
{ Only Black can be pressing here. With the weakened white king and weakness on e2, Black is not interested to trade queens. }
*

