9... Bd6
{ I believe that these moves are pretty much automatic and now White has some choices. }
10. Be2
{ This is a very modest continuation and sort of invites Black to prepare a kingside attack. This position might be reached with a different order of the moves as well. }
10... O-O
{ Before moving forward with the e-pawn I suggest paying close attention to where White is going to position his dark-squared bishop. }
11. O-O Re8
{ The black pawn should remain on f7 so that the light-squared bishop can join the attack at the kingside, if necessary. }
12. Bb2 e4
{ With the dark-squared bishop gone from the c1-h6 diagonal Black can start to launch the kingside attack with ...e4 and not worry about some counter-strikes with f3, with the bishop still defending the e3 pawn. If White would do something else like Rb1 or Qc2, Black has a lot of other useful moves, like ...b6, ...Qe7 and the light-squared bishop to either f5 or g4, at the same time not forgetting about ...e4. }
13. Nd2 Qg5 { Now White can't strike back with f4. } 14. g3 Nb8 15. c4 Nd7
{ Black is calling all the shots here and has good prospects for a strong attack. }
