1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ Since English opening very often is reversed Sicilian with many copied ideas, many players might find it interesting to play a reversed Sicilian Najdorf, Scheveningen, or Dragon system. Thus I decided to make a separate chapter and explain how to properly counter them. Luckily, Black is not under the pressure to get an advantage after the opening and nobody will complain if the arising position is equal. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ White can start with  3.a3  first to avoid any anti reversed Sicilian approaches with ...Bb4+ but that's not what I'm going to recommend here. }
3... Nc6
{ My goal with the course is to build a complete repertoire for Black against 1. c4 so that you can easily switch to familiar positions and can't be tricked with a different order of the moves. For example, if White would now continue with   4.Nc3  ,  that's the two knights variation from the later chapters of the course. You don't need to reinvent a bicycle and play two different systems against the same setup, played in a different order of the moves.   Note that  4.Nc3  will transpose to Chapter 15 and the other reversed Sicilians at White's disposal, having not played a3. }
4. a3
{ This is how normally reversed Sicilian Najdorf would start, but White can still choose e3 and Scheveningen setups. }
4... d5
{ The most principled approach and in the spirit of the entire course - Black is playing actively in the center. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Here White has two more choices - either play reversed Sicilian Scheveningen with e3, reversed Sicilian Najdorf with e4, or switch back to Dragon setups, making it essentially reversed Dragodorf. }
6. e3
{ Setup No.2 - the reversed Sicilian Scheveningen. White is not making any radical decisions in the center and plans to castle short, often provoking Black to start a kingside attack with ...f5 and maybe even ...g5-g4, to meet it with a precise counterstrike at the center. }
6... a5
{ Since a traditional idea for White is to push the b-pawn to b4 to bother the e5 pawn with Bb2 and b4-b5, it makes a lot of sense to take away that opportunity first, and consider continuing to take more space with...a5-a4. }
7. b3
{ Not surprisingly, this is one of the most popular moves in the position - White makes sure that Black can't play ...a4 and is about to position his dark-squared bishop on b2. }
7... Bd6
{ I propose to play the following setup - position both bishops on d6 and d7 for a potential kingside attack which can be accelerated with ...f5 and improved with ...Qe7 and ...Rae8. If White tries to trade-off the dark-squared bishop with Nbd2, just play ...Nb6 and protect it. Even if White will somehow manage to trade off the dark-squared bishop, Black can always recapture it with ...cxd6 and have a nice positional game. }
8. Bb2 O-O 9. Nbd2
{ The white knight is coming to c4 so it's time to stop it. } 9... Nb6 10. Be2
Qe7 11. O-O f5
{ Let me stop here for a moment and explain where the game might be heading. If White was to play  12.Nc4  ,  obviously Black should trade off the knights and continue with ...e4 and some attacking chances at the kingside.  If White would push in the center with   12.d4  ,  on most occasions it makes the most sense to close it with 12...e4  position the light-squared bishop on e6 and make good use of the d5 outpost.     White might consider pushing  12.e4  which is a thematic idea in the Scheveningen. It stops Black's active plans with ...e4 and should Black answer with 12...f4 This now allows White to make the desired breakthrough in the center with d4.   So after e4 the best approach is either to take the pawn on e4 with  12...fxe4  or just ignore it and offer White to take himself on f5. Apart from that, Black is just proceeding with a normal development with ...Bd7, ....Rae8 and thinking about activities at the kingside. They might start with ...Rf6-h6 or ...g5-g4 and then the rook maneuver. There might be some occasions when White could sacrifice a pawn at the queenside with b4 to open some lines and increase the pressure against the e5 pawn - don't miss it. }
12. Qc2
{ Savon,V @@StartBracket@@2390@@EndBracket@@-Webb,L  @@StartBracket@@2240@@EndBracket@@ Vladivostok open 1995 }
12... Bd7 13. Rfe1 Rae8
{ Black is already thinking about ...e4 so let me illustrate two potential plans how White might react. }
14. g3
{ This is a very common idea in the Sicilian Scheveningen to secure the king and at the same time reroute the light-squared bishop to g2. White is provoking Black to play ...f4 so that it can be answered with gxf4, then e4, Kh1, and Rg1, and some major problems on the g-file. If Black would play ...e4, then typically White reroutes the knight from f3-h4 and sometimes to g2, not necessarily always trading the d-pawn first. The bottom line is - if White can afford to maneuver and improve the pieces, obviously Black can do the same. }
14... Qf7 15. Bf1 h6
{ I just want to mention here that probably at any given moment Black can go for the f-pawn push and then with ...Qh5 and ...Bg4-h3 try to conjure something at the kingside. Just remember that it weakens the e4-square for the white knight and the attack won't necessarily succeed. }
16. Bg2 Be6
{ Black is repositioning the light-squared bishop to a more active role on d5. }
17. Rac1 Bd5
{ You might find this entire line to have something in common with cat and mouse - both sides are maneuvering but mostly waiting for the opponent to make a commital decision. For example,  18.Nc4  Nd7  ,  but in general it makes a lot of sense for Black to look towards the kingside because that's where the white king is. }
