17. g3 Nf6
{ The position is about balanced but as a final word, I'd like to mention - don't rush with ...Nd4 if you have to recapture with a pawn. White is looking forward to an ideal endgame position after the trade on d4 to have a strong knight on e4 against a useless dark-squared bishop on d6. Keep the knight on c6 and the tension as long as you can. }
18. Bf1 Be6 19. Bg2 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 h6
{ I can't imagine a single scenario where White would be interested to give away his light-squared bishop on c6 to win a pawn. Don't miss any Nxd6 and d4 thrusts in the center and look for some targets to pressure. Repositioning rooks on d8 and e8 might be a good start. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Reversed Sicilian with 2.d3"]
[Black "4.a3 and 6.b4: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ Since English opening very often is reversed Sicilian with many copied ideas, many players might find it interesting to play a reversed Sicilian Najdorf, Scheveningen, or Dragon system. Thus I decided to make a separate chapter and explain how to properly counter them. Luckily, Black is not under the pressure to get an advantage after the opening and nobody will complain if the arising position is equal. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ White can start with  3.a3  first to avoid any anti reversed Sicilian approaches with ...Bb4+ but that's not what I'm going to recommend here. }
3... Nc6
{ My goal with the course is to build a complete repertoire for Black against 1. c4 so that you can easily switch to familiar positions and can't be tricked with a different order of the moves. For example, if White would now continue with   4.Nc3  ,  that's the two knights variation from the later chapters of the course. You don't need to reinvent a bicycle and play two different systems against the same setup, played in a different order of the moves.   Note that  4.Nc3  will transpose to Chapter 15 and the other reversed Sicilians at White's disposal, having not played a3. }
4. a3
{ This is how normally reversed Sicilian Najdorf would start, but White can still choose e3 and Scheveningen setups. }
4... d5
{ The most principled approach and in the spirit of the entire course - Black is playing actively in the center. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Here White has two more choices - either play reversed Sicilian Scheveningen with e3, reversed Sicilian Najdorf with e4, or switch back to Dragon setups, making it essentially reversed Dragodorf. }
6. b4
{ This is the pawn push that Black always should be ready for - White is threatening to position the dark-squared bishop on b2 and with b5 pawn push challenges the well-being of the e5 pawn. However, so early in the game this push rarely works but still - I suggest keeping a close eye on it in the following moves. }
6... a5
{ Very principled and here it works best - this is a start of a little gambit. }
7. e4
{ This intermezzo is not to be missed but it changes little in Black's approach. }
7... Nb6 8. b5 Nd4 { This transposes to a covered line. } 9. Nxe5
{ Objectively not good but the point of the line is to illustrate what happens if White takes the pawn. }
9... Qf6
{ With the black knight on b6, this maneuver is very powerful - White doesn't have access to retreat with the knight to c4 anymore to sac the rook on a1 after the d4 knight is sacrificed to open the a1-h8 diagonal and try to capture the black queen with Bb2. }
10. f4
{ The only move not to lose material very quickly but now Black develops a deadly attack. }
10... Be6
{ Here Black has multiple threats - White is up a pawn but about to lose the entire game. }
