7... Nd4
{ The point of this jump is not to trade the e5 pawn for the b5 pawn but develop a very dangerous attack. Sometimes Black might take the b-pawn after all, but it's not a priority. }
8. Nxe5
{ Aslett,A-Hammond,A @@StartBracket@@2200@@EndBracket@@ Combined Services-ch 2002. Here Black could have continued with a much more energetic move. }
8... Bc5 9. e3
{ This is not mandatory but everything else looks just bad. After  9.Bb2  Black can include  9...Qh4  first, threatening with ...Ne3 and provoking  10.g3  to be played before retreating with the queen to f6 so that White has weakened the control of the f3 square. }
9... Qe7
{ Black's attack is so strong here that  9...O-O  sacrificing a piece followed by ...Re8 is also a good alternative. }
10. Nf3
{ This feels a little safer but also allows Black to create a strong pin. }
10... Bg4 11. Be2 Nxe2 12. Qxe2 O-O-O
{ Now White can't castle short due to ...Nf4 threat. Depending on the situation, some sacrificial ideas to e3 might work as well. }
