1. c4 e5 2. d3
{ Since English opening very often is reversed Sicilian with many copied ideas, many players might find it interesting to play a reversed Sicilian Najdorf, Scheveningen, or Dragon system. Thus I decided to make a separate chapter and explain how to properly counter them. Luckily, Black is not under the pressure to get an advantage after the opening and nobody will complain if the arising position is equal. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3
{ White can start with  3.a3  first to avoid any anti reversed Sicilian approaches with ...Bb4+ but that's not what I'm going to recommend here. }
3... Nc6
{ My goal with the course is to build a complete repertoire for Black against 1. c4 so that you can easily switch to familiar positions and can't be tricked with a different order of the moves. For example, if White would now continue with   4.Nc3  ,  that's the two knights variation from the later chapters of the course. You don't need to reinvent a bicycle and play two different systems against the same setup, played in a different order of the moves.   Note that  4.Nc3  will transpose to Chapter 15 and the other reversed Sicilians at White's disposal, having not played a3. }
4. a3
{ This is how normally reversed Sicilian Najdorf would start, but White can still choose e3 and Scheveningen setups. }
4... d5
{ The most principled approach and in the spirit of the entire course - Black is playing actively in the center. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Here White has two more choices - either play reversed Sicilian Scheveningen with e3, reversed Sicilian Najdorf with e4, or switch back to Dragon setups, making it essentially reversed Dragodorf. }
6. e4
{ Setup No.3 - the reversed Sicilian Najdorf. Typically White develops the bishops on e3 and e2 but not necessarily always pushes forward the d-pawn. The queenside knight can be developed to both c3 or d2, both with different ideas. }
6... Nb6
{ I chose this move because the arising setup is very similar to the reversed Dragon - the bishops will be positioned on e7 and e6. }
7. Be3
{ I think this move is mandatory in almost every set up so that's why I will start with it. White could start with  7.Be2  and O-O later, but the dark-squared bishop will land on e3 anyway. Positioning the dark-squared bishop on b2 would seem rather strange, especially since Black very often is happy to play ...f6 to strengthen the center. }
7... Be7
{ Here White has several choices:   8.b4   8.d4   8.Nc3   8.Nbd2  and   8.Be2  all of which are covered in this chapter. }
8. Nbd2
{ This continuation has some popularity among strong GMs, although mostly in blitz - White makes sure that Black's ...Bg4 is not a threat as the knight on f3 is supported by the other knight and Black can't easily neither trade the dark-squared bishop on e3 nor fight for the d4 square. }
8... O-O 9. Rc1
{ White still can't play  9.b4  because of the same  9...a5  10.b5  Nd4  11.Nxe5  and here the simple  11...Nxb5  works just fine, with a weak white pawn on a3 and the d4 square still under Black's control. }
9... a5
{ At some moment Black will have to play it as it eliminates White's option to play the active b4 pawn push pretty much forever and comes with an intention not only to gain space advantage at the queenside but also fix the b3 square as a weakness. In order not to mix up, when to push the a-pawn, watch for the movements of White's queenside knight. With the white knight on d2, nobody is bothering the b5 square thus ...a5 is simply good. With the white knight still on b1 or already on c3 the a-pawn's push might be premature as White could play Nc3-b5 and prepare to push d4. The b5 square would make a fine outpost for the knight.   Finally, Black is never afraid that White might trade the dark-squared bishop on e7 as the bishop is much more powerful and Black would gain complete control of the dark squares, most notably d4 and c5. }
10. Be2
{ With the black pawn on a5, it would take forever for White to rearrange the d2 knight via b1-c3 to b5, losing a lot of valuable time. }
10... a4
{ Black has a simple plan of ...Bf6 and either the light-squared bishop on e6 or try to reroute the queenside knight to d4 via d7-f8-e6, which is a very traditional maneuver. Black could have started with ...Bf6 first and avoid the possible exchange sacrifice but then after Nb3-c5 the bishop no longer is challenging the c5 square. }
11. Rxc6
{ This would be an interesting practical try and quite a common sacrifice in Sicilian Najdorf but with the weak pawn on b2, this is a risky choice. }
11... bxc6 12. Nxe5
{ Fedoseev,V @@StartBracket@@2678@@EndBracket@@ -Najer,E @@StartBracket@@2648@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com Titled Tuesday 2020. }
12... Qd6 13. Nec4 Qf6
{ Black is aiming for the weak b2 pawn. The other double pawn is irrelevant and White doesn't want to give up the dark-squared bishop easily. }
14. O-O Ba6 15. e5
{ Immediately  15.Bxb6  cxb6  16.Nxb6  is tempting but not good as Black can continue with  16...Qxb2!  sacrifice the exchange but completely dominate the queenside, and the a3 pawn is lost as well. }
15... Qe6 16. Bxb6
{ Black was already threatening to trade White's dark-squared bishop with ...Nd5. }
16... cxb6 17. Nxb6 Rab8 18. Nbc4 Bb5
{ Black is better and will rearrange the dark-squared bishop to g1-a7 diagonal. The white pawn on b2 is still weak. }
