{ I think that the trickiest move order for White is not defining the placement of the queenside knight thus Black can't play ...a5 just yet as the white knight might jump to c3-b5. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Be6
{ I believe that so far both sides have played out the best moves in the line and the time has come for White to define the placement of the queenside knight. }
10. Nbd2 a5
{ As soon as the white knight makes it to d2, that's a good moment to push the a-pawn. }
11. Nb3
{ Or   11.Rc1  and White is back to the ideas to sacrifice the exchange on c6 - Black can play ...Qd6 and protect the e5 pawn. White's Bc5 is tempting but Black's quite happy to trade the dark-squared bishops. }
11... a4 12. Nc5 Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Re8
{ Although White has managed to get the advantage of the bishop pair, Black controls the most important squares at the queenside and is about to reroute the b6 knight to f8. }
14. Rc1 Nd7 15. Be3 Nf8
{ As soon as the black knight will make it on e6, Black will be in total control of the surrounding squares. It's a good idea to keep an eye on the potential exchange sacrifices on c6 at any given moment - here it doesn't work due to ...Bb3 afterward. }
16. d4
{ Either White pushes the d-pawn at some moment, or what is he doing here? }
16... Bb3
{ This intermezzo initiates a lot of trades and Black comfortably equalizes the game. }
17. Qd3 exd4 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 { All of this is forced. } 19. Bxd4 Ne6
{ Even if White somehow manages to keep the two bishops, Black is very active and the bishop on b3 is stopping White from taking the d-file. }
20. Be3 c5 { Great positional sacrifice! } 21. Bxc5 Qxd3 22. Bxd3 Red8
{ The black rook inevitably penetrates the second rank, winning back the pawn. }
23. Bb5 Nxc5 24. Rxc5 Rd2
{ White's  25.Rb1  can be answered with  25...g6  to ensure that Black won't have any problems with the back rank, and only then ...Ba2. }
