{ My goal with the course is to build a complete repertoire for Black against 1. c4 so that you can easily switch to familiar positions and can't be tricked with a different order of the moves. For example, if White would now continue with   4.Nc3  ,  that's the two knights variation from the later chapters of the course. You don't need to reinvent a bicycle and play two different systems against the same setup, played in a different order of the moves.   Note that  4.Nc3  will transpose to Chapter 15 and the other reversed Sicilians at White's disposal, having not played a3. }
4. a3
{ This is how normally reversed Sicilian Najdorf would start, but White can still choose e3 and Scheveningen setups. }
4... d5
{ The most principled approach and in the spirit of the entire course - Black is playing actively in the center. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Here White has two more choices - either play reversed Sicilian Scheveningen with e3, reversed Sicilian Najdorf with e4, or switch back to Dragon setups, making it essentially reversed Dragodorf. }
6. e4
{ Setup No.3 - the reversed Sicilian Najdorf. Typically White develops the bishops on e3 and e2 but not necessarily always pushes forward the d-pawn. The queenside knight can be developed to both c3 or d2, both with different ideas. }
6... Nb6
{ I chose this move because the arising setup is very similar to the reversed Dragon - the bishops will be positioned on e7 and e6. }
7. Be3
{ I think this move is mandatory in almost every set up so that's why I will start with it. White could start with  7.Be2  and O-O later, but the dark-squared bishop will land on e3 anyway. Positioning the dark-squared bishop on b2 would seem rather strange, especially since Black very often is happy to play ...f6 to strengthen the center. }
7... Be7
{ Here White has several choices:   8.b4   8.d4   8.Nc3   8.Nbd2  and   8.Be2  all of which are covered in this chapter. }
8. Be2
{ I think that the trickiest move order for White is not defining the placement of the queenside knight thus Black can't play ...a5 just yet as the white knight might jump to c3-b5. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Be6
{ I believe that so far both sides have played out the best moves in the line and the time has come for White to define the placement of the queenside knight. }
10. Nc3
{ If the white knight goes to c3, Black can forget about playing ...a5 due to the weakened b5 square for the white knight. }
10... Bf6 { Black makes sure that White won't push d4 any time soon. } 11. a4
{ I think this is the most interesting attempt from White to provoke a mistake or at least a very committal move from Black. After everything else Black just plays ...Qd7 and plays some centralizing moves like ...Rad8 and ...Rfe8, preparing to play ...Nd4 at the right moment @@StartBracket@@which is not to be rushed@@EndBracket@@. White's Na4 Black happily trades. }
11... Nd4
{ Black answers a queenside attack with a counter-strike at the center. Probably   11...a6  is a reasonable alternative and after  12.a5  Nd7  the black knight can be rerouted to a more active square, like c5. }
12. a5
{ 12.Bxd4  might be also possible but after  12...exd4  13.Nb1  a5  Black's chances are not worse, rearranging the dark-squared bishop to b4. }
12... Nd7 13. Bxd4
{ After   13.a6  don't play the 'automatic'  13...b6  which weakens a lot of white squares at the queenside and can make the a6 pawn a real problem to deal with in an endgame, but the simple 13...bxa6, seeking a counterplay at the queenside and the b-file. }
13... exd4 14. Nb5 c5 15. Nd2
{ White is planning to rearrange the knight from b5 to c4, trade the light-squared bishops via g4, and play for a pawn majority on the kingside, leaving Black with the bad dark-squared bishop. }
15... c4
{ Nice way to stop White's plan - Black temporarily sacrifices a pawn. This idea in this pawn structure might not always work, but it's good to know it. }
16. Nxc4 { 16.dxc4  a6  looks the same, but with a worse outcome for White. }
16... Bxc4 17. dxc4 Nc5 { Black inevitably wins back the sacrificed pawn. } 18.
Bd3 a6 { Start of a forced sequence. } 19. Na3 Qxa5 20. Nc2 Qb6 21. b4 Nxd3 22.
Qxd3 Qc7
{ Black has enough counterplay against the c4 pawn and should be satisfied with the outcome after the opening. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Reversed Sicilian with 2.d3"]
[Black "Chapter 2 Exercise: #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1ppq2pp/2n1bp2/p1bnp3/8/3P1NP1/PP1BPPBP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. Rxc5
{ White has just executed a traditional idea via either the e4 or a4 square - knight jump on c5. What is the best setup for Black here? }
13... b6
{ It's important to play this before White has managed to double the heavy pieces at the c-file. }
14. Rc1 Na7
{ Black is about to play ...c5 and set up the Maroczy Bind. At the same time Black keeps vacant the e7 square, should White consider a counter-attack in the center with e4 and d4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Reversed Sicilian with 2.d3"]
[Black "Chapter 2 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k2r/4qppp/2P5/ppbn4/3n2b1/P2PP3/3N1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. Qxg4
{ Another gambit - Black has played out the opening very aggressively and is punishing White for the materialistic approach. Find a forced win! }
13... Nc2+ 14. Ke2
{ 14.Kd1  Ncxe3+  This is the key idea - instead of taking the white rook on a1 Black is looking for more. }
14... f5
{ A stunning sight - the white queen is trapped in the middle of the board! Both black knights can deliver a fork. }
15. Qh5+ { The best hope - after  15.Qg3  Bd6  the result will be the same. }
15... g6 16. Qh6 { The white queen has seemingly escaped...has it? } 16...
Ncxe3 17. fxe3 Bxe3 { Not really - Black has hunted down the white queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Reversed Sicilian with 2.d3"]
[Black "Chapter 2 Exercise: #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/ppp1bppp/2n1b3/3n4/3p4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10. Nb5
{ White just pushed forward the d-pawn and intends to recapture it with a knight and thus try to trade Black's light-squared bishop for a knight. What trick should you know here? }
10... d3
{ A great idea - Black gives up the d-pawn on his terms and secures the d4 square. }
11. Qxd3 Ncb4 12. Qb1 c5
{ The light-squared bishop has avoided the trade and remains one of the strongest pieces on the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Early g3: 3.d4 without Qb3"]
[Black "2.g3 Nf6 (What NOT to do)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3
{ This move has slowly but steadily become one of the most popular continuations against the Reversed Sicilian in the English opening. White fianchettos the bishop on g2 to fight for the center but most importantly - delays the standard knight's development to c3. The reason for that in the line of  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  there is a very popular continuation  3...Bb4  and often trade the knight on c3. This often leads to a Sicilian Rossolimo with colors reversed and pretty much simple setups for Black. With the knight still on b1, this plan is now impossible, and playing Bb4 anyway will just look silly but just like for every plan, there is a setback - Black can immediately set a strong claim for the center with an aggressive play with the pawns. I would like to mention that with the early g3 being played it's impossible to go for the immediate ...d5 and ...Bc5 setups, as recommended in later chapters as White will not allow it. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 Bc5
{ Black might try to insist on the four knights set up with a later ...d5. } 4.
Nc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 d5
{ The problem here is that it just doesn't work because of a simple refutation. }
6. Nxe5
{ With the pawn on  e5  and bishop on  c5  , this is just a standard motif to destroy Black's center.  6.cxd5  Nxd5  would just transpose to some familiar lines, covered in this course. }
6... Nxe5 7. d4 { Black has lost the battle for the center. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Early g3: 3.d4 without Qb3"]
[Black "3.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3
{ This move has slowly but steadily become one of the most popular continuations against the Reversed Sicilian in the English opening. White fianchettos the bishop on g2 to fight for the center but most importantly - delays the standard knight's development to c3. The reason for that in the line of  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  there is a very popular continuation  3...Bb4  and often trade the knight on c3. This often leads to a Sicilian Rossolimo with colors reversed and pretty much simple setups for Black. With the knight still on b1, this plan is now impossible, and playing Bb4 anyway will just look silly but just like for every plan, there is a setback - Black can immediately set a strong claim for the center with an aggressive play with the pawns. I would like to mention that with the early g3 being played it's impossible to go for the immediate ...d5 and ...Bc5 setups, as recommended in later chapters as White will not allow it. }
2... c6
{ Simple and straightforward - before developing any pieces Black immediately sets a strong claim for the center. I find this move to be more precise than the immediate 2...Nf6, followed by ...c6 later as in the arising setups, it's not always a good idea to have the early knight on f6, as it allows quick Bg5 pin ideas. }
3. e4
{ There have been some attempts to play this move to slow down Black's intentions to grab the center but it doesn't work. }
3... d5 4. cxd5
{ I don't think it matters in which order White takes the pawns. } 4... cxd5 5.
exd5 Qxd5
{ Black has a great game here and it is White who needs to play accurately not to get into trouble because of the weak d-pawn. }
6. Nf3 Bg4 7. Be2 Nc6 { Black is continuing normal development } 8. Nc3 Qd7
{ Now black probably should castle short - long castle may be slightly risky. }
*

