[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Early g3: 3.d4 without Qb3"]
[Black "4.a3: (What NOT to do)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3
{ This move has slowly but steadily become one of the most popular continuations against the Reversed Sicilian in the English opening. White fianchettos the bishop on g2 to fight for the center but most importantly - delays the standard knight's development to c3. The reason for that in the line of  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  there is a very popular continuation  3...Bb4  and often trade the knight on c3. This often leads to a Sicilian Rossolimo with colors reversed and pretty much simple setups for Black. With the knight still on b1, this plan is now impossible, and playing Bb4 anyway will just look silly but just like for every plan, there is a setback - Black can immediately set a strong claim for the center with an aggressive play with the pawns. I would like to mention that with the early g3 being played it's impossible to go for the immediate ...d5 and ...Bc5 setups, as recommended in later chapters as White will not allow it. }
2... c6
{ Simple and straightforward - before developing any pieces Black immediately sets a strong claim for the center. I find this move to be more precise than the immediate 2...Nf6, followed by ...c6 later as in the arising setups, it's not always a good idea to have the early knight on f6, as it allows quick Bg5 pin ideas. }
3. d4
{ This is one of the most challenging approaches - before fianchettoing the bishop on g2 White tries to undermine Black's ambition in the center. White is ready to recapture the pawn on d4 with the queen and create an isolated pawn for Black on d5. While it's possible, there's something better. }
3... e4
{ Black immediately sets claim for the space advantage. The pawn on  e4  can be annoying for White because of several reasons. First, it doesn't give the white kingside knight an easy way into the game, and second - it blocks the traditional panoramic views for the bishop on g2. Now it will have to stare at the black pawn in close vicinity. White here has two major choices - either allow Black to play  ...d5  next and then challenge the center with everything he's got or stop it before happening with either  4.d5   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2p5/8/2PPp3/6P1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qa4  All continuations have been analyzed in this course. }
4. a3
{ This is another interesting rare move with some venom - White stops any ...Bb4 lines for good and is ready to waste a tempo for it. }
4... d5 5. Nc3 Nf6
{ This slight inaccuracy was allowed in the 2020 Prague Masters game between David Navara and Nikita Vitiugov, but the Czech GM missed it. }
6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. cxd5 { Fixing the pawn on d5. } 7... cxd5 8. Qa4
{ The pawn on d5 and the bishop's pin on g5 are starting to feel uncomfortable. }
8... Qb6 { This is already the only move. } 9. Qb5 a6 { The lesser evil. } 10.
Qxb6 Nxb6 11. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Black is left with doubled pawns while White can make a very nice outpost on f4 for his knight. While Black is still solid and it's not easy for White to make considerable progress here, White's position is to be preferred. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Early g3: 3.d4 without Qb3"]
[Black "4.a3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3
{ This move has slowly but steadily become one of the most popular continuations against the Reversed Sicilian in the English opening. White fianchettos the bishop on g2 to fight for the center but most importantly - delays the standard knight's development to c3. The reason for that in the line of  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  there is a very popular continuation  3...Bb4  and often trade the knight on c3. This often leads to a Sicilian Rossolimo with colors reversed and pretty much simple setups for Black. With the knight still on b1, this plan is now impossible, and playing Bb4 anyway will just look silly but just like for every plan, there is a setback - Black can immediately set a strong claim for the center with an aggressive play with the pawns. I would like to mention that with the early g3 being played it's impossible to go for the immediate ...d5 and ...Bc5 setups, as recommended in later chapters as White will not allow it. }
2... c6
{ Simple and straightforward - before developing any pieces Black immediately sets a strong claim for the center. I find this move to be more precise than the immediate 2...Nf6, followed by ...c6 later as in the arising setups, it's not always a good idea to have the early knight on f6, as it allows quick Bg5 pin ideas. }
3. d4
{ This is one of the most challenging approaches - before fianchettoing the bishop on g2 White tries to undermine Black's ambition in the center. White is ready to recapture the pawn on d4 with the queen and create an isolated pawn for Black on d5. While it's possible, there's something better. }
3... e4
{ Black immediately sets claim for the space advantage. The pawn on  e4  can be annoying for White because of several reasons. First, it doesn't give the white kingside knight an easy way into the game, and second - it blocks the traditional panoramic views for the bishop on g2. Now it will have to stare at the black pawn in close vicinity. White here has two major choices - either allow Black to play  ...d5  next and then challenge the center with everything he's got or stop it before happening with either  4.d5   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2p5/8/2PPp3/6P1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qa4  All continuations have been analyzed in this course. }
4. a3
{ This is another interesting rare move with some venom - White stops any ...Bb4 lines for good and is ready to waste a tempo for it. }
4... d5 5. Nc3 Be7
{ Since the bishop can't make it to b4 anymore, e7 is the alternative. This is an important order of the moves as the immediate and more logical Nf6 is a slight inaccuracy. }
6. Bg2
{ White is planning to play f3 next to challenge the center. Now that the knight on c3 is unchallenged, the pressure increases against the central pawns. But let's not forget that it took White a whole tempo to achieve it. It's probably worth mentioning that the immediate   6.cxd5  cxd5  7.Qb3  will be met with the typical  7...Nc6!  and Black is doing great, and the inclusion of the a3 move doesn't help White here.  If White challenges the center with   6.Qb3  without trading the pawns on d5, almost always Black can play  6...dxc4  7.Qxc4  Be6  and protect the e4 pawn with ...f5. }
6... Nf6 7. Bg5
{ White can try to challenge the pawn on d5 by trading off the knight on f6, continuing with cxd5 and Qb3 next but it's relatively easy to parry. }
7... Nbd7
{ The second knight is ready to substitute the knight on f6, should a trade happen. }
8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3
{ A curious moment - White is not threatening Nxd5 as Black will win some material with ...Qa5+! }
9... h6
{ For the sake of simplicity, it's a good idea to find out what White is up to. }
10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. Nh3 b6 { Black is just in time to protect the pawn on d5. }
12. Nf4 Bb7 13. f3
{ Here it's a good idea to avoid taking on f3, which would allow White to recapture the pawn with the bishop and win the pawn on d5. }
13... Bd6 { Black wants to take on f4 with a solid position. } *

