{ Since the bishop can't make it to b4 anymore, e7 is the alternative. This is an important order of the moves as the immediate and more logical Nf6 is a slight inaccuracy. }
6. Bg2
{ White is planning to play f3 next to challenge the center. Now that the knight on c3 is unchallenged, the pressure increases against the central pawns. But let's not forget that it took White a whole tempo to achieve it. It's probably worth mentioning that the immediate   6.cxd5  cxd5  7.Qb3  will be met with the typical  7...Nc6!  and Black is doing great, and the inclusion of the a3 move doesn't help White here.  If White challenges the center with   6.Qb3  without trading the pawns on d5, almost always Black can play  6...dxc4  7.Qxc4  Be6  and protect the e4 pawn with ...f5. }
6... Nf6 7. f3
{ 7.Nh3  is hardly a serious option as after  7...h6  to stop Bg5 and Nf4 afterward White will never have time to play cxd5 and Qb3. In this scenario Black always will have the typical Nc6, targeting the pawn on d4, but an early Qb3 without including cxd5 again will allow dxc4 and the white queen will be misplaced on c4. }
7... exf3 8. Nxf3 O-O { Black plays simple and solid. } 9. O-O h6
{ A good positional move that stops any threats of Bg5, trade the knight on f6 and targets the pawn on d5, but also prepares to play Be6 to strengthen the center, so that White has no Ng5. }
10. cxd5
{ If White will play   10.Nh4  immediately without taking on d5 first then Black should respond with  10...dxc4!  11.e4  c5!  and because of the knight's untimely voyage to the edge of the board, the temporary loss of the e5 square control is critical.  12.d5  Bd6  and Black blocks White's central pawns. }
10... cxd5 11. Nh4 Nc6 12. Nf5 Be6
{ We're still following the game between Navara - Vitiugov to the letter, except for the minor inaccuracy in the beginning. Black is very solid. }
13. g4 Re8 { Black is slowly preparing the jump ...Ne4. } 14. Nxe7+ Nxe7 15. g5
{ 15.Bxh6  would be met by  15...Nxg4 } 15... hxg5 16. Bxg5 Nh7
{ This is a temporary retreat - the knight won't stay on h7 forever. } 17. Bh4
Qd7 { Black removes the pin, created by White's dark-squared bishop. } 18. e3
Nf5 19. Qe1 Nf8 { Now the knight is rerouted to a more active square. } 20. Rd1
Ng6
{ Navara,D @@StartBracket@@2717@@EndBracket@@-Vitiugov,N @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@ Prague Masters 2nd 2020, with an excellent game for Black. }
