{ If White wants to play  f3  , this trade has to be included, otherwise  8.f3  will be met with  8...exf3  and 9...dxc4 next.   After  8.Qb3   or  8.Qa4  Black can already safely take on c3 as after bxc3 Black can castle short and not worry about Ba3 cutting off his king. }
8... cxd5 9. f3
{ This was played in a game between two grandmasters @@StartBracket@@Miezis,N @@StartBracket@@2477@@EndBracket@@-Hector,J @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ Swedish Team championship 2019@@EndBracket@@, where Black could have improved his game. }
9... O-O 10. Nf2
{ If White is ready to position his knight so passively, it's okay to take on f3 as the knight from the f2 square can't challenge the pawn on d5. }
10... exf3 11. Bxf3
{ 11.exf3  Nc6  and Black is simply better as it still hasn't taken c3 and probably shouldn't anymore as there's no need. }
11... Nc6 12. e3 Bf5
{ White is solidly worse because it has no serious pressure against the d5 pawn and Black comfortably controls the e4 square. }
13. Nd3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Be4
{ Nailer,A @@StartBracket@@1778@@EndBracket@@-Delchev,A @@StartBracket@@2596@@EndBracket@@ Ordu open 2nd 2016, Black went on to win the game by dominating the light squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Early g3: 3.d4 without Qb3"]
[Black "4.Nc3, 5.Bg2, 6.Nh3: #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3
{ This move has slowly but steadily become one of the most popular continuations against the Reversed Sicilian in the English opening. White fianchettos the bishop on g2 to fight for the center but most importantly - delays the standard knight's development to c3. The reason for that in the line of  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.g3  there is a very popular continuation  3...Bb4  and often trade the knight on c3. This often leads to a Sicilian Rossolimo with colors reversed and pretty much simple setups for Black. With the knight still on b1, this plan is now impossible, and playing Bb4 anyway will just look silly but just like for every plan, there is a setback - Black can immediately set a strong claim for the center with an aggressive play with the pawns. I would like to mention that with the early g3 being played it's impossible to go for the immediate ...d5 and ...Bc5 setups, as recommended in later chapters as White will not allow it. }
2... c6
{ Simple and straightforward - before developing any pieces Black immediately sets a strong claim for the center. I find this move to be more precise than the immediate 2...Nf6, followed by ...c6 later as in the arising setups, it's not always a good idea to have the early knight on f6, as it allows quick Bg5 pin ideas. }
3. d4
{ This is one of the most challenging approaches - before fianchettoing the bishop on g2 White tries to undermine Black's ambition in the center. White is ready to recapture the pawn on d4 with the queen and create an isolated pawn for Black on d5. While it's possible, there's something better. }
3... e4
{ Black immediately sets claim for the space advantage. The pawn on  e4  can be annoying for White because of several reasons. First, it doesn't give the white kingside knight an easy way into the game, and second - it blocks the traditional panoramic views for the bishop on g2. Now it will have to stare at the black pawn in close vicinity. White here has two major choices - either allow Black to play  ...d5  next and then challenge the center with everything he's got or stop it before happening with either  4.d5   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2p5/8/2PPp3/6P1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qa4  All continuations have been analyzed in this course. }
4. Nc3
{ The most popular response - White targets the pawn on e4 and allows Black to play d5 so that the pawn can become a target. Since White has supposedly wasted a tempo for g3 which doesn't help for this pawn setup, Black has more than enough resources to defend his center properly. }
4... d5
{ The logical follow-up - the pawn on e4 needs a proper backup and Black's pieces now freely come into play. }
5. Bg2
{ The main move - White is undecided yet if he wants to take on d5 and pressure the pawn with Qb3, or continue with the f3 push or play Nh3. The way I see it, here are two types of positions - if White plays Qb3 and if he doesn't. On most occasions, White's play will be tied with the f3 thrust anyway to activate the bishop on g2. Taking this into account, I decided to split everything into two chapters - After ...d5, should White play Qb3 or Qa4, or keep the queen on d1? Everything related to the queen's jump to either b3 or a4 is covered in the next chapter. }
5... Bb4
{ This is not the most popular move but from my perspective - the strongest and exactly by this order of the moves. Let me stop here for a moment and explain to you where the game is heading. The main reason why I'm suggesting playing ...Bb4 instead of the more traditional ...Nf6 is the various pin ideas with the bishop on g5. I concluded that they can be easily mixed up as White can play out the opening with a different order of the moves and you might meet Bg5 at any given moment.   The text move is much simpler and if given a possibility, Black will simply play ...h6 first before playing ...Nf6 in order not to worry about the Bg5 move and White will have to decide - what to do with his dark-squared bishop. There will be occasions when Black will have to play ...Nf6 after all and allow White to play Bg5, but those will come with some concessions from White's side, usually having included an early f3. With the bishop on b4, the core idea is to relieve some pressure against the d5 and e4 pawns, and in general Black is just happy to take on c3. Of course, by doing so it's important not to miss the incoming Ba3 so that the black king doesn't get stuck in the center. After a castle, it's already not dangerous. If White is to play f3, most often Black doesn't take on f3 himself not to increase pressure against the d5 pawn but waits for White to take on e4 himself, to be recaptured with a pawn. There will be some exceptions to this rule, as you will see later. If White is forced to recapture on f3 with a pawn, that's not dangerous for Black. }
6. Nh3 { The main move - White takes care of the development first. } 6... h6
{ It's a little paradoxical to spend a tempo for such a seemingly strange move before continuing development but the idea is quite clear - Black doesn't want any business with Bg5 and thus secures the center. Also on some occasions, ... h6 will be a great move as after the typical Nf4 Black will often think about. ..g5 to push the knight away from the center, sometimes back to the corner, and the pawn on g5 will be already protected. }
7. O-O { White finishes his kingside development and intends to play f3. } 7...
Nf6 8. cxd5
{ If White wants to play  f3  , this trade has to be included, otherwise  8.f3  will be met with  8...exf3  and 9...dxc4 next.   After  8.Qb3   or  8.Qa4  Black can already safely take on c3 as after bxc3 Black can castle short and not worry about Ba3 cutting off his king. }
8... cxd5 9. f3
{ This was played in a game between two grandmasters @@StartBracket@@Miezis,N @@StartBracket@@2477@@EndBracket@@-Hector,J @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ Swedish Team championship 2019@@EndBracket@@, where Black could have improved his game. }
9... O-O 10. Nf4
{ White could try to increase the pressure against the d5 pawn before committing to a pawn trade on e4 and taking away from Black the opportunity to include ...Bxh3. }
10... Nc6
{ The most active and logical move, counter-striking against the d4 pawn, should White take on e4. White has hardly anything better, otherwise Black is already thinking about taking on c3 and continuing with Bf5, keeping firm control of the e4 square. }
11. fxe4 { 11.Qb3  would just transpose to one of the covered lines. } 11...
dxe4
{ There is no need to rush with the trade on c3 although the idea is always in the air. In general, it's a good idea to keep this option flexible as circumstances might change and Black might consider retreating with the bishop to d6 at some point. }
12. e3
{ This seems to be necessary as   12.d5  would meet  12...Qb6+  ,  followed by ...Bxc3 and ...Ne5, blocking the c4 square. }
12... Bg4
{ Black is continuing the development - if necessary, be ready to sacrifice the pawn on e4 for an initiative. Black is also looking for a good moment to take on c3 to proceed with ...Na5-c4. }
13. Qc2 Rc8
{ Black's moves are very easy - the pawn on e4 can't be taken with the knight because of the ...Nxd4 and a discovered attack against the queen while taking with the bishop allows a tactic with the same ...Nxd4. In any situation, White shouldn't be interested to trade his light-squared bishop just to win the pawn on e4 as it would forever weaken the white monarch's position. }
14. h3
{ This allows Black to go for a nice positional sacrifice, gaining an outpost on e4. }
14... Bf3 15. Bxf3 exf3 16. Rxf3
{ The pawn on f3 can't be tolerated and has to be accepted. } 16... Bxc3 17.
bxc3 Re8
{ Black gains complete control over the e4 square, which can be accompanied by the c4 square at the queenside. Black's compensation for the pawn is more than sufficient. }
*

