Nf6 8. cxd5
{ If White wants to play  f3  , this trade has to be included, otherwise  8.f3  will be met with  8...exf3  and 9...dxc4 next.   After  8.Qb3   or  8.Qa4  Black can already safely take on c3 as after bxc3 Black can castle short and not worry about Ba3 cutting off his king. }
8... cxd5 9. f3
{ This was played in a game between two grandmasters @@StartBracket@@Miezis,N @@StartBracket@@2477@@EndBracket@@-Hector,J @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ Swedish Team championship 2019@@EndBracket@@, where Black could have improved his game. }
9... O-O 10. fxe4
{ The critical move - White wants to clarify the situation in the center before sending his knight to either f4 or f2. Here Black has a very nice choice so I'll present to you both of them. I'm not sure which of them is better so I'll leave that choice up to you. }
10... Bxc3
{ Black makes preparations to occupy the e4 square - the knight on c3 must go. }
11. bxc3
{ There's no place for fancy tricks with  11.e5  as Black can calmly respond with  11...Bxd4+  12.Qxd4  Nc6  and the pawn on e5 is about to be lost. }
11... Bxh3
{ Black removes the bishop from g2 from its outpost and also makes sure that the knight from h3 won't target the center. }
12. Bxh3 Nxe4
{ This is the critical moment of the entire line so I'll explain what both sides want to achieve. Black is dreaming to block both e4 and c4 squares with his knights and absolutely won't mind if one of them will be traded for the light-squared bishop, as long as the control over the squares remains. Probably that is not going to happen and White will push c4. This opens another outpost on d5 which Black would like to use.   Either way, in any of the scenarios Black's dream position is to have a knight on an outpost against the bad dark-squared bishop. In the meantime, White is dreaming about crashing through in the center, play c4 and trade that pawn on d5, then somehow get rid of the knight at e4 by the means of Rf4, Bg2, or similar maneuvers and push e4. Having that achieved, it's safe to say that White will obtain a huge advantage, as the powerful center will be supported by bishops on b2 and g2. Black will have to stop it. }
13. Qb3
{ This is an alternative square for the white queen, targeting both d5 and b7 pawns. Black should be very quick here and go for that blockade. }
13... Nc6 14. Rf5
{ 14.Qxb7  wins a pawn but after  14...Na5  ,  followed by ...Nc4, Black has reached his dream position, even if it cost a pawn. Under the particular circumstances, the extra pawn on c3 doesn't feel to be important and what matters is the might of the two knights at their outposts. The same ...Na5 maneuver refutes 14.Ba3 and Black can continue to play 15...Re8 next, not worrying about losing any material. }
14... Qb6
{ A cool move - Black is ready to sacrifice the pawn on d5 but exchange it for c3, d4, and e2 pawns. }
15. Bb2
{ Taking on b6 doesn't achieve anything, and Black will continue with ...Na5-c4. }
15... Rad8 16. Bg2 Rfe8
{ Black first defends the outpost on e4 and prepares ...Na5-c4. } 17. Raf1 Qxb3
{ Otherwise, White might continue with Qc2, sacrifice the rook on d5, and recapture on e4 with the bishop for a very unclear position. }
18. axb3 Rd7
{ Black still has the ...Na5 threat, playing for the blockade. The knight from e4 can always return to f6 if the center feels vulnerable. White will need to be very creative to bring his bishops to life. }
