{ The way I see it, this is the most logical move - White protects the c4 pawn and is ready to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
15... b5
{ An aggressive way to gain control of the d5 square but perhaps it's not mandatory. The problem with the more positional   15...b6  and threatening ...Ba6 is that after  16.Bd2  the knight has to retreat to b7, which also might be playable. }
16. cxb5
{ This is seemingly forced otherwise White has already lost the battle against the blockade. Here White at least has a pawn for it. }
16... a6 { Black is playing a gambit. } 17. a4 Qd5
{ It should be apparent that Black has very active pieces, the center is closed and the question remains - how important is this extra pawn? }
18. Rb1 axb5 19. axb5
{ or   19.Qxb5  Be6  and the pawn on a4 shouldn't hold for long  while the logical   19.Rxb5  meets a sad end after  19...Ba6! }
19... Be6
{ Black is thinking about either ...Nc4-d6 or ...Nb7-d6 and storming the queenside with ... Ra2. }
20. Bd2 Nc4
{ Black's activity should give him enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
21. Bb4 Qxb5
{ Probably it's necessary otherwise there might not be another chance to take the pawn. }
22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. Bxe4 Bd5
{ The extra pawn on e3 doesn't feel to be significant. } 24. Bd3 Qc6
{ Freeing from the pin and preparing to play ...Rxe3 next move. } 25. Rbc1
{ The pin looks deadly but in reality, the game just simplifies to a draw.  25.e4  is an interesting attempt but after  25...Bxe4  26.Bxc4  Bxb1  27.Bxf7+  Kh8  the game liquidates into a draw.   It's Black who might think about something more after a very interesting exchange sacrifice  25...Rxe4!?  and play for an initiative. }
25... Rxe3 26. Qxe3 Nxe3 27. Rxc6 Bxc6
{ White's bishop pair doesn't matter anymore - the position has simplified too much and Black looks very solid. }
