[Round "?"]
[White "3. Early g3: 3.d4 without Qb3"]
[Black "Chapter 3 Exercise: #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk1nr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/1bPPp3/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

6. f3 { What is one of the core ideas that Black always should know here? }
6... Nf6
{ Don't take on f3 yourself! This would allow White to take the pawn with the knight and eventually increase pressure against the d5 pawn. The trade is possible at some point later, but immediately it favors White. }
7. Bg5 Nbd7
{ The same principle - the pawn on e4 is protected due to tactical tricks. } 8.
cxd5 cxd5 9. fxe4 dxe4 10. Bxe4 { This is a mistake - what's the refutation? }
10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qa5
{ Black wins back the pawn with a positional interest. } 12. Bxf6 Qxc3+
{ Intermezzo check! } 13. Kf2 Nxf6
{ Black has a huge advantage due to the exposed white king. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Early g3: 3.d4 without Qb3"]
[Black "Chapter 3 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp3pp1/2p2n1p/3p4/1bPPp3/2N3PN/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

8. f3
{ White is back at the idea of pushing the f-pawn but now it can't recapture with a knight. Did White forget something? }
8... exf3 9. Rxf3 dxc4
{ Usually White includes the c-pawn trade before pushing the f-pawn, otherwise, this move is something that White will have to anticipate. }
