[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Early g3: 3.d4 with Qb3"]
[Black "5.cxd5: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5
{ This early capture has been tested also at a 2700 level but ultimately it can't cause Black any problems if he's aware of it and knows the most accurate continuation and it is White who will have to be careful. This allows Black to early develop his queenside knight to c6. }
5... cxd5 6. Qb3
{ If not Qb3, then it remains an open question, why did White take on d5 in the first place, allowing Black to early position his queenside knight on the active c6 square. }
6... Nc6
{ A counter-attack but also an important accuracy as the most logical  6...Nf6  would run into  7.Bg5  and Black is struggling to defend the d5 pawn. }
7. Qxd5
{ This is quite forced as  7.e3  would allow Black to comfortably finish the development with  7...Nf6   and a nice space advantage, and, of course,  7.Nxd5??  drops a piece because of  7...Be6 }
7... Qxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd4
{ A little comical situation - both sides can execute a fork and win a rook, thus other factors come into play as well. The black pawn on e4 slows down White's development at the kingside. }
9. Kd1
{ White might try to stop the fork and threaten with his own but comparing White's efforts, Black doesn't have to do it with the king. }
9... Bd6 10. Bf4 Be6
{ A little trick to get rid of the knight on d5 and the awkward position of White's king on d1 will start to be felt. }
11. Bxd6 Bxd5 12. e3 Nc6
{ Black will continue with ...f5 and ...Nf6 with an excellent game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Early g3: 3.d4 with Qb3"]
[Black "5.cxd5: #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5
{ This early capture has been tested also at a 2700 level but ultimately it can't cause Black any problems if he's aware of it and knows the most accurate continuation and it is White who will have to be careful. This allows Black to early develop his queenside knight to c6. }
5... cxd5 6. Qb3
{ If not Qb3, then it remains an open question, why did White take on d5 in the first place, allowing Black to early position his queenside knight on the active c6 square. }
6... Nc6
{ A counter-attack but also an important accuracy as the most logical  6...Nf6  would run into  7.Bg5  and Black is struggling to defend the d5 pawn. }
7. Qxd5
{ This is quite forced as  7.e3  would allow Black to comfortably finish the development with  7...Nf6   and a nice space advantage, and, of course,  7.Nxd5??  drops a piece because of  7...Be6 }
7... Qxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd4
{ A little comical situation - both sides can execute a fork and win a rook, thus other factors come into play as well. The black pawn on e4 slows down White's development at the kingside. }
9. Nc7+ Kd8 10. Bf4
{ White could delay taking the rook for one reason - so that the check on c2 can be answered by Kd2, supposedly improving the king's position. In reality, it just comes under ...Bb4+. }
10... Nc2+ 11. Kd2 Nxa1 12. Nxa8
{ So far everything's the same as in the mainline of this variation and Black should continue in the same manner. }
12... Be6 13. b3 Bb4+ 14. Kc1
{ This is forced as the king can't go forward. Now Black will go after the knight on a8. }
14... Nf6 15. Nc7 Bd7
{ Black shouldn't allow the knight to escape. Eventually, both knights who managed to create forks and win rooks in the process, will be eliminated and Black will be left with a space advantage, mostly because of the pawn on e4. }
16. e3 Ke7 17. Kb2 Rc8
{ While Black is a little late to recapture the knight, White can't exploit it as his entire kingside stands still. }
18. Kxa1 Ba5
{ Black will recapture the missing piece and is better due to the space advantage and better development. }
