1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5
{ This early capture has been tested also at a 2700 level but ultimately it can't cause Black any problems if he's aware of it and knows the most accurate continuation and it is White who will have to be careful. This allows Black to early develop his queenside knight to c6. }
5... cxd5 6. Qb3
{ If not Qb3, then it remains an open question, why did White take on d5 in the first place, allowing Black to early position his queenside knight on the active c6 square. }
6... Nc6
{ A counter-attack but also an important accuracy as the most logical  6...Nf6  would run into  7.Bg5  and Black is struggling to defend the d5 pawn. }
7. Qxd5
{ This is quite forced as  7.e3  would allow Black to comfortably finish the development with  7...Nf6   and a nice space advantage, and, of course,  7.Nxd5??  drops a piece because of  7...Be6 }
7... Qxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd4
{ A little comical situation - both sides can execute a fork and win a rook, thus other factors come into play as well. The black pawn on e4 slows down White's development at the kingside. }
9. Nc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 Nc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1
{ Here White has a little choice - either try to escape the knight from a8, go for the knight on a1, or perhaps do both. }
12. Be3
{ This is very tempting but objectively - bad. From afar it looks logical - White is attacking the pawn on a7 and after b6 is ready to sacrifice the knight on b6 for two pawns and then just go after the knight on a1. }
12... Be6 { Yet another counter-strike! } 13. b3
{ This logical move loses by force as for Black it's much easier to include all pieces into the game than for White. }
13... Nxb3 14. axb3 Bxb3+ { This is a forced sequence. } 15. Kc1 Ba3+ 16. Kd2
{ Solak,D @@StartBracket@@2567@@EndBracket@@-Volokitin,A @@StartBracket@@2645@@EndBracket@@ Slovenian Team championship 2006. }
16... Nf6
{ More precise than what was played in the game - Black finishes the development. }
17. Bxa7 Ke7
{ White has no time to escape with the knight because the rook and the two bishops will either create a mating net around the white king or White will suffer big additional material losses. }
18. Nb6 { or  18.Nc7  Rd8+  19.Kc3  Ba4!  with huge threats of Rd1 and Rc8. }
18... Bb4+ 19. Kc1 Bc3
{ Black is threatening the inevitable ...Rd8 and either ...Rd1 or ...Rd2-a2-a1. Notice how powerless are those white light pieces at the queenside! }
20. Bg2 Rd8 21. Nh3 Rd2
{ Rook and two bishops make a very deadly combination! } *

