{ This is quite forced as  7.e3  would allow Black to comfortably finish the development with  7...Nf6   and a nice space advantage, and, of course,  7.Nxd5??  drops a piece because of  7...Be6 }
7... Qxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd4
{ A little comical situation - both sides can execute a fork and win a rook, thus other factors come into play as well. The black pawn on e4 slows down White's development at the kingside. }
9. Nc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 Nc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1
{ Here White has a little choice - either try to escape the knight from a8, go for the knight on a1, or perhaps do both. }
12. b3
{ The direct approach to capture the knight doesn't give results as Black will eventually trade the knight for one pawn while the knight on a8 can't do the same. }
12... Nf6 13. Bb2 Nxb3 14. axb3 Be6
{ While at the moment Black is down a piece, the second pawn on b3 is under attack, but the knight on a8 is lost by force. }
15. Kc2 Bd6 { Black captures the stranded knight on a8. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Early g3: 3.d4 with Qb3"]
[Black "5.cxd5: #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5
{ This early capture has been tested also at a 2700 level but ultimately it can't cause Black any problems if he's aware of it and knows the most accurate continuation and it is White who will have to be careful. This allows Black to early develop his queenside knight to c6. }
5... cxd5 6. Qb3
{ If not Qb3, then it remains an open question, why did White take on d5 in the first place, allowing Black to early position his queenside knight on the active c6 square. }
6... Nc6
{ A counter-attack but also an important accuracy as the most logical  6...Nf6  would run into  7.Bg5  and Black is struggling to defend the d5 pawn. }
7. Qxd5
{ This is quite forced as  7.e3  would allow Black to comfortably finish the development with  7...Nf6   and a nice space advantage, and, of course,  7.Nxd5??  drops a piece because of  7...Be6 }
7... Qxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd4
{ A little comical situation - both sides can execute a fork and win a rook, thus other factors come into play as well. The black pawn on e4 slows down White's development at the kingside. }
9. Nc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 Nc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1
{ Here White has a little choice - either try to escape the knight from a8, go for the knight on a1, or perhaps do both. }
12. Bf4
{ Not obvious but this might be the best move for White where he manages to keep an equal game. }
12... Be6 13. b3
{ This is necessary, otherwise the black knight easily makes it back in the game. }
13... Nxb3
{ As you'll see in several variations, this is quite a thematic sacrifice in this line. The black knight was in danger anyway so Black trades it for two pawns and goes for the a8 knight. }
14. axb3 Bxb3+ 15. Kc1
{ 15.Kd2  Bb4+  would just gift Black an important tempo. } 15... Ba3+ 16. Kb1
Ne7
{ Black prepares to play ...Kd7 next and win the knight. White has only one move here. }
17. e3
{ Here the tempting   17.Nc7  would be a mistake - after  17...Bc4!  The light-squared bishop not only imprisons the knight on c7 but also pins White's entire kingside. The knight on c7 will be lost, as soon as the bishop on f4 will be dealt with. }
17... g5
{ The most precise move - Black wins back the sacrificed material by force as the bishop leaves the guarded c7 square for the knight on a8 to escape. }
18. Be5
{ This leads to some very beautiful lines where White will be completely paralyzed, even though enjoying some extra material. }
18... f6 19. Bxf6 { Otherwise ...Kd7 is next. } 19... Rf8 20. Bxg5 Rxf2
{ Black wins due to the incredible piece activity plus there are some mating ideas as well. }
21. Be2
{ 21.Ne2  Bc4  allows Black to immediately recapture the sacrificed piece. }
21... Bd6 { Black makes sure that White doesn't play Bf4. } 22. g4 Kc8 23. Bh4
Rg2 { White can't get rid of this annoying rook! } 24. Bg3 Bxg3 25. hxg3 Nd5
{ Again, above all - piece activity and centralization. The knight on a8 can wait. }
26. g5
{ The last trick - White has prepared to meet  26...Kb8  with  27.g6!  and mate threat Rh8! }
26... a5 { White will lose more material soon. } *

