18. Bxg5 Kd7
{ Now the knight is trapped so White must make haste to recapture the second pawn for the lost piece in order not to get into greater trouble. }
19. Bh3+ Be6 20. Bxe6+ fxe6
{ Of course, not  20...Kxe6  as  21.Nc7+  and the prisoner escapes. } 21. Bxe7
Bxe7
{ White will finish the development and recapture the pawn on e4 but after winning the knight on a8 Black is left with a strong bishop and connected passed pawns at the queenside which should be carefully pushed forward. This is how it was played out in the only correspondence game in the line. }
22. Ne2 Rxa8 23. Rd1+ Ke8 24. Rd4 Rd8
{ Not mandatory but forcing the matters a little. Black could have opted also to keep rooks in the game. }
25. Rxe4 Rd2 26. Nf4 Rxf2 27. Rxe6 Kf7
{ White still needs to be accurate to hold the draw as his kingside pawns are more vulnerable than Black's queenside pawns, plus the white king is cut off. }
28. Rh6 Kg7 29. Rh5 h6 30. Rd5
{ 1/2-1/2 De Bari,V @@StartBracket@@2373@@EndBracket@@-Penafiel Lopez,J  @@StartBracket@@2350@@EndBracket@@ Rochade 20 years email 2009. White managed to escape with a draw. }
