[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Early g3: 3.d4 with Qb3"]
[Black "5.Nh3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Nh3
{ This is a very tricky order of the moves with a considerable venom - before starting a normal development White is threatening to challenge Black's center immediately. }
5... Bb4 6. Qb3
{ White has intentions to pressure the center by withholding the Bg2 for the time being. }
6... a5
{ Black defends the bishop and waits for White to play a3 to take on c3 and play ...a4, not to allow White's dark-squared bishop to land on a3. The reason why here ...a5 is better than the traditional retreat of the bishop to a5 is that because of the early jump Nh3 White has an access to a quite annoying 7.Bg5, causing some considerable disruption in Black's plans. Otherwise ...Ba5 is the standard response. }
7. Bg2
{ Paradoxically this option here is available, although Black can play ...dxc4 and White can't recapture it. Here White apparently can sacrifice the pawn on c4, even if it cost him a tempo. }
7... dxc4 8. Qc2 f5
{ Black simply protects the pawn on e4. Accepting the 2nd pawn is a risky choice -   8...Qxd4  9.O-O  Nf6  10.Ng5  is much less clear although it also could be playable. I don't think that this entire line can be dangerous for Black but I'd like to point out a couple of interesting moments. }
9. a3 Bxc3+
{ The safest choice, which not only gives Black an easy game but also is played in the spirit of this entire course.   9...Be7  allows some weirdness after  10.d5!  Nf6  11.Be3  Nxd5  12.O-O-O!  with Nf4 and g4 ideas. When I had a look at these lines, I thought that Daniil Dubov as Tal of modern times would approve. }
10. Qxc3 Nf6
{ Trying to keep the pawn can backfire as it loses valuable time - Black should just finish the development and control the d5 outpost. The immediate and tempting  10...Be6  runs into the  11.d5  idea and the pawn on g7 is unprotected. }
11. Qxc4 Qe7 12. Bg5 Be6
{ That's it - Black has got an excellent game with an easily executable plan. }
13. Bxf6
{ otherwise ...Nbd7 will follow and after the trade, Black will already recapture with the other knight. }
13... Qxf6 14. Qc3 O-O
{ Black is looking towards creating an outpost on d5 but one little final nuance. }
15. Nf4 Bf7
{ This bishop is too precious to be traded away just like that - most likely White will have to waste a tempo on h4 anyway to keep the knight on f4, and in the meantime, the black knight will find its way to d5. }
*

