1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Nh3
{ This is a very tricky order of the moves with a considerable venom - before starting a normal development White is threatening to challenge Black's center immediately. }
5... Bb4 6. Qb3
{ White has intentions to pressure the center by withholding the Bg2 for the time being. }
6... a5
{ Black defends the bishop and waits for White to play a3 to take on c3 and play ...a4, not to allow White's dark-squared bishop to land on a3. The reason why here ...a5 is better than the traditional retreat of the bishop to a5 is that because of the early jump Nh3 White has an access to a quite annoying 7.Bg5, causing some considerable disruption in Black's plans. Otherwise ...Ba5 is the standard response. }
7. cxd5
{ In most occasions relieving the pressure in the center is the best approach for White as Black almost always is threatening with ...dxc4 and ...Be6 next. Here, however, things are slightly different. The immediate  7.a3  here would be just a loss of time because of the same  7...dxc4   while  7.c5  would release any tension from the center and leave Black in complete control at the kingside. }
