[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Early g3: 3.d4 with Qb3"]
[Black "5.Nh3: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Nh3
{ This is a very tricky order of the moves with a considerable venom - before starting a normal development White is threatening to challenge Black's center immediately. }
5... Bb4 6. Qb3
{ White has intentions to pressure the center by withholding the Bg2 for the time being. }
6... a5
{ Black defends the bishop and waits for White to play a3 to take on c3 and play ...a4, not to allow White's dark-squared bishop to land on a3. The reason why here ...a5 is better than the traditional retreat of the bishop to a5 is that because of the early jump Nh3 White has an access to a quite annoying 7.Bg5, causing some considerable disruption in Black's plans. Otherwise ...Ba5 is the standard response. }
7. cxd5
{ In most occasions relieving the pressure in the center is the best approach for White as Black almost always is threatening with ...dxc4 and ...Be6 next. Here, however, things are slightly different. The immediate  7.a3  here would be just a loss of time because of the same  7...dxc4   while  7.c5  would release any tension from the center and leave Black in complete control at the kingside. }
7... cxd5 8. Bg2
{ White rushes with castling short so that the pawn on d5 becomes vulnerable. }
8... Nc6
{ Because the c-pawns have been traded, Black has gained access to the c6 square for his queenside knight, challenging the white pawn on d4. }
9. Nf4 Nf6
{ Capturing the central pawn with  9...Nxd4  immediately is not good because of  10.Qd1  and the pawn on d5 will fall, and thus the e4 pawn loses its support. }
10. O-O
{ Vishnu, P @@StartBracket@@2518@@EndBracket@@ -Kohlweyer, B @@StartBracket@@2404@@EndBracket@@ Gibraltar Masters 14th 2016 and in the game was played  10...Nxd4?!  which allowed White to continue  11.Qd1  Bxc3  12.bxc3  and the dark-squared bishop lands on a3 with a great position for White. }
10... a4 11. Nxa4
{ This is pretty much forced, otherwise after  11.Qd1  Black would continue with  11...Qa5  intending to play ...a3 next with a strong grip at the queenside. }
11... Qa5
{ Start of a forced sequence, promising Black a good game. The engines here like also  11...g5  ,  which leads to quite an unclear game. The white knight is sent back to its prison at h3 but the black king is weakened in the process. }
12. Nc3 Nxd4 13. Qd1 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Ne6
{ Accepting a second pawn on c3 is risky because of Rb1 and Bb2 threat. Trust your instincts. }
15. Be3 O-O 16. Qd2 Bd7
{ Black has two potential weaknesses in the position - pawns on d5 and b7 and both of them will be protected by the bishop on c6. Black can organize a counterplay either against White's c3 or a2 pawns by doubling the rooks at the a-file. }
