{ White has intentions to pressure the center by withholding the Bg2 for the time being. }
6... a5
{ Black defends the bishop and waits for White to play a3 to take on c3 and play ...a4, not to allow White's dark-squared bishop to land on a3. The reason why here ...a5 is better than the traditional retreat of the bishop to a5 is that because of the early jump Nh3 White has an access to a quite annoying 7.Bg5, causing some considerable disruption in Black's plans. Otherwise ...Ba5 is the standard response. }
7. cxd5
{ In most occasions relieving the pressure in the center is the best approach for White as Black almost always is threatening with ...dxc4 and ...Be6 next. Here, however, things are slightly different. The immediate  7.a3  here would be just a loss of time because of the same  7...dxc4   while  7.c5  would release any tension from the center and leave Black in complete control at the kingside. }
7... cxd5 8. Bg2
{ White rushes with castling short so that the pawn on d5 becomes vulnerable. }
8... Nc6
{ Because the c-pawns have been traded, Black has gained access to the c6 square for his queenside knight, challenging the white pawn on d4. }
9. O-O
{ This is the most precise move in White's arsenal, keeping an option to play Bg5, should Black play ...Nf6. }
9... Nge7
{ It's best to include this move first before attempting to take the pawn on d4. If White is a little slow with his decisions, Black might think about ideas such as ...h5!? to open the h-file and not to castle at all. }
10. Nf4 Nxd4
{ Start of a forced sequence where White sacrifices a pawn for enough compensation but not more than that. }
11. Qd1 Bxc3
{ This is an important intermezzo move, otherwise, the d5 pawn falls immediately and with it the e4 pawn. }
12. bxc3 Ne6 13. c4
{ The only try to get something out of this otherwise dry position. } 13...
Nxf4 14. Bxf4 O-O
{ White will recapture the pawn eventually but Black has nothing to worry about, except playing it out accurately in the next couple of moves. }
15. Rb1 Re8
{ There's no need to rush with ...dxc4 - the rook on e8 joins the game and is indirectly defending the e4 pawn. }
16. Qc2 Bg4
{ Not only Black is targeting the e2 pawn but also provoking White to play h3 which might be used as a tempo for the attack later. }
17. h3
{ It seems that it is useful for White to include this move to relieve some pressure against the e2 pawn but it also weakens the h3 pawn in the process. }
17... Bf5 18. Rxb7 Ng6
{ If White has included  h3  , this is the best move here.  18...Qc8  ,  unfortunately, doesn't work because of  19.Rc7  ,  otherwise that would have been a great idea. }
19. Rb5 Nxf4 20. gxf4 Qc8
{ Thanks to the white pawn on h3, Black holds the balance. } 21. Rxd5 Bxh3
{ The game once again liquidates into an equal position. } *

