[White "4. Early g3: 3.d4 with Qb3"]
[Black "5.Bg2: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2
{ In this chapter we will examine various possibilities that are at White's disposal, should he at some point play Qb3 or Qa4, after Black has already played ...d5. }
5... Bb4 6. Qb3 Ba5
{ If here White will continue with   7.Nh3  ,  it will just transpose to the mainline, where White has an option to include either 8.Qb3 or at some point later. Instead of focusing on development White might try to challenge the center immediately. }
7. cxd5
{ 7.f3  immediately is not good because yet again with the queen on b3 and the pawn standing on c4 Black can continue with  7...dxc4!  8.Qxc4  b5!  and White needs to be careful about the pawn on d4.  9.Qc5  Ne7!  and White must tread carefully as he's not ready to open the center. }
7... cxd5 8. f3
{ The rule for Black remains - just don't take on f3 as White will recapture with the knight and the pressure against the d5 will build up quickly. Let White take on e4 himself. }
8... Nf6 9. Bg5
{ If   9.fxe4  then of course  9...dxe4  ,  not to allow the white knight to land on f3. The knight on e4 might not hold for long. }
9... O-O 10. e3 Nbd7
{ Black brings a substitute for the knight on f6 and ...h6 to follow the next move. }
11. Ne2
{ The pawn on e4 is taboo -   11.fxe4  dxe4  12.Bxe4  Qe8!  and after the following ...h6 and Bxf6, Black will have the intermezzo Qxe3+. }
11... h6 12. Bxf6
{ The bishop on f4 has no perspectives thus the trade is almost forced. } 12...
Nxf6 13. O-O
{ 13.fxe4  suddenly meets an unexpected resource  13...Ng4!  and the pawn on e3 is incredibly difficult to defend unless White is looking for suicide with Kd2. }
13... exf3
{ It's time to clarify the situation a little - this move is not forced but Black has enough resources to protect the d5 square now, and the bonus is the newly founded e4 outpost. }
14. Rxf3 Be6 15. Nf4
{ It makes a lot of sense for White to pressure the d5 pawn.   15.Qxb7  would win a pawn but after  15...Rb8  16.Qxa7  Rxb2  Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn, the white queen is in danger and the white knights are tied. }
15... Bxc3
{ The bishop on a5 has outlived its usefulness and thus it's a good time to trade it, especially since the other knight on e2 is not ready to replace it on c3. Black gains access to the e4 square and has diminished pressure against the d5 pawn. }
16. Nxe6 { Otherwise ...Bf5 and ... Be4 might become a problem real soon. }
16... fxe6 17. Qxc3 Rc8
{ The game is just equal, even the pawn structure is the same. } *

