1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2
{ In this chapter we will examine various possibilities that are at White's disposal, should he at some point play Qb3 or Qa4, after Black has already played ...d5. }
5... Bb4 6. Qa4
{ This is quite a tricky move - White is threatening with cxd5 as there's a pin at the a4-e8 diagonal. Luckily there's a simple solution to this which starts with the trade on c3. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nd7
{ Black is threatening with ...Nb6 so White has to do something about the c4 pawn. }
8. c5
{ It looks tempting to claim the d6 square for the dark-squared bishop but Black is still ahead in development and has a nice reply against Bd6. }
8... Ngf6 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Bd6 Re8 11. e3
{ the position looks alright for White, even though his light squares are begging for some attention. Here, however, Black also has a powerful solution against the bishop on d6. }
11... b5 12. Qc2
{ of course, the pawn can't be taken because of ... Nxb6 and the bishop on d6 hangs. }
12... Nb6 { This should come to White as a cold shower! } *

