1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2
{ In this chapter we will examine various possibilities that are at White's disposal, should he at some point play Qb3 or Qa4, after Black has already played ...d5. }
5... Bb4 6. Bf4
{ White might include at some point Bf4, but on most occasions, it's not clear what is its role there. Here it comes with a specific threat - snatch a pawn on a7. }
6... Nf6
{ Since the dark-squared bishop has already landed on f4, there's no need for ...h6 anymore. }
7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Bxb8
{ 8.Qa4+  attacks the bishop with a check, but Black has  8...Nc6  This is why White eliminates the knight first which forces Black to include Bxc3. }
8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Rxb8 10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qxa7 O-O
{ White has managed to win a pawn, but at a too great cost - White is behind in development for at least 3 tempi. }
