1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2
{ In this chapter we will examine various possibilities that are at White's disposal, should he at some point play Qb3 or Qa4, after Black has already played ...d5. }
5... Bb4 6. Nh3 h6 7. Qa4
{ This would be another attempt to make the pin from a4-e8 diagonal to work, this time including moves Nh3 and ...h6. Black's response is the same. }
7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nd7 9. cxd5
{ The only difference here is that after  9.c5  with an idea to secure the d6 square for White's dark-squared bishop it's best to respond with  9...Ne7  so that the bishop's outpost on d6 can be challenged with a later ...Nf5. }
9... Nb6 10. Qb3 cxd5 11. f3
{ Again, sooner or later White will return to the idea of challenging the center with the f3 push as after  11.Ba3  Black can calmly respond with  11...Nc4  and trade-off the bishop on a3. }
11... Nf6 12. Ba3
{ Developing the dark-squared bishop here immediately without trading the pawns on e4 leads to a forced sequence. }
12... Nc4
{ 12...e3  might be an alternative but the consequences are less clear. } 13.
fxe4 Ne3
{ The point - suddenly for White, it's not so easy to defend his kingside pieces. }
14. Nf4
{ Here  14.Kf2  leaves Black with a very pleasant position after  14...Nxg2  ,  followed by ...Bxh3+, ...Qd7+, ...Nxe4 and castling long. }
14... g5
{ This forces White to sacrifice the piece which with a perfect play should lead to a perpetual check in the end. The position is a complete mess now! }
15. Nxd5 Nxg2+ 16. Kf2 Nxd5 17. exd5
{ Taking with the queen on d5 doesn't look like an alternative as Black will happily trade queens and play ...Bh3 afterward, and block either the e-pawn with ...f5 or c-pawn with ...Rc8. }
17... Bh3
{ The dust has slightly settled - Black has an extra piece for two pawns, and both kings are exposed. White has to take the pawn on b7 as there is nothing better. }
18. Qxb7 Qf6+ 19. Kg1 Rc8
{ Bringing the rook into the game. All of the lines lead to a perpetual check, either delivered by White or Black. }
20. Rf1 Nf4
{ The knight is taboo as it would open the g-file and White is about to be mated with ...Rg8+. }
21. Rf3
{ The difference between playing Rf3 or Rf2 here is that Rf3 stops the mating ideas with ...Nxe2+ and ...Qf1#. So after  21.Rf2  Kd8!  Black is winning as White has no time to execute the Bb4-a5 threat as Black is about to play ...Nxe2, and then there's the ...Rxc3 threat as well. }
21... Rxc3
{ The only move for Black - the rook can't be taken, because  22.Rxc3  would be the same mate threat of  22...Nxe2  Black is also threatening with ... Qxd4+. Now the question is, who will force the perpetual.   @@StartFEN@@4k2r/pQ3p2/5q1p/3P2p1/3P1n2/B1r2RPb/P3P2P/6KR w k - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Qb8+  Bc8  23.gxf4   or  23.Qb5+  Bd7  24.Qb8+  and a draw immediately.   But  23.Rxc3  loses because of mate in two after  23...Nh3+  and ...Qf2. Here Black does need to know a couple of only moves.  @@StartFEN@@1Qb1k2r/p4p2/5q1p/3P2p1/3P1P2/B1r2R2/P3P2P/6KR b k - 0 23@@EndFEN@@  23...Qxd4+  24.Kg2  gxf4  opening the g-file for the kingside rook.  25.Rxc3  Rg8+  a very important check!  26.Rg3  White shields from the check with his extra rook and it seems that Black has miscalculated...  26...Qxd5+!  But in reality Black is just delivering a perpetual check - the rook on g3 can't be recaptured immediately because the bishop on c8 is hanging.  27.Kg1  Qd1+  28.Kg2  Qd5+  If the White king will go to f2, the rook on g3 can be taken with a check. If you and your opponent made it this far - hug as you deserve it as an excellent memory. }
