1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2
{ In this chapter we will examine various possibilities that are at White's disposal, should he at some point play Qb3 or Qa4, after Black has already played ...d5. }
5... Bb4 6. Nh3 h6 7. Qa4
{ This would be another attempt to make the pin from a4-e8 diagonal to work, this time including moves Nh3 and ...h6. Black's response is the same. }
7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nd7 9. cxd5
{ The only difference here is that after  9.c5  with an idea to secure the d6 square for White's dark-squared bishop it's best to respond with  9...Ne7  so that the bishop's outpost on d6 can be challenged with a later ...Nf5. }
9... Nb6 10. Qb3 cxd5 11. f3
{ Again, sooner or later White will return to the idea of challenging the center with the f3 push as after  11.Ba3  Black can calmly respond with  11...Nc4  and trade-off the bishop on a3. }
11... Nf6 12. fxe4
{ White is opening the position for his bishops and targeting the center. }
12... dxe4 { Again, this is a principled approach to close the bishop on g2. }
13. Nf2
{ Here   13.Ba3  would be not so good, mainly because of the unfortunate placement of the white queen in the particular position. Black can play  13...Be6  and win a crucial tempo to block those central pawns, followed by either ...Qd7 or ...Nc4, depending on what White will respond. }
13... O-O
{ There's no time to protect the pawn on e4 but this is quite a thematic pawn sacrifice. }
14. Nxe4
{ The way White has played out this line, this seems to be almost mandatory otherwise Black will just protect the pawn on e4 and block the central c4 and d5 squares with his light pieces. }
14... Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Re8
{ Black has excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn and a strong initiative. }
16. Qc2 Bh3
{ Black imprisons the white king in the center - the pawn on b7 doesn't play any role. }
17. Bxb7 Nd5 18. c4
{ Already the only move   18.Bxa8  would be close to suicide as after the simple  18...Qxa8  ,  followed by ...Bg4, Black's attack is overwhelming. }
18... Nb4 19. Qc3 Qe7 20. Bf3 Bg2
{ A great resource - the bishop can't be taken because of the mate on e2 and Black is also threatening to trade the bishops and deliver a fork on c2. White has the only move here. }
21. Ba3 Bxf3
{ An alternative to continuing the attack here is  21...a5  with intentions to trade the light-squared bishops and continue with ...Ra6-f6. }
22. O-O Bxe2 23. Bxb4 Qc7
{ White's position is not fun. Black will recapture the pawn on c4 with the bishop and try to keep the queens and at least one pair of rooks on the board. With such an exposed king, White has a long and difficult defense ahead. }
