1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2
{ In this chapter we will examine various possibilities that are at White's disposal, should he at some point play Qb3 or Qa4, after Black has already played ...d5. }
5... Bb4 6. Nh3 h6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nf4
{ This is a slightly dubious alternative plan, pressuring the d5 pawn - the white knight on f4 won't hold for long. }
8... O-O 9. Qb3
{ If   9.f3  here then Black can easily hold the pawn on e4 with  9...Re8  10.fxe4  dxe4  with a great position and even a choice should Black take on c3 because the pawn on e4 already is well protected and the bishop might be needed for something else. Now Black's reply is forced.  The same would happen if White had included   9.cxd5  first, but on that occasion, there would be an extra c6 square for the knight, later to be rerouted to c4 square. }
9... Bxc3 10. bxc3
{ The way White played it, this is the logical choice but in reality, it's bad. White's dreaming about fighting the center and activating his bishops but in reality, he's in trouble because of the unfortunate placement of the knight. From afar it may be far from obvious.   10.Qxc3  would allow the simple  10...dxc4  and Black enjoys a better position because of the outpost on d5, which can be taken care of with ...Nb8-d7-b6-d5. }
10... g5 { The white knight is forced to go back! } 11. Nh3 dxc4
{ Now Black wins a couple of critical tempos. } 12. Qxc4 Be6 13. Qb4 Qd7
{ This forces White to sacrifice the knight for two pawns which is not enough to be sufficient compensation. }
14. Nxg5 hxg5 15. Bxg5 Nh7
{ White will manage to win the third pawn for the piece but in the middlegame, a piece always will be superior to three pawns. }
16. Bh6 Re8 17. Bxe4 Bd5
{ The game is already entering a technical phase with Black seeking ways to convert his extra piece. }
