1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2
{ In this chapter we will examine various possibilities that are at White's disposal, should he at some point play Qb3 or Qa4, after Black has already played ...d5. }
5... Bb4 6. Nh3 h6 7. Qb3
{ This maneuver, if executed, makes the most sense here. Black doesn't want to take on c3 just yet as this will make the Ba3 threat real. }
7... Ba5
{ I find this move in the particular line to be more precise than   7...a5  as after a couple of forced moves Black will be forced to take on c3 and then the a5 will have created a weakness on b5. How important is it, that is difficult to tell. }
8. cxd5
{ like I explained elsewhere, this trade will have to happen sooner or later as there will be a time that Black's ...dxc4 will cause White some real headaches. }
8... cxd5 9. O-O Nf6
{ Now that Black is ready to castle short, it's also time to take on c3 as Ba3 won't be a problem. }
10. Nf4
{ 10.f3  will allow Black to include  10...Nc6  and White will need to defend the pawn on d4 first. }
10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O
{ Black has the traditional plans to dominate the light squares. White here has two plans - either push f3 and play something similar to the main lines where Qb3 has been included, or try to resurrect the dark-squared bishop with c4. }
12. f3 Nc6
{ Like in other lines, Black is not interested to take on f3 himself to activate the bishop on g2. }
13. fxe4 dxe4
{ Black's plan traditionally is to block the white squares while White is looking for ways to activate his bishops. }
