{ 10.f3  will allow Black to include  10...Nc6  and White will need to defend the pawn on d4 first. }
10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O
{ Black has the traditional plans to dominate the light squares. White here has two plans - either push f3 and play something similar to the main lines where Qb3 has been included, or try to resurrect the dark-squared bishop with c4. }
12. c4
{ This leads to very sharp lines as White will have to sacrifice his knight on f4. }
12... dxc4 13. Qxc4 g5
{ Black is asking a very direct question - what is White going to do about this knight? }
14. Nh3
{ This doesn't feel right as White is losing two tempos by sending back the knight to the awkward h3 square and Black already controls the d5 square as a blockade. }
14... Nc6 15. Bb2
{ The tempting   15.Nxg5  doesn't work here because of  15...hxg5  and 16...Qd5 next, removing the pin. }
15... Na5
{ Mostly with an idea to push away the queen and make sure that a thematic d5 pawn sacrifice to open the dark-squared bishop doesn't come in with a tempo. Plus, there's a potential outpost on c4! }
16. Qc2 Bf5 { White is in trouble. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Early g3: 3.d4 with Qb3"]
[Black "5.Bg2: #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2
{ In this chapter we will examine various possibilities that are at White's disposal, should he at some point play Qb3 or Qa4, after Black has already played ...d5. }
5... Bb4 6. Nh3 h6 7. Qb3
{ This maneuver, if executed, makes the most sense here. Black doesn't want to take on c3 just yet as this will make the Ba3 threat real. }
7... Ba5
{ I find this move in the particular line to be more precise than   7...a5  as after a couple of forced moves Black will be forced to take on c3 and then the a5 will have created a weakness on b5. How important is it, that is difficult to tell. }
8. cxd5
{ like I explained elsewhere, this trade will have to happen sooner or later as there will be a time that Black's ...dxc4 will cause White some real headaches. }
8... cxd5 9. O-O Nf6
{ Now that Black is ready to castle short, it's also time to take on c3 as Ba3 won't be a problem. }
10. Nf4
{ 10.f3  will allow Black to include  10...Nc6  and White will need to defend the pawn on d4 first. }
10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O
{ Black has the traditional plans to dominate the light squares. White here has two plans - either push f3 and play something similar to the main lines where Qb3 has been included, or try to resurrect the dark-squared bishop with c4. }
12. c4
{ This leads to very sharp lines as White will have to sacrifice his knight on f4. }
12... dxc4 13. Qxc4 g5
{ Black is asking a very direct question - what is White going to do about this knight? }
14. f3
{ White solves his positional problems with a tactical solution. In any case, for the sacrificed material White has perhaps a sufficient compensation, but not more. }
14... gxf4 15. fxe4 Nc6
{ Black is also racing to finish the development otherwise the attack could become overwhelming. }
16. Rxf4
{ This allows Black to simplify the position to a much better endgame by sacrificing the piece back. }
16... b5
{ As you will see, this tempo will be important later. The knight on c6 can't be taken because of 17... Qxd4+ and White loses material. }
17. Qc3 Qxd4+
{ Only now comes the trade - after a forced sequence Black gets a big advantage in the endgame. }
18. Qxd4 Nxd4 19. Rxf6
{ White has regained the sacrificed piece but that's part of Black's plan. }
19... Nxe2+ 20. Kf2 Nxc1 21. Rxc1 Be6
{ White's a-pawn is a big weakness that can be quickly targeted by black rooks. The pawn on h6 is insignificant and doesn't play any role. Notice how including b5 has helped Black to win a critical tempo. }
*

