16. d5
{ Strictly speaking, the only move as in the alternative lines White is suffering in the endgames as the queen's get traded off immediately. }
16... Qb6+
{ An important order of the moves - Black is going to play ...Ne5 next but with this order, the text move takes away from White the opportunity to play Qd4, then trade queens and claim a powerful pawn center for the sacrificed piece. }
17. Kh1 Ne5 18. Qc3 Re8
{ Up to this moment it's forced - the other continuations are not as good. }
19. gxf4 Neg4
{ Black is threatening with ...Nf2+. You shouldn't mind sacrificing back the extra piece, as long as you get a good game. }
20. h3 { 20.Bb2  here is too slow and allows  20...Bd7  and ...Rc8 next. }
20... Nxe4 { The game will liquidate to an equal position very quickly. } 21.
Bxe4 Rxe4 22. Bb2 f6 { Closing the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. }
23. hxg4 Bxg4 24. Rg1 h5
{ As it happens, the white king is more exposed to incoming threats so White will need to be a little careful here. With perfect play, it should end in a draw though. }
