[Black "6.Qb3 and 7.Qxb7: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Qa4
{ This very rare move at a GM level was first played in the 2019 FIDE World Cup but it looks very interesting and also is supported by the chess engines. I separated it into a separate chapter because it doesn't fall into any other categories and has its own pace and ideas. White is stopping Black's idea to play the quick ...d5 as there's a potential pin at the a4-e8 diagonal and intends to target the pawn on e4 very quickly. I decided to offer you a fresh gambit approach, promising Black excellent chances to fight for the win, first championed by GM Anish Giri! I won't be surprised if it will become a popular line! }
4... d5
{ I was considering offering Black a more peaceful alternative with  4...f5  either immediately or a couple of moves later by including ...Na6, which has been played twice in correspondence chess, however, I came to realize that after  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.Bg5  ,  followed by e3, White's game is very pleasant and much easier to play. }
5. cxd5 Bd7
{ The immediate pawn capture  5...Qxd5  is no good as after  6.Nc3  White wins several important tempos, landing Black into a bad position. The idea behind Black's last move is to sell a pawn to win several extra tempos to take over the initiative. It's almost impossible to predict every single continuation that is at White's disposal but I will try to cover most of them and explain the core ideas that Black should know.   Either way, please don't expect Black to win on the spot - this is a pawn sacrifice to help Black to accelerate his development and take over the initiative. The entire line should stand the test of time and practice. }
6. Qb3
{ This is a second alternative to 6.dxc6 - this gives White a choice to take either the pawn on d5 or b7 but mostly the arising positions and plans for Black are quite similar to already covered lines. }
6... cxd5
{ Now White has a little choice. I think he has to accept one of the pawns, otherwise, the entire strategy of playing Qa4 and then Qb3 looks just weird. }
7. Qxb7 { This is a little more forcing. } 7... Nc6 8. Bh3
{ White has to do this in order not to miss any tactical ideas which lead White to big material losses. }
8... Bxh3 9. Qxc6+
{ From a strategic point of view this is a very risky approach - it's not clear how White is going to complete his development at the queenside, not even speaking about the safety of the king. }
9... Bd7 10. Qxd5
{ White has managed to win the second pawn but at a great price. } 10... Nf6
11. Qe5+ Be7
{ Black's advantage in development plus White's completely stalled kingside is more than enough to claim a great compensation for the sacrificed material. }
12. Nc3 O-O 13. Nxe4 { The third pawn is the charm! } 13... Bc6 14. f3 Nxe4 15.
fxe4 Bb4+ { Black has a winning attack. } *

