{ This is a second alternative to 6.dxc6 - this gives White a choice to take either the pawn on d5 or b7 but mostly the arising positions and plans for Black are quite similar to already covered lines. }
6... cxd5
{ Now White has a little choice. I think he has to accept one of the pawns, otherwise, the entire strategy of playing Qa4 and then Qb3 looks just weird. }
7. Qxb7 { This is a little more forcing. } 7... Nc6 8. Bh3
{ White has to do this in order not to miss any tactical ideas which lead White to big material losses. }
8... Bxh3 9. Nxh3 Nxd4
{ The engines slightly prefer  9...Bb4+  with ...Nge7 continuing development and keeping the pawn on d4 intact, but I think the text move is simpler and promises Black a great game as well. }
10. Kf1
{ White might want to keep his pawn on e2 but then Black just continues with normal development. }
10... Bc5 11. Kg2 Ne7
{ Here the black knight on e7 feels better as any Bg5 pin ideas to pressure the pawn on d5 can be calmly refuted with a simple ...f6 push. There's also an unusual idea to trap the queen! Immediately it wouldn't work as after  11...a6  White has  12.Bg5!  and there is no  12...f6  because of  13.Qxg7 }
12. Qa6 Qd7 13. Nc3 O-O
{ Black has nothing to worry about here and it's White who needs to be accurate to hold the balance. }
*

