{ White still needs to understand if the second pawn is up for grabs. This leads to a forced sequence where Black is down two pawns and the queens get traded but the compensation is enormous. }
10... Nc6
{ Be a little careful here - the previously mentioned idea of  10...Bc6  doesn't work now as after  11.Qb3  there's no  11...e3  as White captures the pawn with a check! }
11. Bh3
{ This defensive resource is common in many lines and thus not to be missed for Black. }
11... Rb8 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 14. Bc3 Nb4
{ All of this is forced. Black should be able to recapture one pawn back pretty quickly while still enjoying a good compensation for the second missing pawn. }
15. Kd1 Nbd5
{ Black has multiple threats, most notably - White is risking to get into a total zugzwang! }
16. e3 Ng4 17. Nh3
{ Not a great post for the knight but the alternatives don't look great. }
17... Rhc8
{ Most of White's pieces are tied down and can't move so White should try to give away something to breathe a little. }
18. Nd2 f5
{ Simple and strong - there's no need to rush but the pawn on e4 is important for Black. }
19. Rc1 Ba3
{ While it's possible to continue the positional pressure with other moves like ...a5 or expand at the kingside, this might be a good moment to force things. }
20. Nb3 Nxc3+ 21. Rxc3 Bxb2 22. Rxc8 Rxc8
{ White will have to give up the second pawn with  23.Nc5+  Kd6  24.Ke2  Ba3  ,  because the alternative looks worse. }
23. Kd2 Ba3
{ White is again in a zugzwang because of the weak h2 and f2 pawns but the queenside is vulnerable because of the ...a5-a4 threat. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Early g3: 3.d4 and 4.Qa4"]
[Black "6.Qb3 and 7.Qxd5: #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. Qa4
{ This very rare move at a GM level was first played in the 2019 FIDE World Cup but it looks very interesting and also is supported by the chess engines. I separated it into a separate chapter because it doesn't fall into any other categories and has its own pace and ideas. White is stopping Black's idea to play the quick ...d5 as there's a potential pin at the a4-e8 diagonal and intends to target the pawn on e4 very quickly. I decided to offer you a fresh gambit approach, promising Black excellent chances to fight for the win, first championed by GM Anish Giri! I won't be surprised if it will become a popular line! }
4... d5
{ I was considering offering Black a more peaceful alternative with  4...f5  either immediately or a couple of moves later by including ...Na6, which has been played twice in correspondence chess, however, I came to realize that after  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.Bg5  ,  followed by e3, White's game is very pleasant and much easier to play. }
5. cxd5 Bd7
{ The immediate pawn capture  5...Qxd5  is no good as after  6.Nc3  White wins several important tempos, landing Black into a bad position. The idea behind Black's last move is to sell a pawn to win several extra tempos to take over the initiative. It's almost impossible to predict every single continuation that is at White's disposal but I will try to cover most of them and explain the core ideas that Black should know.   Either way, please don't expect Black to win on the spot - this is a pawn sacrifice to help Black to accelerate his development and take over the initiative. The entire line should stand the test of time and practice. }
6. Qb3
{ This is a second alternative to 6.dxc6 - this gives White a choice to take either the pawn on d5 or b7 but mostly the arising positions and plans for Black are quite similar to already covered lines. }
6... cxd5
{ Now White has a little choice. I think he has to accept one of the pawns, otherwise, the entire strategy of playing Qa4 and then Qb3 looks just weird. }
7. Qxd5
{ The most critical response in the line - the pawn on d5 should be more valuable to White than the b7 pawn. }
7... Bb4+
{ This check is important for an unbelievable reason - so that the pawn on b7 can't be taken! }
8. Bd2
{ This is probably the most logical response - being up a pawn White must be happy to simplify the position a little bit. }
8... Nf6 9. Qb3
{ Now  9.Qxb7  falls into a very cute trap after  9...Bxd2+  ,  followed by ...e3 and ...Bc6,   while  9.Qe5  is answered with  ...Be7  and Black wins a lot of tempos due to the white queen's placement. Now you understand the deep idea behind this clever check! }
9... Bd6
{ The White queen has been forced back so it's time to retreat. In general Black wants to avoid the dark-squared bishop trade, unless it brings something on the table, like winning some tempos. }
10. Bb4
{ This logical move first to trade the dark-squared bishops and only then close the center is not dangerous since Black can at least force a repetition if he's happy for it, and there are many tactical tricks at Black's disposal. }
10... Be6 11. Qa4+
{ 11.Qa3  is no good because of  11...Bxb4+  and Nc6 next, winning the pawn on d4. }
11... Bd7
{ White can't refuse the repetition as  12.Qa5  meets  12...Qc8!  and the threats of Qc1+ and Nc6 bring White material losses. There's a notable variation here. }
12. Qa3 Nc6 13. Bxd6 Nxd4
{ Black has a deadly attack. No matter where you look, White is busted. } 14.
Kd2 { This dooms White because of the terrible pin at the d-file. } 14... Nb5
15. Qc5 Nxd6 16. Qxd6 e3+
{ The threats of ...Ne4+ and ...Bc6 are too big to handle. Does it even feel like Black is down a piece? }
17. Kxe3 Ng4+ 18. Kd2 Bc6 19. Qxd8+ Rxd8+
{ Finally White loses gigantic material proportions. } *

