{ The immediate pawn capture  5...Qxd5  is no good as after  6.Nc3  White wins several important tempos, landing Black into a bad position. The idea behind Black's last move is to sell a pawn to win several extra tempos to take over the initiative. It's almost impossible to predict every single continuation that is at White's disposal but I will try to cover most of them and explain the core ideas that Black should know.   Either way, please don't expect Black to win on the spot - this is a pawn sacrifice to help Black to accelerate his development and take over the initiative. The entire line should stand the test of time and practice. }
6. Qb3
{ This is a second alternative to 6.dxc6 - this gives White a choice to take either the pawn on d5 or b7 but mostly the arising positions and plans for Black are quite similar to already covered lines. }
6... cxd5
{ Now White has a little choice. I think he has to accept one of the pawns, otherwise, the entire strategy of playing Qa4 and then Qb3 looks just weird. }
7. Qxd5
{ The most critical response in the line - the pawn on d5 should be more valuable to White than the b7 pawn. }
7... Bb4+
{ This check is important for an unbelievable reason - so that the pawn on b7 can't be taken! }
8. Bd2
{ This is probably the most logical response - being up a pawn White must be happy to simplify the position a little bit. }
8... Nf6 9. Qb3
{ Now  9.Qxb7  falls into a very cute trap after  9...Bxd2+  ,  followed by ...e3 and ...Bc6,   while  9.Qe5  is answered with  ...Be7  and Black wins a lot of tempos due to the white queen's placement. Now you understand the deep idea behind this clever check! }
9... Bd6
{ The White queen has been forced back so it's time to retreat. In general Black wants to avoid the dark-squared bishop trade, unless it brings something on the table, like winning some tempos. }
10. e3
{ I have a feeling that White will have to play it sooner or later as Black will play ... Nc6 next and attack the pawn on d4. The immediate   10.Bg5  is tempting but Black can at least repeat the position with  10...Qa5+  11.Bd2  Qd8  . }
10... Nc6
{ This is the critical position that should stand the test of practice and time - White has managed to keep an extra pawn and survive an immediate attack, however, Black holds the long-term initiative. Here the plans are pretty much the same as covered in the 6.dxc6 lines and I'm convinced that the compensation for the pawn is excellent. }
11. Ne2 O-O 12. Bg2 Re8 13. O-O Rc8
{ Black is thinking about an attack at the kingside and if the circumstances will allow it, increasing pressure with ...Be6 and ...Qd7. Here White has several ways to continue. }
14. Bc3
{ This allows White to watch out for ...Na5, position the queenside knight on d2, and also protects the b2 pawn. }
14... Be6 15. Qd1
{ Here  15.Qxb7  loses the queen after  15...Bc4!  and ...Re7 next. } 15... Ne7
{ Black has a commanding control of the light squares. } *

