1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5
{ Since Black is threatening to strengthen his center with ...d5, it makes sense for White to at least consider to prevent it from happening and target the pawn on e4 which on some occasions might lack proper support. This move has been tested also at the highest level but my final verdict is - it's harmless and quite easy to parry. }
4... Bb4+
{ As the practice proves, this is the best move here. Black develops his bishop with a tempo and aims for a quick short castle. }
5. Nc3
{ This has been played just a handful of times and while Black can switch to the main lines with just a slightly different order of the moves, there might be something better. }
5... Bxc3+
{ A strong novelty which very much makes sense - in addition to the typical lines here the pawn on c3 will be a weakness and Black gains a potential outpost on c5 for his knight. }
6. bxc3 Nf6
{ The most accurate since the more careful  6...d6  can run into  7.Bf4  and Black will have to decide, what to do with the pawn on d6. Of course, Black could always sacrifice it but that's a different story. }
7. Bf4
{ While it might be tempting for White to occupy the d6 square, it is severely lagging in development and the control of the d6 square is not that important. The light-squared bishop from c8 can always join the game via the a6 square. }
7... O-O 8. Bd6 Re8 9. Qd4 b6 10. Bg2 Ba6
{ Now White has to solve some practical problems of his weak queenside pawns. }
