8. Qc2 { or  8.Qb3  b6  ,  followed by ...Na6-c5 and ...Ba6 } 8... b6 9. Bg2
Ba6 10. Bxe4 Bxc4
{ It's an equal pawn trade as it allows Black to activate his pieces much more quickly. The white pawn on d6 is turning out to be a weakness. }
11. Bf3 O-O 12. Nh3 Na6 13. O-O Rae8
{ White's piece coordination is far from optimal, plus the weak pawns. Black has the advantage here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Early g3: 3.d4 and 4.d5"]
[Black "5.Nc3: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5
{ Since Black is threatening to strengthen his center with ...d5, it makes sense for White to at least consider to prevent it from happening and target the pawn on e4 which on some occasions might lack proper support. This move has been tested also at the highest level but my final verdict is - it's harmless and quite easy to parry. }
4... Bb4+
{ As the practice proves, this is the best move here. Black develops his bishop with a tempo and aims for a quick short castle. }
5. Nc3
{ This has been played just a handful of times and while Black can switch to the main lines with just a slightly different order of the moves, there might be something better. }
5... Bxc3+
{ A strong novelty which very much makes sense - in addition to the typical lines here the pawn on c3 will be a weakness and Black gains a potential outpost on c5 for his knight. }
6. bxc3 Nf6
{ The most accurate since the more careful  6...d6  can run into  7.Bf4  and Black will have to decide, what to do with the pawn on d6. Of course, Black could always sacrifice it but that's a different story. }
7. Qd4 { White goes for the e4 pawn immediately. } 7... d6
{ Now Bf4 and dxc6 are impossible to carry out so Black doesn't have to worry about the d6 pawn anymore. }
8. Bg5 cxd5 9. Bxf6
{ 9.cxd5  Nbd7  and due to the control of some of the critical squares, Black is better. The pawn on e4 can always be protected with ...Qe7 and the annoying bishop on g5 - dealt with ...h6 and recapturing on f6 with the other knight. }
9... Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 11. cxd5 Nd7
{ White's pawns at the queenside make easy targets while Black's doubled f-pawns don't matter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Early g3: 3.d4 and 4.d5"]
[Black "5.Nd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5
{ Since Black is threatening to strengthen his center with ...d5, it makes sense for White to at least consider to prevent it from happening and target the pawn on e4 which on some occasions might lack proper support. This move has been tested also at the highest level but my final verdict is - it's harmless and quite easy to parry. }
4... Bb4+
{ As the practice proves, this is the best move here. Black develops his bishop with a tempo and aims for a quick short castle. }
5. Nd2
{ This maneuver in many openings is a common idea - the opponent wants to keep his bishop on the board and after the eventual a3 possibly gain two bishop advantage, should the opponent take the knight and then slowly grind out the two bishop advantage. Here, however, it's not so simple as White has a potential weakness on d5 thus it's not a surprise that it's a technical novelty - nobody has played it yet. The engines insist that it's playable. }
5... Nf6
{ If you're looking for some improvised fun, think of   5...e3!?  which sacrifices the pawn to gain complete control of the e5 square for your knights. Some GMs have played it at least after 5.Bd2 where it's not so great. }
6. a3 Bxd2+ 7. Bxd2 cxd5
{ Accurate as White already was thinking about dxc6 and positioning his bishop on c3. The white pawn on d5 is lacking the support it could receive on c4. }
8. cxd5 d6
{ 8...Nxd5  9.Bh6  is something that Black wants to avoid - the pawn structure is completely shattered. Here Black follows the traditional plan - short castle, ...Re8, ...Bf5, and ...Nbd7 either to e5 or c5. }
9. Bc3 O-O 10. Bg2 Re8 11. Nh3 Bf5
{ This setup seems to be universal in many of the lines. The bishop on f5 strengthens the e4 pawn and allows Black to finish development with ...Nbd7. }
12. O-O Nbd7 13. Nf4 h6
{ As you will notice in several lines, this is a useful move for Black which might be preparing either ...g5 push and immediately protect the pawn on g5, or create a retreat square for the bishop. Sometimes White is also thinking about g4-g5 ideas, bothering the knight. }
14. f3 Rc8
{ Black is even better because of better piece coordination. There are several ways how Black can improve his pieces, as long as Black refrains from the ...exf3 maneuver which would give White some space advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Early g3: 3.d4 and 4.d5"]
[Black "6.e3 Nf6: #1 (What NOT to do)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5
{ Since Black is threatening to strengthen his center with ...d5, it makes sense for White to at least consider to prevent it from happening and target the pawn on e4 which on some occasions might lack proper support. This move has been tested also at the highest level but my final verdict is - it's harmless and quite easy to parry. }
4... Bb4+
{ As the practice proves, this is the best move here. Black develops his bishop with a tempo and aims for a quick short castle. }
5. Bd2
{ Arguably the main move here as the alternatives don't look impressive. } 5...
Qe7
{ This move is borrowed from the Bogo Indian defense. First comes out the dark-squared bishop, then the queen which protects it on b4 in hopes to win some valuable time. Simply put, there's no need to rush with the bishop trade - strengthen your center first. Almost in every single line Black's plan will be the same - include early ...cxd5, trade the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@sometimes for a knight on c3@@EndBracket@@, fix the pawn on d5 with d6 and continue normal development with ...Nf6, ...O-O, ...Bf5, and ... Nbd7. There might be some occasions when the queenside knight might be developed through a6, possibly including ...a5 first. }
6. e3
{ This is quite a very tricky move and some very good GMs have already fallen into the trap. White is threatening with the not obvious positional threat Bxb4 and Qd2, preparing a quick pressure against the e4 pawn while the pawn on c4 is protected. }
6... Nf6 { This is logical but appears to be a slight inaccuracy. } 7. Bxb4
Qxb4+ 8. Qd2 { Suddenly White starts to pressure the pawn on e4 quick! } 8...
Na6 9. a3 Qxd2+ 10. Nxd2
{ The same fate is in this line - the support of the e4 pawn on c5 won't hold there for long. }
10... Nc5 11. b4 Na4 12. Bg2 cxd5 13. cxd5 a5
{ Rodshtein,M @@StartBracket@@2628@@EndBracket@@-Predojevic,B @@StartBracket@@2603@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com Pro Chess League 2020 }
14. d6
{ Would have been a great improvement over the game, promising White a big advantage. }
