[Round "?"]
[White "6. Early g3: 3.d4 and 4.d5"]
[Black "5.Bd2 and 6.e3: #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5
{ Since Black is threatening to strengthen his center with ...d5, it makes sense for White to at least consider to prevent it from happening and target the pawn on e4 which on some occasions might lack proper support. This move has been tested also at the highest level but my final verdict is - it's harmless and quite easy to parry. }
4... Bb4+
{ As the practice proves, this is the best move here. Black develops his bishop with a tempo and aims for a quick short castle. }
5. Bd2
{ Arguably the main move here as the alternatives don't look impressive. } 5...
Qe7
{ This move is borrowed from the Bogo Indian defense. First comes out the dark-squared bishop, then the queen which protects it on b4 in hopes to win some valuable time. Simply put, there's no need to rush with the bishop trade - strengthen your center first. Almost in every single line Black's plan will be the same - include early ...cxd5, trade the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@sometimes for a knight on c3@@EndBracket@@, fix the pawn on d5 with d6 and continue normal development with ...Nf6, ...O-O, ...Bf5, and ... Nbd7. There might be some occasions when the queenside knight might be developed through a6, possibly including ...a5 first. }
6. e3
{ This is quite a very tricky move and some very good GMs have already fallen into the trap. White is threatening with the not obvious positional threat Bxb4 and Qd2, preparing a quick pressure against the e4 pawn while the pawn on c4 is protected. }
6... cxd5 { Avoid the little trap with the correct order of the moves. } 7.
cxd5 { 7.Nc3  Nf6  changes little from Black's perspective. } 7... Nf6 8. Nc3
{ Now the big point is that the immediate  8.Bxb4  gives White nothing as after  8...Qxb4  9.Qd2  black has  9...Nxd5!  with an extra pawn. That's why it was important to include 6...cxd5 first. }
8... O-O 9. Bg2 Bxc3
{ This is sort of forced but at the same time also the simplest approach to finish the development. Unfortunately Black can't play  9...d6  because of the common tactical trick  10.Nxe4!  and the bishop on b4 hangs. }
10. Bxc3 d6
{ We're now following a game between two Italian players where Black easily got an excellent game. }
11. Ne2
{ 11.Bxf6  Qxf6  12.Bxe4  is not feeling impressive as after  12...Qxb2  Black wins back the pawn and gains the c5 square for his knight. }
11... Nbd7
{ Here it seems to be more accurate to play ...Nbd7 before ...Bf5 as not necessarily in this position the light-squared bishop belongs on f5. With the white pawn on e3 White has weakened his f3 and d3 squares, thus the black light-squared bishop might land on a more active square immediately.   It's also important to note that unlike in some other lines here White is unable to apply huge pressure against the e4 pawn immediately which is not forcing Black to rush with ...Bf5. }
12. O-O Ne5 13. h3
{ If White decides to activate his knight to c3 with a surprise bishop trade  13.Bxe5  Qxe5  14.Qd4  ,  as similarly seen in a game between Albert Bokros vs Zuzana Cibickova in 2017, remember that Black is not obliged to take on d4 which could open the e-file to target that e4 pawn. Sometimes having double pawns is pretty good!  14...Bf5  is simple and good. }
13... Bd7
{ Since nobody is targeting the pawn on e4, the bishop on d7 feels more flexible, with plans to jump to b5 at the right time. }
14. a4 Rac8
{ While the position is equal, I have a feeling here that sooner or later White will run out of sensible moves. Black's game is very easy - either attack the pawn on d5 with the immediate ...Rc5, or create some targets at the kingside. Perhaps various ...Nf3+ ideas or even a timely executed ...h5-h4 might work. }
