{ Arguably the main move here as the alternatives don't look impressive. } 5...
Qe7
{ This move is borrowed from the Bogo Indian defense. First comes out the dark-squared bishop, then the queen which protects it on b4 in hopes to win some valuable time. Simply put, there's no need to rush with the bishop trade - strengthen your center first. Almost in every single line Black's plan will be the same - include early ...cxd5, trade the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@sometimes for a knight on c3@@EndBracket@@, fix the pawn on d5 with d6 and continue normal development with ...Nf6, ...O-O, ...Bf5, and ... Nbd7. There might be some occasions when the queenside knight might be developed through a6, possibly including ...a5 first. }
6. Bg2
{ White might be stubborn and avoid playing Nc3 but the arising positions lead to the same setups. }
6... Nf6
{ Now the only difference here is that Black doesn't have to rush with cxd5 as there's no need for it. }
7. Nh3 { 7.Nc3  would transpose to the mainline. } 7... O-O 8. O-O cxd5
{ Like I mentioned before, better include the c-pawn trade sooner than later. }
9. cxd5 Bxd2 10. Qxd2 d6
{ We're back to a familiar position. The bishops on d2 had to be traded to play ...d6. }
11. Nc3 Bf5 12. f3
{ Here is an interesting moment - I think that both here and in similar setups where White has just played f3 with clear intentions to open the position, Black shouldn't rush with ...exf3 as this would open the e-file and White could get some space advantage. The idea to take on f3 might be possible later under more favorable circumstances. Black is happy to sacrifice the pawn on e4 which will make an easy target. }
12... h6 { Black additionally takes care of any g4-g5 ideas. } 13. Qf4 Bh7 14.
fxe4
{ 14.Nf2  at some moment Black probably doesn't mind the trade as White has made all kinds of awkward moves to force it.  14...exf3  ,  followed by ...Qd8-b6 and .. .Nbd7. }
14... Nbd7 15. Nf2 Rae8 16. Rad1 a6 17. Rd4 Ne5
{ Black has an easy game and it makes sense to gain more space at the queenside as well. Winning back the pawn on e4 shouldn't be a priority. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Early g3: 3.d4 and 4.d5"]
[Black "5.Bd2 and 6.Bxb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5
{ Since Black is threatening to strengthen his center with ...d5, it makes sense for White to at least consider to prevent it from happening and target the pawn on e4 which on some occasions might lack proper support. This move has been tested also at the highest level but my final verdict is - it's harmless and quite easy to parry. }
4... Bb4+
{ As the practice proves, this is the best move here. Black develops his bishop with a tempo and aims for a quick short castle. }
5. Bd2
{ Arguably the main move here as the alternatives don't look impressive. } 5...
Qe7
{ This move is borrowed from the Bogo Indian defense. First comes out the dark-squared bishop, then the queen which protects it on b4 in hopes to win some valuable time. Simply put, there's no need to rush with the bishop trade - strengthen your center first. Almost in every single line Black's plan will be the same - include early ...cxd5, trade the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@sometimes for a knight on c3@@EndBracket@@, fix the pawn on d5 with d6 and continue normal development with ...Nf6, ...O-O, ...Bf5, and ... Nbd7. There might be some occasions when the queenside knight might be developed through a6, possibly including ...a5 first. }
6. Bxb4
{ Although typically in Bogo Indian this move drops a pawn on c4 or b2 by force, apparently White can play here a gambit! So far this has been played only once between two Russian players in 2019. }
6... Qxb4+ 7. Nc3 Nf6
{ The simplest solution - accepting the sacrifice would accelerate White's development. }
8. Qd4
{ White targets the pawn on e4 and is also threatening with a check on e5 but as it happens, the queen at this occasion in the center is misplaced! If  8.Qb3  then after  8...a5!  ,  followed by . ..Na6-c5 Black obtains an excellent game.   Probably White has to continue  8.Qd2  ,  after which Black can either accept the 'free pawn' on c4 or just continue normal development with the traditional plans of ...cxd5, ...O-O, ...d6, ...Bf5, and so on. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O
{ From here on the young Russian grandmaster Petrov mercilessly crushed his opposition in mere 17 moves. }
9... d6 { 9...Na6  might have been a little more accurate. } 10. h3
{ While this is too slow and White should have accepted the Greek gift on e4, but it's the next move which is just unacceptable. }
10... Nbd7 11. dxc6
{ Now the entire queenside now is wide open for a decisive attack. The pawn on d6 is irrelevant. }
11... bxc6 12. Qxd6 Nc5 { Black's attack is too strong. } 13. a3 Qa5 14. Kc2 e3
{ Opening both the diagonal for the bishop and as well as the e4 square for one of the knights. }
15. b4 Bf5+ 16. Kb2 Rab8 17. Nb5 Qa4
{ 0-1 Sadovsky,A @@StartBracket@@2416@@EndBracket@@-Petrov, N @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@ Russian championship Higher League 2019, here White resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Early g3: 3.d4 and 4.d5"]
[Black "5.Bd2 and 6.Nc3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5
{ Since Black is threatening to strengthen his center with ...d5, it makes sense for White to at least consider to prevent it from happening and target the pawn on e4 which on some occasions might lack proper support. This move has been tested also at the highest level but my final verdict is - it's harmless and quite easy to parry. }
4... Bb4+
{ As the practice proves, this is the best move here. Black develops his bishop with a tempo and aims for a quick short castle. }
5. Bd2
{ Arguably the main move here as the alternatives don't look impressive. } 5...
Qe7
{ This move is borrowed from the Bogo Indian defense. First comes out the dark-squared bishop, then the queen which protects it on b4 in hopes to win some valuable time. Simply put, there's no need to rush with the bishop trade - strengthen your center first. Almost in every single line Black's plan will be the same - include early ...cxd5, trade the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@sometimes for a knight on c3@@EndBracket@@, fix the pawn on d5 with d6 and continue normal development with ...Nf6, ...O-O, ...Bf5, and ... Nbd7. There might be some occasions when the queenside knight might be developed through a6, possibly including ...a5 first. }
6. Nc3
{ The main move - White keeps more tension in the center and is considering going for a two-bishop advantage. }
6... Nf6 7. a3
{ This is one of the rare high-level games in this variation - Vishy Anand had no trouble to equalize the game with Black and at some point was standing even better. }
7... Bxc3 8. Bxc3 d6 { Or  8...cxd5  first. } 9. Nh3 cxd5
{ Again an early c-pawn trade. } 10. cxd5 O-O 11. Bg2 Bf5 12. O-O Nbd7
{ So far this is almost forced. The only difference with some other lines is that White has a nice bishop on c3 which is not doing much. }
13. Nf4 h6
{ As you will come to understand, this move is quite standard for these types of positions - Black is securing his king against any g4-g5 ideas and freeing a hideout on h7 for his bishop. }
14. f3 Ne5
{ Black is not in a hurry to open the e-file! There's no need to increase the power of the white rooks and bishops - White just can't force Black to play ...exf3 and as we know, knights operate best in closed positions. }
15. Qd4 Rfc8
{ Indirectly defending the pawn on e4 with the ...Rc4 threat. A little but important difference is that ...Rac8 would leave the pawn on a7 unprotected. }
16. Rad1 b5
{ With a great game for Black. Ding,L @@StartBracket@@2782@@EndBracket@@-Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2803@@EndBracket@@ Grand Slam Final 8th Bilbao 2015. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
