[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5
{ Since Black is threatening to strengthen his center with ...d5, it makes sense for White to at least consider to prevent it from happening and target the pawn on e4 which on some occasions might lack proper support. This move has been tested also at the highest level but my final verdict is - it's harmless and quite easy to parry. }
4... Bb4+
{ As the practice proves, this is the best move here. Black develops his bishop with a tempo and aims for a quick short castle. }
5. Bd2
{ Arguably the main move here as the alternatives don't look impressive. } 5...
Qe7
{ This move is borrowed from the Bogo Indian defense. First comes out the dark-squared bishop, then the queen which protects it on b4 in hopes to win some valuable time. Simply put, there's no need to rush with the bishop trade - strengthen your center first. Almost in every single line Black's plan will be the same - include early ...cxd5, trade the dark-squared bishop @@StartBracket@@sometimes for a knight on c3@@EndBracket@@, fix the pawn on d5 with d6 and continue normal development with ...Nf6, ...O-O, ...Bf5, and ... Nbd7. There might be some occasions when the queenside knight might be developed through a6, possibly including ...a5 first. }
6. Nc3
{ The main move - White keeps more tension in the center and is considering going for a two-bishop advantage. }
6... Nf6 7. Bg2
{ With the black bishop on b4, Black needs to start to pay attention, can White play some tactical tricks with Nxe4. It doesn't work, not yet anyway. }
7... O-O 8. Nh3
{ 8.a3  transforms to the game of Ding - Anand after  8...Bxc3  9.Bxc3  cxd5  10.cxd5  d6 }
8... cxd5
{ Again, an important accuracy - you'll see the difference if Black will forget to include this move! }
9. cxd5 d6 10. O-O { White finishes the development but so does Black. } 10...
Bf5 { Black is strengthening the center and setting up a little trap. } 11. f3
{ 11.Nxe4  would be a huge blunder here because of  11...Bxe4  12.Bxb4  Bxg2  and the incoming ... Qe4+ which would cost White a full piece. }
11... Na6
{ Now Nxe4 is a threat so it makes sense to protect the bishop and develop the remaining knight at the same time. Similarly like in other lines, there's no need to rush to open the e-file although here it might be possible as the dark-squared bishop is still on the board and Black shouldn't be afraid of opening the position. If White played here a3, it would make sense to reevaluate the priorities. Black was happy to trade on c3 before, here things might be different. }
12. Bg5
{ This is a logical novelty, yet to be played with White threatening to open the f-file. }
12... Bxh3 { Black relieves the tension at the f-file. } 13. Bxh3 Bxc3 14. bxc3
h6
{ Black is left with a pair of happy knights with great career opportunities at the outposts. As long as Black is not opening the position too much with moves like ...exf3, the knights should be doing great. }
