13... h6 14. Bh4
{ White keeping the pin alive looks like the most logical response but it weakens the control of the e3 square. }
14... exf3
{ It's time to clarify the situation but there might be other good continuations as well. }
15. exf3 Bxc3
{ Not mandatory but forcing the matters a little bit. This trade also allows Black to secure an outpost on c5 for his knight. }
16. bxc3 Qe3+ 17. Nf2
{ Now here Black has many ways to continue, and one of them is sacrificing a queen for enough material and an entertaining game. }
17... Rfe8 { The most solid continuation. } 18. f4
{ 18.Bxf6  gxf6  doubles the pawns for Black but the remaining pieces on the board are dominating their White colleagues. }
18... Ne4 19. Re1
{ The most logical response, which at the same time liquidates the game into an equal endgame. }
19... Nxf2
{ This is forced as   19...Qxf4?  drops some material after  20.Bxe4!  ,  with an idea to play Bg3 next. }
20. Rxe3 Nxd1 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. Rxd1 f5
{ The final touch - Black parries the annoying f5 threat and secures a good endgame where White is playing for a draw, mostly because of the powerful knight's outpost on c5. }
