[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Early g3 & Early Qb3"]
[Black "Sideline: 4.Nf3 and 5.Nd4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2
{ Against 2...c6 the immediate bishop's positioning on g2 oddly is not the most challenging approach as most often White immediately tries to challenge the center with d4, then target the fixed black pawn on d5 with Nc3, Qb3, and sometimes Nh3-f4. With the bishop already on g2, those plans arrive late as the black pawn on e4 will block the access for the bishop to the d-pawn. However, it comes together with something special that usually is not seen in other lines. }
3... d5
{ From Black's perspective, the plan to take the center doesn't change. } 4.
Nf3
{ Without including cxd5 this is just a suspicious continuation and shouldn't pose any problems for Black if you will be aware that sometimes early ...dxc4 can bring Black good results, especially if it comes with a tempo. }
4... e4 { Of course, move forward with a tempo. } 5. Nd4 dxc4 6. Nc2
{ Or  6.e3  which won't change the objective evaluation of the position as Black can simply play  ...Bc5  and push the knight back - White is worse here. Even if White somehow manages to regain the pawn on c4, Black will always have an excellent game. }
6... f5 7. O-O Nf6 8. b3
{ I imagine this is the only way how White can try to justify the idea by playing it as a gambit, but Black has nothing to be afraid of. }
8... cxb3 9. axb3
{ Cori,J @@StartBracket@@2652@@EndBracket@@-Vazquez,G @@StartBracket@@2527@@EndBracket@@ Iberoamericano Chess24 2020. }
9... Be7 { It's not clear what exactly has White for the sacrificed pawn. } *

