[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2
{ Against 2...c6 the immediate bishop's positioning on g2 oddly is not the most challenging approach as most often White immediately tries to challenge the center with d4, then target the fixed black pawn on d5 with Nc3, Qb3, and sometimes Nh3-f4. With the bishop already on g2, those plans arrive late as the black pawn on e4 will block the access for the bishop to the d-pawn. However, it comes together with something special that usually is not seen in other lines. }
3... d5
{ From Black's perspective, the plan to take the center doesn't change. } 4.
cxd5 cxd5 5. Nc3
{ This is hardly something that Black should be concerned about - if you can push forward the pawn with a tempo and nothing is under attack, that's probably already a good move! }
5... d4 6. Nd5 Be6
{ But this is a novelty however the reason probably is simple - nobody plays like this as White. The knight's position on d5 should be challenged as quickly as possible, otherwise White indeed will get a good position. }
7. Qb3
{ Quite a logical follow-up as White not only defends the knight on d5 but also eyes for the b7 pawn. However, the newly created pin can have consequences. }
7... Ne7 8. Qb5+
{ 8.Qxb7??  Bxd5  9.Bxd5  Qxd5  and White loses a piece as the black rook on a8 is defended. }
8... Nd7
{ 8...Qd7  would be a very big mistake because of the pin after  9.Nc7+ } 9.
Nxe7 Bxe7 10. Qxb7
{ If White played Qb3 with intentions to take the pawn, it's logical to take it! The engines, however, are not impressed and announce that White is losing. }
10... Rc8
{ Either the white queen will get trapped, or Black's attack will become overwhelming. }
11. Qxa7 { If White is to perish, then better with music, right? } 11... O-O
12. Qa4 Nc5 13. Qd1
{ Now there's more than one victory here for Black but the text move is the most flashy! }
13... Bxa2 14. Rxa2 Nb3
{ Neither can White take the knight, nor protect the bishop with Ra1. } 15. Ra8
{ Last try. } 15... Qd6 { Black wins. } *

