[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Early g3 & Early Qb3"]
[Black "5.Nc3: #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2
{ Against 2...c6 the immediate bishop's positioning on g2 oddly is not the most challenging approach as most often White immediately tries to challenge the center with d4, then target the fixed black pawn on d5 with Nc3, Qb3, and sometimes Nh3-f4. With the bishop already on g2, those plans arrive late as the black pawn on e4 will block the access for the bishop to the d-pawn. However, it comes together with something special that usually is not seen in other lines. }
3... d5
{ From Black's perspective, the plan to take the center doesn't change. } 4.
cxd5 cxd5 5. Nf3
{ This is a playable move but not posing any danger for Black. It's important to understand here that the very tempting ...e4 might cause only trouble for Black as White after Nd4 will just pressure the center with the eventual d3 push and Nc3 until it falls apart. Black should just continue with normal development. }
5... Nc6 6. d4
{ If White is not rushing with this, Black has plenty of good moves - ...Nf6, ...Be7, ...O-O and then decide what to do later. }
6... e4 7. Ne5 Bd6
{ Black is challenging the white knight's outpost on e5. Black doesn't mind recapturing on c6 with the pawn as it strengthens the center. }
8. Nc3 Nge7 { Or  8...Nf6  9.Bg5  Be6 } 9. Bf4 O-O
{ All of these moves look logical and just good - the white bishop on g2 doesn't make a good impression. }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. e3 g6
{ Black can focus to play at the kingside and completely ignore what's happening at the queenside as the knight on e7 protects the most vulnerable weakness. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Early g3 & Early Qb3"]
[Black "6.Nc3 d4: (What NOT to do)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2
{ Against 2...c6 the immediate bishop's positioning on g2 oddly is not the most challenging approach as most often White immediately tries to challenge the center with d4, then target the fixed black pawn on d5 with Nc3, Qb3, and sometimes Nh3-f4. With the bishop already on g2, those plans arrive late as the black pawn on e4 will block the access for the bishop to the d-pawn. However, it comes together with something special that usually is not seen in other lines. }
3... d5
{ From Black's perspective, the plan to take the center doesn't change. } 4.
cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3
{ Either as a surprise weapon or simply driven by greed, White might try to win a pawn either on d5 or b7. Sometimes such an aggressive approach pays off, but mostly against an unsuspecting opponent as withstanding sudden pressure in unfamiliar territory can be difficult. However, we're going to be ready for this. You should know that in general, this is a dubious approach as White is inevitably falling behind in development and Black not only solves all of his opening problems by sacrificing a single pawn but very often even takes over the initiative. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ Almost the only move because everything else allows Black to have a harmonious development with no worries. }
6... d4
{ This is not good as Black wastes valuable time that should be spent for developing. }
7. Bxb7 Bxb7 8. Qxb7
{ It becomes obvious that Black has no time to take the knight on c3. } 8...
Nbd7 9. Nd5 Rc8
{ Georgescu,T @@StartBracket@@2397@@EndBracket@@ -Doros,R @@StartBracket@@2319@@EndBracket@@ Ciocaltea Memorial 2010. Now after 10.Nf3 White has a healthy extra pawn. }
