[Round "?"]
[White "7. Early g3 & Early Qb3"]
[Black "5.Qb3, 8.Qxd5, 9.Qb3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2
{ Against 2...c6 the immediate bishop's positioning on g2 oddly is not the most challenging approach as most often White immediately tries to challenge the center with d4, then target the fixed black pawn on d5 with Nc3, Qb3, and sometimes Nh3-f4. With the bishop already on g2, those plans arrive late as the black pawn on e4 will block the access for the bishop to the d-pawn. However, it comes together with something special that usually is not seen in other lines. }
3... d5
{ From Black's perspective, the plan to take the center doesn't change. } 4.
cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3
{ Either as a surprise weapon or simply driven by greed, White might try to win a pawn either on d5 or b7. Sometimes such an aggressive approach pays off, but mostly against an unsuspecting opponent as withstanding sudden pressure in unfamiliar territory can be difficult. However, we're going to be ready for this. You should know that in general, this is a dubious approach as White is inevitably falling behind in development and Black not only solves all of his opening problems by sacrificing a single pawn but very often even takes over the initiative. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ Almost the only move because everything else allows Black to have a harmonious development with no worries. }
6... Nc6
{ A very principled reply - Black shouldn't mind sacrificing the pawn but aim for fast development. }
7. Nxd5 { This is almost forced, otherwise White is already worse. } 7... Nxd5
{ Meet your new approach which has been played just a few times before and never at a GM level! Yet, according to my analysis, I believe that it's the best move. }
8. Qxd5 Bd6
{ Depending on what White will do, Black aims for a very quick ... Nb4 or ...Nd4, especially if it will come with a tempo and threaten with ... Nc2+ fork. If necessary, Black is happy to reach the same setup as after the 'old 7...Nd4' but with improved prospects, such as the healthier pawn structure at the kingside, or better-positioned queen. This variation arose in Beltins, G. vs. Doronkin, S. European Correspondence Championship, 2019 }
9. Qb3
{ The way I treat it, this is the second playable alternative for White, albeit the worst of the two. The queen is fleeing back to the safety on d1. }
9... Nd4 10. Qd3
{ This looks just bleak as Black gains several tempos to accelerate his initiative. }
10... Bf5 11. Be4 Bxe4 12. Qxe4 f5
{ The white queen has to guard the c2 square. } 13. Qd3 Qc7 14. Kf1 Qc6 15. f3
{ After  15.Nf3  Nc2  the incoming ...e4 wins some material for Black. } 15...
O-O
{ Black has a very easy attack while White is struggling with his development, not even speaking about his king safety. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Early g3 & Early Qb3"]
[Black "5.Qb3, 8.Qxd5, 9.Qb3: #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2
{ Against 2...c6 the immediate bishop's positioning on g2 oddly is not the most challenging approach as most often White immediately tries to challenge the center with d4, then target the fixed black pawn on d5 with Nc3, Qb3, and sometimes Nh3-f4. With the bishop already on g2, those plans arrive late as the black pawn on e4 will block the access for the bishop to the d-pawn. However, it comes together with something special that usually is not seen in other lines. }
3... d5
{ From Black's perspective, the plan to take the center doesn't change. } 4.
cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3
{ Either as a surprise weapon or simply driven by greed, White might try to win a pawn either on d5 or b7. Sometimes such an aggressive approach pays off, but mostly against an unsuspecting opponent as withstanding sudden pressure in unfamiliar territory can be difficult. However, we're going to be ready for this. You should know that in general, this is a dubious approach as White is inevitably falling behind in development and Black not only solves all of his opening problems by sacrificing a single pawn but very often even takes over the initiative. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ Almost the only move because everything else allows Black to have a harmonious development with no worries. }
6... Nc6
{ A very principled reply - Black shouldn't mind sacrificing the pawn but aim for fast development. }
7. Nxd5 { This is almost forced, otherwise White is already worse. } 7... Nxd5
{ Meet your new approach which has been played just a few times before and never at a GM level! Yet, according to my analysis, I believe that it's the best move. }
8. Qxd5 Bd6
{ Depending on what White will do, Black aims for a very quick ... Nb4 or ...Nd4, especially if it will come with a tempo and threaten with ... Nc2+ fork. If necessary, Black is happy to reach the same setup as after the 'old 7...Nd4' but with improved prospects, such as the healthier pawn structure at the kingside, or better-positioned queen. This variation arose in Beltins, G. vs. Doronkin, S. European Correspondence Championship, 2019 }
9. Qb3
{ The way I treat it, this is the second playable alternative for White, albeit the worst of the two. The queen is fleeing back to the safety on d1. }
9... Nd4 10. Qd1 Qc7 { Black is threatening with the fork. } 11. Be4
{ While here this leads to a bad position, don't miss this maneuver in similar positions as it's a very common way to stop the immediate ...Nc2 threat or the rook that has penetrated the 2nd rank. Here in particular it's just a waste of even more time as there are other things as well that Black could do, not just focusing on ...Nc2. }
11... f5 12. Bd3 O-O { Black has a significant lead in development. } 13. Nf3
Ne6 { Threatening with ...e4 to win a piece. } 14. Bc2 e4 15. Nh4 Nd4
{ The black knight is back to d4, bothering the bishop on c2 and making the white king feel very much uncomfortable. Notice how the knight on d4 is much stronger than the white knight on h4 - two moves ago that seemed like an equal trade! }
16. Bb3+ Kh8
{ The knight on d4 is stronger than the bishop, thus trade is not in Black's interest who is already thinking about playing ...f4 next move. }
17. e3
{ This allows White to get rid of the annoying knight but weakens the king's position forever. }
17... Nxb3 18. Qxb3 f4
{ In these kinds of positions, it's important to understand that it's not the number of pawns that decide the fate of the game - it's the king's safety. The white monarch is stuck in the center and it should remain there. With the text move the light-squared bishop lands on h3 and the decisive attack will start soon. White's entire queenside is not playing. }
19. exf4 Bh3
{ With a million threats against the white king. It's impossible to imagine how the king will get to safety to either the kingside or queenside, and those two extra pawns don't matter. }
