{ Meet your new approach which has been played just a few times before and never at a GM level! Yet, according to my analysis, I believe that it's the best move. }
8. Qxd5 Bd6
{ Depending on what White will do, Black aims for a very quick ... Nb4 or ...Nd4, especially if it will come with a tempo and threaten with ... Nc2+ fork. If necessary, Black is happy to reach the same setup as after the 'old 7...Nd4' but with improved prospects, such as the healthier pawn structure at the kingside, or better-positioned queen. This variation arose in Beltins, G. vs. Doronkin, S. European Correspondence Championship, 2019 }
9. Qd3
{ This is not a good alternative as also here Black attacks the queen with a tempo. }
9... Nb4 10. Qe4
{ What else?   10.Qb3  Be6  11.Qa4+  b5  looks even worse as after  12.Qxb5+  Bd7  White will lose a full rook because of the fork on c2. Here White is waiting for Black to play ...f5 first and only then to position his queen on c4 so that the e6 square is not available for the black bishop. However, Black has other options as well. }
10... Qc7
{ The most accurate move - White can't play Kd1 and expect that the king will survive the attack in the center. }
11. Kf1 f5 12. Qh4
{ Either this or   12.Qb1  Nc2  and White loses the exchange on the spot, plus a misplaced king which is a major setback, comparing with the mainline of the chapter. }
12... Nc2 13. Rb1 Nd4
{ The black knight enjoys the luxury, provided by the d4 square! The immediate ...Qc2 is a big threat already. }
14. Ra1 Be6
{ Black is threatening with ...Nc2 and ...Bxa2 but please be careful! } 15. d3
O-O
{ Black finishes the development with all of the threats at the queenside remaining. Besides, there's also the ...f4 threat as the white king appears to be unfortunately placed on the same line as the black rook. Don't get carried away with the immediate  15...Nc2  16.Rb1  Bxa2  as it drops a piece with  17.Qa4+! }
*

