{ Starting from this moment the game is almost forced. Since Black is threatening with a fork on c2 and with a tempo, White must step back carefully. }
10. Qe4
{ The only move which doesn't drop something on the spot.   10.Qb5+  would meet an easy  10...Bd7  . }
10... f5
{ It's important to keep the momentum going. Ideally, if Black could manage to achieve the same results and execute the ...Nc2 fork to win an exchange, the f-pawn would feel safer on f7 as on f5 the king feels slightly vulnerable and after a potential White's d4 push in the future, Black will be struggling with the control of the e5 square. }
11. Qc4
{ This is the only alternative to the mainline and according to my analysis - a dubious approach. White is not happy to give away the exchange just yet and wants to keep the black king in the center, at least for the time being. Since ...f5 has been included, now Black has no access to the immediate ...Be6. However, the extra tempo will be handy in other ways. }
11... Qe7
{ Black prepares to play ...Be6 next move. In my opinion, this is stronger than  11...Qf6  as in some lines, should the running white queen land on h4, you will have more options to react. }
12. O-O { The most logical continuation. } 12... Be6 13. Qb5+ Bd7
{ Black can already force a draw here if he's having doubts. } 14. Qc4 Rc8
{ But, of course, he shouldn't, at least not in such a great position! } 15.
Qb3 { Techically, the only move. } 15... Nc2
{ Black is about to show, how one knight can dominate another... } 16. Rb1 e4
17. Ne1 { 17.Nh4  g5  traps the knight. } 17... Nd4
{ Clearly, not going for the trade - the brave knight on d4 has a different value than that pesky horse on e1. }
18. Qd1
{ 18.Qe3  is hardly an alternative as after  18...Bc5  19.Kh1  Be6  the discovered attack is in the air with the decisive effect. }
18... Qf7
{ All of this is a forced sequence. It might seem that Black is eyeing for the pawn on a2 but actually, the big prize lies at the kingside where a very strong attack is about to begin. Castling is not even necessary as Black is ready to attack. }
19. d3
{ White has to do something quickly, otherwise he will be completely overrun. There's no time to protect the a2 pawn. }
19... Qxa2 { It might be possible but this leads to a very double-edged game. }
20. Be3 Nxe2+ 21. Qxe2 Qxb1
{ Now after  22.dxe4  there's a sharp game and White doesn't necessarily have worse chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Early g3 & Early Qb3"]
[Black "5.Qb3, 8.Qxd5, 9.Nf3: #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2
{ Against 2...c6 the immediate bishop's positioning on g2 oddly is not the most challenging approach as most often White immediately tries to challenge the center with d4, then target the fixed black pawn on d5 with Nc3, Qb3, and sometimes Nh3-f4. With the bishop already on g2, those plans arrive late as the black pawn on e4 will block the access for the bishop to the d-pawn. However, it comes together with something special that usually is not seen in other lines. }
3... d5
{ From Black's perspective, the plan to take the center doesn't change. } 4.
cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3
{ Either as a surprise weapon or simply driven by greed, White might try to win a pawn either on d5 or b7. Sometimes such an aggressive approach pays off, but mostly against an unsuspecting opponent as withstanding sudden pressure in unfamiliar territory can be difficult. However, we're going to be ready for this. You should know that in general, this is a dubious approach as White is inevitably falling behind in development and Black not only solves all of his opening problems by sacrificing a single pawn but very often even takes over the initiative. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ Almost the only move because everything else allows Black to have a harmonious development with no worries. }
6... Nc6
{ A very principled reply - Black shouldn't mind sacrificing the pawn but aim for fast development. }
7. Nxd5 { This is almost forced, otherwise White is already worse. } 7... Nxd5
{ Meet your new approach which has been played just a few times before and never at a GM level! Yet, according to my analysis, I believe that it's the best move. }
8. Qxd5 Bd6
{ Depending on what White will do, Black aims for a very quick ... Nb4 or ...Nd4, especially if it will come with a tempo and threaten with ... Nc2+ fork. If necessary, Black is happy to reach the same setup as after the 'old 7...Nd4' but with improved prospects, such as the healthier pawn structure at the kingside, or better-positioned queen. This variation arose in Beltins, G. vs. Doronkin, S. European Correspondence Championship, 2019 }
9. Nf3
{ One of the two main moves here which have been played only once, but in a correspondence game in 2019. }
9... Nb4
{ Starting from this moment the game is almost forced. Since Black is threatening with a fork on c2 and with a tempo, White must step back carefully. }
10. Qe4
{ The only move which doesn't drop something on the spot.   10.Qb5+  would meet an easy  10...Bd7  . }
10... f5
{ It's important to keep the momentum going. Ideally, if Black could manage to achieve the same results and execute the ...Nc2 fork to win an exchange, the f-pawn would feel safer on f7 as on f5 the king feels slightly vulnerable and after a potential White's d4 push in the future, Black will be struggling with the control of the e5 square. }
11. Qc4
{ This is the only alternative to the mainline and according to my analysis - a dubious approach. White is not happy to give away the exchange just yet and wants to keep the black king in the center, at least for the time being. Since ...f5 has been included, now Black has no access to the immediate ...Be6. However, the extra tempo will be handy in other ways. }
11... Qe7
{ Black prepares to play ...Be6 next move. In my opinion, this is stronger than  11...Qf6  as in some lines, should the running white queen land on h4, you will have more options to react. }
12. O-O { The most logical continuation. } 12... Be6 13. Qb5+ Bd7
{ Black can already force a draw here if he's having doubts. } 14. Qc4 Rc8
{ But, of course, he shouldn't, at least not in such a great position! } 15.
Qb3 { Techically, the only move. } 15... Nc2
{ Black is about to show, how one knight can dominate another... } 16. Rb1 e4
17. Ne1 { 17.Nh4  g5  traps the knight. } 17... Nd4
{ Clearly, not going for the trade - the brave knight on d4 has a different value than that pesky horse on e1. }
18. Qd1
{ 18.Qe3  is hardly an alternative as after  18...Bc5  19.Kh1  Be6  the discovered attack is in the air with the decisive effect. }
18... Qf7
{ All of this is a forced sequence. It might seem that Black is eyeing for the pawn on a2 but actually, the big prize lies at the kingside where a very strong attack is about to begin. Castling is not even necessary as Black is ready to attack. }
19. d3
{ White has to do something quickly, otherwise he will be completely overrun. There's no time to protect the a2 pawn. }
19... Qh5
{ Priorities lie at the kingside - the first immediate threat is ...Nxe2+, followed by ...Nxg3+, winning the unprotected queen on d1. }
20. f3 f4
{ This motif you should already remember from the previous sideline - now there are some eye-pleasing lines. }
21. g4
{ Or  21.gxf4  Rxc1!  22.Rxc1  Bxf4  with two threats - mate on h2 or take on c1 and win a piece in the process as White can't recapture because of the fork on e2.   If White would take on f4 with the bishop with  21.Bxf4  ,  then after  21...Bxf4  22.gxf4  e3!  White is powerless against the ...Rc6-h6 maneuver, with a mate to follow. Please note that Rc1 still is not available because of the fork on e2. }
21... Qg5 22. dxe4 h5
{ Black opens more files and diagonals to get to the white monarch - the knight on d4 can't be taken due to ...Bc5. }
23. Rf2 hxg4 24. fxg4 Bc5
{ White should suffer big material losses - the white king's defenses are wide open. }
*

