1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2
{ Against 2...c6 the immediate bishop's positioning on g2 oddly is not the most challenging approach as most often White immediately tries to challenge the center with d4, then target the fixed black pawn on d5 with Nc3, Qb3, and sometimes Nh3-f4. With the bishop already on g2, those plans arrive late as the black pawn on e4 will block the access for the bishop to the d-pawn. However, it comes together with something special that usually is not seen in other lines. }
3... d5
{ From Black's perspective, the plan to take the center doesn't change. } 4.
cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3
{ Either as a surprise weapon or simply driven by greed, White might try to win a pawn either on d5 or b7. Sometimes such an aggressive approach pays off, but mostly against an unsuspecting opponent as withstanding sudden pressure in unfamiliar territory can be difficult. However, we're going to be ready for this. You should know that in general, this is a dubious approach as White is inevitably falling behind in development and Black not only solves all of his opening problems by sacrificing a single pawn but very often even takes over the initiative. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ Almost the only move because everything else allows Black to have a harmonious development with no worries. }
6... Nc6
{ A very principled reply - Black shouldn't mind sacrificing the pawn but aim for fast development. }
7. Nxd5 { This is almost forced, otherwise White is already worse. } 7... Nxd5
{ Meet your new approach which has been played just a few times before and never at a GM level! Yet, according to my analysis, I believe that it's the best move. }
8. Qxd5 Bd6
{ Depending on what White will do, Black aims for a very quick ... Nb4 or ...Nd4, especially if it will come with a tempo and threaten with ... Nc2+ fork. If necessary, Black is happy to reach the same setup as after the 'old 7...Nd4' but with improved prospects, such as the healthier pawn structure at the kingside, or better-positioned queen. This variation arose in Beltins, G. vs. Doronkin, S. European Correspondence Championship, 2019 }
9. Nf3
{ One of the two main moves here which have been played only once, but in a correspondence game in 2019. }
9... Nb4
{ Starting from this moment the game is almost forced. Since Black is threatening with a fork on c2 and with a tempo, White must step back carefully. }
10. Qe4
{ The only move which doesn't drop something on the spot.   10.Qb5+  would meet an easy  10...Bd7  . }
10... f5
{ It's important to keep the momentum going. Ideally, if Black could manage to achieve the same results and execute the ...Nc2 fork to win an exchange, the f-pawn would feel safer on f7 as on f5 the king feels slightly vulnerable and after a potential White's d4 push in the future, Black will be struggling with the control of the e5 square. }
11. Qb1
{ White is ready to give away an exchange but by doing so he will at least get a more or less reasonable game. }
11... Qc7 12. O-O Nc2
{ Black is also threatening with the positional ...e4 so White's reply is almost forced. }
13. d3 Nxa1
{ It is possible to postpone this decision for a move later but I don't see what Black could gain from that, except for unnecessary complications. }
14. Qxa1 O-O
{ Black has a minor material advantage - exchange for knight and a pawn, and a healthy position. Black's ideal position is the queen on e7 where it protects the center, the light-squared bishop should be rerouted to c6 via d7, and the rook on a8 - probably on e8 to solidify the control in the center. In general Black is happy for any trade which doesn't weaken his center or control of squares. If Black can trade the light-squared bishops via c6 - great, this might even give some chances to launch a surprise attack at the kingside. With the queen on e7 Black might have an option to play ...Ba3 and trade the dark-squared bishops. As long as Black is not creating any additional weaknesses and simplifying the position by trading equal pieces, his position should be better.  Ideally Black is aiming for an endgame with a rook versus a light piece and a pawn, assuming there are no dramatic changes in the pawn structure. In the end, the rook should be stronger than the light piece, with the pawn being irrelevant in the position, but obviously, there is a long road ahead. From White I can see the following plans which Black should watch out:   1@@EndBracket@@ White might play the obvious b3 @@StartBracket@@or b4 but it's not clear if White is happy to open the position more than necessary@@EndBracket@@ and Bb2, targeting the pawn on e5. I would suggest refraining from moving forward the central pawns unless Black is gaining something directly, and solidify the position with ...Bd7, ...Rae8, and ...Bc6. Sooner or later White will have to trade some pieces otherwise Black looks quite ready to start hostilities at the kingside with ...f4. Now, ...Kh8 always is a useful move to avoid some surprise checks at the a2-g8 diagonal. With the dark-squared bishop on b2, it makes sense for White to push d4 at the right time. I can't say which decision would be best for which moment, but probably both ...e4, closing White's light-squared bishop or going for simplifications with ...exd4 makes a lot of sense.   Another interesting idea at White's disposal is to play e4, fixing e5 as a potential weakness. However, this also closes his light-squared bishop. Again, if Black can simplify the position, go for it, although the simple ... f4 also makes very much sense.   2@@EndBracket@@ White might try to reroute his only knight to c4. I think in general Black needs to be ready for this and play ...Bd7-c6 as quickly as possible, trading the light-squared bishops. However, I recommend avoiding ruining the pawn structure with ...bxc6 which will make it impossible to get rid of the knight on c4. If it's possible, Black should consider playing ...b5, thus stopping White's idea.   3@@EndBracket@@ At some moment White might try to go for an improvised attack with Ng5 and Bd5+, combined with Rc4-h4. Most of the time these threats are easy to parry - while White holds a temporary initiative, it should evaporate if Black will remain cool.   4@@EndBracket@@ Either directly or mixing with other plans, White might try to open the position with d4 or e4. In general, Black shouldn't object to open the position and trade as many pieces as it can, but Black has to be careful in the process as White would get very active pieces. If you are not sure, perhaps against d4 replying with ...e4 and against e4 replying with ...f4 might be a safer choice. }
15. Bd2 Qe7
{ This is quite accurate - since the Rc1 threat is incoming, the bishop will land on c6 anyway, so it's a better idea to position the queen on the ideal square first. }
16. Bg5 Qe8 17. Nd2
{ It looks like an interesting try to trick Black and stop the light-squared bishop to land on c6, but now White's dark-squared bishop is in danger. }
17... f4 18. Ne4 Bb8 19. gxf4 exf4 20. f3 Be5
{ Black has an obvious advantage - material superiority, plus some weak squares in White's camp. }
*

