17. Rc1 { 17.Nd2  b5  would just transpose to the mainline. } 17... Qb8
{ The only move which keeps the protections of the e5 pawn.   17...Bc6  is not an alternative here and would be premature as the freshly created pin is quite annoying. For example  18.d4  e4  19.d5! }
18. Nd2
{ A very logical follow-up - if the light-squared bishops are still on board, Black should stop the Nc4 maneuver otherwise the bishop trade without the avoidable bxc6 will be difficult to achieve. }
18... b5
{ A good restrictive move - there's no need to allow the white knight to land on c4. The only drawback is that it weakens the control of the c6 square. }
19. a4
{ Obviously, White is fighting for the control of the c4 square, thus in Black's interest is to stop it. }
19... a6 20. axb5 axb5
{ So far the last couple of moves are almost forced. It's not easy for White to find a way to activate his knight. }
21. Bd5+ Kh8 22. Nf3
{ The knight is going back as the way at the queenside is shut and an experienced player might be eyeing for the weakened c6 square. }
22... Re7
{ Black keeps control of the center, is not making any committal decisions/weaknesses with .. .h6 @@StartBracket@@the g6 square@@EndBracket@@ and calmly simplifies the position. The more pieces are off the board, the greater are Black's chances as the power of the extra rook will increase. First Black is aiming to trade one pair of rooks, then the light-squared bishops. It is White who has to constantly prove throughout this chapter, what it has for the sacrificed exchange. }
23. d4
{ Either this at some point or it's not clear how White is going to improve his position. }
23... e4
{ Again, it makes sense to close the position for the time being and force a couple of useful trades. }
24. Ne5 Bxe5 { 24...Be8  is also good, preparing to play ...Rc7 next. } 25.
dxe5 Be6
{ More simplifications are incoming. It's important to notice that there's no pin with Ba3 as Black has access to ...b4. }
26. Bxe6 Rxe6
{ Black controls the game. Probably the objective evaluation is that White is closer to equality than Black is better but with a risk-free game for Black. If Black will manage to trade off queens and a pair of rook, that should be a technically winning endgame as the rook should dominate the bishop. }
