[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Early g3 & Early Qb3"]
[Black "Chapter 7 Exercise: #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/4bppp/4b3/2n1p3/Q2p4/6P1/PP1PPPBP/R1B1K1NR w KQ - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. Qd1
{ White's opening has been a complete catastrophe - even though he has two extra pawns, White has not finished the development. What's the fasted way to punish White? }
13... Bxa2 { Nice shot! Now ...Nb3 is impossible to parry. } 14. Rxa2 Nb3 15.
Ra8
{ Last chance but almost everything wins here.   15.Qxb3  Rxc1+  This would cost White the queen right away. }
15... Qd6 { After the rook trade ...Rxc1 will be crushing. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Early g3 & Early Qb3"]
[Black "Chapter 7 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2n2n2/3pp3/8/1QN3P1/PP1PPPBP/R1B1K1NR w KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

7. Bxd5 { This is a known mistake in the opening - do you remember why? } 7...
Nd4 8. Qc4 { Or   8.Bxf7+  Ke7  ,  which would lead to the same position. }
8... Bf5
{ An important precision - instead of going for the direct fork on c2 Black adds the ...Rc8 threat and the white bishop on d5 will be hanging.   8...Nc2+  This is playable but it's not very convicing as it leads to a mess.  9.Kd1  Nxa1  10.Bxf7+  Ke7  11.Nf3  Black has won a rook but the king is not feeling very secure, plus the knight on a1 will be lost at some point. }
9. Bxf7+ Ke7 10. Bd5
{ It's not clear what else should White do here - after 10.Nd5+ Black can just take the bishop on f7. }
10... Rc8 11. Qb4+ Ke8 12. Qa4+ Bd7
{ Next Black will play ...Nxd5 and fork on c2, given the opportunity. White is suffering material losses. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Early g3 & Early Qb3"]
[Black "Chapter 7 Exercise: #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r1k2r/pp1b2pp/3b4/5p1q/3np3/3P2P1/PP2PPBP/1RBQNRK1 w k - 0 20"]
[SetUp "1"]

20. Be3
{ Black has sacrificed a pawn for a strong initiative and now White tries to give it back and seeks counter-chances. What's the best way to continue the attack? }
20... Nxe2+ 21. Kh1 Rc6
{ A very important move that could be difficult to find - Black is ready to transfer the rook on the 6th rank and has no time for castling short. }
22. dxe4 fxe4 { This is necessary, otherwise White will just play Bf3 next. }
23. Qb3
{ The most stubborn move at White's disposal, keeping the black king in the center.   23.Bxe4  Bxg3!  Tactics work in Black's favor - Black doesn't mind to trade queens to win an extra pawn.  24.Nf3  Bg4!  White has no time to take the knight on e2 due to the checkmate. }
23... Rf8
{ Black yet again is threatening with ...Bxg3. The following moves could be a nice finale to a wonderful attack. }
24. Qxb7 Bxg3 25. fxg3 Nxg3+ { Black rips apart White's defenses. } 26. Kg1
Nxf1 27. Bxf1 Rxf1+ { The final shot. } 28. Kxf1 Qxh2
{ White is about to be mated. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "4.Nh4: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nh4
{ Strangely, this move has been tested only twice! It bears the resemblance of some lines from other repertoires @@StartBracket@@most notably, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Nf6  3.e5  Nh5  and then the idea to break the center with d6@@EndBracket@@. From a practical point of view, this can be tricky and produce unexpected results against an unprepared opponent, but all in all - it can't be a serious move. }
4... d5
{ It's tempting to go after the knight with  4...g5  but after  5.Ng2  Black has made only weaknesses. }
5. cxd5 cxd5
{ Going with the typical  5...Qxd5  here might not be the best choice as the knight on h4 here oddly is not under a direct attack and White can concentrate on the action in the center immediately. }
6. d4
{ This relieves any pressure against Black's center and has a much worse version of what White might play what we already analyzed in Chapters 3 and 4. The knight on h4 is misplaced. }
6... Nc6 7. Nc3 g6
{ Black makes sure that the white knight will stay on h4, but most importantly - prepares ...Bg7 with an idea to force White to push e3, thus not only closing his dark-squared bishop but also considerably weakening the white squares. }
8. Ng2 Bg7 9. Nf4 Nf6
{ The knight on f6 always feels more active than on e7 and now Black doesn't have to worry about the Bg5 pin. If allowed, Black might think about playing .. .g5 real soon, pushing back the knight back to h3, and keep it there by playing ...h6 next. Thus White's next move feels almost forced. }
10. e3 O-O 11. Bg2 Bf5 12. O-O Qd7
{ White is considerably worse - Black has the space advantage with an easy plan to exploit the light-squares at the kingside, while his only weakness on d5 can be easily protected. In this particular game, White got destroyed in 20 moves. }
13. f3 Rfe8 14. Bd2 Rad8 15. Qa4
{ White is running out of ideas - any fxe4 will be answered by ...dxe4 and Black gains another outpost on d5, while the kingside can be opened up with the typical ...h5-h4. }
15... g5
{ A common idea to push away the white knight to a more passive square. } 16.
Nfe2 exf3
{ Black is about to take the e4 square with a storm.  17.Rxf3  Ne4  18.Qd1  a mistake but White's position is already terrible. Black finishes the game with a nice tactical shot.  18...Bg4  19.Rf1  Nxd4!  20.exd4  Nxc3  White loses a lot of material. 0-1 Niklasch, O. @@StartBracket@@2310@@EndBracket@@ Gustafsson, J. @@StartBracket@@2626@@EndBracket@@ GER CupT 2017. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "4.Nh4: #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nh4
{ Strangely, this move has been tested only twice! It bears the resemblance of some lines from other repertoires @@StartBracket@@most notably, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Nf6  3.e5  Nh5  and then the idea to break the center with d6@@EndBracket@@. From a practical point of view, this can be tricky and produce unexpected results against an unprepared opponent, but all in all - it can't be a serious move. }
