{ Going with the typical  5...Qxd5  here might not be the best choice as the knight on h4 here oddly is not under a direct attack and White can concentrate on the action in the center immediately. }
6. d3
{ That's White's idea - try to break the center, either creating a target on e4 or d5 and at the same time provoke Black into ...g5. }
6... Nc6
{ Black seldom wants to take on d3 himself - this would allow White to recapture the pawn with the queen and create an isolated pawn on d5 to target. }
7. Nc3
{ Increasing the pressure against the center before trading the pawns won't help. }
7... Bb4 { Now White can't take on e4 anymore. } 8. a3
{ 8.dxe4  d4  transposes to an already covered line. } 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nf6
{ Black is just better, mainly because of the awkward placement of the knight on  h4  , plus the weak pawn on  c3  . If White would play here  10.dxe4  ,  Black can respond with  10...Nxe4  and going for a quick castle. }
