4. Nh4
{ Strangely, this move has been tested only twice! It bears the resemblance of some lines from other repertoires @@StartBracket@@most notably, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  g6  2.d4  Nf6  3.e5  Nh5  and then the idea to break the center with d6@@EndBracket@@. From a practical point of view, this can be tricky and produce unexpected results against an unprepared opponent, but all in all - it can't be a serious move. }
4... d5
{ It's tempting to go after the knight with  4...g5  but after  5.Ng2  Black has made only weaknesses. }
5. cxd5 cxd5
{ Going with the typical  5...Qxd5  here might not be the best choice as the knight on h4 here oddly is not under a direct attack and White can concentrate on the action in the center immediately. }
6. d3
{ That's White's idea - try to break the center, either creating a target on e4 or d5 and at the same time provoke Black into ...g5. }
6... Nc6
{ Black seldom wants to take on d3 himself - this would allow White to recapture the pawn with the queen and create an isolated pawn on d5 to target. }
7. dxe4 { The most direct approach. } 7... Bb4+
{ This is an important check, otherwise Black will have to deal with the Qxd8 consequences. }
8. Nd2
{ Probably one of the most logical moves as White is preparing to play a3 next to challenge the pin and also the pawn on e4. }
8... dxe4 9. a3 Bxd2+
{ The most practical choice.   9...Be7  10.Nxe4  Qxd1  is very interesting but less forced, but it's clear that Black has full compensation for the pawn after ...Be6, ...Nf6, and ...O-O-O. }
10. Bxd2
{ The most obvious move - the dark-squared bishop is going to be rerouted to c3 while the knight from h4 to e3. Mainly because White can't properly bring the light-squared bishop into the game, the game remains equal, otherwise, that powerful bishop on c3 could cause some headaches. }
10... Nf6 11. Bc3 Qe7
{ This is an important move - as you will see later, the black queen will control a lot more squares than the white queen, plus on e7 it guards the knight on f6 against doubling the pawns, and extra protect the pawn on e4. }
12. Ng2
{ Necessary otherwise  12.Bg2  will run into  g5!  and the knight is trapped. }
12... O-O 13. Ne3
{ From afar White's position looks nice - he's got a great bishop on c3 and a great blocking knight on e3. However, White is is still underdeveloped and the bishop on f1 is not doing anything. It's critical to trade that annoying knight on e3 and strengthen then control over the center as quickly as possible. }
13... Rd8 14. Qa4 Nd5 15. Nxd5 Rxd5
{ That's it - the white knight is gone and the pawn on e4 can now be easily defended. }
16. Bg2 Bf5 17. O-O Rad8
{ Black is solid with no weaknesses. It's not clear how White will bring his light-squared bishop into the game without making commital weaknesses. }
