[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "4.Nd4 and 5.d3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nd4
{ The most logical move - White's idea is to occupy the central square and then with the following d3, Nc3 and Bg2 try to undermine Black's pawn center. }
4... d5
{ The most direct continuation - Black is challenging the center before developing the kingside knight. The reason is that the inclusion of ... Nf6 and White's Nc3 won't allow White to take on d5 with the queen anymore. }
5. d3
{ This is a rare but still quite decent attempt to keep the knight on d4 and destroy Black's pawn center. If Black would take on d3, White would recapture with the queen and after Bg2 and Nc3 pressure the center, so that Black would continue with ... cxd4. }
5... Bc5
{ This is a very nice intermezzo move to know - the white knight must be invited to vacate the central square otherwise it will remain there for a long time. The immediate  5...dxc4  would be interesting if not for  6.dxe4  -  I feel that White is better here, mainly because of the powerful pawn center and the c4 pawn is more likely to become a real weakness than the e4 pawn. }
6. dxe4
{ That's the only reasonable way for White to keep the knight on d4 as   6.e3  is a worse alternative but the bottom line is that Black will easily get a good game here. }
6... dxe4 7. Be3
{ White is going to finish his development, having a nice knight on d4, an outpost for the bishop on e3 which should be strengthened with h3, and plans to attack at the queenside. However, Black's development also is quite straightforward with no visible weaknesses in the position. Black should be a little careful not to miss any white knight jumps from d4 so that the bishop on c5 doesn't hang. }
7... Nf6 8. Nc3 Qe7 { So far this is almost forced and makes the most sense. }
9. Bg2 { This allows Black to eliminate that powerful dark-squared bishop. }
9... Ng4
{ Should White accept the pawn on e4, this will give Black excellent compensation, for example,   10.Nxe4  Nxe3  11.fxe3  Bb4+  12.Kf2  f5  and the queenside knight will quickly join the action at the kingside, hunting the weakened white king. }
10. O-O
{ Stokke,K @@StartBracket@@2336@@EndBracket@@-Hammer,J @@StartBracket@@2621@@EndBracket@@ NOR-ch rapid Drammen 2018. }
10... f5
{ This is an improvement, which comes with an idea to take on e3 later as immediately playing  10...Nxe3  @@StartBracket@@what happened in the game@@EndBracket@@ Black can't continue with ...f5 immediately because the pawn is under attack. Here it's not clear if White can retreat with the bishop as Black has a strong idea of  ...e3!  with an idea to play ...Nf2 next and White will have to sacrifice material, as the knight on d4 is lacking support. }
11. Bf4
{ Otherwise Black will just take the bishop on e3 and enjoy a better game because of the space advantage and two bishops. }
11... g5
{ The immediate  11...e3  is less clear as after  12.f3  Nf2  13.Qa4  Bxd4  14.Nd5!  White forks on c7 and wins the rook. The position remains incredibly complex. }
12. h3
{ If the white bishop will retreat, then the same ...e3 threat will come with even great power as at the end of the line White won't have that fork on c7 because the bishop on f4 is gone. }
12... gxf4 13. hxg4 e3
{ Black is ripping apart White's defenses - now White has to walk a tightrope because Black's dark-squared bishop is ready to deliver some big blows. }
14. gxf4
{ Apparently the only human-looking move, as the other looks much riskier. }
14... exf2+ 15. Kxf2
{ Capturing with the rook is a huge blunder because of  15.Rxf2  Qe3  . } 15...
Qh4+ 16. Kg1 fxg4 17. Qd2 Na6
{ Even if Black won't mate White immediately, he's still left with two strong bishops and dangerous passed pawns at the kingside. The immediate ...g3 with ...Qh2+ might not give immediate results but this idea can be prepared. }
*

