{ White is going to finish his development, having a nice knight on d4, an outpost for the bishop on e3 which should be strengthened with h3, and plans to attack at the queenside. However, Black's development also is quite straightforward with no visible weaknesses in the position. Black should be a little careful not to miss any white knight jumps from d4 so that the bishop on c5 doesn't hang. }
7... Nf6 8. Nc3 Qe7 { So far this is almost forced and makes the most sense. }
9. h3
{ Here I think White has to spend a tempo to secure the bishop's outpost on e3. }
9... O-O
{ Black is threatening to create an immediate pin with ...Rd8 so the white queen must be moved. }
10. Qc2 Nbd7
{ Black's plan here is simple - continue with ...Re8 to protect the pawn on e4, include ...h6 to make sure that Bg5 won't cause some annoyances with defending the e4 pawn, continue with ...Nf8, and start looking forward to creating some threats at the kingside with ...Ng6, followed by ...Qe5-h5. }
11. Bg2 Re8 12. Rd1
{ White could castle first but it makes sense for White to toy with the idea of Nf5, trade the bishops on c5, and continue with Nd6. With the king in the center, it doesn't work. }
12... h6 13. O-O
{ The immediate plan to land the knight on d6 will backfire.  13.Nf5  Qe5  14.Bxc5  Nxc5  15.Nd6  Nd3+  and oops! }
13... Nf8
{ Now an incoming Nf5 might be a problem as the white king has moved away from the center. The way I see it, White here has two plans - either try to expand at the queenside with a pawn push or try to grab the d-file and perhaps pressure the pawn on e4 in the process. Black plans to play ...Ng6, ...Qe5, and ...Qh5, but it might be necessary to pay a little attention to what White is planning at the queenside first. }
14. Qd2
{ A little caution is in order as White is thinking about Na4 next and the dark-squared bishop has no good squares to retreat as on d6 it's jumping under Nxc6 tactics and Black loses some material. The bishop has to retreat so that Black can get onto his plan of attacking the kingside. }
14... Bb6 15. Nc2
{ White wants to trade the bishops, position his other knight on e3, trade queens on d6 and pressure the e4 pawn. It makes sense to keep queens on the board to remind White that something might happen at the kingside as well, as soon as Black will be ready. }
15... Bc7 16. Bf4 Rd8
{ Consistent with the plan. By the way, the black queen controls more squares than its colleague anyway so that wouldn't be an equal trade. }
17. Qc1 Bf5 18. Bxc7 Qxc7 19. Ne3 Bg6
{ Black has nothing to worry about, his position is rock solid. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "4.Nd4 and 5.d3: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nd4
{ The most logical move - White's idea is to occupy the central square and then with the following d3, Nc3 and Bg2 try to undermine Black's pawn center. }
4... d5
{ The most direct continuation - Black is challenging the center before developing the kingside knight. The reason is that the inclusion of ... Nf6 and White's Nc3 won't allow White to take on d5 with the queen anymore. }
5. d3
{ This is a rare but still quite decent attempt to keep the knight on d4 and destroy Black's pawn center. If Black would take on d3, White would recapture with the queen and after Bg2 and Nc3 pressure the center, so that Black would continue with ... cxd4. }
5... Bc5
{ This is a very nice intermezzo move to know - the white knight must be invited to vacate the central square otherwise it will remain there for a long time. The immediate  5...dxc4  would be interesting if not for  6.dxe4  -  I feel that White is better here, mainly because of the powerful pawn center and the c4 pawn is more likely to become a real weakness than the e4 pawn. }
6. dxe4
{ That's the only reasonable way for White to keep the knight on d4 as   6.e3  is a worse alternative but the bottom line is that Black will easily get a good game here. }
6... dxe4 7. Be3
{ White is going to finish his development, having a nice knight on d4, an outpost for the bishop on e3 which should be strengthened with h3, and plans to attack at the queenside. However, Black's development also is quite straightforward with no visible weaknesses in the position. Black should be a little careful not to miss any white knight jumps from d4 so that the bishop on c5 doesn't hang. }
7... Nf6 8. Nc3 Qe7 { So far this is almost forced and makes the most sense. }
9. h3
{ Here I think White has to spend a tempo to secure the bishop's outpost on e3. }
9... O-O
{ Black is threatening to create an immediate pin with ...Rd8 so the white queen must be moved. }
10. Qc2 Nbd7
{ Black's plan here is simple - continue with ...Re8 to protect the pawn on e4, include ...h6 to make sure that Bg5 won't cause some annoyances with defending the e4 pawn, continue with ...Nf8, and start looking forward to creating some threats at the kingside with ...Ng6, followed by ...Qe5-h5. }
11. Bg2 Re8 12. Rd1
{ White could castle first but it makes sense for White to toy with the idea of Nf5, trade the bishops on c5, and continue with Nd6. With the king in the center, it doesn't work. }
12... h6 13. O-O
{ The immediate plan to land the knight on d6 will backfire.  13.Nf5  Qe5  14.Bxc5  Nxc5  15.Nd6  Nd3+  and oops! }
13... Nf8
{ Now an incoming Nf5 might be a problem as the white king has moved away from the center. The way I see it, White here has two plans - either try to expand at the queenside with a pawn push or try to grab the d-file and perhaps pressure the pawn on e4 in the process. Black plans to play ...Ng6, ...Qe5, and ...Qh5, but it might be necessary to pay a little attention to what White is planning at the queenside first. }
14. a3 { White is preparing the obvious b4 push. } 14... a5
{ First Black should take care of the pawn advancement at the queenside as the immediate   14...Ng6  will be answered with  15.b4  ,  followed by c5 and b5, and Black has no time to start his operations at the kingside. }
15. Na4 Ba7 { It's very easy for White to go astray here. } 16. Qc3 Qe5 17. Nc2
{ Now a simple capture on c3 and e3 should ensure Black an equal game, but you can also go for a more ambitious approach. }
17... Qh5 18. Bxa7 Bxh3
{ Black has a powerful attack that is not easy to parry. Simple  18...Rxa7  also should be good but it allows White to play  19.g4  and the white queen is quickly rerouted to the kingside to help the white king. }
19. Bd4 Ng4 20. f3 Bxg2 21. fxg4 { White has nothing better here. } 21... Qh1+
22. Kf2 Bxf1 23. Rxf1 Qh2+ 24. Ke1 e3
{ Black cuts off the white queen from the g3 square while the pawn on g7 is taboo because of ...Rad8 and ...Qxg3+ now comes with a deadly effect. }
25. Nxe3 Qxg3+ 26. Rf2 { 26.Kd2  Rad8  and White is only asking for trouble. }
26... Qg1+ 27. Rf1 Qg3+ { There's nothing better than a perpetual check. } *

