[Round "?"]
[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "4.Nd4 and 5.d3: #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nd4
{ The most logical move - White's idea is to occupy the central square and then with the following d3, Nc3 and Bg2 try to undermine Black's pawn center. }
4... d5
{ The most direct continuation - Black is challenging the center before developing the kingside knight. The reason is that the inclusion of ... Nf6 and White's Nc3 won't allow White to take on d5 with the queen anymore. }
5. d3
{ This is a rare but still quite decent attempt to keep the knight on d4 and destroy Black's pawn center. If Black would take on d3, White would recapture with the queen and after Bg2 and Nc3 pressure the center, so that Black would continue with ... cxd4. }
5... Bc5
{ This is a very nice intermezzo move to know - the white knight must be invited to vacate the central square otherwise it will remain there for a long time. The immediate  5...dxc4  would be interesting if not for  6.dxe4  -  I feel that White is better here, mainly because of the powerful pawn center and the c4 pawn is more likely to become a real weakness than the e4 pawn. }
6. Nb3 { White retreats with a tempo, attacking the bishop on c5. } 6... Bb4+
{ The simplest choice, to relieve the pressure in the center with an upcoming ...dxc4,  keeping the e4 pawn.  6...e3!?  is an interesting way to complicate matters by ruining White's pawn structure but White doesn't have to accept the sacrifice and instead plays  7.Nxc5  Qa5+  8.Nc3  exf2+  9.Kxf2  with a complex game. }
7. Nc3
{ This feels slightly more ambitious but in reality, White is risking to get here a worse position. }
7... dxc4 8. dxc4 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1
{ All of this is forced and now instead of the tempting ...f5 which here actually is an inaccuracy, Black has something better. }
9... Nf6 10. Bg2 Be6
{ Black is happy to trade the e4 pawn for the c4 pawn because the white king is not feeling exactly comfortable in the center, especially since the position is opening. The more solid  10...Bf5  was possible as well. Now White has to trade the pawns. }
11. Nd2 { This is a positional mistake. } 11... e3
{ This motif to ruin the pawn structure is quite standard - in addition to the possibility to target the weak pawns Black gets an outpost on e5 for his knight as well. }
12. fxe3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Nbd7
{ Even though White is up a pawn, he's suffering here and the doubled pawns make easy targets. }
