{ Like I already explained before, here ....exd3 is not good if White can recapture with the queen and quite inevitably forming a pawn majority at the kingside. }
9. dxc4 f5
{ This comes with an idea to strengthen the pawn on e4 as quickly as possible, so that after White's f3 push Black is not obliged to move with the pawn but let it stay there and cramp White's position a little bit. It doesn't mean that Black is not ready to play ...exf3 at a later stage, when the c5 won't be such a glaring positional threat. }
10. Nc3
{ Taking on d8 may not be mandatory for White as the black king will feel perfectly safe on c7 and White's having the same ideas about the c2 square. }
10... Qxd2+
{ Now Black can safely take on d2 himself as White no longer is threatening with c5 and Nc4, and Black has gained an important tempo to protect the e4 pawn in advance and thus is not forced to take on f3. }
11. Kxd2 Nf6
{ With the king still on e8, the black king is not obliged to castle, and instead it could be positioned on f7, to be closer to the center as soon as the endgame will start. }
12. f3
{ Now we're following the only game in this line between two leading Chinese grandmasters Ding Liren and Yu Yangyi from the 2019 FIDE World Cup. White was very close to getting a worse position.   If White would include here  12.Bh3  to stop ...Nbd7 then after  12...Na6  13.f3  exf3!  the bishop on h3 is a loss of time. }
12... Nbd7
{ A very nice resource - White is reminded of his weak pawn on c4, winning Black a tempo. }
13. fxe4 Ne5 14. c5 { There's hardly anything better. } 14... fxe4 15. Bg2 Bf5
{ White spends the remaining part of the game, trying to equalize the game. The pawn on e4 is well protected but the weak squares in White's camp, most notably on e3 can cause some headaches. }
16. Raf1 Nc4+ 17. Kc1 Ne3 18. Rf4 { This is already the only move. } 18... O-O
19. Nd4
{ the pawn on  e4  can't be taken as  19.Bxe4  Nxe4  20.Nxe4  will meet a surprising resource  20...Ng2!  and White loses material. }
19... Nxg2 { Or  19...Bg6  20.Bh3  and White is holding. } 20. Rxf5 Ne3 21. Re5
Rae8 22. Rxe8 Rxe8
{ The position has simplified - Black has a little space advantage and hopes to target the weakness on c5. In the game, both players quickly agreed for a draw because of repetition but Black could have played on.  23.Nc2  Nf5  24.Na3  Ne3   24...Re7  followed by ...Kf7-g6 and ...h5, and Black would still be pressing. Black was probably happy with the draw because of the match strategy.  25.Nc2  Nf5  26.Na3  Ne3  27.Nc2  1/2-1/2 Ding, L. @@StartBracket@@2811@@EndBracket@@ - Yu. Y. @@StartBracket@@2763@@EndBracket@@ FIDE World Cup 2019, Black played a perfect game. }
