[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "5.cxd5 and 6.Nb3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nd4
{ The most logical move - White's idea is to occupy the central square and then with the following d3, Nc3 and Bg2 try to undermine Black's pawn center. }
4... d5
{ The most direct continuation - Black is challenging the center before developing the kingside knight. The reason is that the inclusion of ... Nf6 and White's Nc3 won't allow White to take on d5 with the queen anymore. }
5. cxd5
{ White doesn't want to allow Black to play ...dxc4 next and instead clarifies the situation in the center. }
5... Qxd5
{ Oddly, here this move is the best while in the standard Sicilian Alapin this maneuver is considered to be not so dangerous. That's because of the lack of an alternative because  5...cxd5  will feel too slow because of the extra tempo for White. }
6. Nb3
{ This move is not very popular - White is positioning the knight on the awkward b3 square so that White can challenge the e4 pawn with Nc3, Qc2, and Bg2. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3
{ Or  7.Bg2  Qh5   - the order of the moves here is irrelevant and actually would allow Black to improvise a little with the alternative  7...Bf5  ,  bringing the queen to d7. With the knight on c3 first, this option is impossible. }
7... Qh5
{ Black is threatening with ...Bh3 to trade off the light-squared bishops which also would make the white king more vulnerable after castling short. The immediate  8.Qc2  is easily parried with  8...Bf5 }
8. d3
{ This is a small concession - with the white knight on b3 it makes more sense to target the pawn on e4 rather than trading it. }
8... exd3 9. Qxd3 Na6
{ Black has wonderful coordination of his pieces - ...Nb4 might already be a direct threat, and then there's the ...Bh3 with attack ideas at the kingside. Now we're going to follow a game between two famous grandmasters, Bent Larsen against Boris Gulko, where White got into trouble very quickly. }
10. Nd4
{ Objectively this is not good but it's difficult to evaluate the consequences of the ...Nb4 threat. }
10... Nb4 11. Qe3+
{ Retreating with the queen to d1 would allow Black to play ...Bc5 with the ... Bxd4 threat and fork on c2. White already is behind in development. }
11... Be7 12. a3 Nbd5
{ White seemingly doesn't even have time to finish the development! } 13. Nxd5
{ Larsen,B @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@-Gulko, B @@StartBracket@@2590@@EndBracket@@ Hastings 1988. }
13... Qxd5
{ A little improvement over the game - Black is starting the decisive action right after the opening. }
