[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "6.e3 Nf6: #2 (What NOT to do)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nd4
{ The most logical move - White's idea is to occupy the central square and then with the following d3, Nc3 and Bg2 try to undermine Black's pawn center. }
4... d5
{ The most direct continuation - Black is challenging the center before developing the kingside knight. The reason is that the inclusion of ... Nf6 and White's Nc3 won't allow White to take on d5 with the queen anymore. }
5. cxd5
{ White doesn't want to allow Black to play ...dxc4 next and instead clarifies the situation in the center. }
5... Qxd5
{ Oddly, here this move is the best while in the standard Sicilian Alapin this maneuver is considered to be not so dangerous. That's because of the lack of an alternative because  5...cxd5  will feel too slow because of the extra tempo for White. }
6. e3
{ This is the only serious alternative to Nc2 which will be analyzed in the next chapter. White keeps the knight on d4 and mostly pins his hopes to d3 thrust later, giving White a pawn majority at the kingside. Another plan that White might be thinking of as an alternative is pushing f3 to fight for a strong pawn center. }
6... Nf6
{ This was my initial idea, going for the main move with intentions to make a normal development and play ...Bc5 later. However, I noticed one high-level GM game between Sam Shankland and Jeffery Xiong, played in the Summer Chess Classic 2019 A tournament in Saint Louis. Incidentally, I also happened to play there and observe them play, although I was participating in the C tournament @@StartBracket@@which I won in the end@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Bg2
{ White pins the queen and is threatening to play d3 next which is a more dangerous move than the much more common  7.Nc3 }
7... Qe5 8. d3 exd3 9. Nd2
{ Or castle short first but perhaps it doesn't matter. The idea is that White doesn't develop his knight on the standard c3 square but eyes for a more active role on c4. I did some analysis in this line and was unable to win a clear path to equality for Black. }
9... Bc5 10. Nc4 Qh5
{ This is what Xiong played in the game but there's an alternative. } 11. Qxh5
Nxh5 12. Nb3 { Or castling short and going Rd1 next also looks interesting. }
12... Be7 13. Bd2 O-O 14. Ne5 Nf6 15. Nxd3
{ Shankland,S @@StartBracket@@2717@@EndBracket@@ -Xiong,J @@StartBracket@@2684@@EndBracket@@ Summer Chess Classic A 2019. White has recaptured the pawn and appears to be slightly pressing. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "6.e3 Mainline: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nd4
{ The most logical move - White's idea is to occupy the central square and then with the following d3, Nc3 and Bg2 try to undermine Black's pawn center. }
4... d5
{ The most direct continuation - Black is challenging the center before developing the kingside knight. The reason is that the inclusion of ... Nf6 and White's Nc3 won't allow White to take on d5 with the queen anymore. }
5. cxd5
{ White doesn't want to allow Black to play ...dxc4 next and instead clarifies the situation in the center. }
5... Qxd5
{ Oddly, here this move is the best while in the standard Sicilian Alapin this maneuver is considered to be not so dangerous. That's because of the lack of an alternative because  5...cxd5  will feel too slow because of the extra tempo for White. }
6. e3
{ This is the only serious alternative to Nc2 which will be analyzed in the next chapter. White keeps the knight on d4 and mostly pins his hopes to d3 thrust later, giving White a pawn majority at the kingside. Another plan that White might be thinking of as an alternative is pushing f3 to fight for a strong pawn center. }
6... Bc5
{ Before developing the kingside I find that the precise thing to do is to attack the knight on d4 immediately. This order of the moves don't allow White a tricky idea where I was unable to find complete equality for Black. }
7. Nc3
{ White can't play  7.d3  as Black could simply respond with  7...exd3  and the white rook on h1 is under attack. Any immediate knight retreats from d4 will most likely transpose to one of the covered lines but doing so immediately might give Black a few more options. If the dark-squared bishop on c5 is challenged, typically it's best to retreat with the bishop to b6 where it will keep an eye on what's happening in the center. }
7... Qe5
{ Black centralizes the queen, protects the pawn on e4, and is threatening to take on d4. Now White's got a set of choices here. }
8. Bg2
{ White is increasing the pressure against the e4 pawn and going for quick development. Taking on d4 immediately is tempting but Black will be fighting for equality after  8...Bxd4  9.exd4  Qxd4  10.Nxe4  ,  followed by d3, O-O, and preparing the dark-squared bishop on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
8... Nf6 9. Qc2
{ Now White is being very direct and forcing Black to take on d4,  but this costs White a tempo.  9.d3  or  9.O-O  O-O  10.d3  would just transpose to the main setup. }
9... Bxd4 10. exd4 Qxd4 11. Nxe4 { All of this is forced. } 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4
{ Kourkounakis,I @@StartBracket@@2355@@EndBracket@@ -Chekhov,V @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ Peer Gynt Gausdal 1990. }
12... Na6 { This was a little more aggressive than what happened in the game. }
13. O-O
{ 13.Bxc6+  with a threat to win the rook on a8 would be a huge mistake as Black would just accept the sacrifice and after  13...bxc6  14.Qxc6+  Kd8  start a decisive attack against the stranded king with ...Qd3, preparing to play ... Re8 and ...Nb4 next.   If White would start with  13.d3  first then after  13...Bh3  again the  14.Bxc6+  threat doesn't work, this time because of  14...Kf8  15.Be4  f5  and ...Nb4 next. }
13... Nb4 14. Qb1 Bh3 15. Re1 O-O-O
{ Black has a strong initiative - the black knight will land on d3. } *

