1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nd4
{ The most logical move - White's idea is to occupy the central square and then with the following d3, Nc3 and Bg2 try to undermine Black's pawn center. }
4... d5
{ The most direct continuation - Black is challenging the center before developing the kingside knight. The reason is that the inclusion of ... Nf6 and White's Nc3 won't allow White to take on d5 with the queen anymore. }
5. cxd5
{ White doesn't want to allow Black to play ...dxc4 next and instead clarifies the situation in the center. }
5... Qxd5
{ Oddly, here this move is the best while in the standard Sicilian Alapin this maneuver is considered to be not so dangerous. That's because of the lack of an alternative because  5...cxd5  will feel too slow because of the extra tempo for White. }
6. e3
{ This is the only serious alternative to Nc2 which will be analyzed in the next chapter. White keeps the knight on d4 and mostly pins his hopes to d3 thrust later, giving White a pawn majority at the kingside. Another plan that White might be thinking of as an alternative is pushing f3 to fight for a strong pawn center. }
6... Bc5
{ Before developing the kingside I find that the precise thing to do is to attack the knight on d4 immediately. This order of the moves don't allow White a tricky idea where I was unable to find complete equality for Black. }
7. Nc3
{ White can't play  7.d3  as Black could simply respond with  7...exd3  and the white rook on h1 is under attack. Any immediate knight retreats from d4 will most likely transpose to one of the covered lines but doing so immediately might give Black a few more options. If the dark-squared bishop on c5 is challenged, typically it's best to retreat with the bishop to b6 where it will keep an eye on what's happening in the center. }
7... Qe5
{ Black centralizes the queen, protects the pawn on e4, and is threatening to take on d4. Now White's got a set of choices here. }
8. Nb3
{ Very similarly like with the knight's jump on e2, also this retreat makes little sense as pushing the d-pawn could be done with the knight on d4. }
8... Bb6
{ Here the black bishop will feel much more active than on e7 - the center inevitably will open sooner or later and the bishop on b6 will have a say immediately. }
9. Bg2 Nf6 10. f3
{ This is an alternative, played almost 50 years ago by the German chess legend Robert Huebner against the even more legendary Viktor 'The Terrible' Kortschnoj! White shows his ambitions to fight for the center but with the knight on the awkward b3 square it makes a weird impression. }
10... exf3 11. Qxf3
{ Huebner, R-Kortschnoj, V match 1973. Taking with the bishop would allow Black to continue with  11.Bxf3  Bh3  and ask some direct questions about how exactly White is going to castle. }
11... O-O
{ Black could just continue a natural development instead of the strange-looking  11...Qf5  which was played in the game and White can't claim the center so easily. }
12. d4 Qe7 13. O-O
{ White has no time for the e4 push with the king in the center - the pawn on d4 would be lacking support either because of ...a5 or ...Be6 and ...Na6. }
13... Be6 14. Bd2 Nbd7
{ It's not clear how White is going to play e4 as the knight on b3 will always be under attack and the d4 pawn will fall. At the moment the e4 and d5 squares look like nice candidates for potential outposts for Black's light pieces. }
