{ Of course, taking on d4 would be a bad trade as White not only will get a strong center but also two powerful bishops. The reason why  8...Nf6  is not so good here is that White would capture  9.dxe4  and after  9...Nxe4  10.Bg2  challenge the knight. Capturing the knight on c3 would just strengthen the white knight on d4 and open the b-file for the queenside rook. }
9. Qxd3
{ Technically the only normal-looking move. White could try to avoid some trades in the center with  9.Nf3  first but Black is quite happy placing his queen on h5 which allows Bh3 to happen with standard development,   while  9.Nb3  would just transpose to one of the covered sidelines, which is not particularly good for White. }
9... Nf6 10. Bg2
{ Up to this moment this is the best play between both sides if White chose to play 6. e3 and keep the knight in the center. Now Black's got an interesting choice. }
10... O-O
{ Although there's a good-looking alternative to force the game into an equal endgame, this continuation is a little more fun and also ambitious! }
11. Nf3
{ This is a novelty, to be played - I imagine that someone will try it sooner or later. }
11... Qh5
{ Black is threatening to play either ...Bg4 or ...Bh3 so White's response is quite logical. }
12. h3
{ Castling short here probably is just fine but White can quickly get an inferior position. }
12... Bb6 13. b4
{ Given the circumstances, this makes sense - White takes away the retreat c5 and a5 squares for the black queen and is either preparing to push g4 next with a perpetual attack of the queen or just Bb2. The immediate 13.g4  would allow Black to play   13...Qc5  ,  then regroup with ...Qe7. }
13... Rd8
{ Black prepares to play ...Nd5 next so that the black queen on h5 doesn't have to worry about the g4 push. }
14. Qe2 Nd5
{ Not mandatory - it is possible to wait for a move or two and let White make the commital g4 move which only forces repetition of the position after ...Qg6, White's Ne5, and ...Qg5. }
15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. O-O Bf5
{ The light-squared bishop will land on either e4 or d3, depending on how White will play this out. }
17. Nh4 Bd3
{ An important accuracy - the immediate  17...Be4  would allow White to play  18.Qg4  and after  18...Bxg2  has a very unpleasant intermezzo move  19.Bb2  , threatening a mate on  g7  . }
18. Qb2
{ The only good move since  18.Qd2  allows  18...Qb5!  with ...Na6 next and the white queen is misplaced. }
18... Be4 { Now it's time to trade the bishops and simplify the position. } 19.
Bxe4 Qxe4 20. Bd2 Nd7 21. Bc3 g5
{ This is very energetic although Black should be fine also after  21...g6  22.Bh8  Kf8  ,  preparing to play ...Bc7-e5 next. }
22. Ng2 { Playing  22.Bh8  would cost White a full piece after  22...f6! }
22... Bc7
{ Here both sides should have about equal chances. From a strategic point of view I like Black's position more due to the centralized queen and either the incoming ...Ne5 or ...Be5, while the white knight on g2 appears to be very passive unless Black will somehow miss an incoming e4 push and Ne3-f5. }
