{ The most direct continuation - Black is challenging the center before developing the kingside knight. The reason is that the inclusion of ... Nf6 and White's Nc3 won't allow White to take on d5 with the queen anymore. }
5. cxd5
{ White doesn't want to allow Black to play ...dxc4 next and instead clarifies the situation in the center. }
5... Qxd5
{ Oddly, here this move is the best while in the standard Sicilian Alapin this maneuver is considered to be not so dangerous. That's because of the lack of an alternative because  5...cxd5  will feel too slow because of the extra tempo for White. }
6. e3
{ This is the only serious alternative to Nc2 which will be analyzed in the next chapter. White keeps the knight on d4 and mostly pins his hopes to d3 thrust later, giving White a pawn majority at the kingside. Another plan that White might be thinking of as an alternative is pushing f3 to fight for a strong pawn center. }
6... Bc5
{ Before developing the kingside I find that the precise thing to do is to attack the knight on d4 immediately. This order of the moves don't allow White a tricky idea where I was unable to find complete equality for Black. }
7. Nc3
{ White can't play  7.d3  as Black could simply respond with  7...exd3  and the white rook on h1 is under attack. Any immediate knight retreats from d4 will most likely transpose to one of the covered lines but doing so immediately might give Black a few more options. If the dark-squared bishop on c5 is challenged, typically it's best to retreat with the bishop to b6 where it will keep an eye on what's happening in the center. }
7... Qe5
{ Black centralizes the queen, protects the pawn on e4, and is threatening to take on d4. Now White's got a set of choices here. }
8. d3
{ The main move which will inevitably transpose to the main lines, had Black played 6...Nf6 instead of 6...Bc5. }
8... exd3
{ Of course, taking on d4 would be a bad trade as White not only will get a strong center but also two powerful bishops. The reason why  8...Nf6  is not so good here is that White would capture  9.dxe4  and after  9...Nxe4  10.Bg2  challenge the knight. Capturing the knight on c3 would just strengthen the white knight on d4 and open the b-file for the queenside rook. }
9. Qxd3
{ Technically the only normal-looking move. White could try to avoid some trades in the center with  9.Nf3  first but Black is quite happy placing his queen on h5 which allows Bh3 to happen with standard development,   while  9.Nb3  would just transpose to one of the covered sidelines, which is not particularly good for White. }
9... Nf6 10. Bg2
{ Up to this moment this is the best play between both sides if White chose to play 6. e3 and keep the knight in the center. Now Black's got an interesting choice. }
10... O-O
{ Although there's a good-looking alternative to force the game into an equal endgame, this continuation is a little more fun and also ambitious! }
11. Nf3
{ This is a novelty, to be played - I imagine that someone will try it sooner or later. }
11... Qh5
{ Black is threatening to play either ...Bg4 or ...Bh3 so White's response is quite logical. }
12. h3
{ Castling short here probably is just fine but White can quickly get an inferior position. }
12... Bb6 13. e4
{ White removes Black's access to the f5 and d5 squares and might push either g4 or play Be3 next. }
13... Re8
{ Black increases the pressure against the e4 pawn and since White can't castle short because if the h3 pawn and then there's the ... Na6-b4 threat under the horizon, the next move feels almost forced. }
14. g4 Qa5
{ This comes with a direct threat to take the pawn on e4 and the queenside knight is ready to be transferred to either e5 or c5. }
15. O-O
{ Keeping the white king in the center with  15.Bd2  allows Black to play  15...Nxe4!  and ...Qd5 next, although White should survive the scare and win back the pawn after a couple of moves. }
15... Nbd7
{ Now ...Nc5 already is a serious threat and White has to do something about it. An alternate career for the queenside knight is through f8 to g6 and hope for promotion on f4. }
16. Bd2 Ne5
{ If White won't take it, the knight will be rerouted to g6 with intentions to jump to the juicy f4 square. }
17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Kh1
{ This retreat is logical and with intentions to push f4, but it meets a sweet end with a beautiful combination. }
18... Rd8 19. Qe2 { Or  19.Qc2  ,  it doesn't matter. } 19... Bxg4 20. hxg4
Rxd2 21. Qxd2 Nxg4 { White is about to be mated. } *

