{ So far all players have played this logical move without hesitation as castling short is something that White will want to do anyway. If White wants to avoid the incoming threat of ...Rd8,  then I guess  11.Nf3  is the only try   as  11.Nb3  will just transpose to some of the covered lines with  11...Bb6  and ...Rd8 next. }
11... Rd8
{ The choice so far by such strong grandmasters as Anish Giri, David Navara, and Vidit Santosh Gujrathi and that's going to be also our move here. Black pins the knight on d4 but not necessarily with intentions to win a pawn. }
12. Nce2
{ This protects the pawn on d4 but also loses some time and control of the central squares. Here Black has a good choice between an ambitious move or going for equality. }
12... Bf8
{ I decided to leave this as the main move since the dark square bishop as an extra will protect the c5 pawn and can be rerouted to g7 a couple of moves later. Black is threatening to play ...c5 and ...Nc6 next, gaining some space advantage at the queenside which is the downside of the Nce2 maneuver. }
13. b3
{ The most logical response as the dark-squared bishop belongs in the a1-h8 diagonal. It looks a little risky because of the pin on the d-file but that's not a problem for White as also the rook on d8 is hanging. }
13... c5 14. Nf3 Qe7
{ There's no time to take the rook on a1 as also the rook on d8 is hanging and Black is a little behind in development to go for this while trading the queens should favor White, also because of the same reason. }
15. Qb1
{ Retreating to c2 with   15.Qc2  would allow Black to play  15...Nc6  with ...Nb4 ideas and the tempting  16.Ba3  meets a nice response  16...a5  ,  preparing to play ...Nb4 next and in case of a capture take with the a-pawn to leave the control over the d4 square. }
15... Nc6 16. Bb2 g6
{ Black needs a couple of more moves to reach a perfect position after the opening. }
17. Nf4 Bf5
{ An accurate order of the moves - playing the more natural   17...Bg7  would allow White to play  18.Re1  and now  18...Bf5  is bad because of  19.e4! }
18. Qc1 Bg7 19. Qc4 Be4
{ Black has solved his opening problems and has a harmonious game, focusing on a game on the queenside where it has the pawn majority. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "6.e3 Mainline: #17 (Alternative)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3
{ This is currently one of the hottest and the most played move in the position - White is not going to wait until Black will grab the center and claims his ambition immediately. Black doesn't have a choice but to react immediately. }
3... e4
{ This is essentially Sicilian Alapin but with colors reversed, only White has an extra tempo g3 from the defensive side. So if you happen to know some ideas from the Alapin, it will help! }
4. Nd4
{ The most logical move - White's idea is to occupy the central square and then with the following d3, Nc3 and Bg2 try to undermine Black's pawn center. }
4... d5
{ The most direct continuation - Black is challenging the center before developing the kingside knight. The reason is that the inclusion of ... Nf6 and White's Nc3 won't allow White to take on d5 with the queen anymore. }
5. cxd5
{ White doesn't want to allow Black to play ...dxc4 next and instead clarifies the situation in the center. }
5... Qxd5
{ Oddly, here this move is the best while in the standard Sicilian Alapin this maneuver is considered to be not so dangerous. That's because of the lack of an alternative because  5...cxd5  will feel too slow because of the extra tempo for White. }
6. e3
{ This is the only serious alternative to Nc2 which will be analyzed in the next chapter. White keeps the knight on d4 and mostly pins his hopes to d3 thrust later, giving White a pawn majority at the kingside. Another plan that White might be thinking of as an alternative is pushing f3 to fight for a strong pawn center. }
6... Bc5
{ Before developing the kingside I find that the precise thing to do is to attack the knight on d4 immediately. This order of the moves don't allow White a tricky idea where I was unable to find complete equality for Black. }
7. Nc3
{ White can't play  7.d3  as Black could simply respond with  7...exd3  and the white rook on h1 is under attack. Any immediate knight retreats from d4 will most likely transpose to one of the covered lines but doing so immediately might give Black a few more options. If the dark-squared bishop on c5 is challenged, typically it's best to retreat with the bishop to b6 where it will keep an eye on what's happening in the center. }
7... Qe5
{ Black centralizes the queen, protects the pawn on e4, and is threatening to take on d4. Now White's got a set of choices here. }
8. d3
{ The main move which will inevitably transpose to the main lines, had Black played 6...Nf6 instead of 6...Bc5. }
8... exd3
{ Of course, taking on d4 would be a bad trade as White not only will get a strong center but also two powerful bishops. The reason why  8...Nf6  is not so good here is that White would capture  9.dxe4  and after  9...Nxe4  10.Bg2  challenge the knight. Capturing the knight on c3 would just strengthen the white knight on d4 and open the b-file for the queenside rook. }
9. Qxd3
{ Technically the only normal-looking move. White could try to avoid some trades in the center with  9.Nf3  first but Black is quite happy placing his queen on h5 which allows Bh3 to happen with standard development,   while  9.Nb3  would just transpose to one of the covered sidelines, which is not particularly good for White. }
9... Nf6 10. Bg2
{ Up to this moment this is the best play between both sides if White chose to play 6. e3 and keep the knight in the center. Now Black's got an interesting choice. }
10... O-O
{ Although there's a good-looking alternative to force the game into an equal endgame, this continuation is a little more fun and also ambitious! }
11. O-O
{ So far all players have played this logical move without hesitation as castling short is something that White will want to do anyway. If White wants to avoid the incoming threat of ...Rd8,  then I guess  11.Nf3  is the only try   as  11.Nb3  will just transpose to some of the covered lines with  11...Bb6  and ...Rd8 next. }
11... Rd8
{ The choice so far by such strong grandmasters as Anish Giri, David Navara, and Vidit Santosh Gujrathi and that's going to be also our move here. Black pins the knight on d4 but not necessarily with intentions to win a pawn. }
12. Nce2
{ This protects the pawn on d4 but also loses some time and control of the central squares. Here Black has a good choice between an ambitious move or going for equality. }
12... Bxd4
{ I'm sure that also this move is playable and can put White under a little dilemma. Capturing with the pawn will force White to go to an isolated queen's pawn's position again which we already familiarized in the mainline and this time with a weird knight on e2. Black's idea would be the same - play ...Qf5, ...Na6-c7-d5 and ...Be6 to occupy the d5 square, and at some point play the useful ...h6. }
13. Nxd4 { The only way to make it a little different. } 13... c5 14. Qb5
{ This appears to be a worse alternative as despite his fancy tricks White is losing valuable time. }
14... Na6 15. Nf3
{ 15.Bxb7  loses on the spot because of  15...Nc7!  and White loses a piece. }
15... Qe7 16. Bd2 Nc7 { There's the extra tempo. } 17. Qa4 Bf5
{ Black has got great control over the central squares and has no weaknesses. }
