{ The white knight on d4 is not going anywhere so it's a good idea to win a tempo first by threatening to play ...Nb4. Secretly that's also winning a tempo on its route to d5. }
13. a3
{ Svidler,P @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@-Vidit,S @@StartBracket@@2726@@EndBracket@@ Pepe Cuenca Invitational 2020, here I would like to improve Vidit's play. }
13... Bxd4
{ This is not forced but I like this from a strategic point of view. Black creates an isolated queen's pawn structure and is ready to block it on d5. An alternative idea here is to play   13...Nc7  with intentions to reroute it to e6 with a good game as well - perhaps Black can revisit the idea to take the knight with the bishop at some point later. }
14. exd4 Qf5
{ This wins a nice tempo against the incoming Re1 threat to reroute the pieces to land them on the crucial d5 square. Black is aiming for a strategic plan to exchange the light-squared bishop and position the a6 knight on d5 against White's dark-squared bishop. }
15. Qa4
{ Or  15.Ne4  h6!  and Black proceeds with the idea, described earlier. } 15...
Nc7 16. Bf4
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Zwardon,V @@StartBracket@@2424@@EndBracket@@ -Dhulipalla,B @@StartBracket@@2268@@EndBracket@@ Pardubice 2018, and here Black should have proceeded with the initiated plan to block the d5 square. }
16... Ncd5 17. Be5 Be6
{ with equality and an easy game for Black. A potential idea might be to play...Nxc3 next and continue with ...Nd5, threatening to play ...f7-f6 next, or ...Ng4. }
