{ Since Black is about to play ...Be6 next, White can try to force matters in the center. }
19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Be4
{ White has managed to activate all of his pieces, have the two bishops and a menacing rook in e5. In reality, he's about to run out of moves. }
20... Qf6 21. Bd2
{ Here after   21.Bxd5  cxd5  22.Re8+  Black doesn't have to take the white rook as the black rook on d8 is already protected, and if after  22...Kh7  White plays too greedily with  23.Be5  ,  it backfires with  23...Qf3  and suddenly White loses due to the ...Bh3 threat. }
21... Be6 { I can't imagine White cracking through this blockade. } 22. Re1 Nb6
23. Qc2 Nd7
{ It's a good idea to remind that the white rook on e5 also can be vulnerable and the same applies to the pawn on d4, which Black probably doesn't want to take anyway. }
24. Bh7+ Kh8 25. R5e3 Nb6 26. Bc3 Nd5
{ The blockade is back - Black shouldn't miss the d5 breakthrough which activates White's dark-squared bishop. }
27. Re5 c5
{ Not necessary but the idea always is there. White's  28.dxc5  can be met with  28...Nxc3  29.bxc3  and Rd5 next and the extra doubled pawn for White is insignificant. The black bishop will be rerouted to c6 later and Black is thinking about active counter-attacking chances. }
