13... O-O 14. Rd1 Nbd7
{ Since ...Nb6 seems to be inevitable and White is not going to double Black's f-pawns, the next move is almost forced. }
15. d5 Nxd5
{ It's more accurate to take with pieces first, forcing the trades. } 16. Nxd5
Bxd5 17. Bxd5 cxd5 18. Rxd5
{ White's got a bishop against a knight, but that's not an advantage. With the white king having castled long that might be debatable as the other rook could join the action much more quickly, but here it's still on e1. }
18... Nf6 19. Rd4 Rfd8
{ After trading rooks and positioning the knight on d5, followed by ...f6 and ...Kf7-e6, Black has achieved complete equality. }
