[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.e3"]
[Black "Chapter 8 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/2PNp3/6P1/PP1PPP1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]

5. Nc3
{ Instead of including   5.cxd5  which would lead to a studied theory after  5...Qxd5  ,  White suddenly has included Nc3. Where's the difference? }
5... dxc4 { White can't win back the pawn immediately. } 6. Nc2
{ Now the e4 pawn is under attack - how will you protect your spoils of war? }
6... Nf6
{ Better not to! Focus on development instead.   6...f5?!  White this move is still fine, it's the wrong direction.  7.d3  cxd3  8.exd3  exd3??  This already is a decisive mistake. If Black will try to hold the extra pawn at all costs, it will seriously backfire.  9.Bxd3  Nf6  10.Qe2+  Be7  Now after 11.Bc4 White already has almost a killing attack - the black king can't escape the center. }
7. Bg2 Na6 { Black sells back the pawn and has a harmonius development. } 8.
Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Bxe4 Be6
{ Now it will be White who will be suffering to finish the development at the queenside. }
