[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Early g3: 3.Nf3 and 6.Nc2"]
[Black "7.Bg2: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3 e4 4. Nd4 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. Nc2
{ The most popular continuation in this position - White is retreating with the knight to the flexible c2 square so that he can pursue one of the two typical plans.   1@@EndBracket@@ Attack the far advanced pawn on e4 with Nc3, position the other knight on e3 and increase pressure with Bg2 and Qc2, sometimes Qa4. On this occasion, the dark-squared bishop is typically fianchettoed to b2 either with pushing b3 or b4, which can be prepared with Rb1 or a3. With this plan the light-squared bishop usually remains on f1 so that Black can't easily pursue the ...Qh5 and . ..Bh3 plan.   2@@EndBracket@@ Trade the pawn on e4 with d3 or d4 when Black can take en passant. This is when White is hoping for a pawn majority in the center and the kingside so Black will have to rely on his active pieces to compensate it. Top-level players have also started to explore the possibilities to recapture the pawn with ...exd3, forming an isolated queen's pawn structure. This usually is linked with the idea to push the d-pawn as far as d5 to open the position.   3@@EndBracket@@ It's also possible that White might push f3 and trade the pawns to get a pawn center.   Typically it's alright for Black to take on f3 and pressure that pawn center with an active piece play. Since the white knight is already on c2, sometimes Black is thinking about an early ...h5 idea to bother White's kingside a little. If White would respond with h4 push, this would weaken the g4 square a little and also make any f3 ideas pretty much unlikely. There will be moments when Black will be fine to sacrifice the pawn on e4 just to develop the initiative or have great piece coordination. It's only a pawn after all. }
6... Nf6
{ I'll just mention here that the very tempting  6...e3  to attack the rook on h1 leads nowhere because White will respond with  7.f3  and after the capture on d2 will quickly get a strong center with e4. }
7. Bg2 Qh5
{ With the white bishop on g2 this is the best move although it's still possible to transpose to the mainline with  7...Qe5  ,  as White can't exploit the fact that the knight is still not on c3. }
8. h3
{ It seems to be necessary to stop the bishop trade as  8.Nc3  would meet  8...Bh3  and the pawn on e4 can't be taken, because  9.Bxe4  Nxe4  10.Nxe4  is met by  10...Bg2  , and White loses material. }
8... Qg6
{ A good move, which extra protects the e4 square and makes sure that White can't play d3 and recapture the pawn with the queen. Isolated queen's pawn position for White is something that Black is almost always happy in these kinds of positions, as long as it manages to block it on d5. }
9. Nc3 Bd6
{ Here the bishop is much more active, and also it doesn't slow down the possibility to extra protect the pawn with ...Re8. }
10. O-O O-O 11. d3
{ Either this or what is White doing here? Here playing the standard Ne3, fianchettoing the bishop on b2, and ignoring what's happening at the kingside can seriously backfire as Black is incredibly active and the white king is protected only by a bishop and a couple of pawns. Black could just develop with ...Re8 to strengthen the center and start paying attention to the White king with something like ...Nh5, already threatening with ...Nxg3 and ...Qxg3 next, or ...f5-f4. In this situation, White would have to react with d3 and that's also something that Black should be aware of. Black's ... Nbd7-c5 always looks good. }
11... exd3 12. Qxd3 Qxd3 13. exd3
{ Now Black has to watch out for the d-pawn push as far as d5. } 13... Be6
{ Maybe  13...Na6  is more accurate but the difference is not huge. } 14. Nd4
{ If White would play  14.Bg5  first, then the natural  14...Nbd7  would be a slight mistake as after  15.Nd4!  White forces the knight's trade for the bishop and the d4-d5 idea can become a problem.  Black could just play   14...Na6  and allow White to take on f6. }
14... Bd7
{ Black is still not ready to trade the bishop for a knight. The bishop on d7 looks awkward but the same can be said about the knight on d4. }
15. Bg5 Na6
{ There's hardly anything better - White ruins Black's pawn structure but at the same time, he can't aim for the opening of the position anymore as the dark-squared bishop will be missing. Those doubled pawns actually will take good care of some important squares, most notably e5. }
16. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Black has an easy game - focus on the game at the d-file. Once the queenside rook will be on d8, the light-squared bishop can be rerouted to c8 for the time being as there will be time later to activate it. }
17. Rad1 { This would be the normal way to continue. } 17... Rad8 18. Nc2 Be6
19. d4 Nc7
{ Black has prepared for the d5 push.  20.Ne3  Kg7  Black is thinking about either doubling the rooks on the d-file or about the ...f5-f4 push. White will have to push d5 at some point.  21.d5  Nxd5  22.Ncxd5  cxd5  23.Bxd5  Bc5  This is just equal - Black's doubled f-pawns are well compensated by the piece activity. }
*

