{ Almost mandatory as the alternative  7.Bg2  allows Black to play  7...Qh5  with an idea to play ...Bh3 next. }
7... Qe5
{ With the white bishop still on f1, this is the best response and it's necessary to extra protect the e4 pawn against a potential attack. }
8. Bg2 Be7
{ I don't like this move as it by force leads to a position where Black has to sacrifice a pawn for unclear compensation. }
9. Ne3
{ Now Qc2 is incoming - if Black wants to keep the pawn, he'll have to play ...Bc5 and simply acknowledge the loss of a tempo. }
9... Na6 10. Qc2 { Or  10.a3!?  with intentions to push b4 next. } 10... Nb4
{ 10...Nc5  temporarily protects the pawn but after  11.b3  and Bb2 next, it's only a matter of time until it will fall. }
11. Qb1 Nbd5 { This move fails to impress. } 12. Nxe4 Nxe3 13. dxe3 Bf5
{ Black managed to force the White king to lose the possibility to castle, but the gains are too little to compensate the loss of the pawn. }
14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. e4 Bb4+ 16. Kf1 Bg6 17. h4
