[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3 e4 4. Nd4 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. Nc2
{ The most popular continuation in this position - White is retreating with the knight to the flexible c2 square so that he can pursue one of the two typical plans.   1@@EndBracket@@ Attack the far advanced pawn on e4 with Nc3, position the other knight on e3 and increase pressure with Bg2 and Qc2, sometimes Qa4. On this occasion, the dark-squared bishop is typically fianchettoed to b2 either with pushing b3 or b4, which can be prepared with Rb1 or a3. With this plan the light-squared bishop usually remains on f1 so that Black can't easily pursue the ...Qh5 and . ..Bh3 plan.   2@@EndBracket@@ Trade the pawn on e4 with d3 or d4 when Black can take en passant. This is when White is hoping for a pawn majority in the center and the kingside so Black will have to rely on his active pieces to compensate it. Top-level players have also started to explore the possibilities to recapture the pawn with ...exd3, forming an isolated queen's pawn structure. This usually is linked with the idea to push the d-pawn as far as d5 to open the position.   3@@EndBracket@@ It's also possible that White might push f3 and trade the pawns to get a pawn center.   Typically it's alright for Black to take on f3 and pressure that pawn center with an active piece play. Since the white knight is already on c2, sometimes Black is thinking about an early ...h5 idea to bother White's kingside a little. If White would respond with h4 push, this would weaken the g4 square a little and also make any f3 ideas pretty much unlikely. There will be moments when Black will be fine to sacrifice the pawn on e4 just to develop the initiative or have great piece coordination. It's only a pawn after all. }
6... Nf6
{ I'll just mention here that the very tempting  6...e3  to attack the rook on h1 leads nowhere because White will respond with  7.f3  and after the capture on d2 will quickly get a strong center with e4. }
7. Nc3
{ Almost mandatory as the alternative  7.Bg2  allows Black to play  7...Qh5  with an idea to play ...Bh3 next. }
7... Qe5
{ With the white bishop still on f1, this is the best response and it's necessary to extra protect the e4 pawn against a potential attack. }
8. Bg2 Na6
{ The strongest move in the position and this order of the moves is very important. The knight on a6 might be heading to c5 to protect the pawn but it also protects the b4 square against any early b4 lash outs. Last, but not least - Black keeps the very important option to play ...Bc5 later and trade the knight on e3, so that ...Bf5 becomes possible. If Black would play immediately  8...Bc5  ,  White could respond with  9.b4!  Bb6  10.Bb2  to continue with Na4 and take on b6 to have a powerful dark-squared bishop - this already would be a problem for Black.   If Black would play  8...Be7  ,  White could continue with  9.Ne3!  and Black is missing out on the option to play ...Bc5, take on e3 and protect the pawn on e4 with ...Bf5. }
9. Rb1
{ This otherwise standard English opening maneuver here has been introduced by such strong grandmasters and theoreticians like Shankland and Ganguly. White wants to play b4 and Bb2 next. }
9... Be7
{ My proposed novelty against Rb1 albeit a very logical one - Black doesn't need to be afraid of the White's b-pawn push. In the two games, Black went for the logical  9...Nb4  where Black doesn't fully equalize. }
10. b4
{ White is consistent with the previous move and is about to play Bb2 next. }
10... O-O 11. Bb2
{ 11.b5  can't be good because Black will just take the pawn and play ...Nc5 next. }
11... Qe6
{ It's time to remove the queen from the discovered attack and also prepare to play ...c5 next. }
12. a3 c5
{ Given the circumstances that the black queen was forced to e6 and now ...Nc7 will be too slow because of incoming Nd4 threat and the pawn on e4 starts to become vulnerable, Black has to do something more active, especially since the white knight is still on c2. I suggest you pay extra attention to what is the best plan - either ... Re8 and . ..Nc7 with the ...a5 ideas or the immediate ...c5, because these positions with the countless order of the moves can be quite tricky. }
13. O-O
{ I imagine White could play this out as a gambit to rely on the piece activity - Black has a little choice here. }
13... cxb4 { Very often the most principled continuations are the best ones. }
14. axb4 Nxb4 15. Nb5
{ The trickiest continuation - White is looking for the obvious fork on c7 while also planning to include d3 to open the light-squared bishop. }
15... Nbd5
{ Black has to be ready not to miss any tactical tricks and if necessary - give up the e4 pawn, if the price is right. }
16. d3
{ There are other moves as well but this one is asking for the most direct continuation. }
16... e3
{ Black forces the next couple of moves and the position remains rather unclear - Black's about to sacrifice a whole rook! }
17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Bxd5 Qxd5 19. Nc7
{ Black temporarily sacrifices the rook but the white knight will be recaptured very quickly. The powerful bishops and the passed pawns at the queenside should compensate it the minimal material losses. }
19... exf2+ 20. Rxf2 Qc6 21. Nxa8 Be6 { Both sides have balanced chances. } 22.
Rxf6
{ With such powerful black bishops, I'd expect an experienced player to diminish their power. }
22... gxf6 23. Nd4
{ This still doesn't save the knight on a8 but at least wins back one of the dangerous-looking passed pawns. }
23... Qc5 24. e3 Rxa8 25. Rxb7 a5
{ Black has a straightforward plan - push forward the a-pawn and don't miss any deadly checks from the white queen. Probably the game will end with some perpetual check and both kings are pretty much exposed. }
*

