{ The strongest move in the position and this order of the moves is very important. The knight on a6 might be heading to c5 to protect the pawn but it also protects the b4 square against any early b4 lash outs. Last, but not least - Black keeps the very important option to play ...Bc5 later and trade the knight on e3, so that ...Bf5 becomes possible. If Black would play immediately  8...Bc5  ,  White could respond with  9.b4!  Bb6  10.Bb2  to continue with Na4 and take on b6 to have a powerful dark-squared bishop - this already would be a problem for Black.   If Black would play  8...Be7  ,  White could continue with  9.Ne3!  and Black is missing out on the option to play ...Bc5, take on e3 and protect the pawn on e4 with ...Bf5. }
9. Ne3
{ White has clear intentions to go after the e4 pawn with either Qc2 or Qa4. Now you'll evaluate why it was important to start with ...Na6 and keep the bishop on f8 for the time being. }
9... Bc5
{ With a simple idea to take the knight on e3 so that ... Bf5 becomes possible. The stronger is Black's center is, the stronger is the entire position. }
10. Qa4
{ This is a little more challenging continuation than Qc2 and the way I see it, the difference lies in White's ambition not only to attack the pawn on e4 but after the trade on e3 fight for some space advantage at the queenside with b4-b5. In general Black's approach remains the same. }
10... Bxe3 { There's no need to make commital weaknesses with ...b5. } 11. fxe3
Bf5 12. O-O O-O 13. b4
{ White doesn't appear to be ready to sacrifice the exchange on f5 just yet, mainly because of the underdeveloped queenside. }
13... Nc7
{ Black wants to keep the queens on the board for better control over the center and possible ideas for a future kingside attack. Also watch out for any b5 thrusts which might open the position and those thematic exchange sacrifices, so that those pesky White's bishops don't get a little more oxygen than they should have. }
14. Bb2 Bg6
{ Probably the most difficult move in the line - the bishop trade isn't going anywhere and it's important to secure control over the center first. Black wasn't ready to retreat with the queen on e6 just yet because of the incoming b5 threat and then there's the potential discovered attack from the bishop on b2. }
15. Qa5 Qe7
{ Black has good control over the center. Don't miss the Rxf6 sacrifice as well! }
