11. d4
{ This is what Anish Giri played in the Candidates and I imagine he was still within his preparation. White is aiming for the push of the d-pawn to open the position and Black will have to be very precise. }
11... exd3 12. exd3
{ White is threatening to push the d-pawn as far as to d5 to open the long h1-a8 diagonal so Black must be precise. }
12... Qd4
{ Black rearranges the queen and stops White's plan. If White will allow it, Black can also target the d-pawn immediately with ...Nc5. }
13. Nc2
{ 13.Ne2  doesn't feel like a huge improvement over the line because of  13...Qd8  and most likely White will have to push h4 anyway and the position with an isolated queen's pawn. }
13... Qg4
{ Another precise move - it's difficult for White to decline the queen trade, keeping into account that Black also wants to open the h-file and transfer his queen there. }
14. Bf4 Qxd1 15. Raxd1 Bg4
{ A good disruptive move - for obvious reasons White doesn't want to push f3 as it would close his light-squared bishop, or Rde1 as it would make the other rook on f1 look awkward. In this scenario, Black would continue with 16...Rd8 first, making sure that White can't play Nd4 and only then reposition his light-squared bishop to e6 and go for a total blockade of the d-pawn. }
16. Rd2 O-O-O 17. d4 Nc7
{ Black has played a perfect setup so far and wants to block the d5 square, as long as in the end, he can recapture with a piece. }
18. Ne3 Be6
{ Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2763@@EndBracket@@-Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@ FIDE Candidates tournament 2020, in the game White decided to trade-off most of the pieces with the following   19.d5  You can follow the entire game at the Model games. }
