1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3 e4 4. Nd4 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. Nc2
{ The most popular continuation in this position - White is retreating with the knight to the flexible c2 square so that he can pursue one of the two typical plans.   1@@EndBracket@@ Attack the far advanced pawn on e4 with Nc3, position the other knight on e3 and increase pressure with Bg2 and Qc2, sometimes Qa4. On this occasion, the dark-squared bishop is typically fianchettoed to b2 either with pushing b3 or b4, which can be prepared with Rb1 or a3. With this plan the light-squared bishop usually remains on f1 so that Black can't easily pursue the ...Qh5 and . ..Bh3 plan.   2@@EndBracket@@ Trade the pawn on e4 with d3 or d4 when Black can take en passant. This is when White is hoping for a pawn majority in the center and the kingside so Black will have to rely on his active pieces to compensate it. Top-level players have also started to explore the possibilities to recapture the pawn with ...exd3, forming an isolated queen's pawn structure. This usually is linked with the idea to push the d-pawn as far as d5 to open the position.   3@@EndBracket@@ It's also possible that White might push f3 and trade the pawns to get a pawn center.   Typically it's alright for Black to take on f3 and pressure that pawn center with an active piece play. Since the white knight is already on c2, sometimes Black is thinking about an early ...h5 idea to bother White's kingside a little. If White would respond with h4 push, this would weaken the g4 square a little and also make any f3 ideas pretty much unlikely. There will be moments when Black will be fine to sacrifice the pawn on e4 just to develop the initiative or have great piece coordination. It's only a pawn after all. }
6... Nf6
{ I'll just mention here that the very tempting  6...e3  to attack the rook on h1 leads nowhere because White will respond with  7.f3  and after the capture on d2 will quickly get a strong center with e4. }
