17. Bxc6 Nc5 18. Qxa7
{ It looks a lot scarier but is also possible - although White wins some material, the king is heavily exposed after a couple of forced moves. }
18... bxc6 19. Qa8+ Kc7
{ Not   19....Qb8  20.Qxc6+  and Qc7 because after the queen trade there's a fork on b5. }
20. Qxh8 Nxf2
{ Again, the same idea. The knight sacrifice can't be accepted, otherwise White will have a quick defeat. }
21. Bf4 { 21.Kxf2  Nd3+  22.Kg2  Rg4  23.Rf3  Ne1+  is a crushing attack. }
21... Nh3+ 22. Kh1 Nxf4 23. Rxf4
{ Necessary as   23.gxf4  would allow a killing attack with  23...Qf5  24.Qxg7  Qh3+  25.Kg1  Rd2  , and  26.Rf2  meets a lovely  26...Nd3!  with ...Bc5 incoming.   23.Rae1  meets  23...Ne4 }
23... Rxf4 24. gxf4 Qxf4 { Black's attack looks very scary. } 25. Qxh5 Nd3 26.
Qe2 { So far White's been defending with a lot of only moves. } 26... Bd6
{ It may not be obvious that White has to give away a piece on e4 'for free', just to force the queen trade. }
27. Ne4
{ Now Black can either take the knight on e4 and after the fork on f2 play an equal endgame or continue to play for more. }
27... Qxh4+ 28. Kg1 Be5
{ With a very accurate play White should be able to hold a draw in the end, for example, 29. Qe3-a7, delivering a perpetual check. }
