[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Two Knights: 2.Nc3 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "4.Nd5: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3
{ It's time to move on to the most popular moves in the Reversed Sicilian against the English Opening - early queenside knight's development on c3,  which is the most popular move in the position. One of the reasons is probably to prepare the development of the queenside knight to f3,  otherwise, the immediate  2.Nf3  runs into  2...e4  In the following several chapters of the course, I'm going to cover everything, if White is refraining to early develop the kingside knight as well. Since the white knight already on c3, unlike in the 2. g3 setups now Black has access to ...Bb4 to trade the knight to get a solid grip over the center. }
2... Nf6
{ But first, let's start with developing the knight. Black intends to continue with ...Bb4 next which immediately also is possible with  2...Bb4  but leads to different setups after  3.Nd5  The knight on f6 guards the d5 square and is ready to trade it, should such a jump happen. }
3. g3
{ White is playing traditionally - the light-squared bishop is moved the long diagonal of h1-a8, controlling a lot of squares. }
3... Bb4
{ It would be great if Black could transpose here to the already covered lines with  3...c6  ,  intending to fight for the center with the incoming ...d5. The biggest difference is the inclusion of moves Nc3 and ... Nf6 - now after the accurate  4.Nf3  e4  5.Nd4  Black can't continue with the same setup of  5...d5  and capture the pawn with the queen, but taking with the pawn leads to a slightly worse position as White will break the center with the d3 push. On the board we essentially have Sicilian Rossolimo with colors reversed, thus White has an extra tempo, comparing with the classical Rossolimo. If you are familiar with the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, it will certainly help, although not always everything will be possible to repeat here with Black as the extra tempo at some point should make a difference. }
4. Nd5
{ This jump is more common in a position where the black knight already stands on c6 so that after the recapture White wins a tempo and the knight has to retreat. That's also the reason why I'm not going to recommend any setups that involve the bishop on b4 and knight on c6, if White can jump Nd5. }
4... Nxd5 5. cxd5 O-O
{ I don't think the order of the moves is so important here but Black's plan is following - castle short, play ...c6 to pressure the center and ...d6 to continue the development. }
6. Bg2 d6
{ Probably the most flexible move order, in case Black has some other ideas, instead of ...c6. }
7. e3 c6
{ The pawn on d5 must be eliminated, otherwise Black could suffer long-term pressure against the c7 pawn, once White will double heavy pieces at the c-file at some point later. }
8. a3
{ It makes sense for White to push away the dark-squared bishop a little, although that might not be mandatory. At least it gives White the b2 square for the dark-squared bishop. }
8... Ba5 9. b4 Bb6
{ Here White has a little choice - either take himself on c6 or allow him to do this for Black. Either way, Black is doing fine. }
10. dxc6 Nxc6
{ Black develops a piece with a tempo - if nothing dramatic happens here, Black plans to play either ...Be6 or ...Bf5, put the queen behind on d7 to threaten with the light-squared bishop trade on h3, but there's an interesting alternative to that. }
11. Ne2 d5 12. d3
{ Santiago,Y @@StartBracket@@2422@@EndBracket@@-Mekhitarian,K @@StartBracket@@2555@@EndBracket@@ Brasilian championship 2016. }
12... h5
{ This is a little paradoxical since it's Black who has castled short and while White hasn't. The threat of ...h4 is quite unpleasant and the white king can't escape to the queenside anyway. }
13. h3
{ 13.h4  is no better as Black can continue to play with  13...Bg4  and gain a nice square for the bishop. }
13... h4 14. g4 f5
{ The key move of the entire idea - the white king is more vulnerable than Black's. }
15. gxf5
{ If  15.Qb3  then simply  15...Be6  and take on f5 with the rook. The pawn on d5 can also be protected with ...Ne7. }
15... Bxf5 16. Nc3 Be6
{ Any Qh5 ideas can be parried with the simple ...Rf5. The pawn on h4 is not relevant so Black can just continue with ...Qd7, double the rooks on the f-file, and start an early attack. }
*

