{ This jump is more common in a position where the black knight already stands on c6 so that after the recapture White wins a tempo and the knight has to retreat. That's also the reason why I'm not going to recommend any setups that involve the bishop on b4 and knight on c6, if White can jump Nd5. }
4... Nxd5 5. cxd5 O-O
{ I don't think the order of the moves is so important here but Black's plan is following - castle short, play ...c6 to pressure the center and ...d6 to continue the development. }
6. Bg2 d6
{ Probably the most flexible move order, in case Black has some other ideas, instead of ...c6. }
7. e3 c6
{ The pawn on d5 must be eliminated, otherwise Black could suffer long-term pressure against the c7 pawn, once White will double heavy pieces at the c-file at some point later. }
8. a3
{ It makes sense for White to push away the dark-squared bishop a little, although that might not be mandatory. At least it gives White the b2 square for the dark-squared bishop. }
8... Ba5 9. b4 Bb6
{ Here White has a little choice - either take himself on c6 or allow him to do this for Black. Either way, Black is doing fine. }
10. Ne2 cxd5 11. Bxd5 Nd7
{ The most solid setup - the black knight is rerouted to f6, the queen will stand on e7 so that the pawn on b7 is protected. }
12. Bb2 Nf6 13. Bg2 Qe7 14. O-O Be6
{ Black is doing just fine with good development. White can't easily push d4 as it would weaken the c4 square. Gelashvili,T @@StartBracket@@2576@@EndBracket@@-Van den Doel,E @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@ World chess olympiad Mallorca 2004. }
