{ Played in the spirit of the Sicilian Rossolimo - also there capturing the queenside knight is one of the central themes. Black wants to continue with ...d6 and a solid center. White has to make a big decision here in which direction the game will be heading to. }
5. dxc3
{ This is a solid alternative - White immediately brings into the game the dark-squared bishop and is looking forward to fighting for a space advantage with an incoming e4 at some point later and try to make good use of the two bishop advantage. }
5... d6 6. Bg2
{ Fianchettoing the light-squared bishop is supposedly the only 'normal' looking move but let's have a look at two alternatives here. In the Sicilian Rossolimo sometimes the queenside bishop is threatening to pin opponents kingside knight, which here would be on g5, but mainly that's an option once the queenside knight has been deployed to the 6th rank, here on c6. Thus the immediate  6.Bg5  looks a little awkward as Black can continue with the simple  6...Nbd7  and ...h6 next, recapturing the bishop with a knight.   Another tricky alternative might be linked if White would continue with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/2P5/2P2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qc2  ,  clearly intending to play e4 next and not necessarily the light-squared bishop will be developed to a passive role on g2 and White could even improvise as far as castling long. If White would do this, probably the simplest thing that Black can do is to play the immediate  6...e4!?  to stop the idea. Now after  7.Nd4  h6!  stops any Bg5 ideas and the pawn on e4 is easily defended with ...Qe7 with a good game for Black. Last but not least, retreating with the white knight with  7.Nd2  looks rather dubious because of a simple pawn sacrifice  7...e3! }
6... h6
{ Not exactly mandatory but you will find this move useful very often. Black makes sure that White will never play Bg5 to pin the knight and besides this move frees the h7 square for plans of ... Nh7 and ...f5, should the white pawn already stands on e4. }
7. Nd2
{ This is one of the main ideas in the Sicilian Rossolimo - White wants to play e4 to close the center and without castling short reroute the knight from d2-f1-e3 where it's feeling flexible. }
7... O-O 8. b3
{ I find this to be a little but important accuracy which is very characteristic for the structure - since White most likely is going to need this move later anyway, it makes sense to play it right now, still giving the bishop on g2 one last shot at the long diagonal, most notably pressuring the pawn on b7. }
8... Nc6
{ There is room to be very smart and start playing cat and mouse. Black could postpone the decision to develop the queenside knight and start with  8...a6!?  with an idea after White's  9.e4  continue with  9...b5   However, also White can be smart and wait for it with  9.Qc2   or make a little concession with  9.a4  ,  which already is asking for  9...a5  and reroute the queenside knight to c5. I find the text move to be simpler. }
9. e4
{ If White would want to be very tricky and include  9.Nf1  first, Black could continue with  9...Bf5  and stop the e4 pawn push forever. The bishop will be rerouted to h7 and as soon as White will hint at an e4, Black can push e4 himself. }
9... Be6
{ Black is back at the traditional idea - ...Qd7, trade the bishops on h3, continue with ...Nh7 and push the f-pawn. The bishop trade is not mandatory but you might find that after the f-pawn push White's light-squared bishop will become annoyingly active. There are no other active plans for Black as any ...a6 can always be answered with a4 and you'll remember the original plan. }
10. Nf1
{ An idea, mainly borrowed from the Italian Game - White doesn't waste time on castling short and immediately transfers the knight to e3. The white king might also castle long and this is also one of the reasons why it's not always a good idea to include the ...a5 vs a4 as it might be more difficult to organize an offensive there if needed. }
10... Qd7 { Now White has a choice, either to allow the bishop trade or not. }
11. h3
{ Probably it's quite principled to stop the trade but it's not an obvious decision as the bishop on g2 isn't exactly a candidate for Piece of the Year award. White takes into account that Black's only active plan is tied with ... f5 which should revive it. }
11... Nh7 12. Ne3 Ne7 13. Qc2
{ At some moment White might want to play g4 but it would make more sense to do it with the light-squared bishops already gone. Black should prepare the thrust first and make sure that the pawn on b7 is not lost in the process. }
13... Rae8 14. Bd2 f5
{ Here Black has a fine choice of two plans - push the f-pawn or play ...a6 and ...b5 which especially looks nice since White wants to castle long. For simplicity, let's go with the traditional plan. }
15. exf5 Nxf5 16. Be4
{ The black pawn on  b7  is taboo as after  16.Bxb7  c6!  the white bishop is cut out of the action and ...Ng5-f3 already is a big threat. }
16... Ng5 { Now the position simplifies to a good endgame for Black. } 17. Nxf5
Bxf5 18. Bxg5 hxg5
{ Any White's h4 push can be answered with ...g4. Black has a nice pressure at the f-file and should double the rooks there. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Two Knights: 2.Nc3 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "4.Nf3 and 5.dxc3: #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3
{ It's time to move on to the most popular moves in the Reversed Sicilian against the English Opening - early queenside knight's development on c3,  which is the most popular move in the position. One of the reasons is probably to prepare the development of the queenside knight to f3,  otherwise, the immediate  2.Nf3  runs into  2...e4  In the following several chapters of the course, I'm going to cover everything, if White is refraining to early develop the kingside knight as well. Since the white knight already on c3, unlike in the 2. g3 setups now Black has access to ...Bb4 to trade the knight to get a solid grip over the center. }
2... Nf6
{ But first, let's start with developing the knight. Black intends to continue with ...Bb4 next which immediately also is possible with  2...Bb4  but leads to different setups after  3.Nd5  The knight on f6 guards the d5 square and is ready to trade it, should such a jump happen. }
3. g3
{ White is playing traditionally - the light-squared bishop is moved the long diagonal of h1-a8, controlling a lot of squares. }
3... Bb4
{ It would be great if Black could transpose here to the already covered lines with  3...c6  ,  intending to fight for the center with the incoming ...d5. The biggest difference is the inclusion of moves Nc3 and ... Nf6 - now after the accurate  4.Nf3  e4  5.Nd4  Black can't continue with the same setup of  5...d5  and capture the pawn with the queen, but taking with the pawn leads to a slightly worse position as White will break the center with the d3 push. On the board we essentially have Sicilian Rossolimo with colors reversed, thus White has an extra tempo, comparing with the classical Rossolimo. If you are familiar with the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, it will certainly help, although not always everything will be possible to repeat here with Black as the extra tempo at some point should make a difference. }
4. Nf3
{ This move has some decent popularity albeit it's not the main move. White is exploiting the fact that Black can't play  4...d6  here because of  5.Qa4+  and now after  5...Nc6  6.Nd5  Black's position looks rather unpleasant.   I'm also going to avoid the heavy theory that happens after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/1bP5/2N2NP1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  mainly because I believe that not always the knight is positioned so well on c6. You'll understand it later in this chapter. }
4... Bxc3
{ Played in the spirit of the Sicilian Rossolimo - also there capturing the queenside knight is one of the central themes. Black wants to continue with ...d6 and a solid center. White has to make a big decision here in which direction the game will be heading to. }
5. dxc3
{ This is a solid alternative - White immediately brings into the game the dark-squared bishop and is looking forward to fighting for a space advantage with an incoming e4 at some point later and try to make good use of the two bishop advantage. }
5... d6 6. Bg2
{ Fianchettoing the light-squared bishop is supposedly the only 'normal' looking move but let's have a look at two alternatives here. In the Sicilian Rossolimo sometimes the queenside bishop is threatening to pin opponents kingside knight, which here would be on g5, but mainly that's an option once the queenside knight has been deployed to the 6th rank, here on c6. Thus the immediate  6.Bg5  looks a little awkward as Black can continue with the simple  6...Nbd7  and ...h6 next, recapturing the bishop with a knight.   Another tricky alternative might be linked if White would continue with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/3p1n2/4p3/2P5/2P2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Qc2  ,  clearly intending to play e4 next and not necessarily the light-squared bishop will be developed to a passive role on g2 and White could even improvise as far as castling long. If White would do this, probably the simplest thing that Black can do is to play the immediate  6...e4!?  to stop the idea. Now after  7.Nd4  h6!  stops any Bg5 ideas and the pawn on e4 is easily defended with ...Qe7 with a good game for Black. Last but not least, retreating with the white knight with  7.Nd2  looks rather dubious because of a simple pawn sacrifice  7...e3! }
6... h6
{ Not exactly mandatory but you will find this move useful very often. Black makes sure that White will never play Bg5 to pin the knight and besides this move frees the h7 square for plans of ... Nh7 and ...f5, should the white pawn already stands on e4. }
7. O-O
{ The most classical choice - White accepts that kingside is where the king should be and prepares the e4 and Nh4 plan which is a common motif in the Sicilian Rossolimo. White could opt for   7.c5  and try to undouble the pawns, but it just loses time and Black can continue with a normal development - White typically doesn't go to this position and hurry to undouble the pawns as quickly as possible. }
7... Nc6
{ Black continues a normal development and White has pretty much just one decent plan - play e4, reposition his knight on e3, and hope for a long maneuvering game. If White is too slow with the pawn push, Black keeps the option to improve his plan with ...Bf5 to stop the e-pawn push. }
8. Ne1
{ This is another possible route for the white knight to get rerouted to e3, but Black has enough time to stop e4. }
8... Bf5 9. b3 Qd7 10. Nc2
{ If White is too slow with it's plan, then Black has a nice additional resource to start a quick attack at the kingside, as shown in the following GM game. }
10... Bh3 11. Ne3 h5
{ This comes with an obvious threat to open the h-file and deliver a mating attack, as soon as the black queen will land on h3. Black doesn't hurry with taking on g2 so that White can't defend with h4. }
12. Nd5 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 h4 { Black is saving a tempo on castling. } 14. Rh1 O-O-O
15. Bg5
{ Taimanov,M @@StartBracket@@2454@@EndBracket@@-Rublevsky,S @@StartBracket@@2657@@EndBracket@@ Kortschnoj 70 rapid 2001. }
15... Nxd5
{ An improvement over the game - now  16.cxd5  will meet an unpleasant intermezzo with  16...f6! }
16. Bxd8 Nxc3 17. Qc2 Nxe2 18. Qxe2 h3+
{ Black will take the bishop on d8 and with the following ...Nd4 start a deadly attack. White's rooks are disconnected. }
*

