{ The most consistent move - as you will see, White can try to play this out in several moves, but Black's setup almost always remains the same. If possible, try to place the bishop on f5 to stop the e4 push. If not, then ...Be6, ...Qd7 and with ideas to castle both ways. }
9. Qd3
{ White might want to keep the option to play immediately b4 at some point later, if Black was to castle long. }
9... Qd7 10. Nh4
{ This is one of the main ideas in the Sicilian Rossolimo - the white knight on h4 controls the f5 square to slow down the ...f5 push and also is aiming to be rerouted to e3. Here Black has some interesting continuations - it could play the very principled  10...O-O-O  and allow White to storm forward with  11.b4  . Another option could be insisting on castling short and preparing the ...f5 push with ...Ne7, ...Nh7 etc. }
10... g5
{ This seems to be the simplest - if the white knight will go back, then Black indeed should already castle long and with ...Bh3 start a kingside attack. Here  10...Bh3  would feel like a concession but is also perfectly playable. }
11. Nf5
{ 11.Qf3  is an interesting intermezzo but it allows  11...Nxe4  12.Qxe4  and now the very strong  12...f5! }
11... Bxf5 12. exf5 O-O-O
{ Black has a direct threat of 14...e4 next. If White wants to stop it,  13.f3  is the only move but this allows Black to open the center with  13...d5 }
13. b4 e4
{ Another idea, borrowed from the Sicilian Rossolimo - the queenside knight will join the action in the center very quickly. }
14. Bxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Rhe8
{ If White won't be careful here, Black will quickly launch a strong attack using the light squares. }
