8... e4
{ This move disrupts White's plans and opens the e-file for the black rook. }
9. Nd4
{ White centralizes the knight and hopes to capitalize on the power of his two bishops and the semi-open b-file. Here  9.Ne1  would just transpose to some of the main lines after  9...h6  ,  stopping Bg5 and keeping tension in the center. }
9... h6
{ I advise keeping the tension in the center as long as possible and this move stops the Bg5 move for good. The black pawn on e4 disrupts the power of White's light-squared bishop on g2 and if White is ever going to take on e4 himself, this will seriously weaken the c4 pawn. }
10. Rb1
{ White immediately pressuring the  e4  pawn with  10.Qc2  could seriously backfire - Black can continue with  10...c5!  and the white knight can't make it to the desired e3 spot and again and will have to retreat to the awkward b3 square. That's why it makes sense to position the rook on the semi-open file first - White ties Black's light-squared bishop to c8, at least for the time being. }
10... Nbd7
{ The black knight is heading to c5 to further strengthen the pawn on e4, extra protect the pawn on b7, and also pressure White's pawn on d3. Here   10...c5  would be a positional mistake as the white knight will reach the e3 square via c2 and proceed with d4. }
11. Qc2 Nc5
{ It's not clear how White is going to progress here as Black himself is not going to take the pawn on d3 soon and can only strengthen it with ...b6 and ... Bb7. White might play f3 to force it, but this would close the light-squared bishop and weaken several squares in the center. }
12. Ba3 Qe7 13. Nb3
{ Christiansen,J @@StartBracket@@2207@@EndBracket@@ -Elsness,F @@StartBracket@@2483@@EndBracket@@ Fagernes Norsk op-A 2014. }
13... b6
{ This is a logical improvement over the game - Black looks better and can improve the defense of the e4 pawn. }
