{ This is the most played move in the position which also makes the most sense - White is going after the e4 push and transfer the action to the kingside with an f4 thrust later. }
8... e4
{ This move disrupts White's plans and opens the e-file for the black rook. }
9. Nd4
{ White centralizes the knight and hopes to capitalize on the power of his two bishops and the semi-open b-file. Here  9.Ne1  would just transpose to some of the main lines after  9...h6  ,  stopping Bg5 and keeping tension in the center. }
9... h6
{ I advise keeping the tension in the center as long as possible and this move stops the Bg5 move for good. The black pawn on e4 disrupts the power of White's light-squared bishop on g2 and if White is ever going to take on e4 himself, this will seriously weaken the c4 pawn. }
10. Rb1
{ White immediately pressuring the  e4  pawn with  10.Qc2  could seriously backfire - Black can continue with  10...c5!  and the white knight can't make it to the desired e3 spot and again and will have to retreat to the awkward b3 square. That's why it makes sense to position the rook on the semi-open file first - White ties Black's light-squared bishop to c8, at least for the time being. }
10... Nbd7
{ The black knight is heading to c5 to further strengthen the pawn on e4, extra protect the pawn on b7, and also pressure White's pawn on d3. Here   10...c5  would be a positional mistake as the white knight will reach the e3 square via c2 and proceed with d4. }
11. Qc2 Nc5
{ It's not clear how White is going to progress here as Black himself is not going to take the pawn on d3 soon and can only strengthen it with ...b6 and ... Bb7. White might play f3 to force it, but this would close the light-squared bishop and weaken several squares in the center. }
12. dxe4 { I guess White will have to do it sooner or later. } 12... Nfxe4 13.
f3 Nf6 14. e4
{ Klekowski, M @@StartBracket@@2528@@EndBracket@@-Grigoriants,S @@StartBracket@@2639@@EndBracket@@ Titled Tuesday Chess.com 2017. Here White has finally managed to grab the center and have the two bishop advantage, but at a cost - the pawn on c4 is what will define Black's plan. }
14... b6 15. Rf2 Ba6 16. Bf1 Nfd7
{ White can't find a good use of those two bishops while Black has an easy target. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Two Knights: 2.Nc3 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "4.Nf3 and 5.bxc3: #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3
{ It's time to move on to the most popular moves in the Reversed Sicilian against the English Opening - early queenside knight's development on c3,  which is the most popular move in the position. One of the reasons is probably to prepare the development of the queenside knight to f3,  otherwise, the immediate  2.Nf3  runs into  2...e4  In the following several chapters of the course, I'm going to cover everything, if White is refraining to early develop the kingside knight as well. Since the white knight already on c3, unlike in the 2. g3 setups now Black has access to ...Bb4 to trade the knight to get a solid grip over the center. }
2... Nf6
{ But first, let's start with developing the knight. Black intends to continue with ...Bb4 next which immediately also is possible with  2...Bb4  but leads to different setups after  3.Nd5  The knight on f6 guards the d5 square and is ready to trade it, should such a jump happen. }
3. g3
{ White is playing traditionally - the light-squared bishop is moved the long diagonal of h1-a8, controlling a lot of squares. }
3... Bb4
{ It would be great if Black could transpose here to the already covered lines with  3...c6  ,  intending to fight for the center with the incoming ...d5. The biggest difference is the inclusion of moves Nc3 and ... Nf6 - now after the accurate  4.Nf3  e4  5.Nd4  Black can't continue with the same setup of  5...d5  and capture the pawn with the queen, but taking with the pawn leads to a slightly worse position as White will break the center with the d3 push. On the board we essentially have Sicilian Rossolimo with colors reversed, thus White has an extra tempo, comparing with the classical Rossolimo. If you are familiar with the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, it will certainly help, although not always everything will be possible to repeat here with Black as the extra tempo at some point should make a difference. }
4. Nf3
{ This move has some decent popularity albeit it's not the main move. White is exploiting the fact that Black can't play  4...d6  here because of  5.Qa4+  and now after  5...Nc6  6.Nd5  Black's position looks rather unpleasant.   I'm also going to avoid the heavy theory that happens after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/1bP5/2N2NP1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  mainly because I believe that not always the knight is positioned so well on c6. You'll understand it later in this chapter. }
4... Bxc3
{ Played in the spirit of the Sicilian Rossolimo - also there capturing the queenside knight is one of the central themes. Black wants to continue with ...d6 and a solid center. White has to make a big decision here in which direction the game will be heading to. }
5. bxc3
{ White plans to fight for a strong pawn center with d3-e4, move the knight and push f4. This is something that Black wants to avoid, otherwise, there might be a risk to wind up in a position with no counterplay as the center will be difficult to open, especially taking into account those two white bishops. Under normal circumstances White probably doesn't want to push d4 as the pawn on c4 will become an eternal weakness and an easy target for Black. }
5... d6 6. Bg2 O-O
{ Black is castling short no matter what, especially now that the b-file is open for the white rook and castling long looks very risky. It also allows Black to be a little more flexible on the queenside and not reveal the chosen setup just yet. }
7. O-O
{ White finishes the development on the kingside first and wants to see which setup Black will choose. }
7... Re8
{ An important and very flexible move - Black is getting ready for White to push e4 at any given moment and doesn't reveal the chosen setup at the queenside. Now White has some choices here. }
8. Rb1
{ This might be a tricky way to postpone the idea to play d3 and perhaps also try to trick Black with Nh4 and e4, setting up a position which I recommend to avoid for Black, mainly because of a lack of an active plan. Black should be ready to meet any Nh4 with ...e4 and not have the white knight an escape route to e3 via f5. Thus ...Nbd7 probably is not the best but Black has another useful waiting move here. }
8... h6
{ White doesn't have a lot of tricky options from here.   9.Ne1  will just transpose to the mainline after  9...Nbd7  and the pawn on b7 can't be taken because of the pin with ...Rb8.   9.Nh4  meets  9....e4!  and Black is already threatening to play ...g5, so White has no time to make a breakthrough with f3 and get a strong pawn center. }
9. d3 e4 { The same approach which will repeat every single time. } 10. Nd2
{ White has managed to force Black to take on d3, but that's not something that Black should be concerned about. }
10... exd3 11. exd3 Nbd7
{ The black pawn on b7 is seemingly lost but Black is ready to immediately recapture it with ...Nc5 and ...Nxd3. There might an option to place the knight on b6 as well, but that depends on what White will play here. }
12. Nb3
{ White stops Black's ...Nc5 but it was not the only option for Black. Here Black has a number of good moves to continue. }
12... c5
{ This stops White's Na5 threat - ideally Black would like to trade the light-squared bishops. }
