{ White finishes the development on the kingside first and wants to see which setup Black will choose. }
7... Re8
{ An important and very flexible move - Black is getting ready for White to push e4 at any given moment and doesn't reveal the chosen setup at the queenside. Now White has some choices here. }
8. d4
{ This active move can't be a good choice, mainly because now the light-squared bishop will be shut out of the game for a while and White has some glaring weaknesses at the queenside. }
8... e4 9. Nd2
{ Since White is not threatening with Bg5 just yet, Black can spend time to strengthen the center a little. }
9... Qe7 10. Nb3
{ Bg5 is already a positional threat - White would love to trade the useless dark-squared bishop, close the center with e3 and focus at the queenside. }
10... h6 { There's no reason to make White happy. } 11. a4 a5
{ Stopping the a-pawn's march, the sooner the better. Black also fixes a potential weakness on a4. Since Black is going to play ...b6 pretty quick, it makes the most sense for White to charge forward and trade the double pawn. }
12. c5 dxc5 13. Ba3 { 13.Nxc5  would just meet the immediate  13...b6 } 13...
Nbd7
{ White's light-squared bishop is completely shut out of the game and Black is about to control the light squares at the queenside. }
14. Nxc5
{ This is not forced but Black was already going to play ...b6 and ...Ba6, and the pin is not going to hold forever. }
14... Nxc5 15. Bxc5 Qe6
{ Once the light-squared bishop will reach the c4 square, Black is dominating the game. White's dark-squared bishop feels a little useless. }
