{ This is a tricky move, threatening to win a pawn, but Black has a surprising defense. }
9... Nbd7
{ As it turns out, it's impossible to take the pawn as ...Rb8 would pin the rook and there's no Be4 retreat. Black is not committing to ...c6 just yet as not always it will be necessary. The knight on d7, however, almost always feels great. }
10. Nc2
{ Svidler, P @@StartBracket@@2756@@EndBracket@@-Tari,A @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ World Team championship 2017. }
10... Nb6
{ It makes sense to close the b-file, especially since White can't push a4. }
11. Ne3 e4
{ Black closes the light-squared bishop on g2 - this also allows to finish the light-squared bishop's development and not wasting a tempo on Rb8 to protect the b7 pawn. }
12. d3
{ Here it's interesting to play also  12.f3  but then Black can continue with  12...exf3  and an active play at the kingside. }
12... Bd7
{ Black is ready to reposition his bishop to c6 and if necessary, already take on d3. }
