{ White finishes the development on the kingside first and wants to see which setup Black will choose. }
7... Re8
{ An important and very flexible move - Black is getting ready for White to push e4 at any given moment and doesn't reveal the chosen setup at the queenside. Now White has some choices here. }
8. Ne1
{ Since this is the chosen move of some very high-level GMs and is very tricky, I'll treat this as the main move. White is immediately opening the bishop on g2 with many flexible ideas. One of them might be pushing immediately e4, another is rerouting the knight to e3, combining with Rb1 and pressuring the pawn on b7. One thing is quite clear - the black knight doesn't belong on c6 as then Black indeed will have problems to finish development as White will play Rb1. }
8... h6
{ This is my proposed novelty but first, let me explain how I got there. Checking other possible continuations here I concluded that every single of them comes with some sort of a concession. The text move is a great addition in almost every scenario to stop the future  Bg5  from happening and being ready to play ...e4,  should the situation demand it. I wasn't comfortable with shoving ...e4 here immediately because the white knight is still standing on e1.  So after  8...e4  White could continue with  9.f3  ,  force the pawn trade and go back with the knight to f3, continuing with d3 and e4. Probably it's not much but the text move I like a little better there.   Finally, if White is about to push  8.e4  himself, this will give Black enough time to organize a counterplay at the queenside with c6 and either  8...d5   or  8...b5  . }
9. e4
{ White takes control over the center and is pressing for a space advantage. }
9... c6
{ The most direct - Black is threatening to push either ...d5 or ...b5,  creating some real counterplay at the queenside. The previously mentioned ...a6 and ...b5 plan here is not the best as White hasn't committed himself to Nc2 setup and for the time being will just keep the knight on e1 to continue with d3 and f4. With the knight on e1 White can respond to  9...a6  with  10.a4  and now after the eventual ...Nd7-c5 and ...Bd7 Black doesn't attack the pawn on a4 with a tempo and thus the entire plan of ...b5 might be just helping White. }
10. d3
{ The most logical response. White can't play  10.f4  immediately as Black would just respond with  10...exf4  and White has to recapture the pawn with the rook, otherwise, the pawn on e4 falls. After  11.Rxf4  d5  White doesn't have a good reply. The text move prepares this idea and defends the e4 pawn in advance. White is also not defining the knight's intentions just yet. }
10... b5
{ As long as Black manages to open the queenside for a counterplay, this looks very interesting. I figured that this move is a little simpler than the alternative but the reader is to decide, which feels best. }
11. cxb5 cxb5 12. a4
{ This feels to be almost mandatory as  12.f4  comes with no threat and Black can just continue development with  12...Nbd7  ,  followed by ...Qc7 and ...Bb7. }
12... bxa4 13. Qxa4
{ White has managed to trade-off the double pawn and have some pressure against the black pawn on a7, but it's also a passed pawn. Black should be able to organize some counterplay against White's center pretty quickly, using the light pieces. }
13... a5 14. Nc2 Nbd7 15. Be3 Qc7 16. c4 Nc5
{ That's a very nice blockade and the white pawns are not going anywhere. } *

