11. cxd5 cxd5 12. exd5 Nxd5
{ These moves are pretty much forced and there's nothing better for White. }
13. Qb3
{ White is threatening to win a pawn and Black shouldn't object to it but concentrate on a harmonious development instead. }
13... Nf6 14. Bxb7
{ Not mandatory, but Black would have continued with ...Nc6 and either ...Bg4 or ...Qb6 with a good game. }
14... Bxb7 15. Qxb7 Nbd7
{ It's not clear how White will keep his pawn as Black is very active. } 16.
Be3 Nb6
{ Black is thinking also about .. .e4 and launch a swift attack at the kingside, using the weakened white squares. White will have to tread carefully to try to keep the pawn and not fall under a strong attack. }
17. Rc1 Nbd5
{ The game might continue with Black starting an assault at the kingside and keeping tabs on the d3 pawn. }
18. Qb2 Ne7
{ Black rearranges the knight closer to the kingside and also targets the d3 pawn. }
19. c4 Nf5 { Black has the initiative here but White still has the pawn. } *

