{ This move has some decent popularity albeit it's not the main move. White is exploiting the fact that Black can't play  4...d6  here because of  5.Qa4+  and now after  5...Nc6  6.Nd5  Black's position looks rather unpleasant.   I'm also going to avoid the heavy theory that happens after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/1bP5/2N2NP1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  mainly because I believe that not always the knight is positioned so well on c6. You'll understand it later in this chapter. }
4... Bxc3
{ Played in the spirit of the Sicilian Rossolimo - also there capturing the queenside knight is one of the central themes. Black wants to continue with ...d6 and a solid center. White has to make a big decision here in which direction the game will be heading to. }
5. bxc3
{ White plans to fight for a strong pawn center with d3-e4, move the knight and push f4. This is something that Black wants to avoid, otherwise, there might be a risk to wind up in a position with no counterplay as the center will be difficult to open, especially taking into account those two white bishops. Under normal circumstances White probably doesn't want to push d4 as the pawn on c4 will become an eternal weakness and an easy target for Black. }
5... d6 6. Bg2 O-O
{ Black is castling short no matter what, especially now that the b-file is open for the white rook and castling long looks very risky. It also allows Black to be a little more flexible on the queenside and not reveal the chosen setup just yet. }
7. O-O
{ White finishes the development on the kingside first and wants to see which setup Black will choose. }
7... Re8
{ An important and very flexible move - Black is getting ready for White to push e4 at any given moment and doesn't reveal the chosen setup at the queenside. Now White has some choices here. }
8. Ne1
{ Since this is the chosen move of some very high-level GMs and is very tricky, I'll treat this as the main move. White is immediately opening the bishop on g2 with many flexible ideas. One of them might be pushing immediately e4, another is rerouting the knight to e3, combining with Rb1 and pressuring the pawn on b7. One thing is quite clear - the black knight doesn't belong on c6 as then Black indeed will have problems to finish development as White will play Rb1. }
8... h6
{ This is my proposed novelty but first, let me explain how I got there. Checking other possible continuations here I concluded that every single of them comes with some sort of a concession. The text move is a great addition in almost every scenario to stop the future  Bg5  from happening and being ready to play ...e4,  should the situation demand it. I wasn't comfortable with shoving ...e4 here immediately because the white knight is still standing on e1.  So after  8...e4  White could continue with  9.f3  ,  force the pawn trade and go back with the knight to f3, continuing with d3 and e4. Probably it's not much but the text move I like a little better there.   Finally, if White is about to push  8.e4  himself, this will give Black enough time to organize a counterplay at the queenside with c6 and either  8...d5   or  8...b5  . }
9. e4
{ White takes control over the center and is pressing for a space advantage. }
9... c6
{ The most direct - Black is threatening to push either ...d5 or ...b5,  creating some real counterplay at the queenside. The previously mentioned ...a6 and ...b5 plan here is not the best as White hasn't committed himself to Nc2 setup and for the time being will just keep the knight on e1 to continue with d3 and f4. With the knight on e1 White can respond to  9...a6  with  10.a4  and now after the eventual ...Nd7-c5 and ...Bd7 Black doesn't attack the pawn on a4 with a tempo and thus the entire plan of ...b5 might be just helping White. }
10. Nc2
{ Now that ...d5 is incoming, White might feel that the knight has to be rerouted to e3 as quickly as possible. }
10... Be6
{ This is a useful intermezzo which comes with a tempo, preparing the ...d5 push. It is possible to execute it immediately but this would give White a lot more freedom on how to activate his bishops and fight for the center. }
11. Ne3
{ White has done everything to prevent Black from pushing the pawn forward. }
11... d5
{ Black does it nevertheless! The speed and timing are important as one move late and it might find in a passive position with no active prospects. }
12. exd5 cxd5
{ This trade seems to be quite forced as it opens White's bishop on g2 and now White has some options here. }
13. Rb1
{ This logical intermezzo move, targeting the pawn on b7 and trying to provoke some weaknesses already is a huge mistake and meets a spectacular punishment! }
13... d4 14. Bxb7
{ From afar it may not be obvious, where lies Black's plan. If White would realize his mistake and retreat with  14.Nc2  ,  Black has many great moves here, including  14...e4  , but the simplest is  14...Bxc4  and take everything that is given. }
14... dxe3 15. Bxa8
{ Any other move and Black can just play ...Nbd7 and effectively win two powerful light pieces for the rook. }
15... Qd3
{ Suddenly White has no defense against numerous threats, starting with the simple ... Qxb1, or ...e2, or ...Bxc4. }
16. Rxb8 Rxb8 17. Bf3
{ The best chance to keep the game alive for a while, but White is just strategically busted. }
17... Bxc4 18. Re1 exf2+ 19. Kxf2 e4
{ After this forced sequence Black simplifies the position, fixes numerous weaknesses in White's position with the wide-open king. }
*

