{ This is a useful intermezzo which comes with a tempo, preparing the ...d5 push. It is possible to execute it immediately but this would give White a lot more freedom on how to activate his bishops and fight for the center. }
11. Ne3
{ White has done everything to prevent Black from pushing the pawn forward. }
11... d5
{ Black does it nevertheless! The speed and timing are important as one move late and it might find in a passive position with no active prospects. }
12. exd5 cxd5
{ This trade seems to be quite forced as it opens White's bishop on g2 and now White has some options here. }
13. Qb3
{ White has numerous threats to win some material and the position looks menacing, but Black solves all problems with a simple developing move. }
13... Nc6
{ A powerful counterpunch - Black is threatening to play ...Na5 next so White has to take one of the pawns. }
14. cxd5
{ The obvious choice - take a pawn and create a fork. Suddenly all Black's pieces spark to life. }
14... Na5 15. Qb5
{ Otherwise Black just takes the pawn back on d5 with the knight with a big positional advantage. }
15... a6 16. Qd3
{ Another forced move for White to keep the pawn and here comes one of my favorite moves of the entire chapter. }
16... b5
{ This is so much stronger than the very tempting  16...e4  which would win an exchange for two pawns but the knight is completely shut out of the game. The idea of pushing the e-pawn will remain but with the text move, Black makes sure that the queenside knight will find a way back to the game, stops White's c4, and is either ready to play ...e4, or slowly increase pressure against the pawn on d5. White can't properly protect the queen on d3 to pressure Black into taking the pawn on d5 or leaving with the bishop. }
17. Rd1
{ White escapes from the ...e4 and .. .Bh3 threat, winning the exchange but that's not necessarily Black's goal. Notice how the white queen is dependant on the passive role to protect the d5 pawn. }
17... Rc8 18. a4 Nc4
{ Black is playing for the domination - his pieces are well-positioned and it doesn't feel that Black is missing a pawn. }
19. axb5 axb5 20. Ba3 Qd7
{ A multi-purpose move, mainly with intentions to start a kingside attack. } *

