13... Nc6
{ A powerful counterpunch - Black is threatening to play ...Na5 next so White has to take one of the pawns. }
14. cxd5
{ The obvious choice - take a pawn and create a fork. Suddenly all Black's pieces spark to life. }
14... Na5 15. Qb5
{ Otherwise Black just takes the pawn back on d5 with the knight with a big positional advantage. }
15... a6 16. Qd3
{ Another forced move for White to keep the pawn and here comes one of my favorite moves of the entire chapter. }
16... b5
{ This is so much stronger than the very tempting  16...e4  which would win an exchange for two pawns but the knight is completely shut out of the game. The idea of pushing the e-pawn will remain but with the text move, Black makes sure that the queenside knight will find a way back to the game, stops White's c4, and is either ready to play ...e4, or slowly increase pressure against the pawn on d5. White can't properly protect the queen on d3 to pressure Black into taking the pawn on d5 or leaving with the bishop. }
17. a4 { This move forces Black to act immediately. } 17... e4
{ The black pawn is taboo unless White is looking for trouble. } 18. Qc2
{ 18.Bxe4  Nxe4  19.Qxe4  Bh3  and not only Black wins an exchange for two pawns, but is threatening either ... Nb3, winning the pawn on a4, or ...Nc4. The white pawns don't seem to be ready to form a mighty chain. }
18... Nxd5
{ Here the game is less forced but I'd like to point out that Black doesn't have to keep the material equality in terms of the pawn count at all costs. It is enjoying a great control of the white squares and White's dark-squared bishop is just one giant pawn. }
19. Bxe4 Nxe3 20. fxe3
{ Odd but the only move as the more logical  20.dxe3  would run into  20...Bb3  21.Qb1  and  21...bxa4!  and Black is very happy to sacrifice an exchange for a huge initiative at the h1-a8 diagonal.   The simple  21...Rb8  also would be good. }
20... Bb3 21. Qb1 Rb8
{ Here  21...bxa4  is less clear as for White it's going to be a little easier to defend the king, mainly due to the open f-file. }
22. axb5 Rxb5
{ Black has an excellent compensation, mainly due to the weakened light squares and the white king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Two Knights: 2.Nc3 and 4.Nf3"]
[Black "4.Nf3 and 5.bxc3: #27"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3
{ It's time to move on to the most popular moves in the Reversed Sicilian against the English Opening - early queenside knight's development on c3,  which is the most popular move in the position. One of the reasons is probably to prepare the development of the queenside knight to f3,  otherwise, the immediate  2.Nf3  runs into  2...e4  In the following several chapters of the course, I'm going to cover everything, if White is refraining to early develop the kingside knight as well. Since the white knight already on c3, unlike in the 2. g3 setups now Black has access to ...Bb4 to trade the knight to get a solid grip over the center. }
2... Nf6
{ But first, let's start with developing the knight. Black intends to continue with ...Bb4 next which immediately also is possible with  2...Bb4  but leads to different setups after  3.Nd5  The knight on f6 guards the d5 square and is ready to trade it, should such a jump happen. }
3. g3
{ White is playing traditionally - the light-squared bishop is moved the long diagonal of h1-a8, controlling a lot of squares. }
3... Bb4
{ It would be great if Black could transpose here to the already covered lines with  3...c6  ,  intending to fight for the center with the incoming ...d5. The biggest difference is the inclusion of moves Nc3 and ... Nf6 - now after the accurate  4.Nf3  e4  5.Nd4  Black can't continue with the same setup of  5...d5  and capture the pawn with the queen, but taking with the pawn leads to a slightly worse position as White will break the center with the d3 push. On the board we essentially have Sicilian Rossolimo with colors reversed, thus White has an extra tempo, comparing with the classical Rossolimo. If you are familiar with the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, it will certainly help, although not always everything will be possible to repeat here with Black as the extra tempo at some point should make a difference. }
4. Nf3
{ This move has some decent popularity albeit it's not the main move. White is exploiting the fact that Black can't play  4...d6  here because of  5.Qa4+  and now after  5...Nc6  6.Nd5  Black's position looks rather unpleasant.   I'm also going to avoid the heavy theory that happens after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/1bP5/2N2NP1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  mainly because I believe that not always the knight is positioned so well on c6. You'll understand it later in this chapter. }
4... Bxc3
{ Played in the spirit of the Sicilian Rossolimo - also there capturing the queenside knight is one of the central themes. Black wants to continue with ...d6 and a solid center. White has to make a big decision here in which direction the game will be heading to. }
5. bxc3
{ White plans to fight for a strong pawn center with d3-e4, move the knight and push f4. This is something that Black wants to avoid, otherwise, there might be a risk to wind up in a position with no counterplay as the center will be difficult to open, especially taking into account those two white bishops. Under normal circumstances White probably doesn't want to push d4 as the pawn on c4 will become an eternal weakness and an easy target for Black. }
5... d6 6. Bg2 O-O
{ Black is castling short no matter what, especially now that the b-file is open for the white rook and castling long looks very risky. It also allows Black to be a little more flexible on the queenside and not reveal the chosen setup just yet. }
7. O-O
{ White finishes the development on the kingside first and wants to see which setup Black will choose. }
7... Re8
{ An important and very flexible move - Black is getting ready for White to push e4 at any given moment and doesn't reveal the chosen setup at the queenside. Now White has some choices here. }
8. Ne1
{ Since this is the chosen move of some very high-level GMs and is very tricky, I'll treat this as the main move. White is immediately opening the bishop on g2 with many flexible ideas. One of them might be pushing immediately e4, another is rerouting the knight to e3, combining with Rb1 and pressuring the pawn on b7. One thing is quite clear - the black knight doesn't belong on c6 as then Black indeed will have problems to finish development as White will play Rb1. }
8... h6
{ This is my proposed novelty but first, let me explain how I got there. Checking other possible continuations here I concluded that every single of them comes with some sort of a concession. The text move is a great addition in almost every scenario to stop the future  Bg5  from happening and being ready to play ...e4,  should the situation demand it. I wasn't comfortable with shoving ...e4 here immediately because the white knight is still standing on e1.  So after  8...e4  White could continue with  9.f3  ,  force the pawn trade and go back with the knight to f3, continuing with d3 and e4. Probably it's not much but the text move I like a little better there.   Finally, if White is about to push  8.e4  himself, this will give Black enough time to organize a counterplay at the queenside with c6 and either  8...d5   or  8...b5  . }
9. e4
{ White takes control over the center and is pressing for a space advantage. }
9... c6
{ The most direct - Black is threatening to push either ...d5 or ...b5,  creating some real counterplay at the queenside. The previously mentioned ...a6 and ...b5 plan here is not the best as White hasn't committed himself to Nc2 setup and for the time being will just keep the knight on e1 to continue with d3 and f4. With the knight on e1 White can respond to  9...a6  with  10.a4  and now after the eventual ...Nd7-c5 and ...Bd7 Black doesn't attack the pawn on a4 with a tempo and thus the entire plan of ...b5 might be just helping White. }
10. Nc2
{ Now that ...d5 is incoming, White might feel that the knight has to be rerouted to e3 as quickly as possible. }
10... Be6
{ This is a useful intermezzo which comes with a tempo, preparing the ...d5 push. It is possible to execute it immediately but this would give White a lot more freedom on how to activate his bishops and fight for the center. }
11. Ne3
{ White has done everything to prevent Black from pushing the pawn forward. }
11... d5
{ Black does it nevertheless! The speed and timing are important as one move late and it might find in a passive position with no active prospects. }
12. exd5 cxd5
{ This trade seems to be quite forced as it opens White's bishop on g2 and now White has some options here. }
13. Qb3
{ White has numerous threats to win some material and the position looks menacing, but Black solves all problems with a simple developing move. }
13... Nc6
{ A powerful counterpunch - Black is threatening to play ...Na5 next so White has to take one of the pawns. }
14. cxd5
{ The obvious choice - take a pawn and create a fork. Suddenly all Black's pieces spark to life. }
14... Na5 15. Qb5
{ Otherwise Black just takes the pawn back on d5 with the knight with a big positional advantage. }
15... a6 16. Qd3
{ Another forced move for White to keep the pawn and here comes one of my favorite moves of the entire chapter. }
16... b5
{ This is so much stronger than the very tempting  16...e4  which would win an exchange for two pawns but the knight is completely shut out of the game. The idea of pushing the e-pawn will remain but with the text move, Black makes sure that the queenside knight will find a way back to the game, stops White's c4, and is either ready to play ...e4, or slowly increase pressure against the pawn on d5. White can't properly protect the queen on d3 to pressure Black into taking the pawn on d5 or leaving with the bishop. }
17. a4 { This move forces Black to act immediately. } 17... e4
{ The black pawn is taboo unless White is looking for trouble. } 18. Qc2
{ 18.Bxe4  Nxe4  19.Qxe4  Bh3  and not only Black wins an exchange for two pawns, but is threatening either ... Nb3, winning the pawn on a4, or ...Nc4. The white pawns don't seem to be ready to form a mighty chain. }
18... Nxd5
{ Here the game is less forced but I'd like to point out that Black doesn't have to keep the material equality in terms of the pawn count at all costs. It is enjoying a great control of the white squares and White's dark-squared bishop is just one giant pawn. }
19. axb5 Nxe3 20. fxe3
{ Or  20.dxe3  Bb3!  and now after  21.Qb1  Bc4  22.Bxe4  Rb8  ,  Black looks very active. }
20... Bb3
{ A nice intermezzo move, pushing the white queen to a worse square, before retreating to c4. }
21. Qb1
{ 21.Qb2  Bc4  is the same, with the light-squared bishop landing on d3. }
21... Bc4 22. Rf4
{ A sad necessity as now thanks to the unfortunate placement of the white queen  22.Bxe4  exchange sacrifice doesn't work because of  22...Bxf1  23.Kxf1  Rb8  and Black wins another pawn with multiple incoming threats. }
22... Bd3 23. Qa2 Nc4
{ What a blockade! White's dark-squared bishop on c1 is becoming less and less meaningful. }
24. bxa6
{ This is very tempting as White is up two full pawns but in a terrible position. }
24... Qc8
{ Black makes sure that White can't take on e4 anymore and also eyes towards the a-pawn. It's not clear how White's dark-squared bishop is going to make a single move in this game. }
25. Bf1 Bxf1 26. Rxf1
{ 26.Kxf1  Qh3+  and ...Ne5 next looks painful for White. } 26... Ra7
{ Black can just ignore the pawn on a7 and focus on what's important - the weak white king. The pawn on a6 can be recaptured at any moment by adding the second rook to e6. And then essentially White will be a pawn up but with a terrible bishop against an all-powerful knight. Again, keeping queens on the board is in Black's best interest to grow the initiative. }
