{ Now that ...d5 is incoming, White might feel that the knight has to be rerouted to e3 as quickly as possible. }
10... b5
{ The major difference here is that White has not played d3 just yet and the knight is one step closer to the center. Black is still doing fine though. }
11. cxb5 cxb5 12. a4 bxa4 13. Ne3
{ With the extra tempo of Ne3, White has some direct threats of Ba3 and Nf5, that Black should be aware of. }
13... Nbd7 14. Ba3 Nc5
{ Black's pawn structure seems to be ruined but it should be compensated by the power of the outside passed pawn. }
15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. Rxa4
{ White is threatening to use the d5 square as an outpost, essentially creating a protected passed pawn but Black already has one at the queenside which should be pushed as far as possible. }
16... Bd7 17. Ra3 a5
{ Maybe for someone this approach is simpler than what I'm recommending in the mainline. I'd always treat it like this - it's simpler also for White, avoiding all those nice traps that you could set for your opponent and a lot of difficult to evaluate positional sacrifices. }
