1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. e4
{ This move has sparked a lot of interest at the highest level - in the last couple of years it was frequently used by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen, followed by other elite grandmasters as well. The idea is already known, but for years it was executed differently. Normally White would play the 'standard'  4.Bg2  first and then have the option to play e4 later. The reason why White includes it here is that the bishop is not always going to g2. It might but probably it won't. }
4... Bxc3
{ The most popular continuation and very principled, which is also consistent with Black's approach in the entire course. Here the idea is to stop White from playing Nge2 next so that after a possible capture later White can't take on c3 with the knight. White has two options to capture the bishop, and both have been tested. }
5. bxc3
{ White aims for a strong pawn center and very often, an improvised early attack at the kingside. However, here Black's approach will be a little more straightforward and easier to carry out. Black typically is going for castling short and the immediate ...c6 with ...d5 breakthrough in the center. }
5... O-O
{ Actually with White having played  5.bxc3  ,  if looking for some variety Black could consider going for  5...Nxe4  as  6.Qe2  Nc5  the black knight will be rerouted to e6 with a seemingly solid position where White is enjoying two bishops and a center   while  6.Qg4  Nf6  7.Qxg7  Rg8  8.Qh6  Nc6  ,  followed by ...d5 and ...Rg6 is just unclear. The text move makes more sense though as I'd never advocate for going to a slightly worse position when there's something better. }
6. d3
{ This is a rare move and normally it should fall in the same category of  4.Bg2  ,  which we will cover in the next chapter, should White play d3 at some point later. I came up with it because it makes sense for White to defend the pawn on e4 by delaying the kingside development and fight for a strong pawn center immediately. If Black is very slow with his decisions, White could even think about an improvised g4-g5 to take even more space advantage and slow down Black's ambition to strike in the center, but here it's not going to work. }
6... c6 7. f4
{ Either now or never - White is fighting for the center with the limited time he's got as the simple  7.Bg2  would allow Black to execute ...d5. }
7... exf4
{ No matter how White will recapture the pawn, Black is opening the center. }
8. Bxf4
{ Capturing with the pawn is worse, as Black would respond with the same thrust in the center. }
8... d5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. e5
{ Structure wise White is doing alright - taking control of the center and have two bishops. But the piece development is also important! }
10... Re8 11. Ne2
{ This is already the only move, forcing the black knight to leave the f6 square, otherwise ...Bg4 is incoming and the pawn on e5 will be contested very quickly. }
11... Nh5
{ More precise than the normal looking  11...Ng4  Black is threatening to trade the knight for the bishop and it can't leave because the pawn on e5 is under attack. Now starts a forced sequence. }
12. d4 f6 13. Bg2
{ This is necessary as  13.exf6  meets the very unpleasant  13...Nxf4!  and White will have to recapture on f4 with a pawn, ruining his king's shelter. }
13... fxe5 14. dxe5 { This allows Black to develop an initiative. } 14... Nxf4
15. gxf4 Qh4+ 16. Kf1 Nc6
{ Black is ready to sacrifice the pawn on d5. White will have to spend several tempos to secure his king and has numerous weaknesses in his position. }
