{ A new concept, introduced by Magnus Carlsen in 2020 - the pawn structure which he was using with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/2P1P3/2b3P1/PP1P1P1P/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.dxc3  as well. White's light-squared bishop is not going to g2 anymore but instead White is aiming for a typical Nimzo Indian position by continuing with d4, Bd3, Ne2, Be3 and perhaps pushing h4 and g4 with an attack at the kingside. Since in his quest to fight for a strong pawn center White is hopelessly behind in development, it makes perfect sense for Black to open the position. }
6... b5
{ This is what Fabiano Caruana played against the world champion in one of the online rapid super tournaments - the idea is interesting but I don't see what's wrong with the main move. However, let's keep the concept in mind - you never know you'll need it! }
7. d4
{ An experienced player will easily decide that accepting the free pawn is dangerous  7.cxb5  d5!  ,  followed by ...a6 gives Black a strong initiative and White's entire approach now looks just ridiculous. The move, played in the game, is more consistent with the spirit of the position. }
7... exd4 8. cxd4 bxc4 9. e5
{ All of this is forced, otherwise after  9.Bxc4  Black would enjoy too much playing  9...d5  next. }
9... Nd5 10. Bxc4
{ Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ -Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2835@@EndBracket@@ Clutch Chess 2020, and starting from here Caruana went for the wrong way and was punished spectacularly. }
10... Nb6 11. Bd3 Ba6 12. f4
{ White has got a strong pawn center but Black should counter it with a very active play. }
12... d6 13. Nf3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 dxe5 15. fxe5 Nc6
{ Black should be doing alright but structure-wise Black's position looks a little risky as he has the weak pawn on c7 and after castling short White is eyeing towards an inspired kingside attack. }
