6. f3
{ A new concept, introduced by Magnus Carlsen in 2020 - the pawn structure which he was using with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/2P1P3/2b3P1/PP1P1P1P/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.dxc3  as well. White's light-squared bishop is not going to g2 anymore but instead White is aiming for a typical Nimzo Indian position by continuing with d4, Bd3, Ne2, Be3 and perhaps pushing h4 and g4 with an attack at the kingside. Since in his quest to fight for a strong pawn center White is hopelessly behind in development, it makes perfect sense for Black to open the position. }
6... Re8
{ The most flexible move in the position but mostly Black is preparing to play ...c6 and ...d5 next. Here White has a couple of interesting choices and all of them lead to unique positions. }
7. d4
{ What happens when Magnus Carlsen invents a new idea? Well, people mostly find it exciting and start test it themselves, especially against the inventor himself! This happened after the World Championship match in 2018 with the Sicilian Sveshnikov, and one month after the World Champion invented 6.f3!? in this variation, super-GM Peter Svidler decided to launch it against Magnus, who was this time playing with Black. I'm considering this to be the main move, if White plays 5.bxc3. }
7... Nc6
{ Unfortunately there's no time to play  7...c6  as White would respond with  8.dxe5  ,  followed by Bf4 and a glaring hole on d6.   I find this move to be the most flexible in the position and it immediately parries two of White's ideas - both Nh3-f2 and Bd3-Ne2 as the latter with the first move drops the pawn on d4 too early. Black is threatening with the immediate ...b6, ...Ba6, and ...Na5 while keeping the pawn on d7. This would allow Black at the right time to execute ...c6 and ...c5 in one go. White here has some continuations. }
8. h4
{ White might try to start an improvised attack at the kingside and not 'waste' a tempo for relocating the king. The engine insists that it's playable but from a human perspective it looks very dangerous for White and I'm not sure who would willingly choose this @@StartBracket@@if aware of the next couple of moves@@EndBracket@@ }
8... exd4
{ The same approach as with @@StartFEN@@r1bqr1k1/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2PPP3/2P2PP1/P6P/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Nh3  except here Black isn't winning. }
9. cxd4 d5 10. cxd5 Nxe4
{ It is possible to start also with  10...Qxd5  but after  11.Kf2  I want to mention that grabbing the pawn on d4 with  11...Qxd4  will result in White having an excellent compensation, mainly because of a pawn majority at the kingside and two excellent bishops. }
11. fxe4 Rxe4+
{ So far this is forced, at least from White's potential replies - now the white king has to run and seek salvation at the kingside, otherwise covering from a check with both the knight and the bishop will have disastrous effects after 12...Nxd4, followed by ...Bg4. }
12. Kf2 Qxd5
{ Black has sacrificed a piece for two pawns to completely expose the white monarch but the sacrifices aren't over! }
13. Bg2 Bg4 14. Bxe4
{ It seems to be necessary as  14.Bf3  Qf5!  Black continues his attack and at any given time can just recapture the third pawn for the piece. Of course  14.Qxg4  is impossible because Black will deliver an intermezzo check with  14...Qxd4+  and only then grab the white queen. }
14... Qxe4 15. Nf3 Nb4
{ This ends the forced sequence and we can evaluate the situation. Black has sacrificed a rook for just two pawns but the white king's position is wide open with a lot of threats. I found some forcing lines where Black at least keeps equality with the same plan against almost all of them, but if you are not impressed, you can revisit the entire sacrifice plan at move 8. It was possible to include normal developing moves like 8...d6 and aim for that weak pawn on c4 and if White would charge forward with something like 9. h5 or g4, use the entire sacrifice idea with even better odds as the kingside will be even more open. }
16. a4
{ This comes with another idea to bring into the game the queenside rook immediately and here Black can already force a draw. }
16... Bxf3
{ but the fun part is that it's not even mandatory - Black can also go for the main idea with  16...Nd3+  and  17...Rd8  to execute the ...Ne5 threat. }
17. Qxf3 Qxd4+ 18. Be3 Qb2+
{ Since the white king can't go to the first rank as it would leave the rook on a1 unprotected, the only sensible move is to protect from the check with the queen. }
19. Qe2 Nd3+ 20. Kf3 Ne5+ { The white king is tied to defend the queen. } 21.
Kf2 Nd3+ { The game ends with a perpetual check. } *

