18. a4
{ If White would play  18.Rb1  ,  Black can already play  18...Ne5  without including ...h6 as the rook on b1 is under attack by the black queen. Now after  19.Rb3  Rxd4!  Black restores the material equality on the board with good chances to take over the game. }
18... h6
{ An important intermezzo, making sure that White can't play Ng5, and also creating an escape route for the black king, should it need one. Under the circumstances, Black can also consider including ...Rxd4 before ...Ne5 first. }
19. Ra2 Ne5
{ 19...Nxc1  also works here but the text move is more consistent. } 20. Raf2
Rxd4 { For obvious reasons White can't take the rook on d4. } 21. Nd2 Qd5 22.
Qe1
{ The critical position - White has seemingly regrouped his pieces and the king is sort of protected. However, Black has for the rook now three pawns and the initiative hasn't stopped. }
22... Rd3 23. Rf4
{ Or  23.Kh2  Bd7  with multiple threats, most notably ...Ng4+. } 23... Bd7 24.
Qe4 Qe6
{ Keeping queens on the board is in Black's best interest to keep the attack going. }
25. Qg2 Bc6 26. Ne4 Ng6
{ I can't imagine White keeping the position together for long. } *

