8. Ne2
{ This closes the dreadful pin at the e-file but also weakens the control on the c4 pawn. This is what Black should be concentrating on here. }
8... d6 9. h4 Nd7
{ Against the chosen setup here it's the best choice for Black - remove the kingside knight to save some tempos from the incoming pawn storm and go after the pawn on c4. }
10. g4
{ White is looking towards an inspired kingside attack and most likely it will cost it a pawn. }
10... Nb6 11. Ng3 Na5 12. g5
{ White has no time to protect the pawn on c4 and should sacrifice it, focusing on his game at the kingside. For Black it's easy - take the spoils of war. }
12... Nbxc4
{ Taking with this knight feels a little better as it removes White the option to push the a-pawn as far as a5. }
13. Kf2 c6 14. Bd3 b5
{ Black seeks a game at the queenside with ...Rb8 and .. .b4, or perhaps ...Qb6. White still has to prove what he has at the kingside so the typical plan most likely will involve h5 and g6. I'm not sure if here the traditional ...d5 is a good idea as it would open the White's bishop on d3 to join the attack. }
