[Round "?"]
[White "11. Two Knights: 4.e4 and 6.f3"]
[Black "6.f3 and 7.d4: #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. e4
{ This move has sparked a lot of interest at the highest level - in the last couple of years it was frequently used by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen, followed by other elite grandmasters as well. The idea is already known, but for years it was executed differently. Normally White would play the 'standard'  4.Bg2  first and then have the option to play e4 later. The reason why White includes it here is that the bishop is not always going to g2. It might but probably it won't. }
4... Bxc3
{ The most popular continuation and very principled, which is also consistent with Black's approach in the entire course. Here the idea is to stop White from playing Nge2 next so that after a possible capture later White can't take on c3 with the knight. White has two options to capture the bishop, and both have been tested. }
5. bxc3
{ White aims for a strong pawn center and very often, an improvised early attack at the kingside. However, here Black's approach will be a little more straightforward and easier to carry out. Black typically is going for castling short and the immediate ...c6 with ...d5 breakthrough in the center. }
5... O-O
{ Actually with White having played  5.bxc3  ,  if looking for some variety Black could consider going for  5...Nxe4  as  6.Qe2  Nc5  the black knight will be rerouted to e6 with a seemingly solid position where White is enjoying two bishops and a center   while  6.Qg4  Nf6  7.Qxg7  Rg8  8.Qh6  Nc6  ,  followed by ...d5 and ...Rg6 is just unclear. The text move makes more sense though as I'd never advocate for going to a slightly worse position when there's something better. }
6. f3
{ A new concept, introduced by Magnus Carlsen in 2020 - the pawn structure which he was using with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/2P1P3/2b3P1/PP1P1P1P/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.dxc3  as well. White's light-squared bishop is not going to g2 anymore but instead White is aiming for a typical Nimzo Indian position by continuing with d4, Bd3, Ne2, Be3 and perhaps pushing h4 and g4 with an attack at the kingside. Since in his quest to fight for a strong pawn center White is hopelessly behind in development, it makes perfect sense for Black to open the position. }
6... Re8
{ The most flexible move in the position but mostly Black is preparing to play ...c6 and ...d5 next. Here White has a couple of interesting choices and all of them lead to unique positions. }
7. d4
{ What happens when Magnus Carlsen invents a new idea? Well, people mostly find it exciting and start test it themselves, especially against the inventor himself! This happened after the World Championship match in 2018 with the Sicilian Sveshnikov, and one month after the World Champion invented 6.f3!? in this variation, super-GM Peter Svidler decided to launch it against Magnus, who was this time playing with Black. I'm considering this to be the main move, if White plays 5.bxc3. }
7... Nc6
{ Unfortunately there's no time to play  7...c6  as White would respond with  8.dxe5  ,  followed by Bf4 and a glaring hole on d6.   I find this move to be the most flexible in the position and it immediately parries two of White's ideas - both Nh3-f2 and Bd3-Ne2 as the latter with the first move drops the pawn on d4 too early. Black is threatening with the immediate ...b6, ...Ba6, and ...Na5 while keeping the pawn on d7. This would allow Black at the right time to execute ...c6 and ...c5 in one go. White here has some continuations. }
8. Kf2
{ The most interesting move in White's arsenal - White removes the king from the potential pin at the e-file and is preparing an h4-g4 launch while not defining the setup of the pieces just yet. A very modern approach! }
8... b6
{ I suggest seeking a quick counterplay and say hello to the white pawn on c4,  otherwise, things could quickly get out of hand at the kingside. Black could also employ an already seen idea with  8...d6  ,  followed by  9...Nb6  and ... Na5 but according to my analysis this idea works best if White is starting to reroute the knight from g1 to e2 and g3, giving Black enough time to reroute the knights.   Otherwise White might start with  9.h4  and now after  9...Nd7  White can play  10.Bg5  first to provoke  f6  11.Be3  and it's a completely different dynamic. }
9. h4 Ba6 10. g4
{ White can't play  10.h5  first as Black would just block the pawn with  10...h6  and now  11.g4  comes too late - Black has  11...Nh7  and the entire kingside will be blocked very quickly. }
10... Na5
{ Black is immediately applying pressure against the c4 pawn but I don't think there's anything wrong with the normal  10...d6  as well. It might provoke some hostilities with the tricky  11.Bg5  and after  11...h6  just go back  12.Bc1  ,  having created a target with g5. }
11. g5
{ This would move the game in another direction. I'll just add that the provocative  11.Bg5  would come here with no effect as the extra tempo does make a difference - Black would just continue with  11...Bxc4  and fire away ...d5 next. }
11... Nh5 12. Bh3
{ Black should be a little careful not to fall into a trap if White had played  12.dxe5  as now  12...Rxe5  is bad because of the incoming f4 double attack.   But luckily Black has some other good moves here as well, like  12...Bxc4  ,   12...g6   or even  12...Qe7  with a rich game. }
12... Bxc4 13. Bg4 g6
{ Since White has no time to close the action in the center with d5 as Black always will have ...c6 to open it again, there are a couple of forced moves. }
14. Bxh5 gxh5 15. dxe5 Rxe5 16. Nh3
{ White has his threats but so does Black - remember postponing the decision to play ...d6? }
16... d5 17. Nf4 dxe4 { Black appears to be taking over. } *

