11. Ne2
{ The most consistent move - White is building up his initiative at the kingside. }
11... Bxc4 12. Ng3
{ In order not to get a worse position, Black must light up the center. } 12...
d5
{ Again, the d-pawn push in one go - one tempo here and there can make a big difference. }
13. dxe5
{ The most principled - if White would trade the bishops on c4,  it would just active the queenside knight, while  13.g5  would just push the knight to the d7 square where it wants to be. }
13... Nd7
{ I discarded the straightforward  13...Rxe5  because of  14.Bxc4  and now  14...Nxc4  would run into  15.g5  Nd7  16.f4  with some practical problems for Black,   while  14...dxc4  looks dangerous from a strategic point of view as White will have an easy game at the kingside where lies his pawn majority, and the black king. }
14. Bg5
{ This is quite an important intermezzo move to push away the black queen and before grabbing the center with f4. }
14... Qc8 15. f4 dxe4
{ Don't you even look into the direction of that bishop - that's the perfect Greek gift and the consequences for hunting the bishop could be severe. Black needs to generate some real counterplay in the center where lies the white king. }
16. Nxe4 Nc5
{ Much more dynamic than the obvious trading of the light-squared bishops and rerouting the stranded knight from a5 to c5 via b7 - the white king is exposed and that should be Black's target. }
17. Nxc5 bxc5
{ With the queens off the board, White would have an obvious advantage as the 'extra' pawn at the kingside and some considerable space advantage should play some role. However, here we have still queens on the board and the white king is wondering around half-naked! }
18. h5
{ Otherwise Black might change his mind and play ...h6 after all, now that there are fewer pieces on the board to attack the black king. }
18... Rb8 19. Kg3
{ If White would play here  19.h6  ,  Black could target the white king with the bishop trade, followed by ...Nc4, ...Rb2 and ...Qb7. }
19... Qe6 { Black prepares to play ...f6. } 20. Bg2 f6 21. exf6 Qe3+ 22. Kh2
gxf6
{ Black has created enough counterplay -  23.Bh4  will allow to grab the pawn on f4,   while  23.Bh6  seeks some counterplay with  23...Rb2 }
