[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Two Knights: 4.e4 and 6.f3"]
[Black "5.dxc3 and 6.Qc2: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. e4
{ This move has sparked a lot of interest at the highest level - in the last couple of years it was frequently used by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen, followed by other elite grandmasters as well. The idea is already known, but for years it was executed differently. Normally White would play the 'standard'  4.Bg2  first and then have the option to play e4 later. The reason why White includes it here is that the bishop is not always going to g2. It might but probably it won't. }
4... Bxc3
{ The most popular continuation and very principled, which is also consistent with Black's approach in the entire course. Here the idea is to stop White from playing Nge2 next so that after a possible capture later White can't take on c3 with the knight. White has two options to capture the bishop, and both have been tested. }
5. dxc3
{ This move is trickier than capturing with the b-pawn so let me explain a couple of major differences. Comparing with the capture of the b-pawn, now for Black, it will be much more difficult to go for the d-pawn push as there's one more obstacle - the white queen. Instead of pursuing a strong pawn center and a quick kingside attack here White mostly relies on the space advantage and intends to squeeze Black very slowly. I think the reason why this line has decent popularity among strong grandmasters is that to play it out properly, Black needs to understand the core ideas, less actual theory. }
5... d6
{ Comparing with the b-pawn capture, here   5...Nxe4  is just outright bad and not something even to consider as White has access to  6.Qd5  and immediate advantage of two bishops in an open position. I advise by not rushing with castling short and make several useful moves first to see, where White will put his king. The text move is just useful and strengthens Black's center. }
6. Qc2
{ This is another rare move in the position but with a decent idea - instead of the unorthodox  6.f3  and the following knight jump to h3 and f2, White can reroute the knight to e3 immediately. Structure-wise the plans don't change and they remain about the same. }
6... a5
{ Nothing changes and the a-pawn marches as far as a4, with the same idea to force the position to open at some point and should White consider to castle long, then Black already has an agent there. }
7. Nf3
{ Or  7.b3  Nfd7  ,  positioning both black knights on c5 and c6 and following in the same manner as after 6.f3 a5 7.b3. }
7... a4
{ Mission accomplished, Black is about to start bothering the pawn on c4 to open the position at the queenside. }
8. Nh4 O-O
{ With the black pawn still on h7, I think it's fairly safe to castle and not to worry about a mass of White pawns attacking at the kingside. Black can start it with 8...Nc6 and ...Be6 later first, and only then castle. }
9. Ng2
{ This has been tried in the game Van Wely,L @@StartBracket@@2608@@EndBracket@@-Nguyen,T @@StartBracket@@2535@@EndBracket@@ Novy Bor m1 rapid 2019. }
9... c6
{ The idea is not to play ...d5 but rather limit the white knight's radius! }
10. Ne3 Be6 11. Bg2 Nbd7
{ One of the important lessons of this chapter is to understand, when not to rush! Here  11...d5  would be a positional mistake as White would gladly take twice on d5 with the pawns and then just castle and say thank you for the increased power of the White bishops. It doesn't mean that Black isn't going to play ...d5, just not yet and if necessary, then under much better circumstances. }
12. O-O Qc7
{ For Black, the b-pawn push looks much more dynamic and fighting for more than equality. }
13. f4 exf4
{ From Black's perspective, nothing changes and White shouldn't be allowed to charge forward with f5 and the center closed. }
14. gxf4 Nc5 { White's position can't be desired. } *

