6... O-O
{ One of the rare games in this line was played between some of the best players in the World - Aronian vs Caruana. While both players were trying to play very tricky, you will recognize some of the ideas that I'm mentioning in this chapter. }
7. Nf3 Be6
{ I assume the trick of Fabiano's move is to wait for White to play 8.Nh4 so that Black can immediately proceed with ...c6 and ...d5. I don't think that's mandatory but what Caruana chose for the game. Levon decided not to allow it. }
8. Ng5
{ There are plenty of ways how White can continue to be tricky, for example, start with  8.Be2 }
8... Bd7
{ Black isn't interested to give up the light-squared bishop for the knight - it's a too important piece, and very often Black will base his counterplay on it. }
9. f3 { Aronian switches back to a known setup and now Caruana does the same. }
9... a5 10. Nh3 a4 11. Nf2 Nc6
{ Now Black decided to force matters a little to open the queenside by targeting the c4 pawn. }
12. Be2 Na5 13. b4
{ White didn't have to do it immediately but Black would had forced him with ...Be6 next. }
13... axb3 14. axb3 Nc6
{ Black managed to open the a-file to generate counterplay. After several moves, Caruana built up the breakthrough in the center. }
15. Rb1 Be6 16. Nd1 Ne7 17. O-O c6
{ Now ...d5 already seems to be inevitable. White still can't play f4, here because of a tactical shot after ...exf4, followed by ...Nxe4 and ... Bf5. }
18. Bg5 Nd7 19. Qd2 h6
{ Black pushes back the white bishop to reposition the knight back to f6. } 20.
Be3 Nf6 21. Nf2 d5
{ Black played a flawless strategical game to reach a perfect position after the opening. I'm not sure if you can use this game as a theory but it certainly helps to better understand the arising positions. Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2752@@EndBracket@@-Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2819@@EndBracket@@ Norway Chess 7th 2019. }
