[White "11. Two Knights: 4.e4 and 6.f3"]
[Black "5.dxc3 and 6.f3: #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. e4
{ This move has sparked a lot of interest at the highest level - in the last couple of years it was frequently used by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen, followed by other elite grandmasters as well. The idea is already known, but for years it was executed differently. Normally White would play the 'standard'  4.Bg2  first and then have the option to play e4 later. The reason why White includes it here is that the bishop is not always going to g2. It might but probably it won't. }
4... Bxc3
{ The most popular continuation and very principled, which is also consistent with Black's approach in the entire course. Here the idea is to stop White from playing Nge2 next so that after a possible capture later White can't take on c3 with the knight. White has two options to capture the bishop, and both have been tested. }
5. dxc3
{ This move is trickier than capturing with the b-pawn so let me explain a couple of major differences. Comparing with the capture of the b-pawn, now for Black, it will be much more difficult to go for the d-pawn push as there's one more obstacle - the white queen. Instead of pursuing a strong pawn center and a quick kingside attack here White mostly relies on the space advantage and intends to squeeze Black very slowly. I think the reason why this line has decent popularity among strong grandmasters is that to play it out properly, Black needs to understand the core ideas, less actual theory. }
5... d6
{ Comparing with the b-pawn capture, here   5...Nxe4  is just outright bad and not something even to consider as White has access to  6.Qd5  and immediate advantage of two bishops in an open position. I advise by not rushing with castling short and make several useful moves first to see, where White will put his king. The text move is just useful and strengthens Black's center. }
6. f3
{ Similarly like after 5. bxc3, White also fixes the center here with f3 and intends to press for a long-term space advantage, ideally rerouting the knight to d5 and trying to make good use of the dark-squared bishop. One of White's ideas in the particular pawn setup is also to play Nh3-f2 and push f4-f5 at the right moment. This is something that you're going to pay attention to quite a lot.   Black would love to execute the ...c6 and ...d5 thrust but not right now - you're just not ready for this. The idea will be in the air for a long time and I suggest watching out for the right moment. Also, I don't suggest mixing an early castle and ...h6 and I propose to avoid the latter move as such as this could give White an interesting opportunity to start a kingside attack with g4 and with or without h4 to play g5. Be patient.   There are several ways to play this out position but I suggest planning your game so that you have clear targets - the most dangerous position is one without a clear plan or targets. }
6... a5
{ A deep idea, based on a good understanding of where this game will be heading - with the given pawn structure White is signaling about castling long so the a-pawn early movement is a friendly reminder that Black is capable of organizing an offensive at the queenside. The black pawn is heading to as far as a4 to secure the c5 square for the black knight as an outpost. Should White change his mind and castle short after all, it also will make it a little easier to open the queenside because Black will be targeting the c4 pawn and White will want to include b3.   I suggest for the time being to forget about any pawn thrusts in the center - ...c6-d5 will be quite difficult to make it and the traditional ...f5 can backfire if played at the wrong moment. Focus on developing your pieces on good squares and watch out what White is planning. If castling short, think twice about playing ...h6 as this is something that will only accelerate White's initiative at the kingside. Now White has a choice here - either block the a-pawn's push with a4, meet it with b3 so that any further a-pawn push can be answered by b4 and the position remains closed, or just ignore it. }
7. Nh3
{ White ignores Black's activities at the queenside and focuses on his own. The awkward knight jump is the most flexible move in the position and I imagine on most occasions White will start with exactly this move. The knight is rerouted to f2 and if Black would think about an early d-pawn push in the center, White can respond with f4 or g4-g5 - the knight on f2 extra protects the pawn on e4. White's light-squared bishop typically doesn't go to g2 here but it doesn't mean it's impossible. The bishop for the time being remains on the f1-a6 diagonal which is also one of the reasons why I'm not suggesting the typical ...a6 and ...b5 plan here. }
7... a4
{ Black secures even more space at the queenside. If you're concerned that this burns some of the precious time, White is doing the same with the f3, Nh3-f2 maneuvers, trying to limit your gameplay. Remember, there's no need to castle short just yet and give White a green light to start a massive pawn push at the kingside. }
8. Nf2
{ White might include   8.Be3  first but then Black can continue with  8...Nc6  and the knight from h3 will have to move sooner or later to f2. Black is normally planning to play ...Be6 but this would allow White to play Ng5 and aim for a trade. Black might consider including ...h6 as well but if you can save some time without playing it, that's a little achievement. }
8... Be6
{ The knight from h3 is gone, and now the bishop can be developed. This is perhaps the trickiest order of the moves, not revealing all the cards immediately. The queenside knight might be developed also to d7-c5 but, to be honest, I see no reason to chain the black knights together as it would take away squares that they operate. }
9. Bd3
{ The modern way to continue - White positions his light-squared bishop on d3 for extra protection of the e4 and c4 pawns, intends to continue with Qe2 next so that for Black it's much more difficult to open the game at the queenside. }
9... Nfd7
{ A very flexible move which makes a lot of sense because in this setup the knight of f6 doesn't do anything. From d7 the knight controls a lot more important squares but not necessarily it will have to jump to c5. You'll see, why. Black has also freed the f-file for the f-pawn push but not for ...f5 as the white knight on f2 is only waiting for the e4 square to become vacant - Black wants to play f6 and target the c4 pawn! An additional extra is that the text move opens the d8-h4 diagonal for the queen so if White would consider some oddities with g4 to stop any supposed...f5 pawn advancements @@StartBracket@@not that we want it@@EndBracket@@, there's the annoying ...Qh4 in the end. If possible, Black should be quite happy to trade with the knight on c5 the light-squared bishop on d3 just because the bishop controls some very important squares, most notably c4 and f5. }
10. Qe2
{ White is getting ready to meet ... Nc5 with Bc2 and the pawn on c4 remains protected. Any f4 push should be answered with ...exf4, ...Qe7 and ...Nc5. }
10... Nc6 11. Nd1
{ If the white knight leaves the f2 square and is eyeing towards a bright future on d5, this is when Black can resume the traditional plan of the ...f5 push as the white knight after the trade won't be able to jump on e4 anymore. }
11... O-O 12. Ne3 Ne7
{ Now the question is - what should White do about Black's plan? There are not many options - either allow it, stop it or block it. }
13. Nf5
{ White stopping the f-pawn push with  13.g4  probably is the worst choice at it weakens a lot of squares in the process. For example, after  13...Ng6  14.Ng2  Black can fire away  14...Nh4!  with ...Nc5 next. }
13... Nc5
{ Black is already threatening with a couple of trades, leaving White with multiple light-squared weaknesses, thus the next move feels to be necessary. }
14. Bc2 Qd7 15. g4
{ White has secured the knight's position on f5 but now Black can execute an already familiar idea. }
15... f6 16. h4 Qe8
{ The white knight on f5 is not going to hold for long and White has some problems defending the c4 pawn. }
*

