8. Nh3
{ White has improvised at the opening quite a bit, first going for a strong pawn center and then continuing a slow development. What's wrong with this plan? }
8... exd4 9. cxd4 d5
{ White shouldn't open the center if seriously underdeveloped! Black should seek ways to punish White immediately. }
10. cxd5 Nxe4 11. fxe4 Rxe4+ 12. Kf2 Bg4
{ Black has a huge attack - with a perfect play, White's already lost. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.e4"]
[Black "6.dxc3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. dxc3
{ This is a much less popular move but still perfectly playable and one of the favorite continuations of another leading Latvian grandmaster and my colleague in the Latvian national team Normunds Miezis. White is aiming for a solid setup at the center and makes sure that Black can't go with the ...c6 and d5 setup which is the traditional approach against bxc3 setups. Comparing with the previous chapter, here for Black it's a little easier to organize counterplay on the queenside because the White light-squared bishop is gone from the f1-a6 diagonal and thus Black with some exceptions will mostly rely on the ...a6 and ...b5 setups. }
6... d6
{ White has a few options at his disposal but overall they make a little difference. First, White should decide where he's going to position the queen - on e2 or c2. The kingside knight is normally developed to f3 but an alternative route is h3-f2. Then there's the reaction to Black's activities at the queenside - either try to meet it or just ignore it. I will walk you through step by step. If White wants to position his knight on f3,  it has to protect the  e4  pawn first, because the immediate  7.Nf3  will run into  7...Nxe4  and now  8.Nxe5  already loses the game due to  8...Re8  and White suffers material losses. }
7. Qc2
{ Before bringing the knight out, that's an alternate way to protect the pawn on e4 - additionally, on c2 the white queen extra protects the b3 square which might be important in the arising structures later. However, with this move, the pawn on c4 remains unprotected and Black can quickly provoke White into playing b3, which will allow Black faster to generate counterplay at the queenside. }
7... Be6 8. b3
{ This is almost necessary. White might acknowledge the loss of tempo and play  8.Qe2  but in this scenario, Black has the extra time to reposition his queen from d8-e8-c6 and pressure the pawn on c4. }
8... a5
{ Here this is a better and much direct move than ...a6 thus an exception to the traditional plan - it's time to open the position at the queenside. Here White faces an uneasy choice - allow Black to play ...a4 and give up the a-file, or play a4 himself and create an eternal weakness on b3. }
9. a4
{ This closes the queenside for good, leaving White with some obvious weaknesses in the position. Black should continue the development and prepare the ...f5 push. }
9... Nbd7
{ The black knight will have a wonderful outpost on c5. If White would challenge it with the potential bishop trade either through e3 or a3, Black can always include ...b6 first so that after the capture takes on c5 with the b-pawn and open the b-file for some pressure against the weak b3 pawn, and still go for the ...f5 push. }
10. Nf3 Nc5
{ This comes with some thematic tricks that are not obvious. The careful response here is to protect the b3 pawn. }
11. Nd2
{ 11.Nh4  b5!  looks quite nasty for White - taking with the c-pawn is met by ...Bxb3, but  12.axb5  a4!  White's queenside collapses after  13.bxa4  Bxc4  with numerous threats, most notably ...Bb3 or ... Bxb5. }
11... Qc8
{ Now with the white knight on the passive d2 square and blocking the dark-squared bishop's access to the g5 square, Black can afford not to waste time on ...h6 and go for the light-squared bishop trade to play ...f5 later. The queen on c8 here feels a little more flexible as Black can use the d7 square for a knight retreat, although there's probably nothing wrong by positioning it on d7 as well. }
12. O-O
{ White could play  12.h3  to stop the bishop trade but doing it would simply run out of good moves as castling short has become impossible and Black can carry on with his traditional plans. }
12... Bh3 13. f3 Bxg2 14. Kxg2
{ Mission accomplished for Black - the light-squared bishops are gone and the threat of the f-pawn push is in the air. }
14... b6
{ This move is useful almost always - Black makes sure that White can't launch a surprise counter-attack at the queenside with b4 and Nb3, and also protecting the knight on c5 just in case, ready to recapture it with the b-pawn. }
15. Rf2
{ One of the traditional routes for the white knight but Black is a little faster. }
15... Nh5 16. Nf1 f5
{ Black is about to develop an initiative at the kingside. Notice how Black saved a tempo for not playing ...h6. }
