7. Qc2
{ Before bringing the knight out, that's an alternate way to protect the pawn on e4 - additionally, on c2 the white queen extra protects the b3 square which might be important in the arising structures later. However, with this move, the pawn on c4 remains unprotected and Black can quickly provoke White into playing b3, which will allow Black faster to generate counterplay at the queenside. }
7... Be6 8. b3
{ This is almost necessary. White might acknowledge the loss of tempo and play  8.Qe2  but in this scenario, Black has the extra time to reposition his queen from d8-e8-c6 and pressure the pawn on c4. }
8... a5
{ Here this is a better and much direct move than ...a6 thus an exception to the traditional plan - it's time to open the position at the queenside. Here White faces an uneasy choice - allow Black to play ...a4 and give up the a-file, or play a4 himself and create an eternal weakness on b3. }
9. Nf3
{ White allows Black to play ...a4 and this means Black will always have a good counterplay and won't have to worry about a lack of an active game plan. }
9... a4 10. Rb1
{ This is necessary, otherwise White wouldn't be able to recapture on b3 with the pawn, leaving his pawn structure completely shattered and easy targets. }
10... h6
{ This is a traditional move for the structure that Black should always try to evaluate - can you live without it or not. Here it secures the bishop's position on e6 against various Ng5 jumps and makes sure that White can't play Bg5 later at some point. Had the white knight been on d2, Black could try to save a tempo on this move. }
11. O-O Qd7
{ A multi-purpose move - Black is preparing the bishop trade on h3 and also is about to conquer the a-file. }
12. Nh4
{ I assume that this maneuver makes the most sense as on f3 the knight doesn't do much anyway. }
12... axb3
{ Either now or a move later - Black should open the a-file for business. } 13.
axb3 Nc6 14. Nf5
{ As already common for these types of positions, here  14.f4  is not a good move - Black will continue with  14...exf4  and after  15.gxf4  Bh3  White is left with another weakness on e4. Capturing on f4 with a piece leaves the e5 square as an outpost for a black knight. }
14... Ne7
{ Black pushes away the knight - Black should be quite happy to trade the knights. }
15. Ne3 Bh3
{ In general, this is a good move, even if Black is not thinking about ...f5 just yet. The center feels a little clumsy so trading a couple of pieces will give the black pieces more air. Also, the trade makes sure that White can't push f4 as it would seriously weaken the e4 pawn. Black is focusing on the queenside. }
16. f3 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Ra6
{ Black is a little faster at doing everything. He could position the queen on e6 and either go for the ...c6 and ...d5 push, or prepare the ...f5 thrust. With the queen on d7, even the b5 push looks very much reasonable. White is reacting to Black's threats and hasn't a plan of his own. Perhaps g4 and h4 with a future g5 push might work but I can't imagine this being a serious threat with the a-file already open. }
