6... d6
{ White has a few options at his disposal but overall they make a little difference. First, White should decide where he's going to position the queen - on e2 or c2. The kingside knight is normally developed to f3 but an alternative route is h3-f2. Then there's the reaction to Black's activities at the queenside - either try to meet it or just ignore it. I will walk you through step by step. If White wants to position his knight on f3,  it has to protect the  e4  pawn first, because the immediate  7.Nf3  will run into  7...Nxe4  and now  8.Nxe5  already loses the game due to  8...Re8  and White suffers material losses. }
7. Ne2
{ This is a traditional positional inaccuracy by somebody who doesn't fully understand the nuances of the structure. While seemingly it's a logical move as White is completing his development, the knight on e2 is misplaced and the only way how White could try to activate it is playing later h3 and g4, positioning it on g3, but this is very slow and Black will be a lot faster at the queenside. }
7... a6
{ With the white knight on e2 the ...a6-b5 thrust should be even more powerful. BTW, there's nothing wrong with the normal a-pawn push to a4 as well. }
8. O-O b5 9. cxb5
{ A forced decision as  9.Qd3  to protect the pawn and attack the b5 pawn would meet  9...Nbd7  and not only can White not take twice on b5 because of the ...Ba6 threat and the knight on e2 hangs, but also  10.Be3  is met by the annoying  10...Ng4 }
9... axb5 { The queenside is open, Black has enough targets to pressure. } 10.
h3
{ Just like Black's counterpart of ...h6, this move is useful for White as it allows to position the dark-squared bishop on e3 without worrying about ...Ng4, and also gives the option to play g4 later to reroute the sad knight to g3. }
10... Bb7 11. Qc2 Nbd7
{ Since Black might be thinking about an immediate ...d5, recapturing with the bishop and then focusing on the attack at the kingside, it makes sense for White to slow it down. }
12. Rd1 Ra6
{ As I can tell from my own experience with the Sicilian Rossolimo, this maneuver works especially good if the opponent's knight is standing on the awkward e2 @@StartBracket@@e7@@EndBracket@@ square. }
13. c4
{ White has to do something about the incoming threats and it's difficult to give a piece of good advice. }
13... bxc4
{ Black should open the position as the queenside is where lies Black's gameplay. }
14. Qxc4 Rc6 15. Qd3 Nc5 16. Qe3 Rb6
{ The complications are over - the position is inevitably opening and White hasn't finished his development yet while Black has a very active play. Again, Black managed to save a tempo on ... h6. }
