6... d6
{ White has a few options at his disposal but overall they make a little difference. First, White should decide where he's going to position the queen - on e2 or c2. The kingside knight is normally developed to f3 but an alternative route is h3-f2. Then there's the reaction to Black's activities at the queenside - either try to meet it or just ignore it. I will walk you through step by step. If White wants to position his knight on f3,  it has to protect the  e4  pawn first, because the immediate  7.Nf3  will run into  7...Nxe4  and now  8.Nxe5  already loses the game due to  8...Re8  and White suffers material losses. }
7. Qe2
{ The best move in the position - White makes sure that both c4 and e4 pawns are protected and is about to develop his kingside knight. }
7... Nbd7
{ A good developing move to wait and see which direction White is going to play - the knight from d7 is usually heading to c5 but there might be occasions when it will stay behind. As explained before, usually Black will go for ...a6 and ...b5 setup, with some minor exceptions. }
8. Nh3
{ The white knight is heading to f2 but there might be moments when White might be interested to push f4-f5. Make sure that Black has access to ...exf4 if that happens. }
8... a6
{ White can't play  9.a4  here because after  9...Nc5  Black is threatening with multiple things, starting with winning the pawn on e4, forking on b3, or opening the position with ...Bd7 and ...b5 later. }
9. f3
{ White is consistent with the plan, rerouting the knight to f2.   9.Be3  would transpose to a covered line with a potential pawn sacrifice after  9...b5 }
9... b5
{ Black opens the queenside and offers the b-pawn as a gift. It's risky for White to accept it because after   10.cxb5  axb5  11.Qxb5  Black can play  11...Nc5  with multiple threats, most notably ... Ba6 or ...Nb3 at some point, winning back the a2 pawn. If White doesn't react, Black wants to take on c4 himself, forcing White to take the pawn and then continue with ...a5 and ...Ba6. }
10. Be3
{ Including the pawn trade hands over to Black the control of many squares at the queenside, plus opens the a-file thus it's understandable that White doesn't want to do it if it has a choice. }
10... bxc4 11. Qxc4
{ If White would try to be tricky and play  11.Nf2  instead, you can be pretty sure that he's planning the f4-f5 maneuver and an expansion at the kingside. Just make sure that you can take the f-pawn as soon as it's on f4.  11...Rb8  12.f4  exf4  looks good enough but there might be other interesting options as well. }
11... a5
{ The light-squared bishop is landing on a6 with a tempo and White doesn't have the time to finish the development. }
12. Qd3 Ba6
{ No matter what White chooses here, Black has got a great game at the queenside and shouldn't worry about lacking a plan. }
13. c4
{ It is very tempting to close the position but it comes together with weakening the d4 square for a potential knight outpost in the future, plus Black can rip the blockade apart quite quickly. }
13... Qe7 14. O-O c6 { The thrust in the center already seems inevitable. } 15.
Qc2 d5 16. b3
{ I imagine that here Black has several great ways to continue but the most logical one is to create some weaknesses in White's camp that can be pressured. }
16... dxe4 17. fxe4 Ng4 18. Bc1 Rfd8
{ Black will reroute the d7 knight to d4. } *

