{ Damljanovic,B @@StartBracket@@2579@@EndBracket@@-Drasko,M @@StartBracket@@2471@@EndBracket@@ SCG-chT 2004, if White doesn't accept the sacrifice, Black can go for the traditional idea. }
10... bxc4 11. Qxc4
{ As already mentioned before, White can't push here  11.f4  because Black does have  11...exf4  and  12.e5  doesn't work for White. }
11... a5 12. Qd3 Ba6 13. c4 Qe7
{ Depending on the availability, Black might go for the ...c6 and ...d5 push, or reroute the d7 knight to d4, strengthening it with the c-pawn. }
14. Rfd1 { This stops the ...c6-d5 idea. } 14... Rfd8
{ The black rook is much better positioned here than the b-file as the latter won't do Black much good. Also, Black is keeping eye on the f4-f5 push and is ready to take on f4. }
15. b3 Bb7
{ With the white pawn on b3, the bishop on a6 has nothing to do anymore. } 16.
f3 Nc5 17. Qc2
{ Taking on c5 would just hand Black the d4 outpost on the platter. } 17... Ne6
{ I had a similar position a couple of times with GM Miezis myself - he's been playing this line his entire career. White allows the black knight to jump on d4 and tries to ignore it, as trading the knight on d4 would give Black...cxd4 with a protected passed pawn and an easy game on the queenside. There's a lot of maneuvering involved but I suggest keeping an eye on two things - be ready that White might reroute his knight to d5 and don't miss the f4 thrust. Black looks better here but the entire game is still ahead. It makes sense to go for the ...a4 plan and pressure the b-pawn but be ready that White might respond with b4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.e4"]
[Black "6.dxc3: #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. dxc3
{ This is a much less popular move but still perfectly playable and one of the favorite continuations of another leading Latvian grandmaster and my colleague in the Latvian national team Normunds Miezis. White is aiming for a solid setup at the center and makes sure that Black can't go with the ...c6 and d5 setup which is the traditional approach against bxc3 setups. Comparing with the previous chapter, here for Black it's a little easier to organize counterplay on the queenside because the White light-squared bishop is gone from the f1-a6 diagonal and thus Black with some exceptions will mostly rely on the ...a6 and ...b5 setups. }
6... d6
{ White has a few options at his disposal but overall they make a little difference. First, White should decide where he's going to position the queen - on e2 or c2. The kingside knight is normally developed to f3 but an alternative route is h3-f2. Then there's the reaction to Black's activities at the queenside - either try to meet it or just ignore it. I will walk you through step by step. If White wants to position his knight on f3,  it has to protect the  e4  pawn first, because the immediate  7.Nf3  will run into  7...Nxe4  and now  8.Nxe5  already loses the game due to  8...Re8  and White suffers material losses. }
7. Qe2
{ The best move in the position - White makes sure that both c4 and e4 pawns are protected and is about to develop his kingside knight. }
7... Nbd7
{ A good developing move to wait and see which direction White is going to play - the knight from d7 is usually heading to c5 but there might be occasions when it will stay behind. As explained before, usually Black will go for ...a6 and ...b5 setup, with some minor exceptions. }
8. Be3
{ This is a slightly strange waiting move, not defining the knight's placement just yet, and also guarding the c5 square against a knight jump. Since it's difficult to imagine how the white knight is going to make it on f3 as the pawn on e4 will be under attack, Black can continue with the traditional ...a6 and ...b5 plan as most likely the white knight will be developed to h3. }
8... a6 9. Nh3
{ Here  9.a4  doesn't look so good - Black can continue with  9...Nc5  and not only to threaten to take the e4 pawn but also open the queenside with ...Bd7 and push forward the b-pawn. If White will take on c5, he already agrees to play a slightly worse position. }
9... b5
{ This is an actual pawn sacrifice but it makes a lot of sense as it gives Black several extra tempos to start the initiative and the white knight on h3 feels rather awkward. }
10. cxb5 axb5 11. Qxb5
{ The entire 'snatch the pawn and run away' strategy looks risky but the idea is always there - Black is not bluffing with the sacrifice. }
11... Ba6 12. Qb4
{ This is a strange-looking alternative with intentions to play c4 and Qc3 next but it jumps under the ...c5 tempo which Black should find useful. }
12... c5 13. Qb3 d5
{ Because of the extra tempo with the c-pawn, this is possible immediately. }
14. exd5 e4 15. Bf4 Bd3
{ The arising position looks like a complete disaster for White - I don't see him surviving the incoming attack. }
*

