5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. dxc3
{ This is a much less popular move but still perfectly playable and one of the favorite continuations of another leading Latvian grandmaster and my colleague in the Latvian national team Normunds Miezis. White is aiming for a solid setup at the center and makes sure that Black can't go with the ...c6 and d5 setup which is the traditional approach against bxc3 setups. Comparing with the previous chapter, here for Black it's a little easier to organize counterplay on the queenside because the White light-squared bishop is gone from the f1-a6 diagonal and thus Black with some exceptions will mostly rely on the ...a6 and ...b5 setups. }
6... d6
{ White has a few options at his disposal but overall they make a little difference. First, White should decide where he's going to position the queen - on e2 or c2. The kingside knight is normally developed to f3 but an alternative route is h3-f2. Then there's the reaction to Black's activities at the queenside - either try to meet it or just ignore it. I will walk you through step by step. If White wants to position his knight on f3,  it has to protect the  e4  pawn first, because the immediate  7.Nf3  will run into  7...Nxe4  and now  8.Nxe5  already loses the game due to  8...Re8  and White suffers material losses. }
7. Qe2
{ The best move in the position - White makes sure that both c4 and e4 pawns are protected and is about to develop his kingside knight. }
7... Nbd7
{ A good developing move to wait and see which direction White is going to play - the knight from d7 is usually heading to c5 but there might be occasions when it will stay behind. As explained before, usually Black will go for ...a6 and ...b5 setup, with some minor exceptions. }
8. Be3
{ This is a slightly strange waiting move, not defining the knight's placement just yet, and also guarding the c5 square against a knight jump. Since it's difficult to imagine how the white knight is going to make it on f3 as the pawn on e4 will be under attack, Black can continue with the traditional ...a6 and ...b5 plan as most likely the white knight will be developed to h3. }
8... a6 9. Nh3
{ Here  9.a4  doesn't look so good - Black can continue with  9...Nc5  and not only to threaten to take the e4 pawn but also open the queenside with ...Bd7 and push forward the b-pawn. If White will take on c5, he already agrees to play a slightly worse position. }
9... b5
{ This is an actual pawn sacrifice but it makes a lot of sense as it gives Black several extra tempos to start the initiative and the white knight on h3 feels rather awkward. }
10. cxb5 axb5 11. Qxb5
{ The entire 'snatch the pawn and run away' strategy looks risky but the idea is always there - Black is not bluffing with the sacrifice. }
11... Ba6 12. Qb3
{ Mista,A @@StartBracket@@2561@@EndBracket@@-Balcerak,J @@StartBracket@@2447@@EndBracket@@ BL2-Sued 2012. }
12... Qe7
{ Black has multiple ideas - either push the d-pawn immediately or prepare it with ...c6 first, or play ...Rfb8 with a tempo. Unfortunately the immediate 'punishment' with  12...d5  doesn't work - White can take the pawn with  13.exd5  and meet  13...e4  with  14.Bd4  This maneuver was impossible with the black pawn on c5. }
13. Qc2
{ Or  13.Qd1  ,  Black's response would be the same.   White could try to close the black bishop with  13.c4  but after  13...c6  the incoming ...d5 is unstoppable.   13.f3  would meet the immediate  13...d5! }
13... d5 14. exd5
{ This is forced as White can't keep the position closed. After  14.f3  Black would just open it with  14...dxe4  15.fxe4  Ng4  and the white king under a heavy attack. }
14... e4
{ Mainly Black is threatening with  ...Ne5  and jump either to d3 or f3,  but after  15.Bd4  there's the alternative idea  15...Bd3  ,  followed by ... Nxd5 and ...c5. White has to do something about that dangerous bishop on a6 - either trade it or close it. }
15. Bf1
{ The most human response - this allows the white king to escape at the kingside but drops one extra pawn in the process. }
15... Ne5 16. Bxa6 Rxa6
{ The check on f3 can wait - the white king is going to g2 anyway. } 17. O-O
Nf3+ 18. Kg2
{ The dust has settled - Black has sacrificed a pawn for a strong initiative, the white king feels quite exposed. }
18... Nxd5 19. Ng1 Rg6
{ Black sets a nice trap - after  20.Nxf3  exf3+  21.Kxf3  Black wins after  21...Rf6+  22.Kg2  Qxe3!   but if the white king retreats with  21.Kh1  ,  Black continues the strong attack with  21...Qe6  and ...Qh3. }
20. Qe2 Ne5
{ Black has a powerful initiative and has more than enough compensation for the lost pawn. }
