{ This is engine's choice which looks scary from a human's perspective. } 16...
Qxc4 17. Nf4 Rfe8
{ An important move to prepare to play ...Ne5 next. The point is also not to miss White's idea to include b3 and castle long! }
18. Bf1
{ Here it would be interesting for White to consider  18.b3  Qb5  19.O-O-O  but after  19...g5  the white knight doesn't have a lot of good retreat squares and on h3 it would be imprisoned with ...h6 - that's why the other black knight remains on d7 to protect the knight on f6. }
18... Qa4 19. Qd4
{ White tries to trade off the queens immediately - White could include here  19.b3  Qa3  and keep the queens on the board - We can recapture the pawn back whenever it feels ready and by no means has worse chances. }
19... Bxf1 20. Kxf1
{ Apparently after the intermezzo  20.Qxa4  Rxa4  21.Kxf1  Rb8  for White it is very difficult to defend the b-pawn as  22.b3  is met by  22...Rxb3! }
20... Qa6+ 21. Kg2 g5 22. Nh3 h6
{ The weakened white king and the squares around it should greatly compensate the sacrificed pawn and Black has a long-term initiative. For example,  23.Rhc1  Ne5  24.Rxc7  Rad8  25.Rc5  Nfg4  .  I'm sure this line can be improved somewhere along the way but the entire approach from White doesn't make a lot of sense to go here. Weirder things have happened before, though. }
