8... Nc5
{ The question to White - are you going to position your knight on Nd2 or Nh4? Because depending on the answer, Black's chosen strategy will be different. }
9. Nh4
{ The white knight on h4 feels a little more active but it might get rerouted to e3 anyway. }
9... a6
{ Because the white knight is so far away at the kingside, I suggest switching over to the ...a6-b5 plan and the knight on h4 can't participate in keeping together the queenside. That's essentially the difference between Nh4 and Nd2. }
10. O-O Be6
{ Again, the ...b5 threat is something that White should deal with - the light-squared bishop is eyeing as far as the a2 pawn. }
11. f4
{ With the knight on h4 it might be possible that White might consider this shot and ready to recapture on f4 with the bishop, as the knight is heading to f5 square. }
11... exf4 { The human choice. } 12. Bxf4
{ White can't recapture on f4 with the pawn because the knight on h4 will hang due to the ...Nfxe4 threat. }
12... Ng4 { Now Black's got a nice outpost on e5. } 13. Nf5 Ne5
{ Probably White already has to take on e5 and fight for the balance, otherwise Black will play ...f6 next with a neat but solid advantage. }
14. Bxe5 dxe5 15. Rad1 Nd7 16. c5 Kh8
{ Black has a structural advantage - White has no attack going at the kingside and the pin at the d-file can be easily solved. Still, objectively this is equal. }
