10. O-O Be6
{ Again, the ...b5 threat is something that White should deal with - the light-squared bishop is eyeing as far as the a2 pawn. }
11. b3 b5
{ An alternative is to include  11...h6  first but then the entire idea of pushing the b-pawn comes one move slower. }
12. cxb5 axb5
{ Black already is threatening with ...Nxb3 and the rook on a1 is unprotected. Depending on availability, a strong plan is to double the heavy pieces at the a-file and sacrifice the b-pawn to gain some time. }
13. Bg5 { This initiates a forced sequence where White wins a pawn. } 13... h6
14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxb5 Ra3
{ Black has an amazing compensation for the pawn and can recapture it pretty quick. }
16. b4 Nd7 17. Qb7 Qd8
{ 17...Rxc3  would allow White to force a rook trade and considerably activate his pieces. The pawn isn't going anywhere. }
18. Nf5 Nf6
{ White should have a hard time understanding, what kind of setup to choose. Black can play either ...Qd7 and double the rooks at the a-file, or ...Qb8 to force the queen trade. The a-pawn is lost but Black doesn't have to hurry to recapture it. }
19. Ne3 Qd7
{ Black has a pleasant advantage and might try to hunt the white queen as well. }
