{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. dxc3
{ This is a much less popular move but still perfectly playable and one of the favorite continuations of another leading Latvian grandmaster and my colleague in the Latvian national team Normunds Miezis. White is aiming for a solid setup at the center and makes sure that Black can't go with the ...c6 and d5 setup which is the traditional approach against bxc3 setups. Comparing with the previous chapter, here for Black it's a little easier to organize counterplay on the queenside because the White light-squared bishop is gone from the f1-a6 diagonal and thus Black with some exceptions will mostly rely on the ...a6 and ...b5 setups. }
6... d6
{ White has a few options at his disposal but overall they make a little difference. First, White should decide where he's going to position the queen - on e2 or c2. The kingside knight is normally developed to f3 but an alternative route is h3-f2. Then there's the reaction to Black's activities at the queenside - either try to meet it or just ignore it. I will walk you through step by step. If White wants to position his knight on f3,  it has to protect the  e4  pawn first, because the immediate  7.Nf3  will run into  7...Nxe4  and now  8.Nxe5  already loses the game due to  8...Re8  and White suffers material losses. }
7. Qe2
{ The best move in the position - White makes sure that both c4 and e4 pawns are protected and is about to develop his kingside knight. }
7... Nbd7
{ A good developing move to wait and see which direction White is going to play - the knight from d7 is usually heading to c5 but there might be occasions when it will stay behind. As explained before, usually Black will go for ...a6 and ...b5 setup, with some minor exceptions. }
8. Nf3
{ The main setup and the most normal looking move - the white knight will be rerouted either to d2 or h4 and might end up on e3. Before choosing the best setup, it's important to ask White a question about his intended direction. }
8... Nc5
{ The question to White - are you going to position your knight on Nd2 or Nh4? Because depending on the answer, Black's chosen strategy will be different. }
9. Nh4
{ The white knight on h4 feels a little more active but it might get rerouted to e3 anyway. }
9... a6
{ Because the white knight is so far away at the kingside, I suggest switching over to the ...a6-b5 plan and the knight on h4 can't participate in keeping together the queenside. That's essentially the difference between Nh4 and Nd2. }
10. f3 { Or short castle first, Black's approach will be the same. } 10... Be6
{ Moldavian grandmaster Viktor Bologan already in 2014 showed how to properly counter this system. Before playing the traditional ...b5, Black includes the bishop's development first and now the b-pawn's push looks even stronger. }
11. Be3 Qd7
{ Another great move - the black queen not only is helping to move forward the b-pawn but also can be rerouted to c6 and pressure the c4 pawn. It was possible to start with the b-pawn push as well but that involves a pawn sacrifice and some difficult decisions. The text move is much simpler and very good. }
12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. O-O Rad8
{ The pawn structure is symmetrical but Black's bishop is better. } *

