10. f3 { Or short castle first, Black's approach will be the same. } 10... Be6
{ Moldavian grandmaster Viktor Bologan already in 2014 showed how to properly counter this system. Before playing the traditional ...b5, Black includes the bishop's development first and now the b-pawn's push looks even stronger. }
11. Be3 Qd7
{ Another great move - the black queen not only is helping to move forward the b-pawn but also can be rerouted to c6 and pressure the c4 pawn. It was possible to start with the b-pawn push as well but that involves a pawn sacrifice and some difficult decisions. The text move is much simpler and very good. }
12. O-O
{ Or 12.Bg5 Ne8 first and the entire idea with ...b5 remains the same. } 12...
b5 13. cxb5
{ I don't think White will find it very exciting to play with weak double pawns after   13.b3  bxc4  14.bxc4 }
13... axb5 14. Qf2 Qc6
{ This is the perfect spot for the black queen - there are many targets at the queenside that Black can try to exploit and the old idea of pushing forward the d-pawn reappears again. The white pawn on a2 still appears to be indirectly defended because of the b4 counterpunch but still, this remains something that Black should check every move. If White will play b3, Black can respond with ...Ra3 and doubling the rooks at the a-file. }
15. Nf5
{ Granda Zuniga,J @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@-Bologan,V @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@ Tromsoe Olympiad 2014, you can follow the whole game in the Model games. }
15... Bxf5
{ This appears to be stronger than what Bologan played in the game. } 16. exf5
Rfe8
{ It's two knights vs two bishops! White has several weaknesses in the position which should give the objective evaluation in favor of Black. }
17. a3
{ Or  17.Rfd1  h6  18.g4  Ra4  and Black is controlling all of the important squares. The immediate  17.g4  runs into  17...Nd3!  and the black knight is rerouted to f4. }
17... Nb3 18. Rad1 d5
{ White should be looking forward to a desperate attack at the kingside. } 19.
g4 h6 20. h4
{ Black should remain calm and control all the important squares. } 20... Qc4
21. g5 Nh5
{ Again, controlling the squares very often is more important than the number of pawns. Black is threatening with the incoming ...d4 threat to trade White's dark-squared bishop and occupy the f4 square with the kingside knight. }
22. f4 exf4 23. Bxf4 Re2 24. Qf3
{ 24.Bxd5  Rxf2  25.Bxc4  Rxf1+  26.Bxf1  Nxf4  and White is down a piece. }
24... Nxf4
{ Now the position simplifies with an advantage for Black in the end. } 25.
Qxf4 Qxf4 26. Rxf4 c6
{ White's kingside offensive has ended without results - White has numerous weaknesses, Black has more active pieces. }
