[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.e4"]
[Black "6.bxc3 and 7.Ne2: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. bxc3
{ This is the main move in the position with an ambition to fight for the center with d3, castle short, and push f4. With the light-squared bishop on g2 and the black king already tucked away in safety, it's the right time to strike at the center. }
6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. Ne2
{ This is the most played move in the position and to my understanding, it's been neutralized. Even though White is developing a knight and is about to castle short and strike in the center, the knight on e2 feels to be misplaced and often will cause White some headaches. }
7... d5 { If nobody's stopping it, there's no reason for a delay. } 8. cxd5
cxd5 9. exd5 Nxd5
{ These moves are almost automatic and before we move on to the next one, I'd like to point it out that the alternatives here don't look impressive. }
10. d4
{ White might consider striking in the center while the black knight is still on b8 and not challenging the center. }
10... exd4 11. cxd4
{ This doesn't look good at all. With the white king stuck in the center, Black can already launch a swift attack. }
11... Bg4 12. f3
{ If White has to make this move at some point, it's not because of a good life - it closes the light-squared bishop on g2 and weakens the e3 square. }
12... Be6 13. O-O Nc6
{ In one game, already in a worse position, White decided to activate the closed bishop on g2, but at the wrong moment and things escalated quickly. }
14. f4 Bg4
{ White already is strategically lost. Black wrapped up the game in several moves. }
15. Qb3 Bxe2 16. Rf2 Nb6
{ Now  17.Rxe2  will be met with  17...Nxd4  and White loses a lot of material. }
17. Bxc6 Bc4
{ 0-1 Steindorsson,S @@StartBracket@@2227@@EndBracket@@-Stefansson,H @@StartBracket@@2561@@EndBracket@@ Icelandic Team championships 2005. }
*

