{ It's important to keep the black knight on d5 to counter the activity of the white bishop on g2. }
12. O-O Nc6 13. Qc5 Qb6
{ Black has finished development and has no weaknesses while White has a big one on c3 which is compensated by the power of the bishops. The position probably is dead equal - I can easily imagine both sides trading the pawns at the queenside, leaving 3 vs 3 at the kingside and nothing to play for. }
