7... d5 { If nobody's stopping it, there's no reason for a delay. } 8. cxd5
cxd5 9. exd5 Nxd5
{ These moves are almost automatic and before we move on to the next one, I'd like to point it out that the alternatives here don't look impressive. }
10. O-O Nc6
{ This is the critical position of the entire line and here several moves have been tested. If allowed, Black just wants to finish the development by bringing out the light-squared bishop, followed by ...Qd7 and pressure those white pawns at the queenside. }
11. f4
{ This is a traditional way how White tries to destroy Black's center to take it over later, but here Black has a powerful novelty. Askarov,M @@StartBracket@@2499@@EndBracket@@-Zakhartsov,V  @@StartBracket@@2586@@EndBracket@@ Nezhmetdinov Memorial 32nd 2010. }
11... e4
{ Like thunder from clear skies! Black sacrifices the pawn to accelerate his development and gain total control over the light-squares. The pawn sacrifice has to be accepted, as the alternatives don't look inspiring at all. }
12. Bxe4 Re8
{ For Black it's important to remember - don't look for a forced mate or immediate material gains. Create positional threats, make good-looking moves and the payday will come. }
13. d3 Bh3 14. Rf2
{ Or  14.Bg2  Bxg2  15.Kxg2  Qd7!  and White is running out of moves. Black wants to play ...Rad8 and at the right time either ...Ne3 or even ...b5-b4 to gain more squares. The white king is wide open for an incoming attack. }
14... Nf6 15. Bg2 Bxg2 16. Rxg2 Qd7
{ Black dominates the light squares. White can keep the pawn for the time being but his entire army looks awkward with no real purpose. }
