[Black "6.bxc3 and 7.Ne2: #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. bxc3
{ This is the main move in the position with an ambition to fight for the center with d3, castle short, and push f4. With the light-squared bishop on g2 and the black king already tucked away in safety, it's the right time to strike at the center. }
6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. Ne2
{ This is the most played move in the position and to my understanding, it's been neutralized. Even though White is developing a knight and is about to castle short and strike in the center, the knight on e2 feels to be misplaced and often will cause White some headaches. }
7... d5 { If nobody's stopping it, there's no reason for a delay. } 8. cxd5
cxd5 9. exd5 Nxd5
{ These moves are almost automatic and before we move on to the next one, I'd like to point it out that the alternatives here don't look impressive. }
10. O-O Nc6
{ This is the critical position of the entire line and here several moves have been tested. If allowed, Black just wants to finish the development by bringing out the light-squared bishop, followed by ...Qd7 and pressure those white pawns at the queenside. }
11. Rb1
{ The main move in the position which makes the most sense - White is not defining his setup just yet and instead wants to pressure Black's b-pawn a bit. However, it comes with a downside - now the rook on b1 can be attacked with a tempo, and also the a2 pawn is now unprotected. }
11... Nb6
{ It is possible to start with  11...Re8  to dodge any Ba3 ideas but the text move is the simplest and most tested approach. Black closes the b-file and depending on how White will play, bring out his light-squared bishop to either e6 or f5. If Black will manage to trade the light-squared bishops, his position is already to be preferred. }
12. d4
{ Consistent with the plan - now that the black knight is gone from the d5 square, White lights up the center. }
12... Be6
{ Simple but effective - Black exploits the fact that the white pawn on a2 has lost support but the main idea is to play ...Bd5 to trade the bishops. }
13. a4 { White is threatening to play a5 but Black has an easy reply. } 13...
Bd5 14. Rb5
{ The most direct  14.dxe5  leads to mass trades after  14...Bxg2  15.Kxg2  Nxe5  16.a5  Nbc4  and quite an obvious draw. }
14... Bxg2
{ With the most powerful white piece traded off now Black has nothing to worry about }
15. Kxg2 a6
{ Several moves give Black a good game, but this is the most direct. } 16. Rc5
{ This is what was played between two top Chinese grandmasters and objectively it's a mistake. If White would play here  16.Rb1  ,  keeping the pressure at the b-file, Black has got a nice choice. He can either go for  16...Na5  17.dxe5  ,  trade queens and continue with ...Nxa4 and ...b5 afterward,   or opt for a more aggressive  16...Qd5+  ,  followed by ...Nc4 and sacrificing the b7 pawn for long-term compensation and great control of the light squares. Both look great. }
16... Nd7 17. Rd5 Ne7
{ The white rook is in trouble and Black can already force a draw, if not in the mood for a fight. }
18. Rd6 Nc8 19. Rd5 Ncb6 20. Rd6 Nc4 { Dance with the knights! } 21. Rd5 Qc7
{ Having landed the knight at the outpost on c4, Black has an advantage. } 22.
dxe5 Qc6 23. f3 Ndxe5
{ White has nothing to show for the two weaknesses at the queenside. Li,C @@StartBracket@@2748@@EndBracket@@-Wang,H @@StartBracket@@2705@@EndBracket@@ China Mind Team 3rd 2015. }
