[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.e4"]
[Black "6.bxc3 and 7.Qb3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. bxc3
{ This is the main move in the position with an ambition to fight for the center with d3, castle short, and push f4. With the light-squared bishop on g2 and the black king already tucked away in safety, it's the right time to strike at the center. }
6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. Qb3
{ White could try to stop Black's d-pawn from advancing but practice shows that early queen jumps are rarely good. This is not an exception. }
7... Na6 { Of course! Black shouldn't object to winning a tempo. } 8. Ba3
{ If you say A, it makes sense to say B as well, especially if it comes with a tempo. It could be difficult for White to understand that this tempting move is not a good one. }
8... d6
{ Black has a simple plan - exploit the fact that the white queen is developed early and organize an offensive at the queenside. The ...d5 thrust now becomes irrelevant - there are new targets. }
9. Ne2 Nc5 10. Qc2
{ I don't see White taking on c5 as it would trade away his pride - the two bishop advantage and hope for a strong pawn center in the future. }
10... Be6
{ This forces White to protect the pawn c4 as here  11.d4  would run into some major problems after  11...exd4  12.cxd4  ,  double-take on e4 and ...Qa5 check, winning the bishop on a3. }
11. d3
{ When I saw this position while I was writing the course, it seemed so familiar - I definitely could remember playing it myself! After reviewing my games, I remembered - this is what I played against another Latvian GM Normunds Miezis several years ago, leading to a convincing win! }
11... b5 { The best move, forcing White to open the queenside. } 12. cxb5
{ Technically White doesn't have to take it yet but he will have to sooner or later. White might try to include  12.O-O  first, intending to meet  12...bxc4  with  13.d4!  However, Black has nowhere to hurry and after the accurate   12...Re8  the threats remain, and even more important - White's d4 counter-strike can be punched back with trading the pawns on d4, sacrificing the knight on e4, followed by ...Bxc4 and winning back the knight on e2. }
12... cxb5 13. O-O Re8 14. f4
{ White has the two bishops and a good center - from afar it must look alright. }
14... Rc8
{ If you look closer, it should become apparent that it's very difficult for White to develop an initiative at the kingside while Black is already to start one at the queenside. }
*

