{ When I saw this position while I was writing the course, it seemed so familiar - I definitely could remember playing it myself! After reviewing my games, I remembered - this is what I played against another Latvian GM Normunds Miezis several years ago, leading to a convincing win! }
11... Qa5
{ This is what I played in the game - while it's not as impressive as the text's move, it comes with a beautiful idea. }
12. Bb4 Qa6
{ Black wants to sacrifice the knight on d3,  followed by ...Bxc4 and ...c5 next. Here White would have to play  13.Bxc5  dxc5  14.O-O  b5  but after  15.cxb5  cxb5  16.d4  White should be able to keep the balance, Black continuing with  16...Bc4 }
13. a4
{ My experienced opponent defended against the idea to trap the bishop with ... c5, but there's still the attack! }
13... Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 Bxc4
{ This leads to a very complicated game. White immediately erred. } 15. Qd1
{ 15.Qc2  was better, not minding to lose the third pawn on e4 after  ...Bd3  . }
15... Rad8 16. g4
{ Miezis,N  @@StartBracket@@2506@@EndBracket@@-Neiksans,A @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@ Latvian Team Championship 2016. }
16... c5 17. Ba3 d5 { Black has a powerful attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.e4"]
[Black "6.bxc3 and 7.Qb3: #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. bxc3
{ This is the main move in the position with an ambition to fight for the center with d3, castle short, and push f4. With the light-squared bishop on g2 and the black king already tucked away in safety, it's the right time to strike at the center. }
6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. Qb3
{ White could try to stop Black's d-pawn from advancing but practice shows that early queen jumps are rarely good. This is not an exception. }
7... Na6 { Of course! Black shouldn't object to winning a tempo. } 8. Ne2
{ This move allows Black to proceed with the traditional plan. } 8... d5
{ This is a temporary pawn sacrifice - White is not ready to keep it, and he shouldn't. To be honest, there's nothing wrong with  8...d6  as well, intending to play ...Be6 and ...Nc5 next. }
9. cxd5 cxd5 10. exd5 Nc5
{ Suddenly Black starts to develop a very strong initiative. } 11. Qc2
{ 11.Qc4   or  11.Qb5  hardly looks like an option due to  11...b6  and the incoming ...Ba6. }
11... Bg4
{ With the white queen on c2, this move is a little stronger than 11...e4 which also is playable. White is experiencing some problems finishing the development due to the awkward placement of the knight on e2. }
12. Ba3 Rc8 13. Nc1
{ Problem fixed and the white king can castle away but the knight on c1 is hardly feeling better. }
13... e4 14. O-O Re8 { Black is in complete control over the center. } 15. c4
b5
{ This looks incredibly powerful. The extra white pawn plays no role here and if White would accept it, Black could think about ...Ne6-g5, going after the white king. }
*

