1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. bxc3
{ This is the main move in the position with an ambition to fight for the center with d3, castle short, and push f4. With the light-squared bishop on g2 and the black king already tucked away in safety, it's the right time to strike at the center. }
6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. Qb3
{ White could try to stop Black's d-pawn from advancing but practice shows that early queen jumps are rarely good. This is not an exception. }
7... Na6 { Of course! Black shouldn't object to winning a tempo. } 8. Ne2
{ This move allows Black to proceed with the traditional plan. } 8... d5
{ This is a temporary pawn sacrifice - White is not ready to keep it, and he shouldn't. To be honest, there's nothing wrong with  8...d6  as well, intending to play ...Be6 and ...Nc5 next. }
9. cxd5 cxd5 10. exd5 Nc5
{ Suddenly Black starts to develop a very strong initiative. } 11. Qb1
{ The difference with  11.Qc2  is that here White keeps tabs on the b7 pawn. }
11... e4
{ Now  11...Bg4  wouldn't be so convincing as after  12.Ba3  Rc8  13.Nc1  ,  followed by a castle, capture on c5 and b7, the queen on b1 appears to be doing so much more than on c2. }
12. O-O b6
{ However, every single move comes with a drawback. The queen on b1 doesn't protect the c4 square. }
13. c4 Ba6 14. Qc2 Nxd5 { Black wins back the pawn with a great position. } 15.
Ba3 Rc8 16. f3
{ Black has many interesting options here, most notably  16...Qg5  to play ... Nf6 and ...Rd8 next, or 16...Nd3 to sacrifice the exchange for an initiative. }
16... exf3 17. Bxf3 Ne7 { This looks good and solid enough. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.e4"]
[Black "6.bxc3 and 7.Ba3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. bxc3
{ This is the main move in the position with an ambition to fight for the center with d3, castle short, and push f4. With the light-squared bishop on g2 and the black king already tucked away in safety, it's the right time to strike at the center. }
6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. Ba3
{ It's very tempting for White to land with the bishop on d6 and secure it with c5. There's one little problem with the plan - it doesn't work. I believe that in these setups the dark-squared bishop on a3 has nothing to do and White should be focusing on other things. }
7... Re8
{ Much more direct than the careful  7...d6  - Black wants to play ...d5 in one go. }
8. Qb3
{ White could try to return to the ideas to stop the d-pawn from advancement but you must already know that Black has other ideas as well. }
8... d6 9. Ne2 a6
{ With this particular order of the moves, with White's dark-squared bishop already on a3,  it makes sense to start with this move, preparing to play ...b5 next. Black could have opted for  9...Na6  ,  which essentially should transpose to one of the lines, covered earlier. }
10. O-O b5
{ Black has an incredibly flexible development at the queenside and a lot of targets to pay attention to. }
11. d4 Be6 12. d5 Bg4 { Provocation! } 13. f3 Bc8
{ Black is ready to take over things at the queenside. White's pieces are far from optimally placed and it doesn't feel that it's Black who's technically behind in development. }
14. Qb4 c5 15. Qb3 Nbd7
{ It looks like a great King's Indian position to me - Black is very active at the queenside. }
