[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.e4"]
[Black "6.bxc3 and 7.Ba3: #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. bxc3
{ This is the main move in the position with an ambition to fight for the center with d3, castle short, and push f4. With the light-squared bishop on g2 and the black king already tucked away in safety, it's the right time to strike at the center. }
6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. Ba3
{ It's very tempting for White to land with the bishop on d6 and secure it with c5. There's one little problem with the plan - it doesn't work. I believe that in these setups the dark-squared bishop on a3 has nothing to do and White should be focusing on other things. }
7... Re8
{ Much more direct than the careful  7...d6  - Black wants to play ...d5 in one go. }
8. Bd6
{ White blocks the d-pawn's advancement. It's a nice strategic idea and otherwise, it would be great but being so much behind in development this is the wrong moment to do it. }
8... Re6 9. c5
{ What else? If the bishop would go back, Black could already play ...d5 next. }
9... b6 10. Ne2
{ An important moment here - if White would play  10.Bh3  to chase away the rook, Black should be quite happy to sacrifice it after  10...Nxe4!  11.Bxe6  dxe6  with a powerful initiative. The 'automatic'  10...Re8  could land Black into some real trouble after  11.d3  and now the white bishop on d6 could stay for a very long time. }
10... bxc5 11. Bxc5
{ The blockade is dismantled and Black is ready to fight for the initiative. }
11... Ba6
{ If you can do it to me, I can do it to you as well! Black wouldn't mind jumping with the bishop on d3. }
12. d3 d5 13. exd5 cxd5 14. O-O Nbd7
{ Black already seems to be better with no visible weaknesses and a strong pawn center. Serafimov,T @@StartBracket@@2405@@EndBracket@@ -Shchekachev,A @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@ Paris championship 2005. }
