{ 11.Bf4  Ne5  ,  intending to play ...c5 next looks great for Black and if White would consider being greedy with  12.c5  then after  12...Bg4  ,  threatening with ...Nf3 White's position collapses very quickly. }
11... Nxf6 12. O-O Be6
{ White has no real compensation for the weaknesses at the queenside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.e4"]
[Black "6.bxc3 and 7.d4: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. bxc3
{ This is the main move in the position with an ambition to fight for the center with d3, castle short, and push f4. With the light-squared bishop on g2 and the black king already tucked away in safety, it's the right time to strike at the center. }
6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. d4
{ White is fighting for a strong pawn center immediately, however, to do this with such an exposed king - that's a risky play. }
7... exd4 { Black should be very happy to open the position. } 8. e5
{ White is charging forward to recapture on d4 with a pawn and stop the ...Nxe4 tactical trick. }
8... Re8 9. cxd4
{ Capturing with the queen makes no sense and Black could continue with the simple  9...d6  . }
9... d6
{ Looking at the position, it's difficult to imagine why White would want to go for this position. He enjoys a center and two potentially powerful bishops, but the existing piece development is close to zero. }
10. f4
{ This is already a known mistake - White can't afford to completely disregard the development. }
10... Be6
{ Black quickly finishes the development and will destroy White's center in a couple of moves. White can't take the knight of f6 because of the ...Bg4+ discovered check. Two games have been played in this line, and in both of them White went down in flames very quickly. }
11. Qe2 Nbd7 12. Nf3 { White just needs a couple more tempos. } 12... Nb6
{ But he's not going to get it! } 13. c5
{ White is out of good alternatives -  13.Nd2  dxe5  14.dxe5  Bf5  and the attack continues, with ...Bd3 incoming. }
13... dxc5 14. dxc5 Bc4
{ The last accurate move - the white king remains in the center. } 15. Qd1
{ Or  15.Qc2  Bd3  ,  followed by ...Nc4. } 15... Qxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Na4
{ Black continues the attack and probably can already snatch a pawn along the way. Kriksciunas,B @@StartBracket@@2324@@EndBracket@@-Christiansen,T @@StartBracket@@2317@@EndBracket@@ Baltic Sea tt8 B07 email 2008. }
