6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. d4
{ White is fighting for a strong pawn center immediately, however, to do this with such an exposed king - that's a risky play. }
7... exd4 { Black should be very happy to open the position. } 8. e5
{ White is charging forward to recapture on d4 with a pawn and stop the ...Nxe4 tactical trick. }
8... Re8 9. cxd4
{ Capturing with the queen makes no sense and Black could continue with the simple  9...d6  . }
9... d6
{ Looking at the position, it's difficult to imagine why White would want to go for this position. He enjoys a center and two potentially powerful bishops, but the existing piece development is close to zero. }
10. Nf3
{ White keeps the balance - White has to castle as quickly as possible, even if it will cost him a pawn. }
10... Nbd7 11. O-O
{ White has no choice - protecting the pawn on e5 with either  11.Bb2   or  11.Bf4  can lead to dire consequences after  11...dxe5  and 12...Qa5+ next. }
11... dxe5 { Start of a forced sequence - Black wins a pawn by force. } 12.
dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Rxe5
{ Now White needs to prove what he has for the pawn. The remaining moves are not forced and merely illustrate where the game might be heading. }
15. Rb1 Bg4
{ It is possible to be a little stubborn and go for the slightly passive  15...Re8  and let White figure out what to do next. However, I've always preferred an active game. }
16. f3 Be6 17. Rxb7 Ra5
{ Black is about to win back the extra pawn but because of the two bishops, White should hold this. }
