{ White protects the bishop on e4 and is targeting the black pawn on h7. }
12... dxc3
{ Another principled move - why not!? The pawn on h7 doesn't seem to be critical for the position and if White wants to capture it, it will cost him some time. A more peaceful alternative here is to play  12...d3!?  with intentions to play  13...g6  next and a solid position. However, White's got those two bishops anyway. }
13. Bxh7+
{ It's not mandatory for White to start with the pawn capture but other moves give Black some flexibility. For example,  13.Rd1!?  Qf6  14.Be3  ,  intending to take on h7 and continuing with Rd4-h4. There Black can respond in multiple ways, starting with the solid  14...h6  , considering a moderate response  14...Nd7  with intentions to jump on  e5  and ending with a more spectacular  14...c5!?  15.Bxc5  Nc6  and a double-edged game. Black's chances are not worse in any of them but objectively the position remains equal. }
13... Kh8 14. Be3 Na6
{ An ice-cold move - Black is threatening with ...Nb4 to disrupt the coordination of the queen+bishop battery. }
15. Rfd1 Qf6 16. Bd4
{ 16.Rd4  can backfire because of  16...Nb4  17.Qb1  c2!  and after getting rid of the White's light-squared bishop the white king's defensive setup has seen better days. }
16... Qh6 17. Bd3 Bg4
{ Black has a lot of interesting dynamic options here and has a good control over the light squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.e4"]
[Black "6.bxc3 and 7.Nf3: #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
{ The most standard move in the position, giving White plenty of ways to continue from here. Usually White is continuing with Nf3 afterward, but let's check first, what happens if White tries something else instead. }
4... O-O 5. e4
{ We're back to the traditional idea of White fighting for the space advantage - this is quite similar to what we already covered in Chapter 11 and essentially one of the Sicilian Rossolimo ideas, with colors reversed. The only difference here is that the white light-squared bishop is already on g2 and that should make Black's life a little easier. White wants to play Nge2 next so to justify the bishop's position on b4, capturing the knight on c3 right now seems to be the most critical continuation. }
5... Bxc3 { Consistent with the approach. } 6. bxc3
{ This is the main move in the position with an ambition to fight for the center with d3, castle short, and push f4. With the light-squared bishop on g2 and the black king already tucked away in safety, it's the right time to strike at the center. }
6... c6
{ Black has clear intentions to open the center and have active play. White here has several options but they fall into two categories - either White tries to stop the d-pawn push at all costs or simply ignores it and continues his development. }
7. Nf3
{ This is the most recently tested attempt to get something out of the position - White suggests to trade the e-pawns and inevitably to open the position to increase the power of his bishops. }
7... Nxe4
{ This is very principled - Black accepts the pawn and invites White to show immediately what he's got. White doesn't have a lot of choices here - either take on e5 immediately or castle first and then take. }
8. O-O
{ White castles first before recapturing the pawn. Since there's nothing that Black can do about it, it's a good idea to give it back under the best possible circumstances. }
8... d6
{ Having a free pawn is nice but Black shouldn't forget about his development as well. Now White can either recapture the pawn immediately with simplifications incoming or play it out a little more aggressive. }
9. d4 Nd7
{ The pawn on c3 is taboo unless Black is looking for trouble - it's high time to finish the development. }
10. Re1
{ 10.Ba3  would meet an intermezzo  10...Nb6  and White can't exploit the pin. For example,  11.Qd3  Nf6 }
10... Nef6 { This starts a forced sequence which simplifies the position. } 11.
Ba3 e4 12. Nd2 Nb6 { Black is just in time to protect everything. } 13. c5 dxc5
14. Bxc5 Re8 15. Nxe4
{ White wins back the pawn but this allows Black to finish the development with a comfortable position. }
15... Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Be6 { Black is doing fine and has no weaknesses. } *

