12... exd4 { Black needs some targets, thus the pawn trade is the best. } 13.
cxd4 Bg4
{ Black wants to play ...Qd7 and trade-off the light-squared bishops. The other rook belongs on d8, and Black should including ...h6 at some point to make sure that White has no access to Bg5. }
14. Qd2
{ The only real attempt for White to get something out of the position is to position the dark-squared bishop on b2 and push d5, threatening to take on f6. This is something that Black shouldn't miss. }
14... Re8 15. Bb2 Re2
{ Black has to be very active otherwise the position could turn nasty very quickly. }
16. Qc3 Qb6
{ Black pushes away the white bishop from the long diagonal and makes sure that White can't play d5 just yet. }
17. Bc1
{ After the stubborn  17.Rab1  Bf5  18.Qf3  Black can at least play  18...Rxb2  with equal position. }
17... Bf5
{ Black is threatening to play ...Rc2 real quick and target the c4 pawn so White has to do something }
18. d5
{ 18.Bg5  Rc2  19.Qf3  Be4  would lead to mass simplifications - it's important to see that Black has ...Qd8 in the end, protecting the king. }
18... Rc2 19. Qb3 cxd5 20. cxd5 h6
{ Black is active enough and White's plans to position the bishop on the long a1-h8 diagonal never materialized. With the queens gone, it's not such a big threat anymore. The position is equal. }
