1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O
{ Before we move on to the main theory of White's setup, in this chapter I propose to have a look at the rare alternatives. I think I managed to cover all of them and without too great depth explain the general ideas so that you should be happy with the outcome after the opening. However, to get the most out of the opening it would be great if you could develop yourself the ability to evaluate, how the arising setup compares with the main lines. Sometimes it will be the same, but White might include a useless move like a3 or Qc2 to steer away from the main lines. You should understand the main lines and ideas quite well and compare, how White's included move helps or doesn't help him for the arising setup.  I'll start with an example - if White would play here  5.a3  ,  how would you react? Obviously, the best approach is to take on c3  5...Bxc3  and now it depends how White will continue. After  6.dxc3  you should already compare the results with what you know in Chapter 12, should White continue with e4 or what will be covered in the next chapter to understand, that with dxc3 setups you should continue with ...d6 and that a3 is a great waste of time for White.   If White would play  6.bxc3  then probably a good idea is to play  6...Re8  and if White would continue with  7.e4  ,  break the center with  ...c6  and ...d5 where White's 5. a3 is still a waste of time.   If White would play  7.Nf3  ,  then it might be a good idea to use the plan of  7...e4  8.Nd4  d5  with the idea after  9.cxd5  Qxd5  reroute the queen to h5, which is explained in detail in the next chapter. }
5. Qb3
{ With the white queen on b3 it's time to revisit some principles. In the mainline of the next chapter which has a similar pawn structure, I normally suggest avoiding ...Nc6 as after Nd5 and a potential trade the knight on c6 is under attack. However, here things are different - the white queen on b3 is a subject to win some tempos. }
5... Nc6
{ A little exception to the traditional rule - now White has a wide range of choices here. }
6. Nd5
{ Of course, since the black knight on c6 allows this knight's jump, it's important to know what to do here under the current circumstances. At the moment White is threatening to win the bishop. }
6... a5
{ The most active continuation which involves a potential pawn sacrifice. Black is threatening to push forward the a-pawn and hide the bishop on a5. }
7. a3
{ If White wants to take on b4, most likely he will have to take on c6 as well.   7.Nxb4  axb4  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.Qxb4  White wins a pawn but Black will have a long-term initiative and a strong center, starting with  9...d5  ,  followed by ...Re8 and e-pawn push. The white knight on g1 will be experiencing problems with development and White's light-squares are very weak. }
7... a4 8. Qd1 Ba5
{ A nice idea - Black keeps the dark-squared bishop and makes it for White quite difficult to continue the development and play d3. I'll illustrate a potential mistake. }
9. Nf3
{ Technically  9.Kf1  would be better but again Black is quite happy to sacrifice a pawn for an attack. This time, the a4 pawn falls, after  9...d6  10.Qxa4  Nxd5  11.cxd5  Ne7  and long-term compensation and an obvious attack at the kingside, which starts with the f-pawn push. }
9... e4 10. Nh4
{ 10.Ng5  fails to  10...Nxd5  and the knight on g5 is hanging. } 10... Nd4
{ Suddenly the threat of ...Nb3 becomes very annoying. } *

