5. e3
{ Everything related to  5.e4  we already discussed in the previous chapter - this is a worse alternative for White who intends to continue with Nge2, get rid of the dark-squared bishop with a3, and in the end fight for the center with d4. Black's response here is pretty standard. }
5... Bxc3
{ The same approach was in chapter 12, the same approach is here - Black doesn't wait for the white knight to get on e2. }
6. bxc3 { The only reasonable trade as the other one looks much worse. } 6...
c6 7. d4 e4
{ Not only White has incredibly weak light squares, but the dark-squared bishop on c1 is truly a terrible piece. }
8. Ne2 d5
{ The most straightforward, claiming control over the c4 square, although a more modest  8...d6  with an idea to target the c4 pawn as a weakness is also great. }
9. cxd5 cxd5 10. O-O Nc6
{ Black is about to take good care of the weakened c4 square. } 11. Qc2 Na5 12.
Bb2 b6 13. Nc1
{ White has literally run out of useful moves after already 13 moves } 13...
Ba6
{ Black is strategically winning and an unofficial king of the light squares. Jovanovic, S-Vujic Katanic,B @@StartBracket@@2005@@EndBracket@@ YUG-chT 33rd 1981. }
