{ I'm not sure what kind of setup White has to try here to get a satisfactory position - his light pieces have terrible prospects. Black can prepare to play ...Re8 and ...e4 next, playing on the light-squares and avoiding the queen trade, if necessary. }
10. Rb1 Re8
{ In the example game White pushed forward the d-pawn and quickly found himself in a strategically difficult position. }
11. d4 e4
{ Since Black is about to collect all of the light squares, White decided to do something about it. }
12. c4 dxc4 13. Qa4
{ Markowski,P  @@StartBracket@@2117@@EndBracket@@ -Dowgird,F @@StartBracket@@2256@@EndBracket@@ POL-ch Academic 2018. }
13... a6 { An improvement over the game. } 14. Qxc4 Be6 15. Qc2 Rc8
{ Black dominates the light-squares. Notice how useless is White's dark-squared bishop. }
