1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O
{ Before we move on to the main theory of White's setup, in this chapter I propose to have a look at the rare alternatives. I think I managed to cover all of them and without too great depth explain the general ideas so that you should be happy with the outcome after the opening. However, to get the most out of the opening it would be great if you could develop yourself the ability to evaluate, how the arising setup compares with the main lines. Sometimes it will be the same, but White might include a useless move like a3 or Qc2 to steer away from the main lines. You should understand the main lines and ideas quite well and compare, how White's included move helps or doesn't help him for the arising setup.  I'll start with an example - if White would play here  5.a3  ,  how would you react? Obviously, the best approach is to take on c3  5...Bxc3  and now it depends how White will continue. After  6.dxc3  you should already compare the results with what you know in Chapter 12, should White continue with e4 or what will be covered in the next chapter to understand, that with dxc3 setups you should continue with ...d6 and that a3 is a great waste of time for White.   If White would play  6.bxc3  then probably a good idea is to play  6...Re8  and if White would continue with  7.e4  ,  break the center with  ...c6  and ...d5 where White's 5. a3 is still a waste of time.   If White would play  7.Nf3  ,  then it might be a good idea to use the plan of  7...e4  8.Nd4  d5  with the idea after  9.cxd5  Qxd5  reroute the queen to h5, which is explained in detail in the next chapter. }
5. d3
{ This line has some modest popularity. Usually White intends to play Bd2 next and be flexible with plans in the center, and the pawn on e4 might allow White also to play Nf3,  without the need to worry about ...e4. Similarly like with  5.Qc2  ,  this approach is a little slow and allows Black to fight for a strong pawn center and get an easy development. }
5... Re8
{ The most flexible move in the position - Black keeps open eyes and normally will continue with ...c6 and ...d5 but there might be other continuations, depending on what White would choose. White has tested here several moves, but the most popular choices are 6.Bd2 and 6.e4. }
6. e4
{ White intends to proceed with Nge2 and castle short. You might see some similarities with Chapter 12, but there's one major difference - White has already included d3, thus capturing the knight on c3 at the moment is not necessary as the bishop on b4 pins the knight. }
6... c6
{ It is possible to take on c3 right away but the text move is stronger - Black for the time being preserves the dark-squared bishop and if necessary, will trade it. Had Black traded on c3 first with  6...Bxc3+  7.bxc3  c6  ,  White would have access to an unusual resource  8.g4!?  with an idea to meet  8...d5  with  9.g5  and the pawn on d5 will have to be sacrificed. With the bishop still on b4, the entire idea doesn't work as after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp1p1ppp/2p2n2/4p3/1bP1P3/2NP2P1/PP3PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.g4  d5  8.g5  d4  the complications are in Black's favor. }
7. Ne2 { 7.Qb3  Na6!  with an idea to play ...Nc5 next looks nasty for White. }
7... d5
{ Black has managed to push the d-pawn without the need to give up the dark-squared bishop. }
8. cxd5 cxd5 9. exd5 { This is an alternative. } 9... Nxd5 10. O-O
{ Kortschnoj,V-Ree,H Hoogovens Wijk aan Zee 1968, the simplest way for Black to get a good game is going for the knight's trade. }
10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Ba5
{ Black plans to continue normal development. In comparison to some of the lines in Chapter 12, here Black has kept the dark-squared bishop instead of the knight on d5. }
12. Rb1
{ After   12.d4  Black has the powerful idea  12...Bg4!  with a threat to take either on e2 or c3 and now after  13.Bxb7  Black can sacrifice more material for a massive initiative with  13...Nd7  14.Bxa8  Qxa8  and White's under some heavy fire here, and the absence of the light-squared bishop is critical. For example,  15.d5  Nb6  with huge threats. }
12... Nc6
{ Pretty much against everything Black continues the same setup - queen on c7, the pawn on b6 @@StartBracket@@if it's under attack@@EndBracket@@ and position the light-squared bishop somewhere on the c8-h3 diagonal for active purposes. }
13. Be3 Qc7 14. Qb3
{ 14.f4  would be an interesting idea to bring pieces into life but it runs into the very unpleasant  14...Bg4  and White has numerous problems to solve at the same time, starting with the pawn on c3. }
14... b6
{ 14...Rb8  would allow a crazy idea  15.Nf4!  and Black can't take the knight. The text move is more secure although it shuts out the dark-squared bishop a little. However, it keeps constant pressure on the c3 pawn, and should White continue with c4 and Nc3, Black will be happy to trade it. }
15. c4 Be6 16. Nc3 Bxc3
{ The dark-squared bishop has outlived its usefulness on the a5-e1 diagonal and finally should be traded off. }
17. Qxc3 Rac8
{ Black is very solid and has no weaknesses which can't be said about White. }
*

