5. d3
{ This line has some modest popularity. Usually White intends to play Bd2 next and be flexible with plans in the center, and the pawn on e4 might allow White also to play Nf3,  without the need to worry about ...e4. Similarly like with  5.Qc2  ,  this approach is a little slow and allows Black to fight for a strong pawn center and get an easy development. }
5... Re8
{ The most flexible move in the position - Black keeps open eyes and normally will continue with ...c6 and ...d5 but there might be other continuations, depending on what White would choose. White has tested here several moves, but the most popular choices are 6.Bd2 and 6.e4. }
6. e4
{ White intends to proceed with Nge2 and castle short. You might see some similarities with Chapter 12, but there's one major difference - White has already included d3, thus capturing the knight on c3 at the moment is not necessary as the bishop on b4 pins the knight. }
6... c6
{ It is possible to take on c3 right away but the text move is stronger - Black for the time being preserves the dark-squared bishop and if necessary, will trade it. Had Black traded on c3 first with  6...Bxc3+  7.bxc3  c6  ,  White would have access to an unusual resource  8.g4!?  with an idea to meet  8...d5  with  9.g5  and the pawn on d5 will have to be sacrificed. With the bishop still on b4, the entire idea doesn't work as after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqr1k1/pp1p1ppp/2p2n2/4p3/1bP1P3/2NP2P1/PP3PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.g4  d5  8.g5  d4  the complications are in Black's favor. }
7. Ne2 { 7.Qb3  Na6!  with an idea to play ...Nc5 next looks nasty for White. }
7... d5
{ Black has managed to push the d-pawn without the need to give up the dark-squared bishop. }
8. exd5 cxd5 9. O-O
{ Taking with the c-pawn would just transpose to the previous line. Here White is aiming for a modern Benoni set up and has a powerful light-squared bishop on g2. However, there's a major flaw with the plan - the knight on e2 doesn't do anything. }
9... d4
{ Black should play for the space advantage and chase away the white knight. }
10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 Nd7
{ For the modern Benoni structures the queenside knight instead of the traditional c6 square is always better positioned either on c5 or f6, either pressuring the d3 pawn or looking forward to pushing the e-pawn. }
12. a3 Bf8 13. b4
{ White is fighting for some traditional counterplay at the queenside, otherwise Black could stop it with ...a5 }
13... a5 14. Rb1 axb4 15. axb4
{ Here Black should have prepared the black knight's jump on f6. Predein,V @@StartBracket@@2360@@EndBracket@@-Rublevsky, S @@StartBracket@@2550@@EndBracket@@ Kurgan 1994. }
15... h6
{ Black should stop the knight from being traded for the dark-squared bishop so that Black can plan to push ...e4 at the necessary moment. }
16. Bg2 Nf6 17. h3
{ Here  17.f4  is not good because of  17...e4!  18.dxe4  d3!  and the white knight can't retreat to c3 due to ...Qd4 check. }
17... Bd7
{ Black threatens to position the light-squared bishop on c6 to trade the strong white bishop. White can't take the pawn on b7 because the pawn h3 is under attack. If White would play  18.b5  ,  this would seriously weaken the c5 square. }
