1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O
{ Before we move on to the main theory of White's setup, in this chapter I propose to have a look at the rare alternatives. I think I managed to cover all of them and without too great depth explain the general ideas so that you should be happy with the outcome after the opening. However, to get the most out of the opening it would be great if you could develop yourself the ability to evaluate, how the arising setup compares with the main lines. Sometimes it will be the same, but White might include a useless move like a3 or Qc2 to steer away from the main lines. You should understand the main lines and ideas quite well and compare, how White's included move helps or doesn't help him for the arising setup.  I'll start with an example - if White would play here  5.a3  ,  how would you react? Obviously, the best approach is to take on c3  5...Bxc3  and now it depends how White will continue. After  6.dxc3  you should already compare the results with what you know in Chapter 12, should White continue with e4 or what will be covered in the next chapter to understand, that with dxc3 setups you should continue with ...d6 and that a3 is a great waste of time for White.   If White would play  6.bxc3  then probably a good idea is to play  6...Re8  and if White would continue with  7.e4  ,  break the center with  ...c6  and ...d5 where White's 5. a3 is still a waste of time.   If White would play  7.Nf3  ,  then it might be a good idea to use the plan of  7...e4  8.Nd4  d5  with the idea after  9.cxd5  Qxd5  reroute the queen to h5, which is explained in detail in the next chapter. }
5. d3
{ This line has some modest popularity. Usually White intends to play Bd2 next and be flexible with plans in the center, and the pawn on e4 might allow White also to play Nf3,  without the need to worry about ...e4. Similarly like with  5.Qc2  ,  this approach is a little slow and allows Black to fight for a strong pawn center and get an easy development. }
5... Re8
{ The most flexible move in the position - Black keeps open eyes and normally will continue with ...c6 and ...d5 but there might be other continuations, depending on what White would choose. White has tested here several moves, but the most popular choices are 6.Bd2 and 6.e4. }
6. Qc2
{ White might get to this position starting with 5.Qc2 as well. It's a rare combination of moves but I imagine that White wants to play either a3 next or Bg5 to pin the black knight and make sure that Black can't do the trade and double the white c-pawns in the process for a questionable compensation. }
6... c6 7. a3
{ Consistent with the plan - White is aiming for a two-bishop advantage and the pawn on d3 limits Black's immediate active chances in the center. }
7... Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 d5
{ Black has given up the dark-squared bishop but at the same time controls the center, and the remaining pieces are easily developed. If White doesn't take the pawn on d5, Black should push it forward for a space advantage. }
9. Nf3 d4
{ Since Black has two knights, keeping the position closed is a very reasonable choice. }
10. Qc2 { Leuschner, K-Meltzer,H DDR-ch H corr 1988. } 10... a5
{ This move comes with intentions to fix a weakness on b3 to exploit later and if White would stop the plan. }
11. b3
{ If White has plans to play b4 at some point later, it's probably best to include this move and stop Black's ...a4. }
11... c5 12. O-O Nc6
{ It's almost safe to say that b4 now will never happen. It is debatable if Black needs to include ...h6 to stop the Bg5 maneuver first with intentions to trade the knight of f6, but I don't see it to be a problem. }
13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Nd2 Qe7
{ Black has a considerable space advantage, and if White wants to be active, it will start with the e-pawn push, which Black can just ignore. }
