5. d3
{ This line has some modest popularity. Usually White intends to play Bd2 next and be flexible with plans in the center, and the pawn on e4 might allow White also to play Nf3,  without the need to worry about ...e4. Similarly like with  5.Qc2  ,  this approach is a little slow and allows Black to fight for a strong pawn center and get an easy development. }
5... Re8
{ The most flexible move in the position - Black keeps open eyes and normally will continue with ...c6 and ...d5 but there might be other continuations, depending on what White would choose. White has tested here several moves, but the most popular choices are 6.Bd2 and 6.e4. }
6. Bd2
{ White defends the knight on c3 and either plans to play Nf3 next without the need to worry about ...e4 and the pinned knight on c3, or continue with a3 and after a possible trade on c3 recapture with the bishop. This also makes no obstacles no Black's plan to grab the center. }
6... c6
{ Black continues with the traditional plan, here White in practice has tested several continuations. }
7. Nf3
{ With the dark-squared bishop on d2 this maneuver now is possible as White doesn't fear the incoming . ..e4 threat anymore. }
7... d5
{ if White had castled short already, this would be a bad move due to Nxd5 intermezzo and Black's center would be very vulnerable. }
8. O-O
{ Probably the best move in the position - White doesn't rush with the c-pawn trade which would give Black access to c6 square for the queenside knight. Besides, now White is threatening with Nxd5 so there's no time for a quiet preparation move ...h6. Now Black is at crossroads. }
8... dxc4
{ The alternative  8...d4  works just fine as well but with the text move Black pretty much renders White's light-squared bishop useless, keeps a good grip of the center, and has an easy development. }
9. dxc4 Bf5
{ The most active move which stops White to play Qc2 and comes with a couple of tricks. If Black will be allowed to add ...h6 the next move, the bishop can hide to h7. Probably there's nothing wrong with what Boris Gelfand played against Vugar Gashimov back in 2010 as the order of the moves shouldn't matter much. Structure wise Black almost always has the same plan - play ...a5 to secure the c5 as an outpost, position on c5 the queenside knight, the queen goes to c7 to protect the e5 pawn and if possible, play ...h6 to stop any Ng5 ideas. }
10. Qb3 { This is something that Black should be always aware of. } 10... Na6
11. a3 Bf8
{ Black is not forced to give up the bishop to save the pawn on b7 because White would lose the queen in the process. }
12. Qxb7 Nc5 13. Qxc6 { Or  13.Qb4  a5  . } 13... Rc8
{ The white queen is inevitably trapped. } *

