11. Re1 { White parries the threats but is not improving his position. } 11...
Nbd7
{ The light-squared bishop can be rerouted to e6 to pressure the c4 pawn and it can be secured with ...h6 against Ng5. The queenside knight goes to c5 and is strengthened with ...a5. }
12. Qc2 Be6 13. Red1 Bf8
{ Very similar like in the game between Gashimov and Gelfand, Black retreats with the bishop to f8 not to miss White's a3-b4 advancement and prepares the knight's jump to c5. }
14. b3 Qc7 15. Nf3
{ Kataev,A @@StartBracket@@2118@@EndBracket@@-Khairullin,R @@StartBracket@@2260@@EndBracket@@ RUS PV12 Cl-A email 2012, and here Black has plenty of easy moves to make. }
15... h6
{ Black will continue with ...a5 and ...Nc5. Don't worry about the dark-squared bishop too much, it will find a way to join the game, and not necessarily via ...g6 and ...Bg7. Black has an excellent position. }
