[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 Sidelines"]
[Black "Chapter 13 Exercise: #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/ppp2ppp/2n5/3np3/8/P5P1/1PQPPPBP/R1B1K1NR w KQ - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10. e3
{ White is severely behind in development - he has the two bishop advantage that White's dreaming to use at some point later. What's the best way to punish White for the chosen strategy? }
10... e4
{ Black should try to open the position as quickly as possible, even if it will require some sacrifices. }
11. Bxe4 { 11.Ne2  Ne5!  12.Bxe4  Nf6  Looks just as bad for White. } 11...
Rxe4
{ This is not even an equal trade - the light-squared bishop here appears to be a much more important piece than the black rook as it controls all of the light squares. Without it, White's position looks like a positional nightmare. }
12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qg2 Ne5
{ Black is about to start a decisive attack, exploiting the light-squares. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 Sidelines"]
[Black "Chapter 13 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/2P5/2b1P1P1/PP1P1PBP/R1BQK1NR w KQ - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

6. dxc3
{ White has just captured on c3 with the d-pawn and intends to play e4 next. Is there something wrong with the plan? }
6... e4
{ Yes, there is! Black can thwart White's plan by playing ...e4 himself, thus fixing a few light-squares under Black's control. }
7. Ne2 Nc6 8. O-O Ne5
{ It makes sense for Black to focus on the light-squares at the kingside. White's dark-squared bishop is a useless piece here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 Sidelines"]
[Black "Chapter 13 Exercise: #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqr1k1/pp3ppp/5n2/3pp3/8/P1QP2P1/1P2PPBP/R1B1K1NR w KQ - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

10. Bg5
{ White is pressuring Black's d5 pawn and intends to take on f6. How will you react? }
10... Nc6
{ The right answer is - focus on your threats! The pawn on d5 can be sacrificed, if necessary. }
11. Bxf6
{ Technically not good but then White has to acknowledge that the entire strategy was a bluff. }
11... Qxf6 12. Bxd5 Nd4
{ Suddenly White is under serious pressure - Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop and play ...Rc8 next. }
13. Rc1
{ 13.Nf3  Bg4!  White can't take on d4 as it would open the e-file, nor he can castle short. }
13... Be6 14. Bxb7 Rab8 15. Qc7
{ All of this actually was already once played at the highest level! Ljubojevic,L @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@-Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2765@@EndBracket@@ Amber-rapid 06th 1997. }
15... Bf5
{ Anand here could had gone for a more direct opening of the center. } 16. Nf3
Nb5 17. Qc6 Nd6 18. Ba6 e4 { Black has a crushing attack. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.Nf3"]
[Black "6.Nd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3
{ This line used to be very popular in the past but with modern theory Black is feeling quite comfortable thus White has started to explore the four knight setups with both g3 and e3, as seen in the later chapters of the course. All of the arising positions will seem quite familiar to someone who has played Sicilian Rossolimo, which it is but with colors reversed and an extra tempo for White. }
5... Re8
{ This is the setup that we've been aiming for since the start, postponing the development of the queenside knight on c6. Let me remind you, the reason was the incoming Nd5 threat and Black would have a hard time trade the knight on d5 without losing a tempo, now that the knight is on c6. With the current setup, Black doesn't have to worry about that. Black is about to push forward the e-pawn, eliminate the knight on c3 and cramp White's position with that pawn on e4. }
6. Nd5
{ Without the black knight on c6, this is just an equal trade that costs White a full tempo. }
6... Nxd5 7. cxd5 c6 8. Qb3
{ White is not interested to trade on  c6  himself as Black would just recapture with the knight and a strong pawn center. Perhaps  8.O-O  is a little trickier here however after  8...cxd5  9.Qb3  Nc6  10.Qxd5  d6  ,  Black is about to play ...Be6. }
8... Bf8 9. O-O
{ White could try  9.d4  e4  10.Nd2  but here Black has  10...Qa5!  and White has nothing better than to go for  11.d6  Bxd6  12.O-O  Bf8  ,  followed by ...d5 next and an excellent Karlsbad structure for Black. }
9... Qb6 10. Qc4
{ Kostic,N @@StartBracket@@2385@@EndBracket@@-Popov, S @@StartBracket@@2340@@EndBracket@@ YUG-ch 1992. }
10... Na6 { Black is fighting for the control of the d5 square. } 11. d3 cxd5
12. Qxd5 Nc7 { Black inevitably gains a strong pawn center. } 13. Qb3 Qxb3 14.
axb3 d5 { In addition, White has some weaknesses as well - Black is better. } *

