1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3
{ This line used to be very popular in the past but with modern theory Black is feeling quite comfortable thus White has started to explore the four knight setups with both g3 and e3, as seen in the later chapters of the course. All of the arising positions will seem quite familiar to someone who has played Sicilian Rossolimo, which it is but with colors reversed and an extra tempo for White. }
5... Re8
{ This is the setup that we've been aiming for since the start, postponing the development of the queenside knight on c6. Let me remind you, the reason was the incoming Nd5 threat and Black would have a hard time trade the knight on d5 without losing a tempo, now that the knight is on c6. With the current setup, Black doesn't have to worry about that. Black is about to push forward the e-pawn, eliminate the knight on c3 and cramp White's position with that pawn on e4. }
6. O-O
{ White has finished the development at the kingside - it's time to clarify what's happening in the center. }
6... e4
{ A thematic idea in the Sicilian Rossolimo which works well also in the English opening. Not only is Black pushing away the white knight to win some valuable time in the process, but also taking away from White the idea to play d3 and e4 at some point himself. White here has four possible knight retreats of which three have been tested in practice. }
7. Ng5
{ White is threatening to win the pawn immediately and forces Black to take the knight on c3 @@StartBracket@@which was Black's plan anyway@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Bxc3
{ Here White has a common choice - take with the b-pawn and fight for a strong pawn center, or go for a more positional approach and try to reroute the knight to d5 and activate the dark-squared bishop. }
8. bxc3
{ This position is probably an exception where after White's bxc3 Black doesn't continue with ...d5 and reroute the queen to h5. The reason is the knight on g5 so after  8...d5  9.cxd5  Qxd5  White could continue with  10.d3  and the knight is perfectly placed on g5 to pressure the center. }
8... h6
{ Black should first push away the white knight from bothering the e4 pawn and make sure that White can't continue with f3 and recapture on f3 with the knight. }
9. Nh3
{ Now that the white knight is on h3, f3 is not a thing to worry about. } 9...
d6
{ 9...d5  is possible, it's just that the text move is simply better - the white knight feels awkward at its position. }
10. f3
{ White has tried also to make a breakthrough in the center with this thematical push. }
10... exf3
{ If White would play  11.Rxf3  ,  Black could respond with the very annoying  11...Be6  12.d3  d5! }
11. exf3
{ Tadic,B  @@StartBracket@@2467@@EndBracket@@-Kosic,D @@StartBracket@@2502@@EndBracket@@ Serbia/Montenegro Team championships 2003. }
11... c5 12. Nf4 Nc6 13. d3 Ne5
{ Black's light-squared bishop will be rerouted to c6 and it's not clear how White is going to activate his bishops without making further commital weaknesses. }
