6. O-O
{ White has finished the development at the kingside - it's time to clarify what's happening in the center. }
6... e4
{ A thematic idea in the Sicilian Rossolimo which works well also in the English opening. Not only is Black pushing away the white knight to win some valuable time in the process, but also taking away from White the idea to play d3 and e4 at some point himself. White here has four possible knight retreats of which three have been tested in practice. }
7. Ne1
{ That's another possible retreat, normally coming with the idea to recapture on c3 with the b-pawn and eliminate the black pawn on e4, having ready the knight to support the cause. }
7... Bxc3 8. dxc3
{ This order of the moves in this particular setup looks like a minor concession for White. Comparing with the mainline, Black would have included ...Nc6 which is a move that Black would correct later by rerouting the knight to d7. Here Black can do it in one go. }
8... d6 { Black embraces already known values. } 9. Nc2 Nbd7
{ The black knight on c5 will almost always feel better than on c6. } 10. Ne3
a5
{ With the white knight on e3 and ideas to push the f-pawn forward Black shouldn't rush to position his bishop on b7 but instead focus on useful moves that restrict the mobility of White's pieces. The bishop might be useful on the h3-c8 diagonal for the time being. }
11. a4
{ Since Black might be thinking about ...a4 next, the inclusion of this move makes a lot of sense. After   11.b3  a4  is an annoying problem because after  12.b4  Nb6  makes the white pawn on c4 feel awkward. }
11... b6
{ Normally including a4 and ...a5 favors Black, as White weakens the b3 square. }
12. b3
{ This is a very common maneuver for White who either wants to reposition the knight on d5 and after a potential trade push c4 and position the bishop on b2, or play f4 and reroute the queenside rook via a2 to e2. }
12... Bb7
{ Now should the position open at the kingside with f4 and capture the pawn en passant, Black has a target at the queenside to press - the b3 pawn. }
13. f4 exf3 14. exf3 Nc5
{ Because White has a weakness on b3, now the ...d5 threat looks rather real. }
15. Ra2
{ Normally White plans to reroute the rook on e2 and focus on something at the kingside with g4 and Nf5 perhaps. There's no reason to sit and wait for something to happen. }
15... d5
{ I can't guarantee that this thrust will always work because there might be little nuances or a slightly different position in other lines. However, if this works, then Black is already taking over the game. White's weak pawn on b3 becomes very vulnerable and Rd2 here is impossible because the knight on e3 remains unprotected. }
16. b4
{ The only way to get rid of the strong knight is by creating more weaknesses. }
16... axb4 17. cxb4 Na6 18. Rb2
{ After  18.b5  Nc5  the black knight gets back to the perfect outpost, pressuring the weakness on a4. }
18... c5 19. b5 Nb4 { More forced moves are incoming. } 20. cxd5 Nfxd5 21. Nxd5
Qxd5 22. Rd2 Qc4
{ Black has nothing to complain about while White has a weak pawn on a4. } *

