[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.Nf3"]
[Black "6.O-O and 7.Ne1: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3
{ This line used to be very popular in the past but with modern theory Black is feeling quite comfortable thus White has started to explore the four knight setups with both g3 and e3, as seen in the later chapters of the course. All of the arising positions will seem quite familiar to someone who has played Sicilian Rossolimo, which it is but with colors reversed and an extra tempo for White. }
5... Re8
{ This is the setup that we've been aiming for since the start, postponing the development of the queenside knight on c6. Let me remind you, the reason was the incoming Nd5 threat and Black would have a hard time trade the knight on d5 without losing a tempo, now that the knight is on c6. With the current setup, Black doesn't have to worry about that. Black is about to push forward the e-pawn, eliminate the knight on c3 and cramp White's position with that pawn on e4. }
6. O-O
{ White has finished the development at the kingside - it's time to clarify what's happening in the center. }
6... e4
{ A thematic idea in the Sicilian Rossolimo which works well also in the English opening. Not only is Black pushing away the white knight to win some valuable time in the process, but also taking away from White the idea to play d3 and e4 at some point himself. White here has four possible knight retreats of which three have been tested in practice. }
7. Ne1
{ That's another possible retreat, normally coming with the idea to recapture on c3 with the b-pawn and eliminate the black pawn on e4, having ready the knight to support the cause. }
7... Bxc3 8. bxc3
{ With the knight on e1 this capture makes the most sense - White would love to get rid of the e4 pawn and build up a strong pawn center himself. }
8... d5 9. cxd5
{ This is almost mandatory as  9.Nc2  dxc4  10.Ne3  would stop the black queen's standard route ...Qd5-h5, however now after  10...Nc6!  White has nothing better than to take the pawn on c4, still allowing ...Qd5-h5. }
9... Qxd5
{ White here has tested several possible continuations, with a couple of new ideas to be played yet. }
10. d4
{ This leaves the black pawn on e4 unchallenged and the light-squared bishop on g2 imprisoned so Black has no reason to pursue the standard idea of ...Qh5 which still looks pretty good. Here is something better - White has carelessly weakened the c4 square. Ibragimov,I @@StartBracket@@2520@@EndBracket@@-Lukacs,P @@StartBracket@@2490@@EndBracket@@ Budapest FS02 GM 1995. }
10... Qc6 { This comes with a clear idea to dominate the light-squares. } 11.
Bg5
{ White could try to get rid of the dark-squared bishop as it's not helping much. }
11... Nbd7 12. Qb3 h6
{ Black forces White to make a decision - either get rid of the bishop or leave the knight on f6 alone and Black can continue with taking over all of the light-squares. }
13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Nc2 Be6
{ The incoming ...Nd5 threat already looks quite real. For example  15.Qb2  Nd5  16.Bxe4  Bh3!  17.Nb4  Qxc3  and the complications are in Black's favor. }
