12. dxe4
{ If White would start with the tricky  12.Rb1  then the waiting move  12....h6  looks very strong with ideas to push ...g5 at some point. }
12... Nxe4 13. Qc2 Bf5
{ I believe the played moves so far make the most sense. Black is aggressively pushing for a strong development while White is trying to establish an open position where his bishops would become stronger. The pawn on c7 still can't be taken because Black is threatening with ...Nxg3. }
14. Qb2
{ Here Black's best bet is to sacrifice something to accelerate the initiative. Anything else is too slow. Koerholz,L @@StartBracket@@2295@@EndBracket@@-Becker, M @@StartBracket@@2420@@EndBracket@@ Trier 1998. }
14... g5 15. Bxc7
{ If the bishop would retreat, then Black's ...Nd6 would protect everything and consolidate the position. }
15... Rac8 16. Qxb7 Qg6
{ Black is down two pawns but the white bishop on c7 seemingly is trapped, plus one pawn on c3 is already under attack. Then there's the not obvious ...Rxc7 and ...Re7 threat, trapping the white queen! }
17. Bxe4
{ This starts a forced sequence where White is barely holding. If  17.f3  then  17...Nxc3  18.e4  Qf6  with an idea to meet  19.exf5  with  19...Nd5  ,  recapture the bishop on c7, and have an excellent compensation for the pawn. }
17... Rxe4 18. Rd1 { Now follow several only moves from both sides. } 18... Re7
19. Rd6 Qxd6 20. Qxc8+ Bxc8 21. Bxd6 Rxe2
{ It should become apparent that Black is about to win back both pawns and by the looks is pressing for more. }
22. Nf3 g4 23. Nd4 Nxd4 24. cxd4 Rxa2
{ The probable outcome of the game is a draw, but White is making it, not Black. }
