[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.Nf3"]
[Black "6.O-O and 7.Nd4: #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3
{ This line used to be very popular in the past but with modern theory Black is feeling quite comfortable thus White has started to explore the four knight setups with both g3 and e3, as seen in the later chapters of the course. All of the arising positions will seem quite familiar to someone who has played Sicilian Rossolimo, which it is but with colors reversed and an extra tempo for White. }
5... Re8
{ This is the setup that we've been aiming for since the start, postponing the development of the queenside knight on c6. Let me remind you, the reason was the incoming Nd5 threat and Black would have a hard time trade the knight on d5 without losing a tempo, now that the knight is on c6. With the current setup, Black doesn't have to worry about that. Black is about to push forward the e-pawn, eliminate the knight on c3 and cramp White's position with that pawn on e4. }
6. O-O
{ White has finished the development at the kingside - it's time to clarify what's happening in the center. }
6... e4
{ A thematic idea in the Sicilian Rossolimo which works well also in the English opening. Not only is Black pushing away the white knight to win some valuable time in the process, but also taking away from White the idea to play d3 and e4 at some point himself. White here has four possible knight retreats of which three have been tested in practice. }
7. Nd4
{ The main and not surprisingly also the most active move in the position. }
7... Nc6 8. Nc2
{ This is a common retreat for the knight - on c2 it's rather flexible and not only is threatening to take the bishop on b4 but also can be rerouted to e3. }
8... Bxc3
{ This is necessary and in the spirit of the entire course and here White has the traditional choice - take with the d-pawn or b-pawn. }
9. dxc3
{ This move is a more played alternative but it's not popular at the highest level anymore. Black has already proven in practice that he keeps the position solid. White normally rearranges the knight on e3 and then either to d5 or plans to do something with the f-pawn push. }
9... h6
{ This is a necessary move - with the black knight already on c6, the Bg5 threat is an annoying problem to be dealt with. Had the knight been on b8 like seen in other sidelines, Black could just continue with ...d6 and save the tempo for h6 and meet Bg5 with ...Nbd7 and ... h6 next. }
10. c5
{ That's the difference from the traditional Sicilian Rossolimo - usually in this position White would have already d3  @@StartBracket@@here d6@@EndBracket@@ played so White could try to exploit the little difference that the black pawn is still on d7 and thus get rid of the doubled pawn. }
10... Qe7 { More precise than the immediate  10...b6  . } 11. Bf4
{ Solovchuk, A @@StartBracket@@2409@@EndBracket@@-Kuzubov, Y @@StartBracket@@2651@@EndBracket@@ Ukrainian championship 2016, instead of the solid  11...Qxc5  12.Bxc7  d5  ,  which happened in the game, Black could have gone for something more entertaining. }
11... Ne5 12. Qd4
{ Or  12.b4  b6  13.cxb6  axb6  14.Ne3  Qe6  with a solid setup for Black. }
12... b6
{ Now probably it's quite principled for White to accept the pawn sacrifice. }
13. Bxe4 Nc6 14. Bxc6 dxc6 15. Rfe1 Bf5
{ Black has a lasting initiative. White is not interested to trade the pawns on b6 as this would allow Black to play ...c5 at some point later and position the light-squared bishop on the long a8-h1 diagonal. }
16. e4 bxc5 17. Qc4 Bh3
{ It is already possible to take the pawn on e4 and after 18.f3 return with the bishop to d5, but the text move is a little more aggressive. }
18. f3 g5 19. Be3 Nd7 { Black has a strong initiative. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.Nf3"]
[Black "6.O-O and 7.Nd4: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3
{ This line used to be very popular in the past but with modern theory Black is feeling quite comfortable thus White has started to explore the four knight setups with both g3 and e3, as seen in the later chapters of the course. All of the arising positions will seem quite familiar to someone who has played Sicilian Rossolimo, which it is but with colors reversed and an extra tempo for White. }
5... Re8
{ This is the setup that we've been aiming for since the start, postponing the development of the queenside knight on c6. Let me remind you, the reason was the incoming Nd5 threat and Black would have a hard time trade the knight on d5 without losing a tempo, now that the knight is on c6. With the current setup, Black doesn't have to worry about that. Black is about to push forward the e-pawn, eliminate the knight on c3 and cramp White's position with that pawn on e4. }
6. O-O
{ White has finished the development at the kingside - it's time to clarify what's happening in the center. }
6... e4
{ A thematic idea in the Sicilian Rossolimo which works well also in the English opening. Not only is Black pushing away the white knight to win some valuable time in the process, but also taking away from White the idea to play d3 and e4 at some point himself. White here has four possible knight retreats of which three have been tested in practice. }
7. Nd4
{ The main and not surprisingly also the most active move in the position. }
7... Nc6 8. Nc2
{ This is a common retreat for the knight - on c2 it's rather flexible and not only is threatening to take the bishop on b4 but also can be rerouted to e3. }
8... Bxc3
{ This is necessary and in the spirit of the entire course and here White has the traditional choice - take with the d-pawn or b-pawn. }
9. dxc3
{ This move is a more played alternative but it's not popular at the highest level anymore. Black has already proven in practice that he keeps the position solid. White normally rearranges the knight on e3 and then either to d5 or plans to do something with the f-pawn push. }
9... h6
{ This is a necessary move - with the black knight already on c6, the Bg5 threat is an annoying problem to be dealt with. Had the knight been on b8 like seen in other sidelines, Black could just continue with ...d6 and save the tempo for h6 and meet Bg5 with ...Nbd7 and ... h6 next. }
10. Ne3
{ 10.b3  d6  would just transpose to lines, covered later as the white knight hardly has a better choice as after Nd4 Black has a nice choice between a simple trade or ignore the knight with ...Ne5. }
10... d6
{ Here White is at crossroads - either rearrange the knight to d5 and hope that Black is going to take it, so that White can activate his dark-squared bishop with cxd5, c4, and a pawn expansion at the queenside, or push f3 or f4 and pursue a game at the kingside. There are no other plans for White. For Black, I propose to keep to the same setup against almost everything - play early ...a5 to fight for some space advantage at the queenside and consider pushing ...a4 for some annoyance to White. If White has played a4, bring out the queen with...Qe7 and then either ...Qe5-h5-c5, or ...Ne5-g4. If White doesn't touch the a-pawn, don't rush with Qe7. In general I advise not to rush taking the white knight on d5 unless forced and look for the best circumstances for the trade. The knight on c6 probably will require to be rerouted to d7 either via e5 or b8 while the bishop almost always remains on the c8-h3 diagonal. Black has a lot of freedom. }
11. b3 a5 12. a4
{ 12.Nd5  already allows Black to place the bishop on f5 and secure the center, then proceed with rerouting the knight from c6 to d7. If White plays like this, probably he's considering pushing the f-pawn and bring into game the queenside rook to e2 @@StartBracket@@or d2@@EndBracket@@ via a2. }
12... Qe7
{ With the white pawn on a4 White can never plan anything serious at the queenside. Now the black queen can be activated while you don't know where to place the light-squared bishop just yet. }
13. f4
{ Like I already explained before, with the knight on e3 this is a traditional idea and again you will find it useful to still have the bishop on the c8-h3 diagonal and having not committed to ...b6 just yet. }
13... exf3 14. exf3 Qe5
{ Black is very flexible and the simplest plan is to go for the d-pawn push. }
15. Qd3 Qc5
{ With the e-pawns traded, here the black queen looks perfectly placed. There's no reason here to rush for the bishop trade with Qh5 via h3 as the bishop on g2 isn't doing much and Black would lose control of the f5 square. }
