{ Moskow,E @@StartBracket@@2240@@EndBracket@@-Gurevich,I @@StartBracket@@2510@@EndBracket@@ New York Reshevsky 1992. }
14... b6
{ This is necessary not to miss any incoming c5 threats - the knight from e5 will be rerouted to d7 and if Black will run out of active ideas, he can finally take the knight on d5. }
15. h3 Ned7
{ This is a good place for the black knight which is heading to c5 and bother the b3 pawn. At the same time, Black always watches for the f4 thrust. }
16. Qd2 Nc5 17. Rab1 Nxd5
{ Again, with the white pawn on a4 this trade is almost always good. } 18. cxd5
Qe7
{ Black has free hands at the kingside while White has nothing to do at the queenside. }
