{ White has finished the development at the kingside - it's time to clarify what's happening in the center. }
6... e4
{ A thematic idea in the Sicilian Rossolimo which works well also in the English opening. Not only is Black pushing away the white knight to win some valuable time in the process, but also taking away from White the idea to play d3 and e4 at some point himself. White here has four possible knight retreats of which three have been tested in practice. }
7. Nd4
{ The main and not surprisingly also the most active move in the position. }
7... Nc6 8. Nc2
{ This is a common retreat for the knight - on c2 it's rather flexible and not only is threatening to take the bishop on b4 but also can be rerouted to e3. }
8... Bxc3
{ This is necessary and in the spirit of the entire course and here White has the traditional choice - take with the d-pawn or b-pawn. }
9. dxc3
{ This move is a more played alternative but it's not popular at the highest level anymore. Black has already proven in practice that he keeps the position solid. White normally rearranges the knight on e3 and then either to d5 or plans to do something with the f-pawn push. }
9... h6
{ This is a necessary move - with the black knight already on c6, the Bg5 threat is an annoying problem to be dealt with. Had the knight been on b8 like seen in other sidelines, Black could just continue with ...d6 and save the tempo for h6 and meet Bg5 with ...Nbd7 and ... h6 next. }
10. Ne3
{ 10.b3  d6  would just transpose to lines, covered later as the white knight hardly has a better choice as after Nd4 Black has a nice choice between a simple trade or ignore the knight with ...Ne5. }
10... d6
{ Here White is at crossroads - either rearrange the knight to d5 and hope that Black is going to take it, so that White can activate his dark-squared bishop with cxd5, c4, and a pawn expansion at the queenside, or push f3 or f4 and pursue a game at the kingside. There are no other plans for White. For Black, I propose to keep to the same setup against almost everything - play early ...a5 to fight for some space advantage at the queenside and consider pushing ...a4 for some annoyance to White. If White has played a4, bring out the queen with...Qe7 and then either ...Qe5-h5-c5, or ...Ne5-g4. If White doesn't touch the a-pawn, don't rush with Qe7. In general I advise not to rush taking the white knight on d5 unless forced and look for the best circumstances for the trade. The knight on c6 probably will require to be rerouted to d7 either via e5 or b8 while the bishop almost always remains on the c8-h3 diagonal. Black has a lot of freedom. }
11. Qc2
{ Probably this is the trickiest order of the moves for White is to increase the pressure against the e4 pawn first, then position the rook on d1 and try to make Nd5 work. }
11... a5
{ This is a very standard maneuver - Black is threatening with some space advantage of ... a4 and if White will include a4 to stop it, this will pretty much nullify White's chances for something at the queenside. }
12. Rd1
{ White is threatening with c5 so Black has to choose between ...b6, ...Bd7 or ...Qe7. With the white rook on d1 now any f4 plans look a little strange, but it doesn't mean that they are not possible. }
12... b6
{ Black could go for ...Qe7 but then White has some ambitions with Nd5, forcing Black to trade, recapture with the c-pawn and with the bishop on e3 advance at the queenside with c4, a3, b4, and eventually c5. I'm not saying that it's even worse for Black, but I see no reason to allow this. }
13. b3
{ Kortschnoj, V-Mecking,H Candidates qf 1974, and in this almost 50-year-old game between two chess legends Black could have played a little more tricky. }
13... Nb8
{ Black is waiting for White to play Nd5 so that the bishop can be positioned on f5 and the knight from c6 rerouted to d7. }
14. f4
{ If White wants to switch back to the f-pawn push, probably there's no better moment. }
14... exf3 15. exf3 Bb7
{ The position is open but the white bishops aren't working. Black has an easy game. }
*

