{ Here White is at crossroads - either rearrange the knight to d5 and hope that Black is going to take it, so that White can activate his dark-squared bishop with cxd5, c4, and a pawn expansion at the queenside, or push f3 or f4 and pursue a game at the kingside. There are no other plans for White. For Black, I propose to keep to the same setup against almost everything - play early ...a5 to fight for some space advantage at the queenside and consider pushing ...a4 for some annoyance to White. If White has played a4, bring out the queen with...Qe7 and then either ...Qe5-h5-c5, or ...Ne5-g4. If White doesn't touch the a-pawn, don't rush with Qe7. In general I advise not to rush taking the white knight on d5 unless forced and look for the best circumstances for the trade. The knight on c6 probably will require to be rerouted to d7 either via e5 or b8 while the bishop almost always remains on the c8-h3 diagonal. Black has a lot of freedom. }
11. Qc2
{ Probably this is the trickiest order of the moves for White is to increase the pressure against the e4 pawn first, then position the rook on d1 and try to make Nd5 work. }
11... a5
{ This is a very standard maneuver - Black is threatening with some space advantage of ... a4 and if White will include a4 to stop it, this will pretty much nullify White's chances for something at the queenside. }
12. Rd1
{ White is threatening with c5 so Black has to choose between ...b6, ...Bd7 or ...Qe7. With the white rook on d1 now any f4 plans look a little strange, but it doesn't mean that they are not possible. }
12... b6
{ Black could go for ...Qe7 but then White has some ambitions with Nd5, forcing Black to trade, recapture with the c-pawn and with the bishop on e3 advance at the queenside with c4, a3, b4, and eventually c5. I'm not saying that it's even worse for Black, but I see no reason to allow this. }
13. b3
{ Kortschnoj, V-Mecking,H Candidates qf 1974, and in this almost 50-year-old game between two chess legends Black could have played a little more tricky. }
13... Nb8
{ Black is waiting for White to play Nd5 so that the bishop can be positioned on f5 and the knight from c6 rerouted to d7. }
14. Rb1 Nbd7 15. Nd5 Nxd5
{ At some point Black shouldn't object to the trade, as long as there's a clear plan at the kingside. }
16. cxd5 Nf6
{ Here the knight feels closer to the kingside than on c5 and can participate in an attack. }
17. c4 Bf5 { Black can start to organize something real at the kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.Nf3"]
[Black "6.O-O and 7.Nd4: #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3
{ This line used to be very popular in the past but with modern theory Black is feeling quite comfortable thus White has started to explore the four knight setups with both g3 and e3, as seen in the later chapters of the course. All of the arising positions will seem quite familiar to someone who has played Sicilian Rossolimo, which it is but with colors reversed and an extra tempo for White. }
5... Re8
{ This is the setup that we've been aiming for since the start, postponing the development of the queenside knight on c6. Let me remind you, the reason was the incoming Nd5 threat and Black would have a hard time trade the knight on d5 without losing a tempo, now that the knight is on c6. With the current setup, Black doesn't have to worry about that. Black is about to push forward the e-pawn, eliminate the knight on c3 and cramp White's position with that pawn on e4. }
6. O-O
{ White has finished the development at the kingside - it's time to clarify what's happening in the center. }
6... e4
{ A thematic idea in the Sicilian Rossolimo which works well also in the English opening. Not only is Black pushing away the white knight to win some valuable time in the process, but also taking away from White the idea to play d3 and e4 at some point himself. White here has four possible knight retreats of which three have been tested in practice. }
7. Nd4
{ The main and not surprisingly also the most active move in the position. }
7... Nc6 8. Nc2
{ This is a common retreat for the knight - on c2 it's rather flexible and not only is threatening to take the bishop on b4 but also can be rerouted to e3. }
8... Bxc3
{ This is necessary and in the spirit of the entire course and here White has the traditional choice - take with the d-pawn or b-pawn. }
9. bxc3
{ Currently the most popular move - White is ambitiously fighting for the center. }
9... d5
{ This thrust in the center is a traditional response in almost every setup to the bxc3 pawn structure, except the sideline where the white knight is on g5. }
10. cxd5 Qxd5
{ Black has a simple goal - play ...Qh5, trade the light-squared bishops, and play actively in the center. I was unable to find an advantage for White in a single line. This was featured in: Lambiarro, A. vs. Radwan, I. Afro-Asian Correspondence Championship, 2018 }
11. d3
{ With the white knight on c2 this pin doesn't look dangerous and the entire setup doesn't add up for White. }
11... Qh5 12. Ne3
{ If White here would include the trade  12.dxe4  then after the simple  12...Nxe4  it's not clear what to do with the c3 pawn. }
12... Bh3 { Black simply looks better. } 13. d4
{ White stops Black's queenside knight's journey to g4 but in general this is just a waste of tempo and White could have gone for it two moves ago. Schupp,U @@StartBracket@@2133@@EndBracket@@ -Bindrich,F @@StartBracket@@2507@@EndBracket@@ Nuremberg LGA Cup 7th 2010. }
13... Ne7
{ Here Black could have gone for the same maneuver immediately that he played a move later, with an idea to trade off the knight on e3 so that ...Ng4 becomes a real threat. Black doesn't need to rush with the ...Bxg2 as this would hand away control of the h3 square. }
14. Rb1 b6 15. c4 c6
{ Black is controlling the events both at the center and the kingside. } 16.
Rb2 Rad8 { There's no need to rush with the plan. } 17. Qa4 Rd7 18. Rd2 Red8
{ With a follow-up of either ...c5 to close the center or ...b5 to fight for the d5 square, both look great. }
