11. f3
{ This is just not good, and similarly like with the dubious   11.d3  alternative, with the white knight on c2 this continuation lands White into a worse position. People mix up the setups all the time. }
11... Qc5+
{ Before taking on f3, this is a nice intermezzo check as White can't respond with d4 or place the knight on e3. }
12. Kh1
{ 12.Ne3  Nd5!  and the upcoming triple e-pawns look terrible for White } 12...
exf3 13. Rxf3 Bg4
{ White is already busted so to change the character of the game here White decided to sacrifice an exchange. }
14. Rxf6 gxf6 15. Ne3 Rxe3
{ Black takes an exchange only to get it back a couple of moves later! } 16.
dxe3
{ White's pawn structure is completely shattered and the useless dark-squared bishop is dooming the game. }
16... Rd8 17. Qe1 Qh5 { Black wrapped up the game pretty quick. } 18. c4 Bxe2
19. Bb2 Ne5
{ White's weak light squares will decide the game in favor of Black. Ubilava,E @@StartBracket@@2515@@EndBracket@@-Rashkovsky,N @@StartBracket@@2445@@EndBracket@@ URS-ch FL54 1986. }
