[Black "13.fxe4 Neg4: (What NOT to do)"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3
{ This line used to be very popular in the past but with modern theory Black is feeling quite comfortable thus White has started to explore the four knight setups with both g3 and e3, as seen in the later chapters of the course. All of the arising positions will seem quite familiar to someone who has played Sicilian Rossolimo, which it is but with colors reversed and an extra tempo for White. }
5... Re8
{ This is the setup that we've been aiming for since the start, postponing the development of the queenside knight on c6. Let me remind you, the reason was the incoming Nd5 threat and Black would have a hard time trade the knight on d5 without losing a tempo, now that the knight is on c6. With the current setup, Black doesn't have to worry about that. Black is about to push forward the e-pawn, eliminate the knight on c3 and cramp White's position with that pawn on e4. }
6. O-O
{ White has finished the development at the kingside - it's time to clarify what's happening in the center. }
6... e4
{ A thematic idea in the Sicilian Rossolimo which works well also in the English opening. Not only is Black pushing away the white knight to win some valuable time in the process, but also taking away from White the idea to play d3 and e4 at some point himself. White here has four possible knight retreats of which three have been tested in practice. }
7. Nd4
{ The main and not surprisingly also the most active move in the position. }
7... Nc6 8. Nc2
{ This is a common retreat for the knight - on c2 it's rather flexible and not only is threatening to take the bishop on b4 but also can be rerouted to e3. }
8... Bxc3
{ This is necessary and in the spirit of the entire course and here White has the traditional choice - take with the d-pawn or b-pawn. }
9. bxc3
{ Currently the most popular move - White is ambitiously fighting for the center. }
9... d5
{ This thrust in the center is a traditional response in almost every setup to the bxc3 pawn structure, except the sideline where the white knight is on g5. }
10. cxd5 Qxd5
{ Black has a simple goal - play ...Qh5, trade the light-squared bishops, and play actively in the center. I was unable to find an advantage for White in a single line. This was featured in: Lambiarro, A. vs. Radwan, I. Afro-Asian Correspondence Championship, 2018 }
11. Ne3
{ This is the main move in the position but other continuations have been heavily tested as well. }
11... Qh5
{ Since Black is threatening to play ...Bh3 and proceed with normal developing moves like ...Rad8, White has to do something about it. }
12. f3
{ This maneuver either with or without including Rb1 is White's best hope to get something out of the position. }
12... Ne5
{ This is a very interesting idea, introduced by GM Alexander Grischuk back in 2019 - perhaps somebody will find it to be simpler. White probably has to accept the sacrifice. }
13. fxe4 Neg4
{ In the game Grischuk either forgot his preparation or simply mixed up the moves and moved the wrong knight. }
14. Nxg4 Bxg4 15. Qc2 Bxe2 16. Rf5
{ The major difference is that the knight on f6 stands worse than on e5 and White gets a powerful center, supported by two bishops. }
16... Bd1 17. Qb1 Qe2 18. Rf2
{ Now after repeating the position a couple of times Duda found the correct continuation. }
18... Qh5 19. Rf5 Qe2 20. Rf2 Qh5
{ Now after White's  21.h3  and the following d4 push Black is in a lot of trouble. Duda,J @@StartBracket@@2748@@EndBracket@@ -Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ Hamburg FIDE GP 2019. }
