7. Nd4
{ The main and not surprisingly also the most active move in the position. }
7... Nc6 8. Nc2
{ This is a common retreat for the knight - on c2 it's rather flexible and not only is threatening to take the bishop on b4 but also can be rerouted to e3. }
8... Bxc3
{ This is necessary and in the spirit of the entire course and here White has the traditional choice - take with the d-pawn or b-pawn. }
9. bxc3
{ Currently the most popular move - White is ambitiously fighting for the center. }
9... d5
{ This thrust in the center is a traditional response in almost every setup to the bxc3 pawn structure, except the sideline where the white knight is on g5. }
10. cxd5 Qxd5
{ Black has a simple goal - play ...Qh5, trade the light-squared bishops, and play actively in the center. I was unable to find an advantage for White in a single line. This was featured in: Lambiarro, A. vs. Radwan, I. Afro-Asian Correspondence Championship, 2018 }
11. Ne3
{ This is the main move in the position but other continuations have been heavily tested as well. }
11... Qh5
{ Since Black is threatening to play ...Bh3 and proceed with normal developing moves like ...Rad8, White has to do something about it. }
12. f3
{ This maneuver either with or without including Rb1 is White's best hope to get something out of the position. }
12... Ne5
{ This is a very interesting idea, introduced by GM Alexander Grischuk back in 2019 - perhaps somebody will find it to be simpler. White probably has to accept the sacrifice. }
13. fxe4 Nfg4 { The right knight! } 14. Nxg4
{ This trade is mandatory, unless White wants to play with a completely shattered pawn structure. }
14... Bxg4 15. Qb3
{ 15.Rf2  meets a lovely  15...Nd3!  while   15.Qc2  Bxe2  16.Rf5  Black can play  16...Bd3! }
15... Bxe2 16. Rf5 Qg4
{ Move by move and Black keeps his position together. Now White has a little choice - either push the d-pawn or try to snatch the pawn on b7. }
17. d4 Bc4 { An important intermezzo to protect the f7 pawn. } 18. Qc2
{ There's nothing better -  18.Qa4  meets  ...b5  intermezzo   while  18.Qb4  c5!  and Black can start to take over the game, but 18...a5 works just fine as well. }
18... Nd3 { Black has enough dynamic resources to get a good game. } 19. Rg5
{ 19.Bf4  Nxf4  20.Rxf4  Qd7  looks just completely equal. } 19... Ne1
{ Quite an amazing shot! } 20. Rxg4
{ 20.Qf2  is a nice attempt but after  20...Qd1  21.Rxg7!  Kh8!  22.Rxh7+!  Kxh7  23.Qf5+  White forces a perpetual check. }
20... Nxc2 21. Rb1 f5 22. Rf4
{ White can't take the pawn on f5 due to ... Re1+ } 22... Bd3 23. Rxb7 fxe4
{ The position is dynamic equality. } 24. Rxc7 Rab8 25. Bf1 Rb1
{ To avoid trouble, White has to force a perpetual check } 26. Rff7 Rxc1 27.
Rxg7+ Kh8 28. Rxh7+ { Draw by a perpetual check. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Two Knights: 4.Bg2 and 5.Nf3"]
[Black "Chapter 14 Exercise: #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqr1k1/pp3ppp/2p2n2/3pp3/1bP5/2NP1NP1/PP1BPPBP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

8. O-O { White here has a hidden threat that Black should know. } 8... dxc4
{ It is necessary to clarify things at the center -   8...d4  also is a fine alternative.   8...h6?  No, it's not Bg5! How can White punish Black for the last mistake?  9.Nxd5!  This trick Black shouldn't miss - with the white king still in the center it was impossible due to the intermezzo trade on d2.  9...Nxd5   9...Bxd2  10.Nxf6+  This is too obvious.  10.cxd5  Bxd2  11.Nxd2  cxd5  12.Qb3  Despite the fact that Black has a strong pawn center, it's about to fall.  12...Nc6  The safest move for White here is just  13.Qxd5  - Black has no compensation for the lost pawn. Watch out for your opponent's ideas! }
