[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Four Knights: Reversed Sicilian "]
[Black "4.a3: #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3
{ With the inclusion of 2.Nc3 Nf6 now Black can't continue with the traditional  3...e4  to bother the knight on f3 because now White has access to the g5 square. After  4.Ng5  White wins the pawn on e4 and Black will have to give it up or play a very improvised gambit. }
3... Nc6
{ Finally we've come to the four knights variation, as I call it. As explained already in the previous chapters, practice at the highest level has proven that for White it's important to include Nf3, so that after Black's ...Nc6 the typical ...Bb4 idea now meets Nd5 and the knight on c6 may experience some discomfort. We'll start with the off-beat lines which are quite popular in accelerated time controls among the best players in the World. White doesn't fight for an advantage and essentially plays Sicilian as Black, but up a tempo.   Since the positions will be somewhat similar to what you've already seen in Chapter 2 - Reversed Sicilian, I titled this chapter Part 2 of the Reversed Sicilian, but would like to keep it as an intro for the four knights chapters. Positions often will be quite similar to what you already learned in Chapter 2 but the major difference here is that White has already played Nc3 and not included a3. Sometimes the position will transpose to the previously covered lines, or at least will be very similar. If you have existing knowledge in Sicilian Scheveningen, it could be a little easier for you to play it out and improvise on your own. }
4. a3
{ This move probably will transpose to what you already learned in Chapter 1, but I'll just keep one line here for some variety. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Qc2
{ This is some sort of Sicilian Taimanov with colors reversed. Now both  6.e4  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3np3/8/P1N2N2/1P1PPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.e3  transpose to Chapter 1 as Black takes the knight on c3 and plays ...Bd6. White has wasted a tempo on a3. }
6... Nxc3
{ With the philosophy that White's a3 is a waste of time, this trade is characteristic of Black's general approach. }
7. bxc3
{ A little more aggressive than taking with the d-pawn as White is fighting for a strong pawn center.  7.Qxc3  is not a good idea as Black can continue aggressively with  7...Qd5  and perhaps ...Bg4 to follow. }
7... Bd6
{ Black is back to positioning the dark-squared bishop on d6 and has an easy game at the kingside. Instead of transposing to some of the previously covered lines with  8.e4  or e3, White could try to fianchetto the bishop. }
8. g3 Qe7 9. d3 b6
{ Black has enough time to position the light-squared bishop on b7 to counter White's light-squared bishop on g2. There's a lot of room for improvisation. }
10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O O-O
{ Probably around here it already would be a good idea to stop and mention that Black has excellent development and most certainly is not worse, but I will show you two games, how they developed from here. }
12. Nd2
{ White might be thinking about starting an offensive at the queenside so it's a good moment to trade the light-squared bishops. }
12... Na5 13. Ne4
{ This is a little risky as Black now will have a free initiative at the kingside. }
13... f5 14. Nxd6 cxd6 15. Bxb7 Qxb7
{ As long as Black keeps queens on the board, the white king is feeling a little vulnerable. Behling,R @@StartBracket@@2030@@EndBracket@@-Wacker,P @@StartBracket@@2318@@EndBracket@@ Bodensee open 2019. }
