[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Four Knights: Reversed Sicilian "]
[Black "4.d3 and 6.e4: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3
{ With the inclusion of 2.Nc3 Nf6 now Black can't continue with the traditional  3...e4  to bother the knight on f3 because now White has access to the g5 square. After  4.Ng5  White wins the pawn on e4 and Black will have to give it up or play a very improvised gambit. }
3... Nc6
{ Finally we've come to the four knights variation, as I call it. As explained already in the previous chapters, practice at the highest level has proven that for White it's important to include Nf3, so that after Black's ...Nc6 the typical ...Bb4 idea now meets Nd5 and the knight on c6 may experience some discomfort. We'll start with the off-beat lines which are quite popular in accelerated time controls among the best players in the World. White doesn't fight for an advantage and essentially plays Sicilian as Black, but up a tempo.   Since the positions will be somewhat similar to what you've already seen in Chapter 2 - Reversed Sicilian, I titled this chapter Part 2 of the Reversed Sicilian, but would like to keep it as an intro for the four knights chapters. Positions often will be quite similar to what you already learned in Chapter 2 but the major difference here is that White has already played Nc3 and not included a3. Sometimes the position will transpose to the previously covered lines, or at least will be very similar. If you have existing knowledge in Sicilian Scheveningen, it could be a little easier for you to play it out and improvise on your own. }
4. d3
{ With this order of the moves there's a fair chance that your opponent is hinting for one of the off-beat lines as after  4.g3  White not always rushes with d3. }
4... d5
{ I was considering  4...Bb4  as a potential move as well but then at least after  5.e4  the arising positions feel like a concession to what you've already learned in other chapters. And the text move is the most active. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Now White has a choice - either push the e-pawn to e4, e3, or fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2. Everything else should inevitably transpose to what you already know, or at least allow you to execute one of the studied plans. }
6. e4
{ I'm not sure how to name this setup - it's some sort of a Sveshnikov / Najdorf hybrid with colors reversed. Comparing with the Sicilian Sveshnikov, White here has already d3 included so ...Ndb4 won't work. For Sicilian Najdorf colors reversed White would need the pawn to be on a3 while the queenside knight on b1. Here Black has some interesting choices but I would like to immediately discard  6...Nb6  as it's a concession to what you learned in Chapter 2. White might start with Be3 and a4, not wasting a tempo on a3.  I was considering suggesting  6...Nf6  but some of Vladimir Kramnik's games gave me an impression that Black needs to be accurate as White normally plays h3, Be3, and Black's dark-squared bishop on c5-b6 is challenged with an early Na4. While the setup is completely fine, I decided to drop it and offer something even simpler. }
6... Nxc3
{ I think this is the simplest with an easy plan to execute. Since White has already played e4, it will be difficult for it to fight for a strong pawn center. }
7. bxc3 Bc5
{ Black stops White's immediate d4 and tries to block the pawn movement as long as it can. Even if White will somehow manage to push forward the pawn without consequences, Black can just retreat with the bishop on d6 and it's difficult for White to progress. }
8. Nxe5 { This thematic idea doesn't work here. } 8... Nxe5 9. d4 Bb6
{ The simplest of the great choices. } 10. dxe5 Bxf2+
{ This forces a little sequence of trades. } 11. Kxf2 Qxd1 12. Bb5+
{ White wins back the queen but with a destroyed pawn structure. } 12... Qd7
13. Bxd7+ Bxd7
{ As long as Black keeps at least one rook on the board, he has excellent winning chances in the endgame. }
