4. d3
{ With this order of the moves there's a fair chance that your opponent is hinting for one of the off-beat lines as after  4.g3  White not always rushes with d3. }
4... d5
{ I was considering  4...Bb4  as a potential move as well but then at least after  5.e4  the arising positions feel like a concession to what you've already learned in other chapters. And the text move is the most active. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Now White has a choice - either push the e-pawn to e4, e3, or fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2. Everything else should inevitably transpose to what you already know, or at least allow you to execute one of the studied plans. }
6. e4
{ I'm not sure how to name this setup - it's some sort of a Sveshnikov / Najdorf hybrid with colors reversed. Comparing with the Sicilian Sveshnikov, White here has already d3 included so ...Ndb4 won't work. For Sicilian Najdorf colors reversed White would need the pawn to be on a3 while the queenside knight on b1. Here Black has some interesting choices but I would like to immediately discard  6...Nb6  as it's a concession to what you learned in Chapter 2. White might start with Be3 and a4, not wasting a tempo on a3.  I was considering suggesting  6...Nf6  but some of Vladimir Kramnik's games gave me an impression that Black needs to be accurate as White normally plays h3, Be3, and Black's dark-squared bishop on c5-b6 is challenged with an early Na4. While the setup is completely fine, I decided to drop it and offer something even simpler. }
6... Nxc3
{ I think this is the simplest with an easy plan to execute. Since White has already played e4, it will be difficult for it to fight for a strong pawn center. }
