{ Black stops White's immediate d4 and tries to block the pawn movement as long as it can. Even if White will somehow manage to push forward the pawn without consequences, Black can just retreat with the bishop on d6 and it's difficult for White to progress. }
8. h3
{ It's not clear if White should be afraid of ...Bg4 as that's not something that I'm going to suggest to execute at all costs. The idea is interesting though - if Black could manage to play ...Bg4 and trade-off the knight, it could secure the situation in the center and with the following ...b5-b4 completely take over the d4 square. Things are a little more complicated than that and after ...Bg4. White most likely will retreat with the knight on d2, or sometimes Nxe5 will work. I suggest keeping this idea in your mind, should a good opportunity arise. The fact that White is spending a whole tempo to stop it means you are a little more flexible with your development but keeping to the same plan is a good choice. }
8... O-O 9. Be2 Qe7 10. O-O Be6
{ Black goes for the same setup - position pieces actively in the center and be ready for d4. Under the right circumstances, Black might be ready for a kingside offensive with ...h6, ...Kh8, and ...f5 }
11. a4
{ White can't play  11.d4  due to  11...exd4  12.cxd4  Nxd4  and ...Rd8 to follow, a bishop trade and ... c5. I can imagine that 11. a4 is the trickiest option, available for White. The idea is to provoke Black for the 'automatic' ...a5, so that after Rb1-b5 Black starts to experience some real problems. The a-pawn is not going too far. }
11... Rad8 12. a5 b6 13. axb6 axb6
{ I can't imagine Black experiencing any problems here. } *

