10. Bb2 Rd8
{ With White immediately threatening to play d4, Black needs to position the rook on d8. }
11. h3
{ For already known reasons White's d4 doesn't work - Black takes on d4, sacrifices a piece, and captures the pawn on e4, due to the pinned white queen winning back the piece with some interest. }
11... Be6 12. Qc2
{ If White plays  12.Qa4  to prepare d4, Black can get rid of it with  12...a6  and ...b5 to follow. }
12... Rd7 13. Rad1 Rad8
{ Now a long maneuvering game begins, which is not forced. A sample line could look like this -  14.Qa4  Qf6  ,  taking additional care of the d4 square  15.Bc1  h6  ,  followed by repositioning the dark-squared bishop on b6 and the queen on g6. With the black queen on g6 White's d4 looks like an unreal dream as the pawn on e4 will be under attack. And please remember - even if White manages to play d4, it doesn't guarantee White a success. The position remains equal with chances for both players. }
