{ Black slows down White's d4 as the pawn on e4 will be under attack. } 13.
Rfe1 Kh8
{ A useful move so that ...f6 can be played without a worry about Qb3+. } 14.
Nd2
{ White prepares to play d4. The immediate  14.d4  leads to a strange gambit after  14...exd4  @@StartBracket@@which is not forced@@EndBracket@@  15.cxd4  Qxe4  and the queen trade White is seeking compensation with Rac1 and d5. Black has nothing to worry about there and the best White can achieve there is equality. }
14... b6
{ Black could continue with the aggressive  14...f5  ,  but it would open White's light-squared bishop via the f3 square. }
15. d4 f6
{ Black is about to reroute the knight to d6 and pressure the e4 pawn. } 16. a4
Na5 17. Bd3 Nb7 18. c4
{ If not this, then I don't know what's going to be White's plan. } 18... c5
19. d5 Rb8
{ We've reached some kind of a Nimzo Indian position where Black will get a perfect blockade on d6. The actions at the queenside can be blocked with ...a5. For example,   20.Nb3  a5  21.Reb1  Nd6  and the pawn on b6 is protected in advance. Black should be looking for play on the kingside but don't rush with ...f5. }
