4. d3
{ With this order of the moves there's a fair chance that your opponent is hinting for one of the off-beat lines as after  4.g3  White not always rushes with d3. }
4... d5
{ I was considering  4...Bb4  as a potential move as well but then at least after  5.e4  the arising positions feel like a concession to what you've already learned in other chapters. And the text move is the most active. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Now White has a choice - either push the e-pawn to e4, e3, or fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2. Everything else should inevitably transpose to what you already know, or at least allow you to execute one of the studied plans. }
6. e3
{ This is probably the trickiest approach that White can ever choose in this setup - eventually we'll reach the Sicilian Scheveningen with colors reversed where Black is unable to immediately play the desired ...Bd6 as the knight on d5 hangs. I'm not ready to advocate Black play ...Nxc3 and ...Bd6, because this would be a concession to similar lines, with White having avoided the loss of tempo for playing a3. }
6... Be7
{ Black's setup is to position both bishops on e7 and e6, castle short and be ready to meet White's a3 with ...a5 }
7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Be6 { So far, so good - now White has some choices. } 9. a3
{ White is threatening with the typical b4 but here it has a little disadvantage - the knight already stands on c3 so the pawn push will be less effective as White will have to trade knights first. }
9... a5
{ This is not mandatory - Black can start with  9...f5  first, which is more popular at correspondence chess. White's  10.Nxd5  can be met with  10...Qxd5  and now after  11.b4  there's  11...a5  However, I'd like to keep things simple and stick to the rule - if White wants to fight for a space advantage at the queenside with b4, stop it. This rule you already should remember from Chapter 2 }
10. Bd2
{ Here White is postponing the decision to develop the queen as it might not always go to c2. }
10... f5 11. Rc1
{ If White plays  11.Qb3  ,  pinning Black’s light-squared bishop, it’s interesting to play  11...Nf4  12.Qxb7  Qd7  which effectively wins the white queen, but the position is rather unclear. Instead, it’s best to continue with  11...a4!  Now White can’t play  12.Nxa4  due to  12...Nf4  and the light-squared bishop on e2 is no longer protected.   But after  12.Qxb7  there’s still the same  12...Qd7  ,  trapping the white queen. After the best  12.Qc2  Nb6  Black fixes control over the b3 square. }
11... Kh8 12. Na4
{ Retreating with the knight from the center allows Black to start immediate actions in the center. }
12... e4 13. Ne1
{ Trading the pawns would just favor Black as the position opens and Black's pieces are more active. Utegaliev,A @@StartBracket@@2496@@EndBracket@@ -Ibrayev,N @@StartBracket@@2395@@EndBracket@@ Kazakhstan championship 2020. }
13... Nf6
{ This would have been more pragmatic, keeping things under the control in the center. }
14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Qd6 { Black has good control over the light squares. } *

