6... Be7
{ Black's setup is to position both bishops on e7 and e6, castle short and be ready to meet White's a3 with ...a5 }
7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Be6 { So far, so good - now White has some choices. } 9. a3
{ White is threatening with the typical b4 but here it has a little disadvantage - the knight already stands on c3 so the pawn push will be less effective as White will have to trade knights first. }
9... a5
{ This is not mandatory - Black can start with  9...f5  first, which is more popular at correspondence chess. White's  10.Nxd5  can be met with  10...Qxd5  and now after  11.b4  there's  11...a5  However, I'd like to keep things simple and stick to the rule - if White wants to fight for a space advantage at the queenside with b4, stop it. This rule you already should remember from Chapter 2 }
10. Qc2 f5
{ Black's setup always remains the same - play ...Kh8, reroute the dark-squared bishop to d6, and consider starting an attack at the kingside. I suggest keeping the knight on d5 for as long as possible, even if it allows White to go for the traditional Nxd5 and e4 idea. It's very tempting to reroute the black knight to b6 so that Black would be threatening with ...a4 and fix the weakness on b3, but in reality in only allows White to play b3 and the very typical Na4, allowing Black to double White's a-pawns but suddenly White has an easy game at the queenside, most notably pressuring the b7 pawn. }
11. Rd1
{ With the white rook on d1 White is hoping to apply some pressure against the center. }
11... Kh8 12. Rb1
{ A multi-purpose move, usually preparing to play b4 but one of White's ideas might be to play Nb5 so that after Black's ...a4 there's b3 and recapture with the rook and some counterplay at the queenside. Still, all of this seems a little slow - Black is enjoying some space advantage. }
12... Bd6 13. Nd2 Qg5
{ Black's attack looks more real than whatever White's cooking at the queenside. }
14. Re1
{ Mareco,S @@StartBracket@@2589@@EndBracket@@-Macieja,B @@StartBracket@@2594@@EndBracket@@ World Chess olympiad 2012. }
14... e4 15. dxe4
{ If White is more careful with  15.Nf1  ,  then Black could continue with  15...Nf6  ,  bringing more pieces to the kingside. }
15... Nxe3 16. fxe3 Bxh2+
{ White has no choice but to accept the sacrifices and pray that the storm will end soon. }
17. Kxh2 Qh4+ 18. Kg1 Qxe1+
{ Black will continue with ... fxe4 and a winning attack. White's pieces are completely disconnected at the queenside. }
