{ Black's setup always remains the same - play ...Kh8, reroute the dark-squared bishop to d6, and consider starting an attack at the kingside. I suggest keeping the knight on d5 for as long as possible, even if it allows White to go for the traditional Nxd5 and e4 idea. It's very tempting to reroute the black knight to b6 so that Black would be threatening with ...a4 and fix the weakness on b3, but in reality in only allows White to play b3 and the very typical Na4, allowing Black to double White's a-pawns but suddenly White has an easy game at the queenside, most notably pressuring the b7 pawn. }
