[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "5.Nd5: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nd5
{ This can't be a serious move and only has a certain shock value. } 5... Nb4
{ Black is about to keep the extra pawn. } 6. Nxf6+
{ 6.Nxb4  looks quite bad -  6...Bxb4+  7.Bd2  ,  trade the bishops and play ...c5. }
6... Qxf6 7. a3 Nc6 8. b3
{ This is slightly more careful than playing b4 but it leads to the same thing. }
8... a5 9. Bb2 Bc5 10. e3 Qe7
{ Now White has no choice but to twice take on d4. } 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4
Bxa3
{ Black keeps the pawn! Now after  13.Bd3  Bb4+  14.Kf1  f6  I don't think White has full compensation for the pawn. }
