[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "5.Nxd4 and 6.g3: #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. g3
{ An interesting sideline - White is fianchettoing the light-squared bishop and thus slowing down Black's intention to develop the queenside. There is one major flaw with the plan - Black ruins White's pawn structure and quickly pressures the c4 pawn. }
6... O-O
{ There's no need to rush with the trade on c3 as it's not going anywhere. } 7.
Bg2 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Ne5
{ Suddenly White has got a problem - it needs to do something with the c4 pawn. }
9. c5 { The best move as the alternative is considerably worse. } 9... Qe7
{ Black is directly targeting the pawn - White needs to either protect it or play a gambit.   10.Ba3  here immediately gives Black an excellent game thanks to  10...Nc4  11.Qb3  Nxa3  12.Qxa3  Ne4! }
10. Rb1 { Or  10.Nb5  first and then  11.Rb1  ,  it doesn't matter. } 10...
Qxc5 11. Nb5
{ This looks rather interesting - White is threatening with the direct Ba3, and then there's the Qd4 threat to trade off the queens and win the c7 pawn. }
11... Nc4
{ This move deals with the most dangerous threat Ba3. Now White has to trade queens as everything else is considerably worse. }
12. Bf4
{ White's last move does not impress as it allows Black to consolidate the position. Heberla,B @@StartBracket@@2539@@EndBracket@@-Ram,S @@StartBracket@@2338@@EndBracket@@ Mumbai Mayors Cup 4th 2011. }
12... d6 13. Qd4 Bf5
{ Now Black sells back the extra pawn for great activity. } 14. Rb3
{ White doesn't have a lot of choice as  14.Rb4  meets  14...Be6  and White is not even threatening to take on c5.   Trading the queens on c5 first would lead White by force into a considerably worse endgame -  14.Qxc5  dxc5  15.Rc1  c6  16.Nd6  and after the trade continue with ...Rfe8 with an idea to meet Bxc5 with ...Re5-a5. }
14... a6 { Black forces matters and sets some traps. } 15. Qxc5 dxc5 16. Nxc7
Ra7
{ White has won back the pawn and seemingly the second is under attack on b7 but it can't be taken. After  17.Bxb7  there's the  17...Na5  fork  but if White would trade rooks:   @@StartFEN@@5rk1/rpN2ppp/p4n2/2p2b2/2n2B2/1RP3P1/P3PPBP/4K2R w K - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Rxb7  Rxb7  18.Bxb7  Rb8  ,  there are back rank issues. }
17. Nd5 b5
{ Black is threatening with the direct ...Bc2 to win the exchange so after  18.Ne3  Black can just trade with  18...Nxe3  19.Bxe3  ,  protect the c5 pawn with  19...Rc8  and reroute the other knight to b6 to pressure White's weak queenside pawns. A potential follow-up could be  18.Nxf6+  gxf6  19.Bd5  which parries the ...Bc2 threat. Now after  19...Nb6  20.Bf3  Rd8  21.O-O  Nc4  Black resumes the ...Bc2 threat and looks incredibly active, pretty much controlling all of the events at the center and the queenside. The doubled f-pawns play no role here. }
