1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. g3
{ An interesting sideline - White is fianchettoing the light-squared bishop and thus slowing down Black's intention to develop the queenside. There is one major flaw with the plan - Black ruins White's pawn structure and quickly pressures the c4 pawn. }
6... O-O
{ There's no need to rush with the trade on c3 as it's not going anywhere. } 7.
Bg2 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Ne5
{ Suddenly White has got a problem - it needs to do something with the c4 pawn. }
9. c5 { The best move as the alternative is considerably worse. } 9... Qe7
