1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. Nxc6
{ Either trading the knights now or a move later shouldn't pose Black any problems as White essentially gives up the fight for the center }
6... bxc6 7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2
{ This allows Black to create some real targets to pressure. } 8... Bxc3+ 9.
bxc3 Re8 10. O-O Ne4
{ Black ideally wants to play ...Qe7, ...c5, ...d6 and position the light-squared bishop on the h1-a8 diagonal. White can't easily get rid of the knight as f3 would close his light-squared bishop for good. }
11. Be3
{ Eliseev,A @@StartBracket@@2260@@EndBracket@@-Kholmov,R @@StartBracket@@2435@@EndBracket@@ Chigorin memorial 1996. }
11... Qe7 12. Qc2 { Or  12.Qd3  ,  which would lead to the same position. }
12... c5
{ This is quite a precise order of the moves because after  12...d6  White might consider including  13.c5  himself.  Now after multiple trades on e4 White is simply worse but the tactical trick with   @@StartFEN@@r1b1r1k1/p1ppqppp/8/2p5/2P1n3/2P1B1P1/P1Q1PPBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Bxc5  doesn't work. Black plays  13...Nxc5  14.Bxa8  c6!  and the white bishop is imprisoned and quickly captured after ...Ba6. }
