[Round "?"]
[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "5.Nxd4 and 6.Nxc6: #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. Nxc6
{ Either trading the knights now or a move later shouldn't pose Black any problems as White essentially gives up the fight for the center }
6... bxc6 7. Bd2
{ The idea, which comes together with the knight trade on c6 - this maneuver originally wasn't possible as the knight on d4 was hanging. White is looking towards a positional game and hoping that Black might overpush with an active play in the center, so that after an eventual ...d5 and the c-pawn trade White can block the central pawns and organize counterplay. This is a very slow approach. }
7... O-O
{ The position again bears some resemblance with the Scotch opening - White is behind in development and needs to decide, which direction to take. Normally it's either e3 or g3. From Black's perspective it's important to understand that you don't always have to go for an aggressive pawn push in the center, on this occasion ...d5. }
8. g3
{ Since White is about to fianchetto the bishop on g2, for a moment the white pawn on c4 is feeling vulnerable. }
8... a5
{ A great shot - now the question is, how should White meet the incoming threat? }
9. Bg2
{ After  9.a3  Black can switch to a covered idea - trade the bishop on c3 and play ...Ne4 and trade it off for the bishop and continue with ...c5-d6 next. }
9... Ba6 10. b3
{ The engines insist that  10.a3  also might be playable but the excitement should fizzle out quickly with  10...Bxc3  11.Bxc3  Bxc4  12.O-O  and here among all choices Black can just play  12...Re8  ,  followed by ...a4 and I don't see White aiming for more than equality as a very aggressive play in the center can backfire. }
10... d5 11. cxd5
{ That's a mistake. White had to be careful and continue with  11.O-O  Now after  11...dxc4  12.Bxc6  Rb8  Black seems to be a little more active but overall it's an equal position. Azaladze,S @@StartBracket@@2466@@EndBracket@@ -Magalashvili,D @@StartBracket@@2482@@EndBracket@@ Istanbul open 2012. }
11... Re8
{ Black is threatening to take the knight on c3, and something big is about to explode on e2, so White's got no choice. }
12. Bf3 cxd5
{ Black has won an important tempo and the white bishop on f3 feels awkward. }
13. O-O d4
{ An energetic follow-up, securing Black an advantage. Now the game could continue with  14.Na4  Ne4  15.Bxb4  axb4  16.Re1  Bb5  and Black is ahead. }
