[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "5.Nxd4 and 6.Nxc6: #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. Nxc6
{ Either trading the knights now or a move later shouldn't pose Black any problems as White essentially gives up the fight for the center }
6... bxc6 7. Bd2
{ The idea, which comes together with the knight trade on c6 - this maneuver originally wasn't possible as the knight on d4 was hanging. White is looking towards a positional game and hoping that Black might overpush with an active play in the center, so that after an eventual ...d5 and the c-pawn trade White can block the central pawns and organize counterplay. This is a very slow approach. }
7... O-O
{ The position again bears some resemblance with the Scotch opening - White is behind in development and needs to decide, which direction to take. Normally it's either e3 or g3. From Black's perspective it's important to understand that you don't always have to go for an aggressive pawn push in the center, on this occasion ...d5. }
8. e3
{ This modest move is the most played continuation in the position. Now that White is not directly pressuring the center, it's a good moment to fight for privileges. I'll just add that with the white pawn on e3 here the  8...Bxc3  9.Bxc3  Ne4  idea, unfortunately, doesn't work as White plays  10.Bxg7  and Qg4+ next. This maneuver was not possible with the white pawn standing on e2. }
8... d5
{ Black's ideal setup is to reroute the dark-squared bishop to d6 and start a kingside attack since this is where the white king will be going. }
9. Be2 Rb8 10. O-O Bd6
{ Black has excellent chances for an attack and for an inspired kingside storm. White's plan to block the 'hanging pawns' on d4 and c5 is miles away. }
11. cxd5
{ A difficult choice for White - if the trade is not included, White has to watch out for ...dxc4 idea, followed by either ...Ng4, or even ...Bxh2+ first, followed by ...Ng4 and either ...Qh4 or ...Qd6. It won't necessarily work immediately, but this should keep White's mind busy and it's just easier to take on d5. I suggest not to rush with ...dxc4 ideas but keep it in mind. }
11... cxd5 12. Nb5
{ Probably this is the best choice for White, which was played between Farago,S  (2390)  - Lengyel,B  (2345)  Budapest FS04 GM 1994. Black should preserve the dark-squared bishop which currently is one of the most active pieces on the board. }
12... Be5
{ Black looks just fine. He has healthy development, the potential to organize a strong pawn center with ...c5 and a semi-open b-file for the rook. The pawn on a7 can be sacrificed, if necessary, as long as Black doesn’t blunder a fork on c6. }
