[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "5.Nxd4 and 6.Bg5: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. Bg5
{ Historically this is the main move in the line - White pins the knight which could become an annoyance in the long-term because Black is not interested to retreat the dark-squared bishop to e7. }
6... h6
{ It's best to start with this move - White is not going to take on f6 anyway as the dark-squared bishop is an important piece. }
7. Nxc6
{ Including the knight trade for White is considered to be a small concession. }
7... bxc6 8. Bh4 Bxc3+
{ I like this move the most - Black creates some weaknesses in White's camp and then fixes the position. }
9. bxc3 c5
{ If White would now consider playing e3 and Qf3 with a double attack, the light-squared bishop looks great on b7 and can be moved to c6. If White will fight for a center with f3-e4, then the bishop has nothing to do on b7. }
10. Rb1
{ This stops ...Bb7 for the time being but also might be just a waste of time. }
10... d6 11. e3 g5
{ A great positional move - White's bishops are not exactly the best pieces on the board. }
12. Bg3 { Goldstein,M-Purdy,C Sydney 1944. } 12... Qe7 13. Bd3 O-O
{ White's h4 is not a threat as White is not capable of using the h-file, and the white king is still in the middle of the board. Black could react in several ways, starting with the calm ...Kg7 or the more aggressive ...Bg4. }
14. O-O Ne4
{ It's best for Black to keep the light-squared bishop and reroute it to c6 so that it both controls the center and the b7 square. Black is better. }
