[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "5.Nxd4 and 6.Bg5: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. Bg5
{ Historically this is the main move in the line - White pins the knight which could become an annoyance in the long-term because Black is not interested to retreat the dark-squared bishop to e7. }
6... h6
{ It's best to start with this move - White is not going to take on f6 anyway as the dark-squared bishop is an important piece. }
7. Bh4 Bxc3+
{ It's time to create weaknesses, otherwise White will play Rc1 and will be ready to recapture with the rook. }
8. bxc3 Ne5
{ This maneuver also arises from another sideline! Not only Black is attacking the pawn on c4, but most importantly the knight is rerouted to g6 to avoid playing ...g5, get rid of the pin and trade White's dark-squared bishop. Here White has tried everything. }
9. e3
{ One of the most played moves in the position but in reality, White will be balancing between an equal and a slightly worse position. Here White continues a normal development and also protects the pawn on c4. }
9... O-O
{ Again, castle first and then see what happens. White has tested several moves here. }
10. Nb5
{ White is back with the tricks to take on f6 and then capture the pawn on c7. Here the circumstances are slightly different - Black has already castled and ...gxf6 would be highly undesirable. }
10... d6 { It's that time again for a gambit! } 11. Bxf6
{ If White doesn't do it, Black is ready to play next ...g5, followed by ...a6 and trade-off the dark-squared bishop with ...Ne4. The knight on e5 will be protected just in time not to miss any c5 tactical tricks from White. }
11... Qxf6 12. Nxc7
{ White has won a pawn but is seriously behind in development. Now comes a nice tactical shot. }
12... Nf3+
{ White can't take the knight as after ...Qxc3+ White will either lose the rook on a1 or with ...Qxc4+ the knight on c7. }
13. Ke2 { The Bongcloud! } 13... Bg4
{ Black is threatening with a discovered check to win the white queen. } 14.
Nd5 { It's time to go back for White. } 14... Nxh2+ 15. Ke1
{ White doesn't have a great choice as after  15.f3  Black just plays  15...Bxf3+  and at least collects the rook on h1. }
15... Qg5
{ The only move which is important to know - Black must now save the stranded knight on h2. White can't play Be2 as after the bishop trade the pawn on g2 hangs. Too bad that after the Bongcloud White can't castle long! }
16. Qd4 Nxf1 17. Kxf1 Be6
{ There's material equality on the board but Black's chances are slightly better. }
18. Rd1
{ Filippov,V @@StartBracket@@2632@@EndBracket@@-Svidler,P @@StartBracket@@2695@@EndBracket@@ Russian Team championships 2001. }
18... Rfc8 19. Qh4 Qxh4 20. Rxh4 Rc5
{ The white doubled c-pawns make an easy target. } *

