{ Again, castle first and then see what happens. White has tested several moves here. }
10. f3
{ White can keep the dark-squared bishop for unclear long-term plans. However, White's bishop pair makes a strange impression as they are not doing much, but the weak c-pawns are obvious targets. }
10... Ng6 11. Bf2 d6
{ Black's first idea is to quickly rearrange the knight from f6 to c5 for a great outpost career. }
12. Be2 Nd7 13. O-O Nc5
{ White is still struggling to understand, how to activate those bishops. } 14.
Qc2 Bd7 15. Rae1 f5
{ Black is just better. Any White's Nb3 Black is ready to meet with ...b6 and recapture with the b-pawn, positioning the bishop on c6. I want to mention that during the creation of the course I noticed many games by the Russian GM Yuri Yakovich who showed a great understanding of the arising positions. Jolles,H @@StartBracket@@2280@@EndBracket@@ -Yakovich,Y @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ Leeuwarden open 1993. }
