{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. Bg5
{ Historically this is the main move in the line - White pins the knight which could become an annoyance in the long-term because Black is not interested to retreat the dark-squared bishop to e7. }
6... h6
{ It's best to start with this move - White is not going to take on f6 anyway as the dark-squared bishop is an important piece. }
7. Bh4 Bxc3+
{ It's time to create weaknesses, otherwise White will play Rc1 and will be ready to recapture with the rook. }
8. bxc3 Ne5
{ This maneuver also arises from another sideline! Not only Black is attacking the pawn on c4, but most importantly the knight is rerouted to g6 to avoid playing ...g5, get rid of the pin and trade White's dark-squared bishop. Here White has tried everything. }
