[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "5.Nxd4 and 6.Bg5: #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. Bg5
{ Historically this is the main move in the line - White pins the knight which could become an annoyance in the long-term because Black is not interested to retreat the dark-squared bishop to e7. }
6... h6
{ It's best to start with this move - White is not going to take on f6 anyway as the dark-squared bishop is an important piece. }
7. Bh4 Bxc3+
{ It's time to create weaknesses, otherwise White will play Rc1 and will be ready to recapture with the rook. }
8. bxc3 Ne5
{ This maneuver also arises from another sideline! Not only Black is attacking the pawn on c4, but most importantly the knight is rerouted to g6 to avoid playing ...g5, get rid of the pin and trade White's dark-squared bishop. Here White has tried everything. }
9. e4
{ This move, just like 9. e3, protects the c4 pawn with the bishop but makes the e4 pawn a target. }
9... Ng6 { Black forces White to trade off the dark-squared bishop. } 10. Bxf6
Qxf6 11. g3
{ It makes sense for White to counter Black's knight on g6 by fianchettoing the light-squared bishop on g2. Now there's a very nice trick that you should be aware of. }
11... O-O 12. Bg2 c5
{ Black fixes the weak pawn on c4 and prepares a spectacular idea. A more positional alternative is to play the simple  12...d6  and proceed with normal development, starting by rerouting the knight to d7-c5. }
13. Nb5
{ Retreating with the knight on e2 is not so good -  13.Ne2  Uddin,S @@StartBracket@@2102@@EndBracket@@-Mohammed Abdul,M @@StartBracket@@2179@@EndBracket@@ Bangladesh championship 2016, as here Black could have continued with  13...Qa6  ,  targeting the pawn on c4, followed by ...d6 and both ...Be6 and ...Ne5. White loses a pawn for no compensation. }
13... d5
{ A wonderful idea! Black wants to play ...a6 to win the pawn on c3 but this would allow the white knight to jump on d6 for a huge compensation. With the text move this option now is not possible. }
14. O-O dxe4
{ White’s ruined pawn structure at the queenside promises Black slightly better chances, although objectively the position remains equal. A sample line could be  15.Bxe4  Rd8  ,  where Black is planning to play ...Qe7 and ...a6 to push away the white knight to the awkward a3 square. Thus after the logical  16.Qf3  Qxf3  17.Bxf3  Black has some edge after  17...Ne5  18.Bd5  Bg4!  This comes with an idea to sacrifice the b7 pawn for some activity. Now after  19.Bxb7  Rab8  20.Bg2  Rd7  Black protects the a7 pawn and is about to recapture the white pawn on c4 or become very active with rooks if White will try to keep it with Na3. Note that White’s  21.Bd5  is impossible due to  21...Rxb5    If at any moment Black is worried about his development, just sacrifice the pawn on b7 to accelerate your own. Don’t try to keep the pawn on b7 at the cost of the piece activity. }
