1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4
{ This move used to popular in the past but nowadays it's considered to be relatively harmless, at least at the GM level. White's idea, similarly to the Scotch opening, is to fight for the center but just like in the Scotch, one of White's pieces moves already for the second time. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ Our concept doesn't change - the dark-squared bishop still goes to b4 to attack the knight and if allowed - double the c-pawns. Now White has a little choice. }
6. Bg5
{ Historically this is the main move in the line - White pins the knight which could become an annoyance in the long-term because Black is not interested to retreat the dark-squared bishop to e7. }
6... h6
{ It's best to start with this move - White is not going to take on f6 anyway as the dark-squared bishop is an important piece. }
7. Bh4 Bxc3+
{ It's time to create weaknesses, otherwise White will play Rc1 and will be ready to recapture with the rook. }
8. bxc3 Ne5
{ This maneuver also arises from another sideline! Not only Black is attacking the pawn on c4, but most importantly the knight is rerouted to g6 to avoid playing ...g5, get rid of the pin and trade White's dark-squared bishop. Here White has tried everything. }
9. f4
{ The main move in the position - White is ready to give away the dark-squared bishop but by doing so limit Black's piece activity. }
9... Ng6
{ Just don't accept the free pawn with  9...Nxc4  .  White is quickly crushing with  10.e4  Ne3  11.Qd3  Nxf1  and here the very strong  12.e5  will turn into a nightmare for Black. }
10. Bxf6
{ White's got no choice, otherwise, the weakness of the e4 square already should decide the fate of the game. }
10... Qxf6 11. g3
{ That's White's idea which already has been thoroughly tested - the light-squared bishop goes to g2 and White builds a strong pawn center. However, the weak c-pawns remain where they are and Black's got no weaknesses. Now comes a very important maneuver. }
11... Nf8
{ Black uses the circumstances that the king hasn't castled yet and rearranges the knight to a more active square, preferably on c5. }
12. Bg2
{ White can't stop it - after  12.e4  Black plays  12...d6  first to stop e5 from happening,   12.f5  is just a terrible move and the black knight gets to c5 anyway, but via the d7 square, starting with  12...d6 }
12... Ne6 13. f5
{ Positionally this move makes no sense as it creates another weakness on e5, but sometimes there are exceptions. }
13... Nc5 14. Nb5
{ Here lies White's idea - Black can't defend the c7 pawn with the queen from  d8  because of Qd4.  14...Qb6  looks very risky due to  15.f6!?  and a4-a5 idea right after it. }
14... Kd8 { The black king feels pretty safe there. } 15. Qd4 d6 16. Qxf6+ gxf6
{ For the remainder of the game White has to fight for a draw as Black dominates the dark-squares and has a better pawn structure. Because of the closed character of the position, a draw is the likely outcome Laine,J @@StartBracket@@2166@@EndBracket@@ -Avotins,M @@StartBracket@@2414@@EndBracket@@ Champion's League 2017/C6 email 2017. }
