{ Practice proves that White has nothing here and the little space advantage is well compensated by the doubled c-pawns. }
15. Qd2
{ The standard continuation, allowing White to connect both rooks and try to do something active in the center. }
15... Nc5 { 15...Bd7  is still fine but the black knight belongs on c5. } 16.
Rae1 Rb8
{ This is just fine as well, as shown by the former world champion Anatoly Karpov. }
17. Re3 Bd7 18. Nb3 Nxb3
{ Normally this would be a concession for Black but specifically here with the white pawns on e4 and f4 it doesn't play a big role - the position is about to simplify. }
19. axb3 Bc6
{ White can't progress - if he will include b4, Black will respond with ...a6. }
20. Qd4 a6 { Black is not taking the queen on d4. } 21. Qxf6
{ Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2765@@EndBracket@@-Karpov, A @@StartBracket@@2775@@EndBracket@@ Las Palmas 1996, both players agreed to a draw here. }
21... gxf6
{ Indeed, it should be clear that none of the sides can progress. Black's doubled pawns play no role. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "Chapter 16 Exercise: #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pppp1pp1/5qnp/8/2PNP3/2P3P1/P4P1P/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

12. Bg2 { What important motif should you know in this pawn structure? } 12...
c5 { First, fix the weakness on c4. } 13. Nb5
{ 13.Ne2  This protects the pawn on c3 but leaves the c4 pawn vulnerable.  13...Qa6!  14.Qb3  d6  White is about to lose something and perhaps a pawn is the least of his worries. }
13... d5
{ A fantastic resource - before playing ...a6 to win the pawn on c3, Black can include this move to take away the d6 outpost for the white knight.   13...a6?!  This very tempting move is a risky strategic choice - it wins a pawn by force but allows White to position his knight on a very powerful outpost.  14.Nd6  Qxc3+  White can just play  15.Ke2  next, followed by a queen trade, enjoying an excellent compensation for the pawn. It's not clear how exactly Black should get rid of the knight from the d6 square. }
14. O-O { Probably White should escape the center as quickly as possible. }
14... dxe4
{ Most certainly not   14...a6  as after  15.Nc7  Black loses something. Now Black simply has a better pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "Chapter 16 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp1p1pp1/5qnp/2p5/2PN1P2/2PBP3/P5PP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. Ne2
{ Quite similar to the previous test, here the white knight retreated to e2, but the c4 pawn is protected. How can Black fight for an initiative?   13.Nb5  d5!  This motif you should already recognize. }
13... b5
{ Very often it's all about the speed of the attack - Black is willing to give up a pawn just to win an important tempo. }
14. cxb5 Bb7 15. O-O
{ White doesn't have a choice - a short castle is the only option where to hide the white king. }
15... Rfe8 16. Qd2
{ 16.e4  Probably this is a more peaceful alternative but from White's perspective, it might not be an obvious choice at all.  16...Bxe4  17.Bxe4  Rxe4  The position is equal. }
16... Nh4 17. e4
{ White is trying to sell back the pawn. How will you develop the initiative?   17.Rf2  Around here White should already notice the following tactical motif.  17...Bxg2!  The knight can't be taken because of the fork. }
17... Rxe4
{ This works because White is powerless against the incoming ...Bxg2 threat. }
18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Rf2 Bxg2
{ The same motif as in the previous sideline - the knight can't be taken, or White loses the queen. Black wants to retreat with the bishop and go after the white king. Black is not interested to trade queens. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Four Knights: with 4.d4"]
[Black "Chapter 16 Exercise: #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1rb2rk1/p1ppqppp/1pn2n2/2P5/5P2/1NP3P1/P3P1BP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. e4
{ White just played e4 and has two pawns under attack. Which one will you take? }
13... Nxe4
{ White can't be allowed to play e5.   13...bxc5  Wrong pawn! By taking it Black loses the battle for the center.  14.e5  Ne8  15.Ba3  15...Rb5  Black should lose material very quickly but even without it - the position is quite ugly. }
14. Re1 f5 15. Ba3
{ Here lies White's idea - White is threatening with Nd2 and also the cxb6 threat might appear very quickly. At the moment the bishop on a3 is undefended. }
15... Bb7 { First, continue the development and protect the knight on e4. } 16.
Nd2 Na5 17. Bb4 Qe6
{ The only move - now White's cxb6 is no longer a threat as Black can recapture the pawn with a check. Black is just in time to defend everything. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Four Knights: with 4.e4"]
[Black "5.Be2: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e4
{ This move has become quite fashionable lately - White is fighting for space advantage and intends to play d4 next. Black's reply here is very principled. }
4... Bc5
{ The critical move of the position which leads to some theoretical debate. The alternative is  4...Bb4  but if Black is considering to play ...d6 next and then reroute the bishop to c5 for some control of the d4 square, this essentially is a loss of time. }
5. Be2
{ This modest move allows Black to immediately protect the pawn on e5 and control the central squares. In this scenario, it's not clear why White has weakened the d4 square. It doesn't mean that this setup is unplayable for White, it's just that Black is doing more than fine and on occasions can immediately fight for better perspectives. }
5... d6
{ There are a couple of things I want to mention about this position - normally Black wants to play ...Bg4 to trade off the bishop for the knight and completely control the d4 square, and play against the 'bad' White's light-squared bishop. If White wants to stop it with h3,  then consider quickly rerouting your f6 knight via d7 and f8 to e6 for even greater control of the center. White could be tricky and play  6.O-O  ,  with intentions to meet  6...Bg4  with  7.Nxe5!  On this occasion, it's best to include  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/2b1p3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1PBPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...O-O  ,  and if necessary, execute an alternate idea, starting with ...h6, ... Nh7, and ...f5. Any White's a3 Black is always ready to meet with ...a5 and should White threaten to trade off the bishop for the knight, take complete control of the d4 square and play against White's 'bad' light-squared bishop. }
6. h3
{ This gives Black enough time to reroute the knight from f6 and the inclusion of h3 actually will feel like a waste of time. }
6... Nd7
{ This is a very traditional maneuver to reroute the knight to e6 but it's important to meet d3 and Be3 with the knight already on e6, otherwise White will be just in time to push d4. }
7. a3 a5 8. d3 Nf8 9. Rb1 Ne6
{ After the opening Black is simply better as it controls both d4 and f4 squares while the d5 square doesn't play a significant role and Black can always push any intruders away with a later ...c6. }
10. Be3 O-O 11. O-O Bd7 12. Qd2 a4
{ This was played in the game Elgabry,M @@StartBracket@@2305@@EndBracket@@ -Sekar,B @@StartBracket@@2137@@EndBracket@@ Mumbai Wealth open 2019, where Black was controlling pretty much everything on board. }
*

