[White "17. Four Knights: with 4.e4"]
[Black "5.Nxe5 and 8.Qd3: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e4
{ This move has become quite fashionable lately - White is fighting for space advantage and intends to play d4 next. Black's reply here is very principled. }
4... Bc5
{ The critical move of the position which leads to some theoretical debate. The alternative is  4...Bb4  but if Black is considering to play ...d6 next and then reroute the bishop to c5 for some control of the d4 square, this essentially is a loss of time. }
5. Nxe5
{ This is the only real way how White could try to fight for an opening advantage but I'm confident that Black is doing great in all of the lines. White's alternative looks not very inspiring. }
5... Nxe5
{ This is forced as  5...Bxf2+  is a terrible alternative. After  6.Kxf2  Nxe5  7.d4  White has a powerful pawn center, two bishops, Black is about to lose a million tempi when White will push forward the pawns to attack the black knights, and the supposed weakening of the white king plays no role. }
6. d4 Bb4 { So far this is forced. } 7. dxe5 Nxe4
{ The pawn on e5 is traded for the e4 pawn and there's serious pressure against the white knight on c3. Now White has a set of choices but the most serious moves are   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qf3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd4  .  The alternatives  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd3  or  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qc2  are quite rare while  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qg4  is a mistake.    We will cover all of these options as well as the dubious  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bd2 }
8. Qd3 { This is a rather rare continuation but still quite interesting. } 8...
Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5
{ Similarly to the mainline, the Black bishop retreats to a5 to pressure the c3 pawn so that the Qg3 maneuver has adequate defense. White here has some choices but often they could transpose to the main lines after 8. Qf3. }
10. Qg3 { This transposes to one of the sidelines of the main line. } *

