{ The pawn on e5 is traded for the e4 pawn and there's serious pressure against the white knight on c3. Now White has a set of choices but the most serious moves are   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qf3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd4  .  The alternatives  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd3  or  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qc2  are quite rare while  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qg4  is a mistake.    We will cover all of these options as well as the dubious  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bd2 }
8. Qd3 { This is a rather rare continuation but still quite interesting. } 8...
Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5
{ Similarly to the mainline, the Black bishop retreats to a5 to pressure the c3 pawn so that the Qg3 maneuver has adequate defense. White here has some choices but often they could transpose to the main lines after 8. Qf3. }
10. Bf4
{ With the white queen on d3 this spectacular idea to castle long feels to be some sort of a concession to one of the main ideas of the mainline which is quite popular today, but still, it might be playable. }
10... O-O 11. O-O-O Qe7 12. Kb2 b5
{ Black sacrifices a pawn and intends to open the queenside with ...a6, should White accept the gift. The difference between the white queen on d3 and not on f3 is that Black can immediately push the b-pawn and not 'waste' time for ...Rb8. Plus White can't close the center with c5 immediately as the pawn is simply under attack. }
13. Qd5
{ Here  13...Rb8  might be just fine but Black has a stunning resource at his disposal. }
13... Bb7
{ White has no choice but to accept it as after  14.Qxd7  Bxc3+  Black starts a decisive attack with  15.Kxc3  Qa3+  and at the right time ...Be4 combined with ...Rad8. }
14. Qxb7 bxc4
{ No matter where the white queen will retreat, the next moves are forced. }
15. Qd5 Rab8+ 16. Kc2 Qa3 17. Qxc4
{ This position is inevitable - now follow a couple of forced moves. } 17...
Qb2+ 18. Kd3 d5
{ Black is down a piece but the white king is in the middle of the crossfire. }
19. exd6
{ White doesn't have a choice - after  19.Qc5  Black will just take the pawn on a2 with ...Rb3 and ...Bb6 threats. }
19... cxd6
{ Black's ...Rfc8 is a huge threat and if White would try to protect the c-pawn with  20.Rc1  ,  then after  20...Rfe8!  Black stops White's light-squared bishop to join the game, intending to continue with ...Qxf2 and ...Rb2 next.  After   20.Bd2  Rfc8  21.Qd4  d5!  White is literally out of moves. }
20. Rd2 { The only move to keep the game alive. } 20... Qc1
{ From here the game is not forced but if White defends perfectly, Black should win back the sacrificed piece. }
21. g3
{ Or  21.Rc2  Qd1+  22.Rd2  Qc1  with a repetition.  White might try to get greedy with   22.Bd2  but then after  22...d5!  and either ...Rb1 or ...Qh5 Black continues a very strong attack. }
21... Rfc8 22. Bg2
{ It looks tempting to play  22.Bh3  but after  22...Qxh1  23.Bxc8  d5!  Black wins back the piece as there's the ...Qe4 mate threat. }
22... Qa3 23. Bc6 d5
{ The final touch - the game is drifting towards a draw now. } 24. Qxd5 Qxc3+
25. Ke2 Rxc6
{ More simplifications are incoming.  26.Bxb8  Re6+  27.Kf1   or  27.Kd1  Qa1+  28.Kc2  Qc3+  27...Qxd2  28.Qxd2  Bxd2  29.Bxa7  Ra6  A draw is inevitable. I don't claim that I've posted all of the lines, but you should have a pretty good idea what to expect from this line. }
