8. Qd4
{ This is historically the most played move which recently has stepped back to give most of the spotlight to the modern  8.Qf3  .  Still, there's some venom left in the line and Black will have to play carefully. Typically in this line, White holds a temporary initiative. With accurate play, Black can gain the initiative and play a better endgame, at least in an ideal scenario. }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Be7
{ Here the bishop has to retreat to e7,  otherwise after  9...Ba5  10.Ba3  would be a big problem and  10...Qg5  will be met by  11.f4  Black's idea is trying to play ...d6 as quickly as possible, neutralize White's temporary initiative and play for the weak c-pawns, should the opportunity arise. }
10. Bd3
{ The peaceful alternative - White gives priority to development but also makes Black's life a little easier. Black's next move is obvious. }
10... d6 11. Bf4 { After this move all you need to know is just one trick. }
11... dxe5 12. Bxe5 O-O
{ Black sets up a nice trap - now after  13.Bxg7  Black suddenly wins with  13...c5  and White is overloaded to keep both bishops protected. }
13. O-O
{ Here Black has some ways to equalize, including the very direct  13...Bf6  and trading everything that moves. }
13... Re8 { Black keeps the trap alive and hopes for more. } 14. Rfe1
{ White might get a little ambitious with  14.Qe4  but after  14...g6  15.Qf3  Bd6  16.Bf6  Black has a great shot  16...Bg4!  with chances to take over the game. }
14... Qxd4 { Alright, White has avoided all traps, it's time to equalize. } 15.
cxd4 c6
{ There's not much to see. There have been some correspondence games in the line but it is too dry for White to hope for success. One of them continued with  16.Rab1  b6  17.Be4  Bd7  and Black comfortably held the position. Matyukhin,S @@StartBracket@@2504@@EndBracket@@ -Zhak,B @@StartBracket@@2528@@EndBracket@@ W-ch30 final email 2017. }
