{ This is the only real way how White could try to fight for an opening advantage but I'm confident that Black is doing great in all of the lines. White's alternative looks not very inspiring. }
5... Nxe5
{ This is forced as  5...Bxf2+  is a terrible alternative. After  6.Kxf2  Nxe5  7.d4  White has a powerful pawn center, two bishops, Black is about to lose a million tempi when White will push forward the pawns to attack the black knights, and the supposed weakening of the white king plays no role. }
6. d4 Bb4 { So far this is forced. } 7. dxe5 Nxe4
{ The pawn on e5 is traded for the e4 pawn and there's serious pressure against the white knight on c3. Now White has a set of choices but the most serious moves are   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qf3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd4  .  The alternatives  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd3  or  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qc2  are quite rare while  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qg4  is a mistake.    We will cover all of these options as well as the dubious  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bd2 }
8. Qd4
{ This is historically the most played move which recently has stepped back to give most of the spotlight to the modern  8.Qf3  .  Still, there's some venom left in the line and Black will have to play carefully. Typically in this line, White holds a temporary initiative. With accurate play, Black can gain the initiative and play a better endgame, at least in an ideal scenario. }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Be7
{ Here the bishop has to retreat to e7,  otherwise after  9...Ba5  10.Ba3  would be a big problem and  10...Qg5  will be met by  11.f4  Black's idea is trying to play ...d6 as quickly as possible, neutralize White's temporary initiative and play for the weak c-pawns, should the opportunity arise. }
10. Qg4
{ The most challenging move - White uses the circumstances that Black can't safely castle short anymore as after  10...O-O  11.Bh6  Black doesn't have the typical ...Bxc3+ defensive resource. However, Black can go for an intuitive exchange sacrifice which starts with  11...g6  ,  and then quickly open the position. I imagine that that would be a reasonable decision for experienced players at accelerated time controls where the temporary initiative is very important. }
10... Kf8
{ Another serious alternative is  10...g6  but it weakens the kingside and a lot of dark squares.   With the recommended move Black wants to play ...d6 as quickly as possible and if necessary, can make an artificial castle with either ...h5-g6-Kg7 or ...h5-h4 and ...Rh6-h5. In practice, White has tested here several moves and after all of them, Black starts with ...d6. White might start with  11.Be2  or  11.Be3  but the positions will transpose to one of the covered lines. }
11. Qe4
{ Since Black is about to push forward the d-pawn, e4 seems to be the most suitable retreat square for the white queen actively placed in the centre of the board. }
11... d6
{ Again, White has to choose between a bishop move as everything else is sort of worse. }
12. f4
{ Not a good choice - White creates even more weaknesses and is stalling the development. }
12... dxe5 13. fxe5 Bd7
{ Not only Black has the better pawn structure but he also has better-developed pieces. Here  14.Qxb7  is dangerous due to  14...Qe8  and the threat of ...Bc6 looks too strong. }
14. h4 Bc6 15. Qf4 Qd7
{ Black continues a normal development, gradually improving the pieces. } 16.
Rh3 Re8 17. Be3
{ Bukal,V @@StartBracket@@2424@@EndBracket@@-Gabrielsen,T @@StartBracket@@2262@@EndBracket@@ Oslo OSS 2004, and here Black had an interesting way to show some ambitions. }
17... h6 18. c5 g5
{ Black is better - White's piece coordination looks quite awkward, not to mention the weak pawns. }
