{ This is not mandatory but reasonable. White might start a gambit again with  14.Bd3!?  ,  inviting Black to keep the pawn and then figure out, how to protect the king. The simplest way to meet it here would be  14...Qc6!  and the gambit is over. If White trades the queens, the position is just equal, but after  15.Qxe5  Bf6  the queen trade is inevitable. }
14... Bd6 15. Qxe8+
{ A difficult choice for White as the philosophy of the line should be - if Black trades the queens, he's doing fine. However, continuing with the gambit approach for White can backfire. }
15... Kxe8 16. Bd4 Kf8
{ Black is just too solid for White to hope for anything. If there's somebody who can run into trouble, it's White as those weak c-pawns are not going anywhere }
17. c5 Be7 18. Bc4 h5
{ White has done everything to make it difficult for Black to bring pieces into the game, but there's always a way! }
19. O-O Rh6 20. Rfe1 Be6 { The arising endgame should be equal. } *

