8. Qf3
{ Currently this is the most contested move, thanks to the highest level game between the World champion Magnus Carlsen and the previous championship challenger Fabiano Caruana in the 2019 FIDE Grand Swiss. }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5
{ It seems to be the best move but I strongly suggest paying close attention, which bishop retreat is recommended for which white queen maneuver so that you don't mix them up - there are 3 different scenarios. My favorite approach, even if I don't remember the move, I try to remember the arising ideas. Specifically here Black is pressuring the c3 pawn so that it may come in handy, should White switch to a kingside attack with Qg3 and Bh6. White here has several choices. }
10. Ba3
{ It's very tempting to try to cut-off the black king from castling short but thanks to the placement of the white queen, Black has a satisfactory pawn sacrifice. }
10... d6
{ This is a typical maneuver - White might win a pawn but Black will be fully developed and the white king is still in the center. }
11. Be2
{ This would be an attempt to sharpen the game and offer the e5 pawn for an initiative but Black is not obliged to take it. }
11... dxe5
{ This is quite risky - the e5 pawn will be lost with precise play anyway. }
12. O-O
{ Including  12.Qg3  and Rd1 next probably was the best way for White to start. }
12... Qf6 13. Qe3 c6
{ Black should be trying to close the annoying bishop on a3 with either a well-timed ...c5, or ...Be7 or d6.. }
14. Bf3 Bb6 15. Qe2
{ Ju,W @@StartBracket@@2557@@EndBracket@@-Kosteniuk,A @@StartBracket@@2529@@EndBracket@@ World Team championship 2015. }
15... Bf5 16. Rad1 Rd8
{ White's attack doesn't seem to be so dangerous and Black still has the pawn. White's game most certainly can be improved before. }
