{ The pawn on e5 is traded for the e4 pawn and there's serious pressure against the white knight on c3. Now White has a set of choices but the most serious moves are   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qf3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd4  .  The alternatives  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd3  or  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qc2  are quite rare while  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qg4  is a mistake.    We will cover all of these options as well as the dubious  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bd2 }
8. Qf3
{ Currently this is the most contested move, thanks to the highest level game between the World champion Magnus Carlsen and the previous championship challenger Fabiano Caruana in the 2019 FIDE Grand Swiss. }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5
{ It seems to be the best move but I strongly suggest paying close attention, which bishop retreat is recommended for which white queen maneuver so that you don't mix them up - there are 3 different scenarios. My favorite approach, even if I don't remember the move, I try to remember the arising ideas. Specifically here Black is pressuring the c3 pawn so that it may come in handy, should White switch to a kingside attack with Qg3 and Bh6. White here has several choices. }
10. Ba3
{ It's very tempting to try to cut-off the black king from castling short but thanks to the placement of the white queen, Black has a satisfactory pawn sacrifice. }
10... d6
{ This is a typical maneuver - White might win a pawn but Black will be fully developed and the white king is still in the center. }
11. Be2
{ This would be an attempt to sharpen the game and offer the e5 pawn for an initiative but Black is not obliged to take it. }
11... O-O
{ Black doesn't have to take the pawn and now there's the immediate ...Bg4 with ...Bxc3+ threat. }
12. Rd1
{ The remaining choices don't change much - now that the ...Bg4 threat no longer is available, Black wants to play ...Bd7-c6 and sacrifice the pawn on d6,  and include ...Re8 if necessary. If White would start with  12.O-O  ,  then  12...Bd7  first and the pawn on b7 is indirectly defended because of the ...Bxc3 threat. }
12... Re8
{ This is a little more precise than the immediate ...Bd7 as Black wants White to take on d6 and not keep the pressure on the d6 pawn for too long. }
13. exd6
{ Playing  13.Qg3  would set a trap - Black can't take the pawn on e5 immediately as the queen on d8 hangs. However, after  13...Qe7  now the threat to take on e5 with the Queen is very real as the white king still is in the center and the pin is very dangerous. }
13... Bd7
{ Black has finished the development and White still can't take the pawn on b7 as the white pawn on c3 hangs with check, leaving the white king too exposed to a direct attack. After  14.Qxb7  Bxc3+  ,  followed by ...cxd6 this is good enough for Black, but the immediate  14...Ba4  appears to be stronger, since  15.dxc7  is impossible due to  15...Qxd1  mate. The deadly pin of the bishop on e2 should decide the fate of the game in favor of Black. }
14. O-O Bc6
{ Black has complete equality and very active play, even if it will mean a temporary pawn loss on d6. The game might continue with  15.Qh5  cxd6  16.Rxd6  Qc7  ,  and now after  17.Bf3  Bxf3  18.Qxf3  Qxc4  Black has won back the pawn. }
