{ It seems to be the best move but I strongly suggest paying close attention, which bishop retreat is recommended for which white queen maneuver so that you don't mix them up - there are 3 different scenarios. My favorite approach, even if I don't remember the move, I try to remember the arising ideas. Specifically here Black is pressuring the c3 pawn so that it may come in handy, should White switch to a kingside attack with Qg3 and Bh6. White here has several choices. }
10. Be2 d6 { It's important to get rid of the e5 pawn as quickly as possible. }
11. Qg3
{ White is threatening to cause some serious problems at the kingside but you shouldn't be worried about this.  11.Ba3  would just transpose to a covered line. }
11... O-O 12. Bh6 Bxc3+
{ The point! Black is just in time to defend against the mate threat and even wins a pawn in the process. }
13. Qxc3 gxh6
{ The black king is a little exposed but as long as Black is happy to give away the extra pawn to protect the king, everything should be fine. White is missing pieces to conduct a serious attack. }
14. Rd1
{ Here and in similar positions White might want to pin the pawn first before taking it but again - Black is perfectly happy to give away the extra pawn. }
14... Qe7 15. exd6 cxd6 { White will win back the pawn, but not more. } 16.
