{ It seems to be the best move but I strongly suggest paying close attention, which bishop retreat is recommended for which white queen maneuver so that you don't mix them up - there are 3 different scenarios. My favorite approach, even if I don't remember the move, I try to remember the arising ideas. Specifically here Black is pressuring the c3 pawn so that it may come in handy, should White switch to a kingside attack with Qg3 and Bh6. White here has several choices. }
10. Bf4
{ The most recent discovery where White is still trying to prove something. White is about to castle long and hopes for a quick attack at the kingside. The bishop on f4 makes Black's ambition to play ...d6 a little harder but then again - there are always other ideas as well! }
10... O-O 11. Be2
{ This makes a strange impression together with Bf4 but it's playable - White might be toying with ideas to castle on either side. Now Black returns to ... d6 plans as White might not castle long after all. }
11... d6 { The threat of ...Bg4 and ...Bxc3+ appears again. } 12. Rd1
{ If White would play here  12.O-O-O  ,  then it's not clear for what purposes he has included Be2. Black could continue with  12...Re8  ,  already defending in advance against Qg3 and Bh6 threats and now after  13.Rhe1  can resume a known idea with  13...Bd7  & Bc6. Black sacrifices the pawn on d6 to open the position and the piece activity and the doubled white c-pawns fully compensate it. }
12... Bd7 { This is a motif that you will already recognize. } 13. exd6
{ With the white king still in the center this is risky. } 13... Bc6 14. dxc7
Qf6 15. Qg3 Bxc3+ { Even  15...Rfe8  looks very powerful here. } 16. Kf1 Rfe8
{ The white pawn on c7 should be inevitably lost, leaving White with a worse pawn structure. }
