{ The most recent discovery where White is still trying to prove something. White is about to castle long and hopes for a quick attack at the kingside. The bishop on f4 makes Black's ambition to play ...d6 a little harder but then again - there are always other ideas as well! }
10... O-O 11. O-O-O
{ Welcome to the 21st century - I wonder what kind of impression this move would make on the old masters. }
11... Qe7 { Black is threatening ...Qa3+. White's reply is almost forced. } 12.
Kb2
{ On b1 the white king stands worse as it doesn't protect the a3 square and the c3 pawn is not protected. }
12... Rb8
{ Black is about to push forward the b-pawn - now White has some choices again. We will cover   13.Qe3  ,   13.Bd3   and  13.Rd5 }
13. Bd3
{ White finishes the development but this allows Black to start the assault at the queenside immediately. I believe that with perfect play Black achieves a forced draw. }
13... b5 14. cxb5 Bb7
{ Black is inevitably going to open the queenside but the development should always be priority. }
15. Qh3
{ There's nothing better for White who badly needs to create some targets. }
15... g6 16. Qe3
{ Here Black has several ways to continue, starting with ...Qe6 and ending with the very brave ...Bxg2 but I suggest to follow Caruana's approach. }
16... Rfe8
{ Black frees the f8 square for the queen and makes sure that White is not threatening with Bg5-f6 and Qh6 to follow. }
17. Rhe1
{ White is renewing the threat of Bg5-f6 as the pawn on e5 is now protected. }
17... a6
{ In the course, I recommend the more precise  17...Bc6  17...a6 is also possible but it gives White more freedom to react, like positioning the light-squared bishop to b3 and continuing to play. In the only game featuring this line, White forced a draw. }
18. Bg5 Qf8 19. Bh6 Qe7 20. Bg5 Qf8
