11... Qe7 { Black is threatening ...Qa3+. White's reply is almost forced. } 12.
Kb2
{ On b1 the white king stands worse as it doesn't protect the a3 square and the c3 pawn is not protected. }
12... Rb8
{ Black is about to push forward the b-pawn - now White has some choices again. We will cover   13.Qe3  ,   13.Bd3   and  13.Rd5 }
13. Qe3
{ Probably the trickiest continuation - White is threatening or at least making it look like a threat to take on a7. }
13... b5 { Nevertheless, Black pushes forward - White can't take the pawn. }
14. cxb5
{ This continuation has not been tested in practice - it allows Black to open the queenside for equal attacking chances. }
14... a6 15. Bg5
{ Or  15.Bc4  axb5  16.Bb3  b4  ,  forcing White to close the light-squared bishop with  17.c4 }
15... Qe6 16. Qg3 d6
{ This is a necessary move, defending against White's Bf6 with ...Qg4. } 17.
exd6 axb5 { Now it's safe to take the pawn. } 18. Be7
{ I guess this is the critical try for White - after  18.dxc7  Black starts a decisive attack with  18...Ra8 }
18... Re8 19. Qe3
{ With a pawn up, obviously White is interested to trade queens and thus keeps his king protected. Black's answer is obvious.  19.dxc7  would be a mistake due to the same  19...Ra8 }
19... Qd7 20. dxc7
{ With this move, White keeps the extra pawn and will even win an exchange. However, the weakened white king and the many pieces on the board give Black sufficient compensation. }
20... Qxc7 21. Bd6 Qc6 22. Qf3
{ After  22.Qc5  Black can play  22...Qd7  and the Bishop is pinned. } 22...
Qb6 { Activity above all! } 23. Bxb8 Qxb8
{ The storm has ended and Black has sacrificed an exchange and a pawn. Because the white king is so weak, Black should be able to deliver at least a perpetual check. }
24. Bd3 Bxc3+
{ Also  24...Be6  with an idea to play ...Rc8 next is interesting } 25. Kxc3
Qe5+ { The black queen starts to hunt down the king. } 26. Kc2 Qc5+ 27. Kb1
Qb4+ { If White is accurate, draw is inevitable. } *

