[White "17. Four Knights: with 4.e4"]
[Black "5.Nxe5, 8.Qf3, 10.Bf4: #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e4
{ This move has become quite fashionable lately - White is fighting for space advantage and intends to play d4 next. Black's reply here is very principled. }
4... Bc5
{ The critical move of the position which leads to some theoretical debate. The alternative is  4...Bb4  but if Black is considering to play ...d6 next and then reroute the bishop to c5 for some control of the d4 square, this essentially is a loss of time. }
5. Nxe5
{ This is the only real way how White could try to fight for an opening advantage but I'm confident that Black is doing great in all of the lines. White's alternative looks not very inspiring. }
5... Nxe5
{ This is forced as  5...Bxf2+  is a terrible alternative. After  6.Kxf2  Nxe5  7.d4  White has a powerful pawn center, two bishops, Black is about to lose a million tempi when White will push forward the pawns to attack the black knights, and the supposed weakening of the white king plays no role. }
6. d4 Bb4 { So far this is forced. } 7. dxe5 Nxe4
{ The pawn on e5 is traded for the e4 pawn and there's serious pressure against the white knight on c3. Now White has a set of choices but the most serious moves are   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qf3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd4  .  The alternatives  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qd3  or  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qc2  are quite rare while  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Qg4  is a mistake.    We will cover all of these options as well as the dubious  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/8/4P3/1bP1n3/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bd2 }
8. Qf3
{ Currently this is the most contested move, thanks to the highest level game between the World champion Magnus Carlsen and the previous championship challenger Fabiano Caruana in the 2019 FIDE Grand Swiss. }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Ba5
{ It seems to be the best move but I strongly suggest paying close attention, which bishop retreat is recommended for which white queen maneuver so that you don't mix them up - there are 3 different scenarios. My favorite approach, even if I don't remember the move, I try to remember the arising ideas. Specifically here Black is pressuring the c3 pawn so that it may come in handy, should White switch to a kingside attack with Qg3 and Bh6. White here has several choices. }
10. Bf4
{ The most recent discovery where White is still trying to prove something. White is about to castle long and hopes for a quick attack at the kingside. The bishop on f4 makes Black's ambition to play ...d6 a little harder but then again - there are always other ideas as well! }
10... O-O 11. O-O-O
{ Welcome to the 21st century - I wonder what kind of impression this move would make on the old masters. }
11... Qe7 { Black is threatening ...Qa3+. White's reply is almost forced. } 12.
Kb2
{ On b1 the white king stands worse as it doesn't protect the a3 square and the c3 pawn is not protected. }
12... Rb8
{ Black is about to push forward the b-pawn - now White has some choices again. We will cover   13.Qe3  ,   13.Bd3   and  13.Rd5 }
13. Qe3
{ Probably the trickiest continuation - White is threatening or at least making it look like a threat to take on a7. }
13... b5 { Nevertheless, Black pushes forward - White can't take the pawn. }
14. c5
{ The most reasonable choice for White it to close the queenside so that he can focus on the kingside. }
14... b4 { Black, in return, is looking for ways to open the queenside. } 15.
c4 b3
{ A nice pawn sacrifice - now after  16.axb3  Black can continue with  16...Bb4  and win back the pawn on c5, but also continuing the attack looks reasonable. }
16. a3
{ An uneasy decision for White but the white king has found shelter behind the enemy pawn. One mistake and this pawn can turn into a deadly weapon. I suggest treating this pawn as a necessary sacrifice - there might be occasions when White might be threatening to win it - with the queens on the board it would only expose the white king. }
16... Bb7
{ Black has finished the development and if necessary, can protect the b3 pawn with ...Bc6-a4. Black is looking for ways to generate counterplay in the center with ...f6 but avoid trading queens. }
17. h4
{ A very logical attempt - not only is White threatening to push forward the h-pawn and start an attack, but the rook can also be transferred to h3 to target the b3 pawn. As long as the queens don't get traded, it's time to open the center. }
17... f6 18. Qd4 Qe6
{ Probably this is one of the most difficult moves in the line - Black can't take on e5 just yet as it would activate White's dark-squared bishop, and at the same time White was threatening to take on f6 and trade the queens as recapturing with the rook would allow a pin with Bg5. The pawn on d7 is not really under attack as after  19.Qxd7  Qxd7  20.Rxd7  Black recaptures the pawn with  20...fxe5  ,  followed by 21...Bc6 and ...Rfd8, fighting for the d-file and if necessary, sacrificing the b3 pawn. White will have to give up the g2 pawn. }
19. f3
{ If White would take on f6, Black would recapture with the rook for a very sharp and dynamic position. With the last move, White protects the pawn on g2 and is about to rearrange his light-squared bishop to d3 and if necessary, later to b1. However, with the white pawn on f3 White can no longer challenge the b3 pawn with the kingside rook, and also the support of the e3 square for the dark-squared bishops is gone. Thus now, if Black is interested, a queen trade is back on the table. }
19... Rbe8 20. exf6 Qxf6 21. Qxf6 Rxf6
{ The game might continue with  22.Bg5  Rfe6  23.Kxb3  Bc6  ,  where Black is threatening both ...Re5 and ...Rb8+ with ...Ba4 to follow. }
*

