[SetUp "1"]

11. Qg3
{ White is attacking the pawn on g7 - after short castling, he intends to continue with Bh6. What will you do? }
11... O-O
{ With the dark-squared bishop on a5, this maneuver is very much possible! }
12. Bh6 Bxc3+
{ The key move - Black defends the king with this intermezzo move. White has no choice but to accept it. }
13. Qxc3 gxh6
{ The black king is a little weak but Black can always sell back the extra pawn to secure an equal position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Four Knights: with 4.e4"]
[Black "Chapter 17 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pppp1ppp/8/b3P3/2P2B2/2P2Q2/P4PPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. Be2
{ White tries to slow down Black's intentions to play ...d6 - how will you continue the development? }
11... d6
{ This is a common pawn sacrifice - priority should always be given to fast development. Besides, White's extra pawn is doubled. If White had already castled long, this wouldn't be good. }
12. Rd1
{ Castling long here is quite dangerous as Black has already played ...d6 and will just sacrifice the pawn.   12.exd6  Bg4!  If not careful, White can get into a trouble quickly. }
12... Bd7
{ Another important move - the pawn on b7 can't be taken as Black will grab the pawn on c3 with a check. Black intends to continue with   13...dxe5  and ...Qe7 next, so the question is - what happens if White takes the pawn? }
13. exd6 Bc6 { Black starts to take over the game. } 14. dxc7
{ 14.Qg3  Re8  should be the same. } 14... Qf6
{ This is much stronger than taking the exchange with   14...Qxd1+  ,  followed by ...Bxf3 - it would be temporary anyway. }
15. Qg3 Bxc3+ 16. Kf1 Rfe8
{ The game is highly tactical but the bottom line is - White needs to take care of his king. While he does it, the pawn on c7 should be lost. }
