1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3
{ In the Reversed Sicilian English opening this is one of the most topical lines today and pretty much every self respecting player who's playing modern English opening lines, has a decent experience with both  4.e3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2N2N2/PP1PPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center. }
4... d5
{ The problem with the traditional approach of pushing forward the d-pawn is that White immediately can apply pressure against the e5 pawn. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5
{ Now Black is starting to experience some issues with the e5 pawn so the trade on c3 already seems to be mandatory. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. d4 Bd7
{ Probably playing this position as a gambit should work just fine for Black. However, the entire line feels like a concession to some of the sidelines where White has included a3 as a waste of time. }
