1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3
{ In the Reversed Sicilian English opening this is one of the most topical lines today and pretty much every self respecting player who's playing modern English opening lines, has a decent experience with both  4.e3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2N2N2/PP1PPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center. }
4... Bb4
{ The top move in the position which goes throughout the entire course and should be already a familiar setup. Black is ready to trade away the dark-squared bishop to ease up the pressure against the central squares. Of course, the downside is the probability of playing against a two-bishop advantage, which could especially feel if the position would open too much. White here has two main moves. }
5. d4
{ A relatively rare move that is perfectly playable but from a strategic point of view doesn't make a lot of sense, since Black has a perfectly positioned bishop on b4 for a serious counter attack against White's center. }
5... exd4 6. exd4
{ Sort of necessary as after  6.Nxd4  Ne4  Black can double White's c-pawns for no visible compensation and even keeps the dark-squared bishop alive. After  7.Nxc6  there's even time for tricks, borrowed from the Scotch opening, which start with  7...Qf6! }
6... d5 { Black has an easy development with no visible weaknesses. } 7. Bg5
{ White might try to pressure Black into taking on c4 but with the white king still in the center, you shouldn't be worried about the d5 pawn too much. }
7... O-O 8. cxd5
{ What else? Black is already threatening to play ...Re8+ and take the pawn on c4. I should note that  8.Bxf6  is a very risky attempt to win a pawn and can land White into trouble very quickly. For example,  8...Qxf6  9.cxd5  Ne7  and White doesn't have the time to protect the extra pawn on d5.  10.Qb3  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  Re8  and something nasty is brewing on the e-file as after  12.Be2  Ng6  Black is already attacking with full force. }
8... Qe8+
{ The point - Black gets rid of the pin and recaptures the pawn on d5. } 9. Be2
Nxd5
{ The game yet again is not forced here but I just want to mention that Black is not interested to take on c3 himself unless forced. The pawn on d4 makes a fine target and the dark-squared bishop can retreat to e7 if White's pushing for it. }
10. Bd2 Be6 11. O-O Rd8
{ The position is objectively equal but Black has some visible targets to pressure while White does not. Here is one game in the line. }
12. Bb5 Nde7 13. Ne4 Bxd2 14. Qxd2
{ Stoma,P @@StartBracket@@2209@@EndBracket@@-Zontakh,A @@StartBracket@@2529@@EndBracket@@ Kazimierz Dolny open 2001 - Black could have been a little more accurate. }
14... a6
{ This comes with a plan to get rid of the pin first and only then play ...Nf5. }
