[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Four Knights: 4.e3 and 5.Nd5"]
[Black "5.Nd5 and 6.Nxb4: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3
{ In the Reversed Sicilian English opening this is one of the most topical lines today and pretty much every self respecting player who's playing modern English opening lines, has a decent experience with both  4.e3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2N2N2/PP1PPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center. }
4... Bb4
{ The top move in the position which goes throughout the entire course and should be already a familiar setup. Black is ready to trade away the dark-squared bishop to ease up the pressure against the central squares. Of course, the downside is the probability of playing against a two-bishop advantage, which could especially feel if the position would open too much. White here has two main moves. }
5. Nd5
{ White uses the opportunity that Black's queenside knight already stands on c6 so that after trading the knights Black loses a critical tempo. As I already explained before, that's the reason why the two knight setups have become so popular today. Besides, White is also targeting the bishop on b4 for a two-bishop advantage. }
5... e4
{ This is the most direct way to try to undermine White's strategy - White's queenside knight lacks good retreat squares as its colleague on c6 guards the most important one on d4. }
6. Nxb4
{ If White takes on b4 right away, probably it means that he's preparing the knight jump to d4. }
6... Nxb4
{ Black has temporary control over the d3-square and on some occasions Black can consider moving the knight there for a trade if they can keep the pawn after that. }
7. a3
{ With the white knight still on f3 now it's not a good idea for Black to trade both knights as it would only open the position and increase the power of White's bishops. Also the immediate  7...Nd3+  is not good as the pawn will be lost. }
7... Nc6 8. Ng1
{ Here  8.Nd4  would allow Black to trade the knights, followed by ...d5 and most likely White would have to play an isolated queen's pawn structure with no real attacking chances. The position would be about equal but more pleasant for Black to play. }
8... d5
{ Black has to play aggressively in the center, otherwise White will play b4-Bb2 and slowly open the position. }
9. cxd5
{ A necessary trade - now White's  9.b4  doesn't look so good as Black can yet again divide White's position in two halves with the dynamic  9...d4!  10.Bb2  d3!  and even though White has a very strong dark-squared bishop, it's very difficult to develop the kingside. For example,  11.f3  O-O  12.g3  Re8  and Black is preparing to play ...a5 so that after b5 the knight can be rerouted to e5. Some temporary pawn sacrifices are involved, as usual.   And finally, if instead of the trade White would start with  9.d4  then Black can reroute the queenside knight to e7 first so that after a potential trade on d5 Black can recapture already with a knight. Black is focusing on a game at the kingside where it enjoys a considerable space advantage. }
9... Qxd5 10. d4 { Black was already threatening with ...Ne5-d3. } 10... O-O
11. Ne2
{ Maier,C @@StartBracket@@2360@@EndBracket@@-Gajewski,G @@StartBracket@@2653@@EndBracket@@ Greek Team championship 2013. }
11... Ne7 { This plan feels more natural - the black knight is heading to d5. }
12. Bd2 Re8 13. Nf4 Qg5 14. Bc4 Ned5
{ Black is in time to block the center - the entire kingside belongs to Black. }
