[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Four Knights: 4.e3 and 5.Nd5"]
[Black "5.Nd5 and 6.Nxb4: #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3
{ In the Reversed Sicilian English opening this is one of the most topical lines today and pretty much every self respecting player who's playing modern English opening lines, has a decent experience with both  4.e3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2N2N2/PP1PPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center. }
4... Bb4
{ The top move in the position which goes throughout the entire course and should be already a familiar setup. Black is ready to trade away the dark-squared bishop to ease up the pressure against the central squares. Of course, the downside is the probability of playing against a two-bishop advantage, which could especially feel if the position would open too much. White here has two main moves. }
5. Nd5
{ White uses the opportunity that Black's queenside knight already stands on c6 so that after trading the knights Black loses a critical tempo. As I already explained before, that's the reason why the two knight setups have become so popular today. Besides, White is also targeting the bishop on b4 for a two-bishop advantage. }
5... e4
{ This is the most direct way to try to undermine White's strategy - White's queenside knight lacks good retreat squares as its colleague on c6 guards the most important one on d4. }
6. Nxb4
{ If White takes on b4 right away, probably it means that he's preparing the knight jump to d4. }
6... Nxb4
{ Black has temporary control over the d3-square and on some occasions Black can consider moving the knight there for a trade if they can keep the pawn after that. }
7. Nd4
{ White is looking towards to trade the knight on d4 for the annoying intruder on b4 and give some room for the dark-squared bishop on b2. }
7... c5
{ Very strong and active - now the white knight has several retreat squares but only one is reasonable. }
8. Nc2
{ White would love to trade the knights and position the dark-squared bishop on b2. Black's reply is almost forced. }
8... Nd3+ { Thanks to the white knight on c2 Black wins some time. } 9. Bxd3
exd3 10. Na3 d5
{ Nothing has changed - Black still charges forward as White might target the pawn on d3 with Qb3 and it will need to be protected, unless Black is fine to play an improvised gambit. }
11. Qb3
{ Or  11.Qa4+  which would lead to the same position after  11...Bd7  12.Qb3  Be6  .  I'm not sure that White even needs to go here -   instead, he could play something more positional like  11.b3  and 12. Bb2 next but this would allow Black to have a harmonious game where nobody is bothering the d3 pawn. }
11... Be6
{ Black indirectly defends the pawn on d3 - now  12.Qxd3  would be met with  12...dxc4  and White can't capture the pawn on c4. If White would decline the queen trade, Black can protect the pawn with ...Qd5. }
12. Qb5+
{ Taking the pawn on b7 is too much - after  12.Qxb7  O-O  Black is simply threatening to the take pawn on c4 and White can't afford to lose more time as Black is about to storm the kingside with either ...Ne4 or ...Ng4 and ...Qh4 to follow. The white king is left alone and the queenside pieces won't help it. }
12... Qd7 13. cxd5
{ This probably is just a worse alternative for White, which was played in Nei,I-Smyslov,V USSR Championship final 1960. }
13... Qxb5
{ Here the former world champion Vassily Smyslov could have quickly seized the advantage with a lot more precise continuation. }
14. Nxb5 Nxd5
{ Black just in time protects against the fork on c7. White is out of good options  15.e4  is met by  15...Nb4  and Black as well is threatening with a fork. }
15. Nd6+
{ This would temporarily win a pawn but Black is about to win it back. } 15...
Ke7 16. Nxb7 Nb4 { White is losing material due to ...Nc2 and ...Bxa2 threat. }
