{ Ignoring the threat with  13.Qd4  will backfire -  13...Ng4  14.Nxe4  Nxf2  Black wins the pawn but the critical moment arises after  15.Nxd6  Qxd4  16.exd4  .  Here a much safer choice instead of grabbing the rook on h1 is  16...cxd6  and now after  17.Rg1  b6  and ...Bb7 to follow Black looks just better and White is still underdeveloped. }
13... b6 14. O-O { This loses in a stunning fashion. } 14... Ba6
{ Black deflects the light-squared bishop from protecting the g4 square. } 15.
Bxa6
{ White doesn't have a choice as after the bishop trade Black has the . ..Nf3+ threat as well with checkmate to follow. }
15... Ng4 16. h3 Nxf2 { So far all of this is forced. } 17. Rxf2 Rxf2
{ A very important accuracy - rushing with  17...Qxg3  would allow White to save himself with  18.Rf4! }
18. Nxe4
{ The last practical chance - after  18.Kxf2  Qxg3+  and ...Rf8 to follow White is swiftly mated.   But after  18.Nh1  Rf5  Black will reroute the rook to g5 for a killing ...Qxh3 threat. }
18... Qxe4 19. Kxf2 Rf8+
{ Black should either hunt down the white king or win a decisive material advantage. For example,  20.Ke1  Bg3+  21.Kd2  Qxd5+  and now after  22.Kc2  Rf2+  23.Bd2  Black can just collect the bishop on a6 with ...b5 and ...Qc6+ to follow. }
