[White "18. Four Knights: 4.e3 and 5.Nd5"]
[Black "5.Nd5 and 6.Ng1: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3
{ In the Reversed Sicilian English opening this is one of the most topical lines today and pretty much every self respecting player who's playing modern English opening lines, has a decent experience with both  4.e3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2N2N2/PP1PPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center. }
4... Bb4
{ The top move in the position which goes throughout the entire course and should be already a familiar setup. Black is ready to trade away the dark-squared bishop to ease up the pressure against the central squares. Of course, the downside is the probability of playing against a two-bishop advantage, which could especially feel if the position would open too much. White here has two main moves. }
5. Nd5
{ White uses the opportunity that Black's queenside knight already stands on c6 so that after trading the knights Black loses a critical tempo. As I already explained before, that's the reason why the two knight setups have become so popular today. Besides, White is also targeting the bishop on b4 for a two-bishop advantage. }
5... e4
{ This is the most direct way to try to undermine White's strategy - White's queenside knight lacks good retreat squares as its colleague on c6 guards the most important one on d4. }
6. Ng1
{ The main move in the position - it's difficult to explain this but that's where modern chess is heading today. White has lost two tempos, he's done it voluntarily and yet this is a topical line. The idea hides in the fact that Black's pawn on e4 is lacking proper support and it can be either challenged or traded away with either f3 or d3, giving White some space advantage. }
6... O-O
{ Black has finished the development at the kingside and can easily protect the e4 pawn. }
7. Ne2
{ Allowing the black bishop to stay on b4 is a risky approach as Black can already start an offensive right after the opening. }
7... Nxd5 8. cxd5 Ne5 9. Ng3
{ Positioning the knight on c3 would be worse as Black would happily trade the knight and bring out the queen to g5. On f4 the knight has nothing to do and Black could start by indirectly defending the pawn on e4 with ...Re8. }
9... f5 10. a3 Bd6
{ Black has a very straightforward game while White needs to be a little careful. }
11. d3 Qh4
{ The simple double trade on d3 looks fine as well, followed by ...Qf6, ...a5 and ...b6, bringing out the light-squared bishop to a6 or b7. }
12. dxe4 fxe4
{ Black is threatening with ...Ng4 so White must do something about it } 13.
Be2
{ Ignoring the threat with  13.Qd4  will backfire -  13...Ng4  14.Nxe4  Nxf2  Black wins the pawn but the critical moment arises after  15.Nxd6  Qxd4  16.exd4  .  Here a much safer choice instead of grabbing the rook on h1 is  16...cxd6  and now after  17.Rg1  b6  and ...Bb7 to follow Black looks just better and White is still underdeveloped. }
13... b6 14. Bd2
{ The only move which holds the position - everything else is worse. } 14...
Bb7
{ Black is not only threatening to win the pawn on d5 but there's also the ...Nd3+ threat. }
15. Bb4 { The best defense which forces some trades. } 15... Bxb4+ 16. axb4
Nd3+ 17. Bxd3 exd3 { White still needs to be accurate to hold this. } 18. e4
{ Here Black doesn't have anything better than going for a spectacular line which should end with an equal position. }
18... Bxd5 19. Qxd3
{ With the white king still in the center, accepting the sacrifice would be an instant end of the game.   19.exd5  Rae8+  20.Kf1  Re2  and mate to follow. }
19... Bxe4 20. Nxe4 Rae8
{ The position inevitably reaches an equal endgame. For example,  21.O-O  Qxe4  22.Qxd7  Qxb4  23.Qxc7  but perhaps Black can push a little with  23...a5  . }
