1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3
{ In the Reversed Sicilian English opening this is one of the most topical lines today and pretty much every self respecting player who's playing modern English opening lines, has a decent experience with both  4.e3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2N2N2/PP1PPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center. }
4... Bb4
{ The top move in the position which goes throughout the entire course and should be already a familiar setup. Black is ready to trade away the dark-squared bishop to ease up the pressure against the central squares. Of course, the downside is the probability of playing against a two-bishop advantage, which could especially feel if the position would open too much. White here has two main moves. }
5. Nd5
{ White uses the opportunity that Black's queenside knight already stands on c6 so that after trading the knights Black loses a critical tempo. As I already explained before, that's the reason why the two knight setups have become so popular today. Besides, White is also targeting the bishop on b4 for a two-bishop advantage. }
5... e4
{ This is the most direct way to try to undermine White's strategy - White's queenside knight lacks good retreat squares as its colleague on c6 guards the most important one on d4. }
6. Ng1
{ The main move in the position - it's difficult to explain this but that's where modern chess is heading today. White has lost two tempos, he's done it voluntarily and yet this is a topical line. The idea hides in the fact that Black's pawn on e4 is lacking proper support and it can be either challenged or traded away with either f3 or d3, giving White some space advantage. }
6... O-O
{ Black has finished the development at the kingside and can easily protect the e4 pawn. }
7. Nxb4
{ With Ng1 and black having already castled this is an interesting option at White's disposal and a final attempt to get the two bishop advantage. }
7... Nxb4 8. a3 Nc6
{ 8...Nd3+  is possible but after  9.Bxd3  exd3  10.Qb3  Black needs to be ready to play a gambit for some lead in the development. The text move is a safer choice which is easier to predict. }
9. b4
{ Sooner or later someone will play this novelty - White brings out the dark-squared bishop to b2 but the true idea is revealed a couple of moves later.   9.b3  would be considerably slower as Black could proceed with  9...d5  10.Bb2  d4  - an option which is not available here due to the pawn on b5 }
9... a5
{ Black creates an extra potential weakness on c5 - you never know when it might be handy. }
10. b5 Ne5
{ White's idea here is to find a good moment to push f4 so that if Black captures the pawn, then the g-file could open for a potentially devastating attack which is fueled by White's dark-squared bishop on b2. Here immediately it's not so great as after  11.f4  Black could just proceed with  11...Nd3+  12.Bxd3  exd3  and now after  13.Qb3  Black has a nice resource of  13...Ne4  with a threat of both ...Qh4+ and ...Nc5, protecting the pawn on d3. Remember including ...a5? }
11. Bb2 d6 12. Qc2
{ The trickiest move which takes under control the d3 square and prepares to play f4. After the straightforward  12.f4  Black can play the planned  12...Nd3+  13.Bxd3  exd3  with a good position as the pawn on d3 can be easily defended both with the light-squared bishop, or ...Ne4-c5. }
12... Bg4
{ This is the move that I like the most as it considerably slows down the f4 plan. If necessary, the light-squared bishop can be rerouted as far as g6,  controlling both e4 pawn and the d3 square. The immediate  12...Bf5  allows White to play  13.Nf3! }
13. f4 { This is a very risky approach but there is one nuance. } 13... exf3
14. gxf3 Bxf3
{ Take with the bishop.  14...Nxf3+  costs Black one critical tempo and now after  15.Nxf3  Bxf3  16.Rg1  White has a serious initiative. }
15. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 16. Kd1
{ That's the difference of the tempo - Black is in time to regroup and protect the king while the white king is walking. }
16... Ne5 { Because of the wandering white king Black has the better chances. }
