Nxd5 11. cxd6 Ncb4
{ Or the other knight to b4 first - it doesn't matter. Black gets to play ...Nd3+ and win a rook in the process. }
12. axb4 Nxb4 13. Qc3
{ Probably the most stubborn defense because after  13.Qxc7  Black can take the other rook as it will be easier to escape with the knight from the queenside -  13...Qxc7  14.dxc7  Nc2+  ,  winning the rook on a1. }
13... Nd3+ 14. Kd1 Nxf2+ 15. Ke1
{ If the white king goes the other way with  15.Kc2  then the most precise move here is  15...b4!  and only then take the rook, so that White's dxc7 has less power. After  16.dxc7  Qe7  and Black should be winning the game. }
15... Nxh1
{ The only chance for White to save this game is somehow to trap the knight on h1 but Black has enough resources to either save it or trade the knight for another piece. }
16. g3 Qg5 17. Bg2 Qh5
{ This comes with the idea to meet  Bxh1  with ...Qxh2 and effectively winning the bishop. After  18.h3  Black can include  18...Qf5!  with ...Qf2+ threat and now after  19.Bxh1  resume the  19...Qxh3  idea. }
