{ White pushes back the bishop so that the pawn on e4 can be challenged with Qc2. White usually does this early while Black's dark-squared bishop doesn't have access to the f8 square. }
7... Bd6 8. Qc2
{ This is the most played move in the position, usually intending to follow with Ne2 and threatening to win the pawn on e4 by trading the knights. However, according to the modern engines White appears to be simply worse and that's the reason why strong players have started to research other options in this line. }
8... Re8 9. Ne2
{ Now it's time for Black to show why it's not recommended to stay behind in development. }
9... b5
{ This move was invented by the legendary GM Oleg Romanishin back in 1979 with no engines and it's doing great today as well! Black offers White to play a gambit to capitalize on his supremacy in development. }
10. Nxf6+ { The most tested move but White has other alternatives as well. }
10... Qxf6 11. cxb5
{ I think that given the circumstances this is the best practical attempt for White - ask Black to prove what's he got for the sacrificed pawn, plus the second is hanging on e4. }
11... Ne5 12. Qxe4
{ In a poker term, White moves all-in and hopes that the river will bring one of the few outs @@StartBracket@@meaning, Black won't find the best way in the jungle of complications@@EndBracket@@. I've always thought that it's much easier to attack than to defend though. I'll present to you the most critical lines and tricks you should be thinking about. The thought alone that not only you are very close to winning, but also playing a high adrenaline masterpiece, should feel very good! }
12... Bb7 13. Qd4
{ This move has been tested no less than 6 times in over the board games, plus once in correspondence chess. White keeps an eye on the d3 square and is up to two pawns but Black should have a winning attack. }
13... a6
{ The most straightforward move to open the position but there are other good moves as well, like  13...Rad8  with an idea to play ...c5 next and open the d-file, and even engines  @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/pbpp1ppp/3b1q2/1P2n3/3Q4/P3P3/1P1PNPPP/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...h5!?  with a purpose I have yet to understand! Black is not obliged to find a forced win - having a very strong attack is good enough. }
14. h4
{ This weird move comes with an idea to play f4 next and 'force' Black to trade queens. White simply doesn't have any other moves as  14.bxa6  Bxa6  is too much for White to handle, with Black threatening both ...Nd3+ and win the queen in the process, or the more subtle ...c5. }
14... Qg6 { Black provokes the white knight to jump to f4. } 15. Nf4 Qf5
{ Only now the black queen goes to f5 so that nobody can bother it. Now Black is threatening with both ...axb5 and ...Ng4. }
16. b4
{ This is a reasonable attempt to continue the development but now the rook on a1 might be under attack. Now there are some sharp lines but as long as you will remember the first moves, you will be doing great. }
16... Ng4
{ Maybe somebody will find  16...axb5  an easier move to play to meet  17.Bb2  with  17...f6  and a great gambit, but this move is the strongest. }
17. bxa6 { This is something that Black always should be ready for. } 17... Be5
{ The only move - Black attacks the white queen but not necessarily always take the rook. }
18. Bd3
{ After  18.Qc5  d6  19.Qa5  White pins Black's dark-squared bishop. Now after  19...d5  the game is very messy but Black is ahead. }
18... Qf6 19. Qxd7 Bxg2
{ Nice shot - now the f2 pawn is under attack as well. } 20. Rg1 Bf3 21. Rxg4
Rad8
{ The last finesse - White inevitably loses material as too many things are under attack. }
22. Qf5 Bxg4 23. Qxf6 gxf6
{ White has several pawns for the rook but not enough to call it compensation. }
