14. h4
{ This weird move comes with an idea to play f4 next and 'force' Black to trade queens. White simply doesn't have any other moves as  14.bxa6  Bxa6  is too much for White to handle, with Black threatening both ...Nd3+ and win the queen in the process, or the more subtle ...c5. }
14... Qg6 { Black provokes the white knight to jump to f4. } 15. Nf4 Qf5
{ Only now the black queen goes to f5 so that nobody can bother it. Now Black is threatening with both ...axb5 and ...Ng4. }
16. bxa6
{ I guess from a practical point of view it makes sense for White to take the pawn before Black does it and pray that the position holds together. All of this has already been played before in Tao, T @@StartBracket@@2366@@EndBracket@@-Chan, L @@StartBracket@@2210@@EndBracket@@ Doeberl Cup 2018, and here Black instead of the flashy  16...Bf3  had to go for a strong exchange sacrifice. }
16... Rxa6 17. Be2
{ White can't take the rook as there will be too many threats to parry, starting with the simple ...Nc6 and ending with some spectacular ...Qxf4!! }
17... c5 { Black pushes away the white queen from the center. } 18. Qc3 Nc6 19.
Qb3
{ I'm not sure who would be even capable to pick up such a cold move when everything is hanging. After the more human  19.Qd3  Black surprisingly can just trade the queens with  19...Qxd3  and the knight on f4 hangs. After  20.Nxd3  c4  it is trapped in the middle of the board. }
19... Na5 { Now ...Bxf4 is almost inevitable so White has to trade queens. }
20. Qd3 Qxd3 21. Nxd3
{ White is up to two pawns but is about to lose a piece. } 21... Nb3 22. Rb1 c4
{ There's nothing White can do. The knight can't go to f4 as Black will simply take it and pin the bishop on e2 with ... Nd4 }
23. Nb4 Bxb4 24. Bxc4
{ Or  24.axb4  Be4  25.Bxc4  Rc6  26.d3  Rxc4!  and Black is up a piece. }
24... Be4 25. Bxa6 Bxb1 26. axb4 Nxc1
{ We're straight to the converting phase - Black is winning. } *

