{ If  16.f3  then the light-squared bishop returns to e6 and the supposed weakness on d5 is now well compensated by the pawn on e3. }
16... Bxe2 17. Qxe2 Rc8
{ If necessary, Black is ready to sacrifice the d5 pawn. It's difficult for White to develop the queenside and keep the pin at the d-file alive. }
18. Rb1
{ Or  18.cxd5  cxd5  19.Qb5  Qe7  ,  Black's response is the same - drop the d5 pawn and organize a strong counterplay at the queenside due to the undeveloped White's pieces. }
18... Qe7 19. cxd5 cxd5
{ White can't take the pawn on d5 as after  20.Rxd5  Black plays  20...Rfd8  21.Rxd8+  Rxd8  22.Bd2  Qe4  and not only Black wins back the pawn, but emerges with a better endgame as well. }
