[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Four Knights: 4.e3 and 5.Nd5"]
[Black "5.Nd5 and 6.Ng1: #31"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3
{ In the Reversed Sicilian English opening this is one of the most topical lines today and pretty much every self respecting player who's playing modern English opening lines, has a decent experience with both  4.e3  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2N2N2/PP1PPPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.g3  White normally is threatening to play d4 and seize a solid control over the center. }
4... Bb4
{ The top move in the position which goes throughout the entire course and should be already a familiar setup. Black is ready to trade away the dark-squared bishop to ease up the pressure against the central squares. Of course, the downside is the probability of playing against a two-bishop advantage, which could especially feel if the position would open too much. White here has two main moves. }
5. Nd5
{ White uses the opportunity that Black's queenside knight already stands on c6 so that after trading the knights Black loses a critical tempo. As I already explained before, that's the reason why the two knight setups have become so popular today. Besides, White is also targeting the bishop on b4 for a two-bishop advantage. }
5... e4
{ This is the most direct way to try to undermine White's strategy - White's queenside knight lacks good retreat squares as its colleague on c6 guards the most important one on d4. }
6. Ng1
{ The main move in the position - it's difficult to explain this but that's where modern chess is heading today. White has lost two tempos, he's done it voluntarily and yet this is a topical line. The idea hides in the fact that Black's pawn on e4 is lacking proper support and it can be either challenged or traded away with either f3 or d3, giving White some space advantage. }
6... O-O
{ Black has finished the development at the kingside and can easily protect the e4 pawn. }
7. a3
{ White pushes back the bishop so that the pawn on e4 can be challenged with Qc2. White usually does this early while Black's dark-squared bishop doesn't have access to the f8 square. }
7... Bd6 8. d3
{ This is currently the most popular move at the highest level as after everything else Black has shown enough resources to get a great game. White is hoping that after the eventual knight's trade on d5 he can create some pressure against Black's queenside pawns. }
8... exd3
{ Black wants to play next ...Ne5 and get rid of the white knight on d5 with ...c6. }
9. Nf3
{ The latest word in the line is not to rush taking the pawn and develop the knight first so that the ...Ne5 threat can be met with the knight trade first and only then capturing the pawn on d3, keeping the light-squared bishop. }
9... Ne5 10. Nxe5
{ If White wants to keep the light-squared bishop, this is necessary. } 10...
Bxe5 11. Bxd3 c6
{ The safe move. To be honest, I don't think there's something wrong by just taking the knight on d5 and playing some normal developing moves but the pawn on c7 could become a weakness at some point later. If Black would push it forward, White would trade it and long-term pressure both Black's d-pawn and c-pawn. Here the circumstances are slightly different than in one of the previous sidelines where White had a pawn on f4 - Black won't be having the counterplay against White's center. }
12. f4
{ One last attempt - after everything else Black will just push forward the d-pawn with a fine game. }
12... Bd4
{ A marvelous move! Black is ok to trade the dark-squared bishop for the knight but under better terms. Now White is not interested to play  13.exd4  as after  13...cxd5  White has to hurry with castling and Black will continue with ...dxc4 and ...d5 later, fixing the e4 square as an outpost for the knight and a better game. }
13. Bc2
{ A strong move - White is threatening to take the bishop with the queen. Black has no choice. }
13... cxd5 14. Qxd4 dxc4 15. Bd2
{ This would have been an interesting attempt to spice up things, inviting Black to play the 'obvious'  15...d5  Then after  16.Bc3  , O-O-O  and g4 White could organize an offensive at the kingside with interesting results. }
15... b5
{ The safest move in the position which serves two purposes. Not only the light-squared bishop gets placed on the long diagonal, controlling the e4 square, but Black is also one step closer to organizing a counterplay at the queenside, should White castle long. As soon as White will play e4, Black is ready to fire back with ...d5 and after e5 ...Ne4. }
16. O-O-O Bb7 17. e4
{ Now  17.Bc3  is already risky as Black is firing first with  17...a5  and ...b4 next. }
17... d5 18. e5 Ne4
{ White will have to take on e4 sooner or later as the attack is over and Black is about to start his own at the queenside. }
