{ This is what was played in the only game in the line so far. } 15... b6
{ Black has an easy development and as much White would love to position both bishops on c2, c3, castle long and fire away g4-g5, he simply doesn't have time for it. }
16. Bd2 Bb7
{ Black is just in time to control what's happening in the center. } 17. Bc3
Re8 18. Qd4 Qe7 19. O-O-O
{ White has played out the most aggressive setup possible, both bishops on c2 and c3 and castled short. This also drops the e3 pawn in the process which is possible to take, but then the d7 pawn falls as well. }
19... Be4
{ The safest continuation - Black eliminates one of the White's bishops. } 20.
Rhe1
{ If White would take on e4 with  20.Bxe4  Qxe4  21.Qxe4  Nxe4  ,  there are few pieces left. If White takes on d7, Black trades on c3 and wins back the pawn on e3. If it doesn't happen, Black just plays ...d6. }
20... Rac8
{ It's important to focus on an active counterplay than trying to defend own weaknesses. }
21. g4 Qf8
{ Black protects the g7 pawn with an equal position and also sets up a nice trap. If White would play here  22.g5  ,  Black can suddenly start a strong counter-attack with  22...Rxc3!  and White can't recapture with the queen due to ...Rc8. So after  23.bxc3  Qxa3+  24.Kd2  Bxc2  25.Kxc2  Qa2+  Black's attack is quite strong, followed by ...Ne4 next. If White dodges this trick, normally Black wants just to trade the bishops and play ...Ne4 next. }
