[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Four Knights: 4.e3 and 5.Nd5"]
[Black "Chapter 18 Exercise: #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n2n2/8/QPB1p3/4P3/P2P1PPP/R1B1K1NR w KQ - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. Bb2
{ White has two strong bishops here but has some considerable weaknesses in the position. How can Black claim an advantage here? }
11... a5 { Black doesn't have a lot of time and should act quickly. } 12. a3
{ 12.b5  This allows Black to immediately jump to b4 and claim control of the d3 square.  12...Nb4  13.a3  Be6!  If White was to capture on e6, Black delivers an intermezzo check on d3 first. }
12... Be6
{ An important intermezzo move - Black is threatening with ... axb4. } 13. Bxe6
{ 13.b5  This allows Black to transpose to the previously shown idea.  13...Nb4!  The bishop on c4 now is undefended. }
13... axb4 14. Qb3 fxe6
{ White is still underdeveloped and probably needs to give up the pawn to finish the development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Four Knights: 4.e3 and 5.Nd5"]
[Black "Chapter 18 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rr2k1/Qp1q1ppp/4b3/8/4n3/NPPpP3/PB3PPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

19. c4
{ White has two extra pawns - how can Black exploit the fact that White's entire army is concentrated at the queenside? }
19... Rc5
{ Black first cuts off the white queen from coming back to help the white king. Black has four pieces that are ready to attack the white king.   19...Bh3  This would be very tempting but please pay attention to your opponent's ideas as well!  20.Qd4  Qg4  21.Qxg7+!  Qxg7  22.Bxg7  Kxg7  After  23.gxh3  White is up two pawns. }
20. f3 Bh3
{ A stunning move - the white king is left alone and his pieces can't help it. }
21. Rf2
{ The best practical chance.   21.fxe4  This leads to a lovely mate.  21...Qg4  22.Rf2  d2  Black is about to promote a second queen.  23.Qxc5  d1=Q+  24.Rxd1  Rxd1+  25.Rf1  Qxg2   21.gxh3  Rg5+  22.Kh1  Qxh3  Black mates in the next move. }
21... Rg5
{ Taking the rook with   21...Nxf2  would be a mistake because of  22.Qxc5 }
22. fxe4 d2 23. Rd1 Qg4 { The most beautiful win -   23...Bxg2  is also good. }
24. Rdxd2 Qd1+ { White is about to be mated. } 25. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 26. Rf1 Rxg2+ 27.
Kh1 Rxf1# { There were other ways to win as well, but this is the prettiest! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Four Knights: 4.e3 and 5.Nd5"]
[Black "Chapter 18 Exercise: #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/1bpp1ppp/p2b4/1P3q2/1P1Q1NnP/P3P3/3P1PP1/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

17. Nd3
{ White has just defended from the ...Be5 threat. How would you continue the attack? }
17... Re4
{ Black wants to play ... Nxf2 and ...Bg3 to follow but immediately it doesn't work - please always pay attention to your opponent's defensive resources!   17...Nxf2??  18.Bb2  This intermezzo move changes everything. }
18. Qb2
{ White keeps the queen on the 2nd rank so that after ...Nxf2 and ...Bg3 White can play d3. }
18... Be5 19. Qa2
{ The most stubborn response, still keeping the queen on the 2nd rank. How can you get to the f2 square?   19.Qc2  After this move White would go down in flames.  19...Nxf2!  20.Nxf2  Rxe3+!  21.Kd1  Bf3+!  White collapses. }
19... Rd4
{ Remove the defender! If honestly, this is one of the most beautiful moves I've seen recently - Black sacrifices a whole rook just to get to the f2 pawn. }
20. exd4 Bxd4 { Black's attack is too strong for White to survive. } 21. Bb2
Re8+ 22. Kd1 Bd5 { Total domination of Black's pieces! } 23. Qb1 Nxf2+ 24. Nxf2
{ 24.Kc2  This would be a little more stubborn but Black wins anyway.  24...Bxb2  25.Kxb2  Nxh1  Black has won back all of the sacrificed material. The shattered pawn structure and the exposed white king should decide the game in favor of Black. }
24... Bb3+ 25. Kc1 Re1+ { Black delivers a mate in the next move. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.bxc3"]
[Black "6.dxc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2
{ Currently this is the most popular continuation at White's disposal which I decided to split into two chapters. White here has three strategic goals:   1@@EndBracket@@ Keep the e4 square under control so that Black can't play the immediate ...e4 and push White's kingside knight to an awkward square.   2@@EndBracket@@ Now that Black has the queenside knight placed on c6, White threatens to play Nd5 so that trade is not in Black's interest as the e5 pawn falls, plus Black doesn't have the typical ...e4 counterstrike, as seen in the previous chapter.   3@@EndBracket@@ Besides, White is threatening to play a3 and gain a two bishop advantage for a long-term pressure. }
5... Bxc3
{ The serious alternative is  5...O-O  which allows  6.Nd5  but I like this continuation the most as it fights for the control of the center. The downside of this move is that Black has voluntarily given up the bishop and if Black won't be active, the absence of the dark-squared bishop might feel at some point later. White here has two major choices. }
6. dxc3
{ Pretty much nobody plays like that. Strategically wise this would be interesting if only White could manage to play e4 next and open the dark-squared bishop, but that's not going to happen. }
6... e4
{ Of course - you should already be familiar with the motif of fighting for a space advantage. The text move also makes a nice potential weakness on d3. }
7. Nd4 Ne5
{ Black correctly declines the knight trade as the black knight controls the d3 square. No matter what White will do, the e4 pawn won't move while the white knight on d4 won't hold for long and in fact, will become useless. }
8. b3 d6 9. Qd2
{ In the sample game Black decided to play a little flashy and walk with the king but to be honest, that's not even necessary and Black can start with  9...a6  first. }
9... c5 10. Nb5 Ke7
{ Even though Black can't castle anymore, the black king on e7 feels pretty safe. }
11. h3 Bf5 12. Bb2 a6 { Black pushes away the white knight. } 13. Na3 h5 14.
O-O-O h4
{ Black has a considerable space advantage in Brodowski,P @@StartBracket@@2425@@EndBracket@@ -Matlakov,M @@StartBracket@@2695@@EndBracket@@ European Rapid Championship 2014, and none of White's pieces have any active prospects. The pawn on d6 can be easily defended and Black can focus either at the queenside or jump with the knight to d3 at the right time. }
