[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.bxc3"]
[Black "7.Be2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2
{ Currently this is the most popular continuation at White's disposal which I decided to split into two chapters. White here has three strategic goals:   1@@EndBracket@@ Keep the e4 square under control so that Black can't play the immediate ...e4 and push White's kingside knight to an awkward square.   2@@EndBracket@@ Now that Black has the queenside knight placed on c6, White threatens to play Nd5 so that trade is not in Black's interest as the e5 pawn falls, plus Black doesn't have the typical ...e4 counterstrike, as seen in the previous chapter.   3@@EndBracket@@ Besides, White is threatening to play a3 and gain a two bishop advantage for a long-term pressure. }
5... Bxc3
{ The serious alternative is  5...O-O  which allows  6.Nd5  but I like this continuation the most as it fights for the control of the center. The downside of this move is that Black has voluntarily given up the bishop and if Black won't be active, the absence of the dark-squared bishop might feel at some point later. White here has two major choices. }
6. bxc3
{ Taking with the b-pawn is a very interesting strategic approach. White now has a mass of pawns in the center that will be backed by two bishops - that's a powerful concept, which is quite familiar in Nimzo Indian variations. }
6... O-O
{ Or  6...d6  first but I like the text move first as Black is immediately considering to play ...e4, followed by ...Re8 and ...Ne5. Now White is at even more crossroads - both major lines start with  7.e4  and then choose where to develop the light-squared bishop, but there are two lesser popular alternatives as well. }
7. Be2
{ This move normally should transpose to one of the previously covered lines. With the white king in the center, playing the immediate   7...e4  leads to a double-edged position after  8.Nd4  Ne5  9.f4  and if Black would consider taking on f3, recapture with the g-pawn and organize an offensive at the g-file. If the knight would retreat to g6, White could storm forward with the pawns. }
7... d6
{ Black is consistent with the plan - now   8.e4  or  8.d3  transposes to other lines with a different order of the moves. }
8. O-O
{ This is a risky strategic decision - now the ...e4 thrust is particularly strong. }
8... e4 9. Ne1
{ Or   9.Nd4  Ne5  10.f4  Ng6  and White can't launch all of the kingside pawns as their king is residing there! Black will push away the knight from d4 with ...c5. }
9... Bf5
{ Now we're following a game by the former world champion Vassily Smyslov, who showed a perfect understanding of how to treat this position. }
10. Qb2 b6 11. f3
{ White manages to remove the splinter from the center which cripples his pawn structure but Black has perfectly placed pieces to meet it. }
11... Qd7 12. fxe4 Nxe4
{ The black knight will be rerouted to c5, the light-squared bishop to g6 and Black is seriously pressuring the most important squares at the center. }
13. d3 Nc5 14. Rf4 Bg6 15. Qd2 Rae8
{ White lacks an active plan while Black has easy targets. White's dark-squared bishop still hasn't found a way to join this game. }
16. Nc2 Ne6 17. Rf1 f5
{ Black was better in Suba,M @@StartBracket@@2500@@EndBracket@@ -Smyslov,V @@StartBracket@@2565@@EndBracket@@ Las Palmas Interzonal 1982, and could either pressure those weak white pawns at the center or prepare a kingside attack. }
