{ White would like to fight for a strong pawn center with d4 but to do it, Be2 is necessary as the immediate  8.d4  is bad due to the simple  8...exd4  and ...Nxe4 next. Black should be seeking ways to organize a counterplay at the kingside. }
8... Nh5
{ Black is threatening to play both ...f5 and ...Nf4 which should be good enough to claim a good game. }
9. d4
{ The alternatives don't look dangerous as Black will immediately push forward the f-pawn. As a side note, White can't win a pawn with  9.Nxe5  because after  9...Nxe5  10.Bxh5  Black has a very strong  10...Qg5  and White will suffer big material losses. For example,  11.Bf3  Nxf3+  12.gxf3  Qg2  and ...Bh3 next. }
9... Qf6
{ Black increases the grip over the center and is preparing the ...Nf4 jump so that it's possible to recapture with the queen and not give up the center. }
10. g3
{ White stops the black knight from reaching the f4 square but at a price. }
10... exd4 11. Nxd4
{ The most precise order of the moves as after  11.cxd4  Black doesn't have to take on d4 @@StartBracket@@but he can, for the sake of simplicity@@EndBracket@@ and can continue with the more aggressive  11...Bg4  12.Qd3  Rae8  and strong pressure against White's center. For example,  13.h3  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  g6!  with a great dynamic game for Black and some immediate ...Nxd4 or ...Nb4 threats. }
11... Nxd4 12. cxd4 Qxd4
{ Since the white rook is under attack, White doesn't have time to grab the black knight on h5. }
13. Bb2 Qc5
{ The forced moves have ended - White has sacrificed a pawn and has two bishops but a pawn is a pawn! Needless to say, Black has no weaknesses in the position which could arise when Black will play ...Nf6, but this will cost White the bishop pair. }
14. O-O
{ This continuation has been tested at the correspondence level already 3 times - White is going for long-term compensation for the missing pawn. }
14... Nf6 15. Bxf6
{ There's nothing better, otherwise Black can consider to reroute the knight to d7 and close the a1-h8 diagonal with ...f6. }
15... gxf6
{ The critical position - I can't imagine that White could cause Black any serious problems here as there are not so many pieces left and White could use a knight. White has compensation for the pawn, but not more. At the right moment, Black shouldn't mind giving it back to simplify the defense. All 3 games ended with a draw, each with a different scenario. Let's follow one of them. }
16. Rfd1 Qe5 17. Rac1 Re8 18. Bf3 Be6
{ Black has finished the development and White can't crash through. } 19. Rb1
Rab8 20. Rb5 c5
{ Black was alright to give away the pawn on d6 in Zolochevsky,V @@StartBracket@@2351@@EndBracket@@-Zubov,Y @@StartBracket@@2357@@EndBracket@@ EU-ch 2018 sf09 email 2018, while also fixing a potential weakness on c4. At the right time, Black might consider trading some pawns with ...f5 but this should be done with great care. Don't miss White's f4. }
