1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2
{ Currently this is the most popular continuation at White's disposal which I decided to split into two chapters. White here has three strategic goals:   1@@EndBracket@@ Keep the e4 square under control so that Black can't play the immediate ...e4 and push White's kingside knight to an awkward square.   2@@EndBracket@@ Now that Black has the queenside knight placed on c6, White threatens to play Nd5 so that trade is not in Black's interest as the e5 pawn falls, plus Black doesn't have the typical ...e4 counterstrike, as seen in the previous chapter.   3@@EndBracket@@ Besides, White is threatening to play a3 and gain a two bishop advantage for a long-term pressure. }
5... Bxc3
{ The serious alternative is  5...O-O  which allows  6.Nd5  but I like this continuation the most as it fights for the control of the center. The downside of this move is that Black has voluntarily given up the bishop and if Black won't be active, the absence of the dark-squared bishop might feel at some point later. White here has two major choices. }
6. bxc3
{ Taking with the b-pawn is a very interesting strategic approach. White now has a mass of pawns in the center that will be backed by two bishops - that's a powerful concept, which is quite familiar in Nimzo Indian variations. }
6... O-O
{ Or  6...d6  first but I like the text move first as Black is immediately considering to play ...e4, followed by ...Re8 and ...Ne5. Now White is at even more crossroads - both major lines start with  7.e4  and then choose where to develop the light-squared bishop, but there are two lesser popular alternatives as well. }
7. e4
{ The main move in the position - White fixes the center and is fighting for a space advantage. }
7... d6
{ The last big choice for White - where to position the light-squared bishop. The most obvious option is on e2, but recently quite popular has to fianchetto on g2. }
8. Be2
{ White would like to fight for a strong pawn center with d4 but to do it, Be2 is necessary as the immediate  8.d4  is bad due to the simple  8...exd4  and ...Nxe4 next. Black should be seeking ways to organize a counterplay at the kingside. }
8... Nh5
{ Black is threatening to play both ...f5 and ...Nf4 which should be good enough to claim a good game. }
9. d4
{ The alternatives don't look dangerous as Black will immediately push forward the f-pawn. As a side note, White can't win a pawn with  9.Nxe5  because after  9...Nxe5  10.Bxh5  Black has a very strong  10...Qg5  and White will suffer big material losses. For example,  11.Bf3  Nxf3+  12.gxf3  Qg2  and ...Bh3 next. }
9... Qf6
{ Black increases the grip over the center and is preparing the ...Nf4 jump so that it's possible to recapture with the queen and not give up the center. }
10. d5
{ The way I see it, this somewhat illogical move which weakens the c5 square is the most critical approach - White is going for a long-term pressure at the kingside. The immediate  10.Bg5  looks tempting but after  10...Qg6  White's center is shaky and after  11.Be3  Nf6  something is about to fall. }
10... Nb8
{ Here unlike some of the correspondence players think, I believe that from a practical point of view this retreat is a safer choice. }
11. g3
{ White stops Black from playing ...Nf4 but an important moment is invisibly happening at the queenside. }
11... Na6
{ This stops any positional pawn sacrifice ideas with c5 push, followed by c4 and Bb2,  strongly pressuring the e5 pawn with a later f4. This would have been the case, had Black played the more tempting @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppp2ppp/2np1q2/3Pp2n/2P1P3/2P2N2/P1Q1BPPP/R1B1K2R b KQ - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Na5  Then after  11.g3  b6  White is in time to play  12.c5!?  dxc5  13.c4  and I don't like how it looks in the long run. Black has a weak pawn on e5, the knight on h5 still feels weird. If White's f4 crashed through, Black would find himself in a very difficult situation. }
12. Be3
{ Tonne,G @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@-Ivanov,H @@StartBracket@@2192@@EndBracket@@ BdF 60 jub Worldopen EM05 email 2007, now White no longer is threatening with c5 because this would force White to trade off the dark-squared bishop. Instead White is focusing on a strong pull at the kingside. }
12... Bg4
{ I think it makes perfect sense to trade off a piece, especially if in a slightly cramped position. Black will be basing his counterplay at the queenside with a prepared ...c6. }
13. Nh4
{ White might consider keeping the light-squared bishop on the board with  13.Qd1  -  then after  13...Qe7  14.h3  Black shouldn't mind trading off the bishop with  14...Bxf3  15.Bxf3  Nf6  and focus on a counterplay at the queenside. Either way, the position is pretty closed, and Black doesn't have any weaknesses at the kingside. That being said, don't make one! }
13... Bxe2 14. Qxe2 g6
{ Now the forced moves are over and White is concentrating on an attack at the kingside. Black should be doing the same at the queenside. }
15. Ng2 b6
{ First, before seeking some action, it's a good idea to bring all pieces into play. The knight on c5 might be useful if White would consider rushing with g4 and Black wants to recapture on c5 with the b-pawn. Then ...Nf4 will force to trade off the knights, giving the white bishop a strong outpost on d4, which should be quickly countered by Black's queenside knight with ...Nd7-e5. This is also the reason why the black queen should remain on f6 for the time being. }
16. f3 Nc5
{ I'd like to illustrate the most principled scenario - White castles long to attack at the kingside. }
17. O-O-O Rac8
{ Black prepares to play ...c6 but be ready that White might trade on c5 and reroute the knight to e3-d5. Overall it's not a big deal, just a little annoyance - the knight can always be traded off with ...Nf6. It's important to remember - always think about where are your active countermeasures. Playing an equal position with no counterplay is a risky strategical choice. }
18. Kb1 { 18.Kb2  leads to some repetition after  18...Na4+  19.Kb3  Nc5+ }
18... Na4
{ Black first removes White the option to take on c5 to occupy the d5 square. }
19. Rc1 c6
{ Black has managed to organize a sufficient counter-attack at the queenside while White's big attack at the kingside hasn't even started yet. }
