13... axb5 14. Nh4
{ White relies on some attacking chances at the kingside but the queenside is vulnerable. If Black will manage to keep the head cool and find the right maneuvers, he will be rewarded with a better position as White's weaknesses are not going anywhere and they're here to stay. }
14... h6
{ A good prophylactic move - Black is preparing a potential rook + queen battery at the queenside and makes sure that White doesn't have access to Bg5. Let me present to you two games from correspondence chess where Black managed to completely outplay White. }
15. Be3
{ White might postpone the decision to push the f-pawn and first protect the weakness on a2 and develop the remaining of the pieces. This allows Black to start to execute the previously mentioned plan. }
15... Nc6 16. Rb2
{ I should probably mention that the pawn on b5 is taboo due to ...Nd4. } 16...
Ra6 17. h3
{ Since the a-pawn has already been well defended, here Black correctly changed the course of the game. }
17... Ne7
{ Black mobilizes his pieces and is ready to strike at the center with either ...c5 or ...d5. Every single White's action might cause more weaknesses. }
18. Rd1
{ The tempting  18.f4  now actually would be a positional mistake because of  18...exf4  19.gxf4  c5  and White's center is very vulnerable and has become an easy target with a timely executed ...c4.   In the meantime  18.d4  would just weaken the c4 square and Black could just march back with  18...Nc6  Are you familiar with the concept of cat and mouse? }
18... Qc8 19. g4 d5
{ Finally Black decided to act first and strike at the center, creating some more weaknesses in White's camp. }
20. Bc5 Qd8
{ The game Loeschnauer, R @@StartBracket@@2458@@EndBracket@@-Prozorovsky, V @@StartBracket@@2415@@EndBracket@@ W-ch42 sf01 email 2018 continued with  21.Re1  h5  22.f3  g5!  23.Nf5  Ng6  ,  Black firmly controlling the most critical squares of the game. }
