[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.bxc3"]
[Black "7.e4 and 8.g3: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2
{ Currently this is the most popular continuation at White's disposal which I decided to split into two chapters. White here has three strategic goals:   1@@EndBracket@@ Keep the e4 square under control so that Black can't play the immediate ...e4 and push White's kingside knight to an awkward square.   2@@EndBracket@@ Now that Black has the queenside knight placed on c6, White threatens to play Nd5 so that trade is not in Black's interest as the e5 pawn falls, plus Black doesn't have the typical ...e4 counterstrike, as seen in the previous chapter.   3@@EndBracket@@ Besides, White is threatening to play a3 and gain a two bishop advantage for a long-term pressure. }
5... Bxc3
{ The serious alternative is  5...O-O  which allows  6.Nd5  but I like this continuation the most as it fights for the control of the center. The downside of this move is that Black has voluntarily given up the bishop and if Black won't be active, the absence of the dark-squared bishop might feel at some point later. White here has two major choices. }
6. bxc3
{ Taking with the b-pawn is a very interesting strategic approach. White now has a mass of pawns in the center that will be backed by two bishops - that's a powerful concept, which is quite familiar in Nimzo Indian variations. }
6... O-O
{ Or  6...d6  first but I like the text move first as Black is immediately considering to play ...e4, followed by ...Re8 and ...Ne5. Now White is at even more crossroads - both major lines start with  7.e4  and then choose where to develop the light-squared bishop, but there are two lesser popular alternatives as well. }
7. e4
{ The main move in the position - White fixes the center and is fighting for a space advantage. }
7... d6
{ The last big choice for White - where to position the light-squared bishop. The most obvious option is on e2, but recently quite popular has to fianchetto on g2. }
8. g3
{ This tricky move comes with an idea not only to fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2 but also stop Black's counterplay of ...f5 with Nh4. The pawn on g3 now protects the h4 square against a sudden attack. }
8... a6
{ A wonderful concept - since White's light-squared bishop is about to land on g2, it's high time to remind that Black has some ideas at the queenside. White has a choice - either stop it or ignore it. }
9. Rb1
{ This is the most tested continuation at the correspondence chess which in over-the-board chess probably will result in worse positions for White, at least most of the time. }
9... Na5
{ A cunning move - Black not only slows down White's ambition to fianchetto the light-squared bishop but also prepares the b-pawn's push and the black knight on a5 will be assisting the charge with a great effect. }
10. d3
{ To position the light-squared bishop on g2, the white pawn on c4 needs protection. }
10... Bd7
{ The b-pawn push already is inevitable as after White's  10.a4  Black can respond with the cool  10...Qe8  ,  targeting it and after  11.Ra1  go for it. }
11. Bg2 b5 12. O-O
{ Here lies White's idea - Black is offered to grab the pawn so that after  12...bxc4  13.d4  White has a strong pawn center while the black knight is misplaced on a5. }
12... Re8
{ Black renews the threat to take on c4 so that now after ...bxc4 White can't play d4 because Black would just take on d4 and White can't recapture with the pawn as e4 is hanging. Also the rook on e8 protects the e5 square so that White might not consider walking past the b-pawn with c5. }
13. cxb5
{ If White has some ambitions at the kingside, this move has to be played, otherwise there might be no potential kingside attack. The drawback of the plan is quite obvious - the weak pawn on a2. }
13... axb5 14. Nh4
{ White relies on some attacking chances at the kingside but the queenside is vulnerable. If Black will manage to keep the head cool and find the right maneuvers, he will be rewarded with a better position as White's weaknesses are not going anywhere and they're here to stay. }
14... h6
{ A good prophylactic move - Black is preparing a potential rook + queen battery at the queenside and makes sure that White doesn't have access to Bg5. Let me present to you two games from correspondence chess where Black managed to completely outplay White. }
15. f4 { The obvious choice - White is preparing an assault at the kingside. }
15... Ra6
{ This is a very cool move - nothing is happening at the kingside, at least not just yet. The rook on a6 not only extra protects the pawn on d6 for an imminent c-pawn push but also as far as the knight on f6 so that White doesn't have access to some later Bxh6 ideas, winning a pawn. Suninen,J @@StartBracket@@2360@@EndBracket@@-Kazantsev,R @@StartBracket@@2427@@EndBracket@@ FIN jub50 final email 2016. Black won a positional masterpiece and you can find the full game annotation in the Model games. }
