1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2
{ Currently this is the most popular continuation at White's disposal which I decided to split into two chapters. White here has three strategic goals:   1@@EndBracket@@ Keep the e4 square under control so that Black can't play the immediate ...e4 and push White's kingside knight to an awkward square.   2@@EndBracket@@ Now that Black has the queenside knight placed on c6, White threatens to play Nd5 so that trade is not in Black's interest as the e5 pawn falls, plus Black doesn't have the typical ...e4 counterstrike, as seen in the previous chapter.   3@@EndBracket@@ Besides, White is threatening to play a3 and gain a two bishop advantage for a long-term pressure. }
5... Bxc3
{ The serious alternative is  5...O-O  which allows  6.Nd5  but I like this continuation the most as it fights for the control of the center. The downside of this move is that Black has voluntarily given up the bishop and if Black won't be active, the absence of the dark-squared bishop might feel at some point later. White here has two major choices. }
6. bxc3
{ Taking with the b-pawn is a very interesting strategic approach. White now has a mass of pawns in the center that will be backed by two bishops - that's a powerful concept, which is quite familiar in Nimzo Indian variations. }
6... O-O
{ Or  6...d6  first but I like the text move first as Black is immediately considering to play ...e4, followed by ...Re8 and ...Ne5. Now White is at even more crossroads - both major lines start with  7.e4  and then choose where to develop the light-squared bishop, but there are two lesser popular alternatives as well. }
7. e4
{ The main move in the position - White fixes the center and is fighting for a space advantage. }
7... d6
{ The last big choice for White - where to position the light-squared bishop. The most obvious option is on e2, but recently quite popular has to fianchetto on g2. }
8. g3
{ This tricky move comes with an idea not only to fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2 but also stop Black's counterplay of ...f5 with Nh4. The pawn on g3 now protects the h4 square against a sudden attack. }
8... a6
{ A wonderful concept - since White's light-squared bishop is about to land on g2, it's high time to remind that Black has some ideas at the queenside. White has a choice - either stop it or ignore it. }
9. a4
{ Probably the most logical response that everyone could think of - White stops the traditional Black's b-pawn advancement to b5 for good. However, there's a little problem with the plan - this makes the a4 pawn a target. }
9... Nd7
{ Black fights on two fronts at the same time - a counterplay at the queenside and bothering White with the ...f5 threat. }
10. Be2
{ White could be very smart and mix two ideas in one - play g3 to have access for Nh4 to stop the f-pawn push and position the light-squared bishop on e2 to stop Black's b-pawn push. If your opponent is doing that, just stand up and applaud for his determination! }
10... Qe7
{ This is a necessary move before playing ...Nc5, otherwise d4 will become a problem. Now Black keeps a watch over the e4 pawn, just in case. }
11. O-O Nc5 { Black is back to the f-pawn push idea. } 12. Nh4 Na5 13. Ba3 Bh3
14. Rfe1 Rae8
{ There's a lot of maneuvering involved and while Black can't immediately strike either at the queenside or the kingside, neither can White. }
15. Bb4 b6 16. d4
{ In the sample game, White finally gathered the courage and decided to push forward the d-pawn. }
16... exd4 17. cxd4 Nxe4 18. Bf3 f5
{ Andersson,M @@StartBracket@@2404@@EndBracket@@-Wagner,R @@StartBracket@@2450@@EndBracket@@ ICCF GMN/057 email 2017, eventually White won the pawn back and the game was drawn. }
