8... a6
{ A wonderful concept - since White's light-squared bishop is about to land on g2, it's high time to remind that Black has some ideas at the queenside. White has a choice - either stop it or ignore it. }
9. a4
{ Probably the most logical response that everyone could think of - White stops the traditional Black's b-pawn advancement to b5 for good. However, there's a little problem with the plan - this makes the a4 pawn a target. }
9... Nd7
{ Black fights on two fronts at the same time - a counterplay at the queenside and bothering White with the ...f5 threat. }
10. Nh4
{ Or  10.d3  Nc5  and then  11.Nh4  ,  it's the same - this is the main move in the position. For obvious reasons White is not interested to allow Black to carry out the f-pawn push which should give Black a great game - that's why White played g3 earlier to have the Nh4 resource right now. }
10... Nc5 11. d3
{ 11.Bg2  would just transpose to the previously covered bad line for White, which starts with  11...Na5  The text move is necessary. }
11... Na5
{ Black is threatening to win the pawn on a4 with ...Bd7 and ...Qe8. } 12. Be3
Bd7
{ Black shouldn't mind if White would take the knight on c5 - this immediately gives Black an excellent position and the positional threat of ...b5 remains. }
13. Be2 Qe8
{ Now White has to make a decision - take the knight on c5 and part of the two bishop advantage, protect the a4 pawn with Bd1 or sacrifice it for unclear compensation. }
14. O-O Bxa4
{ Black can snatch the pawn but this is not mandatory - Black can keep the option hanging like the sword of Damocles and protect the knight on a5 with ... b6 first so that the pawn grab and retreat can be done in one go. I'd assume that White would have to revisit either Bxc5 or Bd1 ideas and forget about the gambit. }
15. Qa2 b5
{ Perhaps White has some compensation here in terms of a center and a potential kingside attack but Black should feel quite comfortable with the extra pawn. }
