14. Bd1
{ A very natural response - White doesn't want to trade the dark-squared bishop, nor give up the pawn on a4. Diermair,A @@StartBracket@@2501@@EndBracket@@-Esipenko,A @@StartBracket@@2589@@EndBracket@@ Barcelona Sants open 2018. }
14... b5 { Black should open the queenside to generate enough counterplay. }
15. axb5 axb5 16. cxb5 Bxb5 17. Bxc5
{ This seems to be necessary as  17.Be2  will run into  17...Nc4!  18.Rxa8  Nxe3!  intermezzo and Black is a lot better,   while  17.c4  Bd7  and White will experience some serious issues with the d4 square that Black can exploit with ...Nc6. }
17... dxc5 { Black is threatening to push forward the c-pawn. } 18. O-O c4 19.
Be2
{ The safe move -  19.d4  is a little risky for White as after  19...exd4  20.cxd4  Nb3  Black does have the passed pawn and good counterplay against White's center. }
19... Rd8
{ The most accurate - the trade on c4 is not going anywhere and then there's the ...Nb3 and ...Ba4 threat, should a white rook land on d1. }
20. dxc4 Nxc4 21. Rfd1 Qe6
{ Both sides have no weaknesses thus the position is equal. } *

