1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. a3
{ This is a signal that White is about to push forward the d-pawn and with the last move White just in case defends the b4 square. Still, it's a little loss of time which Black should try to take an advantage of immediately. }
7... d5 8. cxd5
{ This pawn trade will just transpose to a somewhat unfavorable Scheveningen's structure for White, which is covered in this chapter. Black's plan remains the same - reroute the knight to b6 and pressure the white pawn on d3. }
8... Nxd5 9. Qb3
{ Otherwise ...e4 could become a big problem as the white knight doesn't have any good squares to retreat. }
9... Nb6
{ It's not clear for what purpose White has included a3 if the queen is blocking the b-pawn from advancing. }
10. d3 Bf5
{ Or  10...Bg4  which with the current order of the moves is not the most active but it should transpose to some of the covered lines later in this chapter. Black has the luxury to consider castling long. }
