{ Normally, if nothing dramatic happens, Black wants to take on d5 with the rook and place the light-squared bishop on f5. }
12. Be2
{ White continues a normal development and keepsin the mind the perfect setup with f3-e4. Black's priority remains the same - trade-off the light-squared bishops. }
12... Rxd5 13. Qh4
{ The most reasonable retreat - White pins the black knight on f6 with a secret offer to trade queens at some point later, should an opportunity arise. I'll just mention that after  13.Qf4  Black's approach remains the same -  13...Bf5  14.O-O  and perhaps the only nuance here is that including  14...a5  first before trading the bishops on d3 is a good idea as the trade already is inevitable but fighting for some extra space advantage is a nice bonus. }
13... Bf5 { Black immediately accomplishes the goal to trade the bishops. } 14.
Bf3
{ This was played in Hansen, T @@StartBracket@@2209@@EndBracket@@-Brynell, S @@StartBracket@@2489@@EndBracket@@ Gausdal Classics GM 2001 and it's a mistake. Here instead of the automatic  14....Be4  @@StartBracket@@which is still fine, according to the plan@@EndBracket@@ Black could have taken over the initiative. }
14... Rd6 15. O-O
{ Taking the pawn is a suicide -  15.Bxb7  Rb8  16.Bf3  Bd3  and the white king remains in the center under a heavy attack. }
15... Rad8
{ White still has not finished the development, Black is very active and can choose the best moment when @@StartBracket@@and if@@EndBracket@@ to trade the bishops. Again, taking the pawn on b7 is taboo, this time because of ...Bd3 and ...c6, trapping it. }
