[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "7.a3: #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. a3
{ This is a signal that White is about to push forward the d-pawn and with the last move White just in case defends the b4 square. Still, it's a little loss of time which Black should try to take an advantage of immediately. }
7... d5 8. d4 { White is opening the position but this means a lot of trades. }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 { These trades are forced. } 10... O-O
{ I treat this move to be more accurate than the more popular  10...c5  which can be a little tricky. Black is not dismissing the idea of playing ...c5 later but continuing the development should be a priority. Black should be looking for ways to trade the light-squared bishops to diminish the power of the two bishops' advantage. Now White has some choices here. }
11. c5
{ The only drawback of Black castling early and not including ...c5 is this White's option to close the position with c5 and White's plan to position the dark-squared bishop on the a1-h8 diagonal  @@StartBracket@@ideally on d4@@EndBracket@@, taking control of the most important central squares with f3. Black should be active. }
11... a5
{ The most energetic move in the position - Black makes sure that White can't strengthen the c5 pawn with b4 without opening the position and is about to target the c5 pawn with either ...Ne4 or ...b6, followed by cxb6 c5 Black is happy to trade one pair of bishops to eliminate the long-term pressure of two bishops. }
12. b3
{ This is a tricky move - White's idea is to meet  12...Ne4  with  13.Bb2  and since the mate is hanging on g7, Black doesn't have time to take the c5 pawn. This move, however, seriously weakens the b3 pawn. }
12... b6 { The best response - Black temporarily sacrifices a pawn. } 13. c6
{ This was played in Koch,J @@StartBracket@@2454@@EndBracket@@ -Kosteniuk,A @@StartBracket@@2555@@EndBracket@@ French Team Championships Top 12 2018 - it is a decent attempt to complicate things. }
13... Qc5 14. Qxc5 bxc5
{ White is about to experience the downside of the weak pawn on b3 - Black plans to either immediately pressure the b-pawn with ...Rb8 or play ...Ba6 and ... Rfb8. }
15. a4
{ 15.Bb2  looks rather risky for White as Black can continue with  15...Rb8  16.Bc3  Rxb3  17.Bxa5  Be6  and Black appears to be calling the shots here. }
15... Ba6 16. Bb2 Rfb8
{ Now after some trades we should reach an equal endgame. } 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18.
O-O-O Rxb3
{ There's no need to rush with the bishop trade - allow White to take on a6 himself, gifting Black an important tempo to target the c6 pawn. The game might continue with  19.Rxd5  Ra3  20.Kb2  Rxa4  and it's White who needs to be accurate here. }
