{ White's trick lies in the following line -  17...Rxb3  18.Bxf6  and now the obvious  18...Qxf6  loses to a dagger stab  19.Qa4  ,  attacking both rook on b3 and the mate threat on e8!  18...gxf6  would give White some sort of a long-term compensation due to the exposed king and the ruined pawn structure.   Also  17...c4  is a double-edged choice as after  18.Bd4  Rxb3  19.Bc2  White has some pretty powerful bishops and the extra pawn doesn't feel to be so significant. }
17... Ba6 18. Bxa6 Raxa6
{ The position eventually should simplify to an equal rook endgame. } *

