1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. a3
{ This is a signal that White is about to push forward the d-pawn and with the last move White just in case defends the b4 square. Still, it's a little loss of time which Black should try to take an advantage of immediately. }
7... d5 8. d4 { White is opening the position but this means a lot of trades. }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 { These trades are forced. } 10... O-O
{ I treat this move to be more accurate than the more popular  10...c5  which can be a little tricky. Black is not dismissing the idea of playing ...c5 later but continuing the development should be a priority. Black should be looking for ways to trade the light-squared bishops to diminish the power of the two bishops' advantage. Now White has some choices here. }
11. Bd2
{ White is threatening to play Bb4 and most likely close the center with c5, which is somewhat popular at the correspondence level. }
11... Rd8 12. Bb4
{ If White wants to close the position, this move is necessary - the immediate  12.c5  is not so good due to  12...Ne4  and not only Black is targeting the pawn on c5, but there's also the ...Qh4 threat. }
12... Qe8 13. c5
{ Now it's critical to trade off one of White's bishops as quickly as possible, otherwise White will play Bd3, Bc3, f3 and completely control the central squares. }
13... Ne4
{ Now ...a5 is inevitable and depending on how White will respond, ...Bf5 also might become an option. Here  14.f3  is not so good as Black can proceed with  14...a5!  15.fxe4  dxe4  first and only then capture the bishop on b4. }
14. Bd3
{ Here the bishop is positioned more active but if White would consider  14.Be2  ,  this would give Black an extra option with  14...a5  15.Bc3  Qf8!  and White is starting to experience some problems with the c5 pawn, as seen in Latas,P  @@StartBracket@@2055@@EndBracket@@-Emelyanov,M @@StartBracket@@2411@@EndBracket@@ EU-chT7 qual 3-07 email. }
14... Bf5
{ I think this is more accurate than the tempting  14...a5  15.Bc3  Nxc3  16.bxc3  ,  where White is enjoying a little plus and threatening with an interesting plan of pushing h4-h5 and some annoying pressure at the b1-h7 diagonal. }
15. O-O Bg6
{ Black is threatening to play either ...a5 and trade-off both bishops, or reroute the knight to e6, as seen in one correspondence game. }
16. Rfc1 Ng5
{ Black trades the light-squared bishops and keeps the knight on the board. }
17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Bc3 Ne6 19. Qd1 c6
{ Due to the flexible knight Black already looked better in Teichmann, C @@StartBracket@@2361@@EndBracket@@ -Scherbakov, Y @@StartBracket@@2286@@EndBracket@@ EU-ch 2016 sf07 email. The game continued with  20.b4  f6  21.Rab1  a6  22.Qc2  g5  and the black knight was rerouted to c7 but the queen - to e4. }
