[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "7.b3: #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. b3
{ White might want to consider placing the dark-squared bishop on b2 and pressure Black's e5 pawn early on. This also is an interesting way to provoke a confrontation in the center with ...d5,  which White usually meets with d4. White would have played  7.b4  immediately, if not for  7...Qxb4  and White doesn't have time to recapture the pawn on e5 due to the fork on c2. }
7... d5 8. cxd5
{ Some solid GMs have played this but mostly at accelerated time controls which makes me think that they improvized at the board. }
8... Nxd5 9. Qb2
{ The whole purpose of the idea is to pressure the black pawn on e5 but Black has a variety of great responses here, starting with castling short - even the modest 9...a6  looks just good. }
9... Bg4 { A strong novelty. } 10. Bb5 Bxf3 11. gxf3 O-O-O
{ White's entire setup doesn't make any sense - Black is threatening with the immediate ...Ndb4 to occupy the d3 square. }
12. Bxc6
{ This is sort of forced as  12.a3  Rd6  White has nothing to show for the multiple weaknesses and it's not clear where the white king is going to hide. }
12... bxc6 13. Qc2
{ White's only chance is to try to hold the center and persuade Black to trade queens. Black's doubled c-pawns play no role as White can't even pressure them or exploit the weakened black king.  13.Qa3  would be met by the simple  13...Nb4 }
13... Qf6 14. Qe4
{ Just when White might start to get some hopes to survive this as there's no clear route for the black knight to the d3 square... }
14... Nf4 { The horse finds it anyway! } 15. d4
{ Probably the only practical chance as  15.exf4  exf4  looks terrible - the white rook is hanging on a1 and Black is threatening with ...Rae8. White might try to hold everything together with  16.Qb1  but after  16...Rhe8+  the white king is left unguarded against all heavy Black's pieces. After  17.Kd1  the position would quickly collapse with  17...Qc3  and threat to take on f3,   but after  17.Kf1  the simplest way to start the decisive attack probably  is  17...Qe5  with a threat to play ...Qe2 and ...Rd3. }
15... Rhe8
{ Now Black has to find a couple of only moves to secure a large advantage but they are easy to find. }
16. Kf1 Qe6 17. h4
{ 17.exf4  Qh3+  and ...exd4 finishes the game immediately. } 17... f5 18. Qc2
{ The pawn on e5 can't be taken due to the back rank mate. } 18... Nd5
{ From here the game is less forced but it's clear that Black is storming the kingside. }
19. dxe5 Qxe5 20. Bb2 { This allows a yet another spectacular shot. } 20...
Qxe3
{ After  21.Qxf5+  Kb7  the fork is still alive but after  22.Qxd5  Qe2+  intermezzo check decides everything. }
