{ White might want to consider placing the dark-squared bishop on b2 and pressure Black's e5 pawn early on. This also is an interesting way to provoke a confrontation in the center with ...d5,  which White usually meets with d4. White would have played  7.b4  immediately, if not for  7...Qxb4  and White doesn't have time to recapture the pawn on e5 due to the fork on c2. }
7... d5 8. d4
{ The point - White intends to open the position and increase the power of the bishops and this motif is both explored after  (7.a3 and 7.Be2.) }
8... Bg4
{ I love this move as it directly resembles the mainline! Black offers to play gambit and White's options are limited and it will be walking a tightrope. }
9. Nxe5
{ Strictly speaking, the only move as the alternative looks quite dangerous. }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Ne4 11. Qb2
{ This is the wrong square for the queen in such a dynamic position. } 11...
O-O-O 12. f3
{ Now we're following a high level GM blitz game - here the stunned White quickly blundered away the game but the best defense already was not obvious -  12.c5  Rhe8  13.Be2  Bxe2  14.Qxe2  Qxe5  and probably Black will just collect the pawn on c5. }
12... Bxf3 { Now the threat of ...Qh4+ bags Black some material. } 13. gxf3
Qh4+ 14. Kd1 dxc4+
{ It was possible to take the rook with the fork but this is more powerful. }
15. Kc2
{ White was swiftly mated in a few moves - the rook on h1 doesn't even play a role anymore as there's a bigger prize to hunt. }
15... c3 16. Qa3 Qf2+ 17. Kb1 Nd2+ 18. Bxd2 Rxd2
{ White got quickly checkmated in Sevian,S @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@ -Najer,E @@StartBracket@@2648@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com Titled Tuesday 2020. }
