[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "7.b3: #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. b3
{ White might want to consider placing the dark-squared bishop on b2 and pressure Black's e5 pawn early on. This also is an interesting way to provoke a confrontation in the center with ...d5,  which White usually meets with d4. White would have played  7.b4  immediately, if not for  7...Qxb4  and White doesn't have time to recapture the pawn on e5 due to the fork on c2. }
7... d5 8. d4
{ The point - White intends to open the position and increase the power of the bishops and this motif is both explored after  (7.a3 and 7.Be2.) }
8... Bg4
{ I love this move as it directly resembles the mainline! Black offers to play gambit and White's options are limited and it will be walking a tightrope. }
9. Nxe5
{ Strictly speaking, the only move as the alternative looks quite dangerous. }
9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Ne4 11. Qc2
{ The best move as White should try to close the center with c5. White can't play  11.Qd4  due to  11...c5  and the pawn on d5 is untouchable due to the ...Rd8-d1 threat. }
11... O-O-O
{ If White at any moment will include h3, the black bishop is ready to retreat to h5 and White's kingside has one weakness more, should the white monarch try to hide there. }
12. c5
{ Now Black has a pleasant choice - either press for more with the tricky  12...Kb8  so that after  13.Bb2  Nxc5  Black has won back the sacrificed pawn with a good position @@StartBracket@@after  14.h3  Bh5  there is no Qf5 check!@@EndBracket@@ or go for a spectacular line which normally should end with a draw. }
12... Qxe5 13. Bb2 d4
{ I think that the mood here for White should be pretty low @@StartBracket@@Black is crushing me right after the opening@@EndBracket@@. I'll illustrate to you a couple of mistakes that White could make right here. }
14. exd4
{ Obviously, taking on d4 with the bishop would allow Black to go for the easiest exchange sacrifice of all times and finish off White with ...Re8 but taking on d4 with a pawn opens the position slightly more than it should be and this allows Black some spectacular tricks. }
14... Qf4 15. Bc1 { Very logical, isn't it? } 15... Nd2 { A very pretty move. }
16. Qxd2
{ After  16.Bxd2  Black wins with  16...Rhe8+  17.Be3  Qxd4  and now after  18.Rc1  Qb4+  White gets mated on d1! }
16... Rhe8+ 17. Be2
{ Amazingly, White is still alive but with a much worse position. } 17... Qxd2+
18. Kxd2 Rxe2+ 19. Kc3 Rxf2
{ I'm not a seer but maybe with a very accurate defense White can hold this. }
