{ The point of this intermezzo move is to win a couple of important tempos, eventually rerouting the kingside knight to c5. }
8. Qd3
{ Necessary, otherwise Black will take the pawn on d4 and White can't recapture it due to the potential discovered check at the e-file. }
8... exd4 { Black forces some trades. } 9. Nxd4 Nc5
{ There goes another tempo. } 10. Qd1
{ It pretty much doesn't matter where the white queen will retreat as Black will just take on d4. The only exception is  10.Qe2  - then Black just castle short and keep the idea of ...Nxd4 and ...Nd3+ in the air. }
10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O
{ The first phase of development is over, Black is looking towards a strong grip over the center with ...b6, ... Bb7, probably ...a5, and if necessary, ...d6 and ...f5. It's possible that at the right time the d-pawn push as far as d5 might work so just keep the option in your mind - don't rush with ...d6 just yet as you might use this square for your rook. If possible, Black would like to trade the light-squared bishops and an ambitious player as White would like to keep them. }
12. b3
{ If White wants to get a sharper position, he will have to castle long and take risks. The idea is to fianchetto the bishop on b2, somehow manage to salvage the light-squared bishop and place it on c2 and try to push forward the h-pawn as far as possible. This also puts the white king under harms way at the queenside so the arising position could be very double-edged. }
12... b6 13. Bb2 Ne6
{ Black protects the king against a mate - the knight will go back to  c5  as soon as the development is finished. The immediate  13...f6  or 13...f5 would allow  14.Qd5+  with unclear consequences. }
14. Qc3 { The most sensible move, keeping the battery. } 14... Bb7 15. O-O-O
{ Black needs to be a little careful not to allow White to play Bd3-c2 and f3, otherwise it's a risky position with those powerful bishops sniping at the black king. }
15... f5
{ Black looks like having things under control and the next several moves are easy - ...Nc5, ...Rae8, ...a5, ...d6 and then see what happens. White would love to but can't open files at the kingside so be ready to meet any g4 with ...f4. }
16. Bd3
{ This is an interesting idea to sac the pawn, but Black doesn't have to take it. }
16... Nc5 17. Bc2 Be4
{ Black trades off the light-squared bishops and kills all White's illusions for a big attack at the kingside. }
