{ Necessary, otherwise Black will take the pawn on d4 and White can't recapture it due to the potential discovered check at the e-file. }
8... exd4 { Black forces some trades. } 9. Nxd4 Nc5
{ There goes another tempo. } 10. Qd1
{ It pretty much doesn't matter where the white queen will retreat as Black will just take on d4. The only exception is  10.Qe2  - then Black just castle short and keep the idea of ...Nxd4 and ...Nd3+ in the air. }
10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O
{ The first phase of development is over, Black is looking towards a strong grip over the center with ...b6, ... Bb7, probably ...a5, and if necessary, ...d6 and ...f5. It's possible that at the right time the d-pawn push as far as d5 might work so just keep the option in your mind - don't rush with ...d6 just yet as you might use this square for your rook. If possible, Black would like to trade the light-squared bishops and an ambitious player as White would like to keep them. }
12. b3
{ If White wants to get a sharper position, he will have to castle long and take risks. The idea is to fianchetto the bishop on b2, somehow manage to salvage the light-squared bishop and place it on c2 and try to push forward the h-pawn as far as possible. This also puts the white king under harms way at the queenside so the arising position could be very double-edged. }
12... b6 13. Bb2 Ne6
{ Black protects the king against a mate - the knight will go back to  c5  as soon as the development is finished. The immediate  13...f6  or 13...f5 would allow  14.Qd5+  with unclear consequences. }
14. Qc3 { The most sensible move, keeping the battery. } 14... Bb7 15. O-O-O
{ Black needs to be a little careful not to allow White to play Bd3-c2 and f3, otherwise it's a risky position with those powerful bishops sniping at the black king. }
15... f5
{ Black looks like having things under control and the next several moves are easy - ...Nc5, ...Rae8, ...a5, ...d6 and then see what happens. White would love to but can't open files at the kingside so be ready to meet any g4 with ...f4. }
16. h4
{ Pavlov,S @@StartBracket@@2471@@EndBracket@@ -Predke,A @@StartBracket@@2611@@EndBracket@@ European Individual championship 2019. }
16... Nc5
{ The most accurate, not letting the light-squared bishop land on d3. } 17. h5
h6 18. f3 Rae8 19. Kb1
{ White avoids the check on e3 - the pawn on g7 is still hanging thus Black's next move is understandable. }
19... Rf7 20. Re1 Qg5 { Black is very solid. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "7.d4 and 8.Qd3: #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. d4
{ This is one of the most popular moves in the position but it comes without any hidden tricks and allows for Black to force a simple setup that is easy to remember and feels pretty safe. }
7... Ne4
{ The point of this intermezzo move is to win a couple of important tempos, eventually rerouting the kingside knight to c5. }
8. Qd3
{ Necessary, otherwise Black will take the pawn on d4 and White can't recapture it due to the potential discovered check at the e-file. }
8... exd4 { Black forces some trades. } 9. Nxd4 Nc5
{ There goes another tempo. } 10. Qd1
{ It pretty much doesn't matter where the white queen will retreat as Black will just take on d4. The only exception is  10.Qe2  - then Black just castle short and keep the idea of ...Nxd4 and ...Nd3+ in the air. }
10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O
{ The first phase of development is over, Black is looking towards a strong grip over the center with ...b6, ... Bb7, probably ...a5, and if necessary, ...d6 and ...f5. It's possible that at the right time the d-pawn push as far as d5 might work so just keep the option in your mind - don't rush with ...d6 just yet as you might use this square for your rook. If possible, Black would like to trade the light-squared bishops and an ambitious player as White would like to keep them. }
12. Be2 { The positional choice - White aims for a short castle. } 12... b6
{ Black's plan to fianchetto the bishop remains. It's important to note that any time soon White can't push the b-pawn to b4 without consequences as Black would respond with ...Ne6, the pawn on b4 is under attack, and next ...a5 would force White to play b5 and give up the c5 square. }
13. Bf3
{ Understandably, Black is about to have this powerful bishop on b7, but in these types of positions White usually tries to preserve the two bishops and hope for the long-term pressure. With the light-squared bishops traded it should feel like a little victory for Black. }
13... Bb7 14. Bxb7 Nxb7 15. O-O Nc5
{ Black has solved all opening problems. Now we're following a sample game. }
16. b3 d6 17. Bb2 f5 18. Rfe1 a5
{ Black had set up the perfect position in Raahul,V @@StartBracket@@2294@@EndBracket@@-Predke,A @@StartBracket@@2615@@EndBracket@@ Gujarat open 2018 and could focus on the kingside. }
