[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "7.Be2 and 8.cxd5: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. Be2
{ I think that among all choices this is the trickiest move at White's disposal. White is flexible, not rushing with the d4 thrust just yet, and is inviting Black to reveal his cards. }
7... d5
{ Staying true to the spirit of the entire course, Black does not shy away from fighting for the center. Now White has a choice - fire back at the center with d4 and aim for an open position, take on d5 and have a Scheveningen structure or keep things closed with d3. }
8. cxd5
{ This trade leads to a very comfortable Sicilian Scheveningen type structure for Black. }
8... Nxd5
{ Black already is threatening with ...e4 so White can't afford to lose much time. }
9. Qb3 Nb6 10. d3
{ Here Black is flexible with plans as this is essentially Sicilian Scheveningen with colors reversed. Black can castle long and an attack at the kingside - White would have to respond with a3-b4-b5 quickly. Then there's an immediate assault at the kingside in the spirit of Keres variation with  10...g5!?  However, the most solid seems to be castling short and a nice pressure against the d3 pawn. Probably Black can mix the ideas for some interesting results. }
10... O-O 11. a3
{ White might prepare to move forward the b-pawn and a3 is a standard preparation move. If White would continue with the immediate   11.Qc2  ,  then Black can already set up the Maroczy Bind with 11...Nb4  and ...c5 next for strong pressure. }
11... a5 { Black prepares to fix a weakness on b3. } 12. Bd2 Be6 13. Qc2
{ 13.Qc3  allows Black to include 13... Na4-c5 and only then fix the weakness on b3. }
13... a4 14. Rc1
{ Sakadin,A @@StartBracket@@2415@@EndBracket@@ -Oksanen,Y @@StartBracket@@2390@@EndBracket@@ Baltic Sea tt7 B06 corr 2002. }
14... Nd7
{ Depending on availability, Black should reroute the knight to either c5 or f8, and prepare for actions at the center. One of White's typical ideas in the position is to play e4, Be3, and push forward the d-pawn. }
15. Bc3 Rfd8 16. O-O Bb3 17. Qb1 Bd5
{ Here Black has a wide choice of how to continue, but rerouting the knight via the c5 square to b3 is a reasonable plan. }
*

