[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "7.Be2 and 8.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. Be2
{ I think that among all choices this is the trickiest move at White's disposal. White is flexible, not rushing with the d4 thrust just yet, and is inviting Black to reveal his cards. }
7... d5
{ Staying true to the spirit of the entire course, Black does not shy away from fighting for the center. Now White has a choice - fire back at the center with d4 and aim for an open position, take on d5 and have a Scheveningen structure or keep things closed with d3. }
8. d3
{ White might want to keep things closed for the time being but this again gives Black a lot of freedom. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Rd8
{ Black remains consistent with the Scheveningen approach, should White take on d5 after all, and also preparing to play ...d4. }
10. b3 a5
{ First Black gains more space at the queenside. Now the obvious  11.Bb2  awaits  11...d4 }
11. a3 Bg4
{ Since Black is threatening with either ...e4 or ...d4, White most likely will have to take on d5 at some point. }
12. cxd5
{ After  12.h3  Black could play  12...Bxf3  13.Bxf3  d4!  with intentions to recapture with the knight. Now after  14.Qc2  very strong is  14...e4  ,  then ...d3 and recapture the pawn on e4 with the queen. }
12... Rxd5
{ One of those occasions when taking with the rook is more active. Black applies pressure against the d3 pawn. }
13. Bb2 Rc5 { Black pushes away the white queen. } 14. Qe1 Rd8 15. h3 Bh5
{ Black is doing excellent - there are some correspondence games in the variation. }
16. Rb1 Bg6
{ White has to do something about that weak pawn on  d3  . Now after  17.e4  Black can just return with the bishop to h5 and threaten to trade off the knight to control the d4 square. }
17. b4
{ This is a very interesting pawn sacrifice to solve the positional problems. }
17... axb4 18. axb4 Rb5 19. e4
{ Here Black can just take the pawn but there are other good moves as well. }
19... Rxb4
{ The game in question Lunek, F @@StartBracket@@2348@@EndBracket@@-Maldonado Pacheco, J @@StartBracket@@2356@@EndBracket@@ ESP AEAC XV W/08/ email 2018 continued with  20.Qc3  Nd4  21.Nxd4  exd4  22.Qc2  c5  23.Ba3  Rxb1  24.Rxb1  Nxe4  ,  which leads to an equal endgame. Again, the line is not forced and Black could just easily respond to  20.Qc3  with  20...Rb6  ,  keeping the pawn and also parrying the threat of  21.Nxe5  with  21...Nd4! }
