9. Nxe5
{ This alternative pawn grabber appears to be a mistake but from afar it may not be very obvious even to a strong player. }
9... Bxe2 10. Nxc6
{ Directly taking the knight with  10.Kxe2  is a lot worse - the white king is now seriously exposed.  10...Ne4  and now the white queen is under attack with a check  11.Qb3  Nxe5  12.dxe5  and here  12...Qh4  is the most active move. }
10... Qe4
{ The whole point of the idea - the white pawn on g2 is intermezzo under attack. }
11. f3
{ Probably the best attempt to complicate things in an already not-so-good position as  11.Kxe2  Qxg2  doesn't look good for White and now after  12.Qe1  bxc6  13.Qg1  the black queen can just retreat to g6 for some advantage for Black. }
11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 Qh4+
{ Black doesn't have the time to take the pawn on f3 due to Rf1. } 13. Ke2 bxc6
{ White is temporarily down a pawn. } 14. cxd5 O-O 15. dxc6 Rfe8
{ Black has just sacrificed two pawns in a row and has a strong attack. } 16.
Bd2 Nd5 17. Qc4 Qg5 { Something is hanging on e3. } 18. Rag1 Rxe3+
{ This comes with a lovely idea that capturing on  e3  is impossible due to  19.Bxe3  Qxe3+  20.Kd1  Qxg1+  and ...Ne3+ fork next. }
19. Kd1 Qf5 20. Kc1 Nb6
{ Black will win back the pawn on f3 with a good position. White's pawn on c6 is quite weak. }
