[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "7.Be2 and 8.d4: #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. Be2
{ I think that among all choices this is the trickiest move at White's disposal. White is flexible, not rushing with the d4 thrust just yet, and is inviting Black to reveal his cards. }
7... d5
{ Staying true to the spirit of the entire course, Black does not shy away from fighting for the center. Now White has a choice - fire back at the center with d4 and aim for an open position, take on d5 and have a Scheveningen structure or keep things closed with d3. }
8. d4
{ Now comes the critical moment of the chapter - White is inviting Black for mass trades at the center, opening his bishops. }
8... Bg4
{ This is my novelty and I hope you will appreciate it! My initial analysis proves that Black is doing great in all of the lines but the final word belongs to the practice. The reason, why I stumbled upon this move - I'm not a big fan of the traditional mainline, which starts with @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppppqppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2Q1PN2/PP1PBPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.d4  Ne4  9.Qd3  exd4  10.Nxd4  Qb4+  .  It ruins White's king's castling opportunities but the more I was looking at the lines, the less I liked them. Black can't exploit the weakening of the white king. and the biggest problem is the white knight which is incredibly flexible with its maneuverings. It felt that there always will be a way for White to improve the game and it was difficult to explain things in an easy language for the reader. At some point, I just dropped the line and started to look for something else. I found this idea with a question - why nobody plays here the logical...Bg4? And the rest is already history. You will find the lines to be very dynamic and White has several ways to make a mistake. }
9. cxd5 { This is another move that doesn't make a lot of sense. } 9... Nxd5
10. Qb3 O-O-O
{ Black has a comfortable lead in the development and already a good attack. }
*

