{ This is my novelty and I hope you will appreciate it! My initial analysis proves that Black is doing great in all of the lines but the final word belongs to the practice. The reason, why I stumbled upon this move - I'm not a big fan of the traditional mainline, which starts with @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppppqppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2Q1PN2/PP1PBPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.d4  Ne4  9.Qd3  exd4  10.Nxd4  Qb4+  .  It ruins White's king's castling opportunities but the more I was looking at the lines, the less I liked them. Black can't exploit the weakening of the white king. and the biggest problem is the white knight which is incredibly flexible with its maneuverings. It felt that there always will be a way for White to improve the game and it was difficult to explain things in an easy language for the reader. At some point, I just dropped the line and started to look for something else. I found this idea with a question - why nobody plays here the logical...Bg4? And the rest is already history. You will find the lines to be very dynamic and White has several ways to make a mistake. }
9. dxe5 { The main and the most principled move at White's disposal. } 9... Ne4
{ Now White has two major choices here - either retreat with the queen to c2 or a3 as everything else seems to be worse. }
10. Qa3
{ One of the two most principled moves in the position. This allows White to keep the e5 pawn for a long time but due to Black's activity and the doubled a-pawns the extra pawn doesn't feel very significant. }
10... Qxa3
{ Maybe the immediate  10...dxc4  works as well - I didn't analyze it. } 11.
bxa3 O-O-O
{ Black is threatening to take the pawn on c4 and with ...Nxe5 threaten with a mate on d1. }
12. Bb2
{ White keeps the pawn, continues the development, and defends from the mate threat - a very reasonable choice. }
12... dxc4 { If White doesn't take the pawn, Black will. } 13. Bxc4
{ The only reasonable move as after  13.Rc1  Black can just push forward with  13...c3  ,  forcing some mass trades.  14.Bxc3  Nxc3  15.Rxc3  ,  then a couple more with  15...Bxf3  16.gxf3  Nxe5  and Black has won back the pawn and White's pawn structure has seen better days. }
13... Nc5
{ It could be difficult for White to understand how to play here - Black is threatening with both ...Nd3 to force White to trade off the light-squared bishop for the ongoing compensation for the pawn, or ...Na4 to win back the e5 pawn. The pawn on f7 can't be taken and the tempting  14.Ng5  is a mistake due to  14...Na4  and suddenly it's impossible to defend the bishop due to the back rank mate problem,   and the same happens after  14.Ke2  . }
14. Rc1
{ This defends against the ...Na4 threat, now that White has access to the a1 square, but the ...Nd3+ threat still remains. }
14... Nd3+ 15. Bxd3 Rxd3
{ I think that as soon as Black has managed to trade off White's light-squared bishop, he has nothing to worry about, and winning back the pawn on e5 is not a priority anymore. }
16. Nd4
{ After  16.Ke2  don't forget to retract your rook to d5 so that the incoming Nd4 is not a surprise and the rook on d3 hangs.  16...Rd5  17.Rhd1  Rb5  ,  where Black can already take back the pawn on e5. }
16... Nxd4 17. exd4
{ White has managed to keep the extra pawn and even cut off the black rook, but the weak pawn on a2 and the weaknesses of light-squares don't promise White any chances for success }
17... Rd8 18. f3 Bd7
{ This is quite accurate in order not to miss Ke2 which now can be answered with ...Bb5. }
19. Rc2 Ba4 { Black is already threatening with ... c5 to open the position }
20. Rd2
{ Here Black can either force a perpetual check with  20...Re3+  and now  21.Kf2  is impossible because of  21...Rxe5  and the white rook on d2 hangs, but Black can even safely trade rooks. }
20... Rxd2 21. Kxd2 Bc6
{ Black places the bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal, activates the rook with ...Rd5 and pushes forward the c-pawn for an equal endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "7.Be2 and 8.d4: #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. Qxc3
{ The main move - White keeps the pawn structure healthy and would like to make good use of the two bishop advantage in the long-term. }
6... Qe7
{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. Be2
{ I think that among all choices this is the trickiest move at White's disposal. White is flexible, not rushing with the d4 thrust just yet, and is inviting Black to reveal his cards. }
7... d5
{ Staying true to the spirit of the entire course, Black does not shy away from fighting for the center. Now White has a choice - fire back at the center with d4 and aim for an open position, take on d5 and have a Scheveningen structure or keep things closed with d3. }
8. d4
{ Now comes the critical moment of the chapter - White is inviting Black for mass trades at the center, opening his bishops. }
8... Bg4
{ This is my novelty and I hope you will appreciate it! My initial analysis proves that Black is doing great in all of the lines but the final word belongs to the practice. The reason, why I stumbled upon this move - I'm not a big fan of the traditional mainline, which starts with @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppppqppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2Q1PN2/PP1PBPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.d4  Ne4  9.Qd3  exd4  10.Nxd4  Qb4+  .  It ruins White's king's castling opportunities but the more I was looking at the lines, the less I liked them. Black can't exploit the weakening of the white king. and the biggest problem is the white knight which is incredibly flexible with its maneuverings. It felt that there always will be a way for White to improve the game and it was difficult to explain things in an easy language for the reader. At some point, I just dropped the line and started to look for something else. I found this idea with a question - why nobody plays here the logical...Bg4? And the rest is already history. You will find the lines to be very dynamic and White has several ways to make a mistake. }
9. dxe5 { The main and the most principled move at White's disposal. } 9... Ne4
{ Now White has two major choices here - either retreat with the queen to c2 or a3 as everything else seems to be worse. }
10. Qa3
{ One of the two most principled moves in the position. This allows White to keep the e5 pawn for a long time but due to Black's activity and the doubled a-pawns the extra pawn doesn't feel very significant. }
10... Qxa3
{ Maybe the immediate  10...dxc4  works as well - I didn't analyze it. } 11.
bxa3 O-O-O
{ Black is threatening to take the pawn on c4 and with ...Nxe5 threaten with a mate on d1. }
12. Bb2
{ White keeps the pawn, continues the development, and defends from the mate threat - a very reasonable choice. }
12... dxc4 { If White doesn't take the pawn, Black will. } 13. Bxc4
{ The only reasonable move as after  13.Rc1  Black can just push forward with  13...c3  ,  forcing some mass trades.  14.Bxc3  Nxc3  15.Rxc3  ,  then a couple more with  15...Bxf3  16.gxf3  Nxe5  and Black has won back the pawn and White's pawn structure has seen better days. }
13... Nc5
{ It could be difficult for White to understand how to play here - Black is threatening with both ...Nd3 to force White to trade off the light-squared bishop for the ongoing compensation for the pawn, or ...Na4 to win back the e5 pawn. The pawn on f7 can't be taken and the tempting  14.Ng5  is a mistake due to  14...Na4  and suddenly it's impossible to defend the bishop due to the back rank mate problem,   and the same happens after  14.Ke2  . }
14. Rd1 { Arguably the most critical move as it deals with both threats. }
14... Rxd1+ { This effectively pins the white knight. } 15. Kxd1 Bh5
{ This must be one of the most difficult moves of the entire line - Black 'wastes' a tempo to protect the pawn on f7. Since Black has so many threats, White can't deal with all of them. I checked several continuations that White could choose, and you will see a common pattern. }
16. Ke1
{ This is a little trickier than  16.Ke2  as the white king is now not pinned but the downside is that the white rook still can't join the game. }
16... Rd8 17. h3 Bg6
{ An easy move with additional control for the  d3  square but it might be difficult to immediately spot with the otherwise standard  17...Nd3+  here is a mistake. White would continue with  18.Bxd3  Rxd3  19.g4  Bg6  20.Nd2!  and Black has no active progress. }
18. Bc3 a6
{ White is in a little stalemate - now  19.Ke2  meets the annoying  19...b5!  and the light-squared bishop lacks good retreating squares. If the white knight will jump somewhere, it will relinquish the defense of the e5 pawn. }
19. h4 h5 20. e6
{ At some moment White might want to push forward the e-pawn, trying to trade it for the g-pawn, just be ready to counter it. }
20... f6 { The white pawn on e6 should fall pretty quick. } *

