{ This is my novelty and I hope you will appreciate it! My initial analysis proves that Black is doing great in all of the lines but the final word belongs to the practice. The reason, why I stumbled upon this move - I'm not a big fan of the traditional mainline, which starts with @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppppqppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2Q1PN2/PP1PBPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.d4  Ne4  9.Qd3  exd4  10.Nxd4  Qb4+  .  It ruins White's king's castling opportunities but the more I was looking at the lines, the less I liked them. Black can't exploit the weakening of the white king. and the biggest problem is the white knight which is incredibly flexible with its maneuverings. It felt that there always will be a way for White to improve the game and it was difficult to explain things in an easy language for the reader. At some point, I just dropped the line and started to look for something else. I found this idea with a question - why nobody plays here the logical...Bg4? And the rest is already history. You will find the lines to be very dynamic and White has several ways to make a mistake. }
9. dxe5 { The main and the most principled move at White's disposal. } 9... Ne4
{ Now White has two major choices here - either retreat with the queen to c2 or a3 as everything else seems to be worse. }
10. Qc2
{ White keeps queens on the board but now Black can win some nice tempos to accelerate the initiative. }
10... Nb4 11. Qd1
{ Retreating with the queen on d1 immediately is possible as well. } 11... dxc4
12. Bxc4
{ Not a very obvious mistake, but it is! Check out the following lines. } 12...
Rd8
{ The white queen has no good retreat squares -   13.Qe2  there's going to be an eternal problem with the light-squared bishop on g4 and the ...Ng5 threat ideas, so the immediate  13...Nc6!  with ...Qb4+ next and a strong attack looks terrific for Black.   13.Qb3  Nc5  looks even worse for White as one of the black knights will jump to d3 with a devastating effect. }
13. Qa4+ c6 14. O-O
{ 14.a3  meets a lovely punishment in the form of  14...Bxf3  15.gxf3  Nd3+  16.Bxd3  and just when White is starting to feel safe, there comes  16...Nc5  ,  attacking the white queen and taking the bishop on d3 with a check. }
14... Bxf3
{ A lot stronger than the tempting  14...b5  as Black now wins by force, thanks to some beautiful attacking motives. I'm not going to demonstrate every single line, just the most important motives. }
15. gxf3 Qg5+ 16. Kh1 Qh5
{ Mainly it's going to be about ...Qxf3 and ...Ng5 threat but there are a couple of other nice ideas as well. For example,  17.fxe4  Qf3+  18.Kg1  Qg4+  ,  followed by ...Qxe4+ and ...Qxc4, winning back the material and keeping the attack going.   Or  17.Qxb4  Qxf3+  18.Kg1  Qg4+  19.Kh1  Nxf2+  and ...Rd1+ next. White loses the queen on b1 due to the pin of the black queen.   17.Kg2  loses as well due to the very beautiful  17...Nc2!!  and if White takes the knight with  18.Qxc2  then  18...Qg6+  and knight's retreat with a check wins the white queen. Finally, after  @@StartFEN@@3rk2r/pp3ppp/2p5/4P2q/Q1B1n3/4PP2/PPn2PKP/R1B2R2 w k - 5 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Rb1  Black simply mates with  18...Qg5+  19.Kh1  Ne1!  and either a checkmate on g2 or f2. }
17. Be2 { Probably this is the most resilient defense. } 17... a5
{ White is in an unbelievable zugzwang, Black threatening with ...b5. The point of this move is to drive away the white queen from a4 so that Black can play ...Nd3 and the black knight on e4 is not under attack. }
18. a3
{ 18.e6  might be an interesting way to trick things but Black can respond with the cool  18...Rd5  ,  effectively bringing another piece into the attack. }
18... b5 19. Qb3
{ Now both ...Nd3 or ...Rd3 win the game but the latter is more spectacular. }
19... Rd3
{ Black drives away the white bishop from protecting the vital f3 pawn } 20.
Bxd3 Qxf3+ 21. Kg1
{ Black already has a draw in the pocket but it would be a shame to agree to one when there's a win! }
21... Qg4+
{ An important intermezzo check before taking the knight on d3, otherwise the immediate   21...Nxd3  meets  22.Qd1 }
22. Kh1 Nxd3 { Now Qd1 is impossible due to the fork on f2. } 23. Qxd3 Qf3+ 24.
Kg1
{ You might have seen already this mating motif before - Black checkmates the white king with the queen and the knight. }
24... Ng5 25. h3 Nxh3+ 26. Kh2 Ng5
{ There's no defense against ...Qh3+ and ...Nf3 mate. } 27. Kg1 Qg4+
{ That's a mate in two. } *

