{ The black bishop is back where it belongs - this should lead to a forced draw but White can make mistakes along the road. }
15. Qa4
{ Either here or b3,  there are not so many retreat squares for the white queen.  15.Qe2  is a positional mistake due to  15...Ng5  and the pin on f3 will cost White something. For example,  16.e4  Nxf3+  17.gxf3  Bh3  and ...Nc6-e5 or d4 next with a very strong attack. }
15... Bxf3 16. gxf3
{ With the white queen on  a4  there are some nuances - if Black would play immediately  16...Qg5+  17.Kh1  Qh5  ,  here White actually can play  18.Be2  and now  18...Nd3  is a bad mistake as the knight on e4 hangs.   With a perfect play, it's still a draw, only Black would have to continue with  18...c5  with an idea to play ...Rhe8-e6-h6 and White will have to find a way to force a perpetual himself at the queenside. The lines are long and complex, and the following move is simpler. }
16... Nd2 { First this! } 17. Bxd2 Qg5+
{ Only then comes the check with the queen! } 18. Kh1 Qf5
{ An odd but important moment -  18...Qh5  loses due to  19.Be2  Rxd2  20.Rad1  and the white bishop on e2 can't be taken as White would checkmate in a few moves with Qd7-d8+. The black queen on f5 protects the d7 square. }
19. f4 Rxd2 { With such an exposed white king, all of the lines are drawing. }
20. Qxb4 Qe4+
{ Black will force a perpetual with ...Qg6+ and ...Qe4+. White can't play  21.f3  due to  21...Qc2  and because of the mate threat on h2 and g2 White will have to give up the queen. }
*

