9. dxe5 { The main and the most principled move at White's disposal. } 9... Ne4
{ Now White has two major choices here - either retreat with the queen to c2 or a3 as everything else seems to be worse. }
10. Qc2
{ White keeps queens on the board but now Black can win some nice tempos to accelerate the initiative. }
10... Nb4 11. Qa4+
{ This intermezzo check seems to be a good and practical choice as it removes Black's light-squared bishop from the  g4  square.  11.Qb3  Nc5  12.Qc3  Black can already repeat the position with either ...Ne4 or the more spectacular looking ...Na4. }
11... Bd7 12. Qd1
{ Let's treat this as the main move - White has managed to push back the black bishop to d7 and it hopes to convert the extra pawn. Black must act with determination. }
12... dxc4
{ The only move but it's good enough. Black is still undecided where to castle but if there's no direct refutation, castling long always seems to be more principled. }
13. O-O { White rushes to finish the development. } 13... O-O
{ A very important moment here - Black can't castle long due to Qd4 double attack against the knight on e4 and pawn on a7. This wasn't possible with the white king still on e1 because of the fork on c2. }
14. a3
{ That's the only practical way how White can try to squeeze something out of the position. The immediate  14.Bxc4  would leave Black with a fine choice between the aggressive  14...Rad8  15.Qb3  a5  and some perpetual attack ideas with ...Nc5-e4-c5,   or the immediate  14...Bg4  but this would allow White to include  15.Be2  Either way, Black wins back the e5 pawn. }
14... Nd3 15. Bxd3
{ There's nothing better -  15.Qc2  meets  15...Bb5  16.Nd4  Qxe5  and Black is happy. }
15... cxd3 16. Qxd3
{ The first phase of the opening is over - both kings have castled, White has managed to keep the extra pawn but his light-squares are weak and the dark-squared bishop still hasn't joined the game. }
16... Nc5
{ Black's plan is simple - either make good use of the weakened light-squares or win back the pawn on e5 by trading the light-squared bishop for the knight on f3 via either the g4 or d5 square, depending on availability. }
17. Qc4 { Or  17.Qc3  first, see a sideline a move later. } 17... Be6
{ With the light-squared bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal, now the bishop can attack the white knight from the d5 square to win back the e5 pawn. }
18. Qc3 Bg4 19. b4
{ White might try to keep the extra pawn and finally also bring the dark-squared bishop into the game, but this comes at the expense of the white king's safety. After alternative  19.Nd4  Qxe5  Black recaptures the pawn and after a sooner or later will play ...Ne6 to an equal opposite color bishop endgame with some heavy pieces. The only thing I want to mention - don't allow your bishop on g4 to be trapped with an inspired f4-f5 push. Immediately it doesn't work. }
19... Bxf3 20. gxf3 Na4
{ Black is already threatening to recapture the pawn on d4. } 21. Qd4 Rad8
{ With perfect play the game should end with a perpetual check, delivered by the black queen via g5-h5-f3 squares. For example,  22.Qe4  Nc3  23.Qc4  Qg5+  24.Kh1  Qf5  and either Black forces a perpetual check, or wins back the pawn on e5. }
