18... Nb3 19. Rb1 Qd7
{ Since White is looking towards an attack at the kingside, it's a great idea to bother the white rook at the queenside and slow down White's intentions to bring the dark-squared bishop into the game. I checked several options at White's disposal - the immediate  20.Qg3  allows Black to win back the pawn with  20...Qd3  21.e4  Qxe4  and an equal position. }
20. Nd4
{ This is a nice attempt but it can be disarmed quickly if Black stays alert. }
20... Bc4 21. Nf5 Bd3
{ The knight on f5 is far more important than the rooks and it must be dealt with. }
22. e4 { The only move, everything else loses. } 22... Nd4
{ Black is just in time to eliminate the dangerous knight. } 23. Nxd4 Qxd4 24.
Rd1 Qxe4 { The position yet again simplifies to an equal endgame. } *

