{ Black first protects the pawn on e5 and prepares to push forward the d-pawn for an active play. Black can't afford to play this position passively with moves like  6...d6  Then White would eventually either play b3 and Bb2 or d4 first, open the position and the power of the two bishops at some point could become significant. }
7. Be2
{ I think that among all choices this is the trickiest move at White's disposal. White is flexible, not rushing with the d4 thrust just yet, and is inviting Black to reveal his cards. }
7... d5
{ Staying true to the spirit of the entire course, Black does not shy away from fighting for the center. Now White has a choice - fire back at the center with d4 and aim for an open position, take on d5 and have a Scheveningen structure or keep things closed with d3. }
8. d4
{ Now comes the critical moment of the chapter - White is inviting Black for mass trades at the center, opening his bishops. }
8... Bg4
{ This is my novelty and I hope you will appreciate it! My initial analysis proves that Black is doing great in all of the lines but the final word belongs to the practice. The reason, why I stumbled upon this move - I'm not a big fan of the traditional mainline, which starts with @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppppqppp/2n2n2/4p3/2P5/2Q1PN2/PP1PBPPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...O-O  8.d4  Ne4  9.Qd3  exd4  10.Nxd4  Qb4+  .  It ruins White's king's castling opportunities but the more I was looking at the lines, the less I liked them. Black can't exploit the weakening of the white king. and the biggest problem is the white knight which is incredibly flexible with its maneuverings. It felt that there always will be a way for White to improve the game and it was difficult to explain things in an easy language for the reader. At some point, I just dropped the line and started to look for something else. I found this idea with a question - why nobody plays here the logical...Bg4? And the rest is already history. You will find the lines to be very dynamic and White has several ways to make a mistake. }
9. dxe5 { The main and the most principled move at White's disposal. } 9... Ne4
{ Now White has two major choices here - either retreat with the queen to c2 or a3 as everything else seems to be worse. }
10. Qc2
{ White keeps queens on the board but now Black can win some nice tempos to accelerate the initiative. }
10... Nb4 11. Qa4+
{ This intermezzo check seems to be a good and practical choice as it removes Black's light-squared bishop from the  g4  square.  11.Qb3  Nc5  12.Qc3  Black can already repeat the position with either ...Ne4 or the more spectacular looking ...Na4. }
11... Bd7 12. Qd1
{ Let's treat this as the main move - White has managed to push back the black bishop to d7 and it hopes to convert the extra pawn. Black must act with determination. }
12... dxc4
{ The only move but it's good enough. Black is still undecided where to castle but if there's no direct refutation, castling long always seems to be more principled. }
13. O-O { White rushes to finish the development. } 13... O-O
{ A very important moment here - Black can't castle long due to Qd4 double attack against the knight on e4 and pawn on a7. This wasn't possible with the white king still on e1 because of the fork on c2. }
14. a3
{ That's the only practical way how White can try to squeeze something out of the position. The immediate  14.Bxc4  would leave Black with a fine choice between the aggressive  14...Rad8  15.Qb3  a5  and some perpetual attack ideas with ...Nc5-e4-c5,   or the immediate  14...Bg4  but this would allow White to include  15.Be2  Either way, Black wins back the e5 pawn. }
14... Nd3 15. Bxd3
{ There's nothing better -  15.Qc2  meets  15...Bb5  16.Nd4  Qxe5  and Black is happy. }
15... cxd3 16. Qxd3
{ The first phase of the opening is over - both kings have castled, White has managed to keep the extra pawn but his light-squares are weak and the dark-squared bishop still hasn't joined the game. }
16... Nc5
{ Black's plan is simple - either make good use of the weakened light-squares or win back the pawn on e5 by trading the light-squared bishop for the knight on f3 via either the g4 or d5 square, depending on availability. }
17. Qc4 { Or  17.Qc3  first, see a sideline a move later. } 17... Be6
{ With the light-squared bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal, now the bishop can attack the white knight from the d5 square to win back the e5 pawn. }
18. Qf4
{ The way I see it, the only practical attempt for White is to go for an inspired kingside attack. }
18... Nb3 19. Rb1 Qd7
{ Since White is looking towards an attack at the kingside, it's a great idea to bother the white rook at the queenside and slow down White's intentions to bring the dark-squared bishop into the game. I checked several options at White's disposal - the immediate  20.Qg3  allows Black to win back the pawn with  20...Qd3  21.e4  Qxe4  and an equal position. }
20. Qh4
{ Perhaps is the trickiest of them all as now  20...Qd3  looks a little risky due to  21.e4  and the rook on b1 can't be touched due to Bh6 and Qg5 mate threat. I propose to take the charge and don't wait for White to attack. }
20... f6
{ Much more energetic than the alternatives - we're playing chess here after all! }
21. exf6
{ 21.e4  Bc4  ,  followed by ...Bd3 and ...Qb5, if necessary, would cost White something. }
21... Rxf6 22. e4
{ White needs to bring the dark-squared bishop into the game as quickly as possible }
22... Rxf3
{ This sacrifice comes together with the previous active move - Black takes over the initiative. }
23. gxf3 Nd4
{ For White it could be already difficult to find the proper defense. } 24. Kh1
Bc4
{ This comes with an idea to reroute the bishop to e2 and take the pawn on f3 with a disastrous effect. }
25. Be3
{ Probably for White it's best to give away the exchange right away. Here Black can keep the initiative going with  25...Nxf3  and ...Rf8 next, but it's okay to take back the spoils of war. }
25... Bxf1 26. Rxf1 Nxf3
{ If White will trade queens with 27.Qh5-d5, it should be about equal endgame. }
*

