{ Since White is looking towards an attack at the kingside, it's a great idea to bother the white rook at the queenside and slow down White's intentions to bring the dark-squared bishop into the game. I checked several options at White's disposal - the immediate  20.Qg3  allows Black to win back the pawn with  20...Qd3  21.e4  Qxe4  and an equal position. }
20. e4
{ Black needs to know here a couple of only moves, but they are pretty straightforward. }
20... Bc4 21. Re1
{ After  21.Qg3  Bxf1  22.Bh6  Black defends everything in time with  22...f6  -  the black queen is well placed on d7. Here a critical line is  23.exf6  Rxf6  24.Ne5  ,  White attacks both the queen and the knight on b3. Black has a stunning resource  24...Nd4!!  which is threatening with a fork on e2 and remaining up some material. }
21... Bd3 22. Qg3 { This again is available with the same Ne5 trick. } 22...
Bxb1 23. Bh6 { Start of a forced sequence. } 23... f6 24. exf6 Rxf6 25. Ne5
{ Luckily for Black, the only moves are pretty obvious. } 25... Qe7 26. Qxb3+
{ 26.Bg5  meets a nice refutation in the form of  26...Nd4  and the bishop on b1 can't be touched due to the fork on e2. }
26... Qe6
{ Again, a necessary move, otherwise White would just pin the rook with Bg5. }
27. Qxb7 Re8
{ The position objectively is equal. For example,  28.Bg5  Rff8  29.Rxb1  Qxe5  and White will get two pawns for the exchange, but the position is pretty open for the black rooks to operate. }
