Nxe4
{ White is left with a very dangerously looking pin at the g-file but unfortunately it's not possible to exploit it. }
31. h4 h6 { Now after  32.h5   or  32.f3  White still keeps the balance. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "Chapter 20 Exercise: #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kr3r/ppp2ppp/8/2P1q3/3pn1b1/1P2P3/PBQ2PPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. exd4
{ While capturing the pawn with the bishop would result in Black sacrificing an exchange on d4 and a devastating attack at the e-file, this move feels a little safer as after the exchange sacrifice here White is not obliged to accept it and can continue with Be2. What did White miss? }
14... Qf4 15. Bc1
{ White needs just one more move - Be3 and the position seems quite solid. }
15... Nd2
{ Black sacrifices a piece to open the e-file for a devastating effect. The same motif would be available, had White developed the light-squared bishop. }
16. Bxd2
{ This leads to a beautiful win.   16.Qxd2  The most stubborn defense.  16...Rhe8+  17.Be2  Qxd2+  18.Kxd2  Rxe2+  19.Kc3  Rxf2  Black is ahead due to more active pieces and the better pawn structure, but at least White is not losing immediately. }
16... Rhe8+ 17. Be3 Qxd4
{ The two biggest threats are ...Qxa1 and ...Qb4+, White can't parry them both as there's a third threat - mate on d1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "Chapter 20 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2kr3r/p1p2ppp/2p2q2/3np3/8/1P2PP2/P1QP1P1P/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. Qe4 { How can Black use his lead in development? } 14... Nf4
{ This is a common idea from the Sicilian but still should feel quite special! }
15. d4
{ 15.exf4  exf4  16.Qb1  This would allow White to keep the extra piece but the king is left alone against three heavy pieces.  16...Rhe8+  17.Kf1   17.Kd1  is no better because of  17...Qc3  .  17...Qe5  Black is about to deliver a mating attack. }
15... Rhe8 16. Kf1 Qe6
{ White doesn't have time to take the knight - Black's attack is very swift. }
17. h4 f5 18. Qc2
{ 18.Qxe5  This allows a simple mate.  18...Qxe5  19.dxe5  Rd1 } 18... Nd5
{ Black's attack continues - if White won't take on e5, then Black will just march past the white d-pawn with ...e4. If White will take on e5, then after   19.dxe5  Qxe5  20.Bb2  Black has a stunning resource  20...Qxe3! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Four Knights: 5.Qc2 and 6.Qxc3"]
[Black "Chapter 20 Exercise: #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/p1p2ppp/2P5/3n2q1/2QP4/4PP2/PP1BK2P/R6R w - - 0 18"]
[SetUp "1"]

18. Rag1 { How should Black proceed here? } 18... Rxe3+
{ Train your tactical vision to spot unexpected resources! While this sacrifice seems quite standard, the follow-up might not be so obvious! }
19. Bxe3
{ After   19.Kd1  Qf5  Black removes the pin, keeps the fork threat alive, and is about to win back the f3 pawn with better chances. }
19... Qxe3+ 20. Kd1 Qxg1+ { The point of the entire sacrifice. } 21. Rxg1 Ne3+
{ Black is up a piece. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Four Knights: 4.g3 Sidelines"]
[Black "5.d4: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3
{ Now that White has forced Black to play ...Nc6 to protect the e5 pawn, he can fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2 and meet the otherwise traditional  4...Bb4  with  5.Nd5  It's a different branch with a big theory which I'm not going to explore. Instead, I offer to use the opportunity to play actively in the center. }
4... d5 5. d4
{ This is a very rare sideline which shouldn't cause any problems for Black. }
5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ The simplest - the alternative of  6...dxc4  is also possible which will lead to a temporary extra pawn and queens traded, but with a ruined pawn structure. }
7. Qxd4 dxc4 8. Qxd8+
{ After the queen trade White will be balancing an equal to worse position as the pawn on c4 still stands. }
8... Kxd8 9. Bg5 c6
{ A good positional move, visibly limiting the white knight's maneuvering capabilities. The black king could go to c7 but not always - it will stand just fine on e8 as well. }
10. a4
{ This was played in Munoz Garcia,F @@StartBracket@@1867@@EndBracket@@ -Ramirez Madrid,G @@StartBracket@@2033@@EndBracket@@ Costa Rica championship 2020, it is too slow. }
10... Kc7 11. e4 Be6 { Black simply keeps the extra pawn. } 12. Bf4+ Kc8
{ White has no compensation for the lost pawn and the slightly awkward position of the black king is irrelevant as White can't exploit it. }
*

