{ The simplest - the alternative of  6...dxc4  is also possible which will lead to a temporary extra pawn and queens traded, but with a ruined pawn structure. }
7. Qxd4 dxc4 8. Qxc4
{ The pragmatic move - White hopes for a strong pawn center with e4, f4, and would like to push e5 at some point later for some space advantage. }
8... c6
{ The black pawn on c6 will greatly limit White's light-square bishop's gaze and allow Black to continue with ... Be6. }
9. Bg2 Be6 10. Qa4 Be7
{ Black has an excellent position out of the opening - the slightly more active  10...Bc5  also was possible. }
11. O-O O-O 12. e4
{ Czebe,A @@StartBracket@@2491@@EndBracket@@-Sangma,R @@StartBracket@@2314@@EndBracket@@ New Delhi Parsvnath open 2017. }
12... Nd7
{ Black can start to take good care of the weakened central squares. If White would continue  13.Rd1  ,  then  13...Bc5  with the idea to play ...Qf6 and ...Ne5 next, and perhaps even ...g5-g4 to fix the dominating knight's outpost on e5. }
