{ The critical attempt to get something out of the position. Taking with the knight would be a huge blunder - after  8.Nxc6  Qf6  White loses as it is impossible to defend both the queen which is under attack and the f2 square. }
8... bxc6
{ Now White has two choices, but after either of them Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. }
9. bxc3 { White tries to keep the pawn. } 9... Qd5
{ Surprisingly, instead of the 'automatic' knight's retreat to f3 White here has a choice, and it has some venom. }
10. Nf3 { White defends both pieces with one move. } 10... Bh3
{ Black stops White from castling but this is not even mandatory - some correspondence games have seen Black simply castling short and then enjoying a very good compensation. }
11. Rg1
{ So far the only predecessor in the line is Burschowsky,M @@StartBracket@@2145@@EndBracket@@-Gsteu,P Austrian Team championship 1999, and here Black has excellent compensation. }
11... O-O 12. d4 Bd6
{ Black naturally will be trying to avoid the queen trade and any unnecessary trades in general, going for the stranded white king as it's not clear where it should hide. }
13. g4 h5 14. gxh5 Rfe8
{ Black has a strong initiative but with a perfect play White should be holding. }
