[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Four Knights: 4.g3 Sidelines"]
[Black "5.cxd5, 6.Bg2, 7.Nxe5: #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3
{ Now that White has forced Black to play ...Nc6 to protect the e5 pawn, he can fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2 and meet the otherwise traditional  4...Bb4  with  5.Nd5  It's a different branch with a big theory which I'm not going to explore. Instead, I offer to use the opportunity to play actively in the center. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5
{ This continuation has seen a big boom of popularity which started with the game between Pavel Eljanov against Alexander Grischuk in the 2017 FIDE Grand Prix in Geneva. It wasn't a novelty at the time and had been played prior multiple times at an amateur level, but with this game, the variation got the attention of pretty much everyone. Ever since the leading players of the world have been exploring this line, culminating as one of the hot topics in the World Championship match between Magnus Carlsen and Fabiano Caruana in 2018, where the challenger twice repelled the champion's ambitions and held the games to a draw. Black's main idea is with tactical motifs keep the knight on d5 so that it doesn't have to retreat to the traditional b6 square, and the bishop on c5 is pretty active itself. }
7. Nxe5
{ This tactical motif you should be perfectly aware of either right now or in the next several moves. With this little tactical shot, White is threatening to win a pawn and that's the reason why previously most of the players were unanimously retreating the knight to b6. Here, however, things are under control. This was Ding's choice against Radjabov in the World Cup, 2019. }
7... Nxc3 8. Bxc6+
{ The critical attempt to get something out of the position. Taking with the knight would be a huge blunder - after  8.Nxc6  Qf6  White loses as it is impossible to defend both the queen which is under attack and the f2 square. }
8... bxc6
{ Now White has two choices, but after either of them Black has excellent compensation for the pawn. }
9. bxc3 { White tries to keep the pawn. } 9... Qd5
{ Surprisingly, instead of the 'automatic' knight's retreat to f3 White here has a choice, and it has some venom. }
10. Nf3 { White defends both pieces with one move. } 10... Bh3
{ Black stops White from castling but this is not even mandatory - some correspondence games have seen Black simply castling short and then enjoying a very good compensation. }
11. Qb3
{ One of the World's leading players Ding Liren tried this continuation in his 2019 FIDE World Cup final match against Teimour Radjabov, with intentions to keep the pawn and play safe for the win. The Azerbaijani GM played a model game and showed the perfect way to equalize. }
11... Bg2
{ This is the best move, even if White trades the queens - the significance of the extra pawn will be almost irrelevant. Now come several forced moves. }
12. Qxd5 cxd5 13. Rg1 Bxf3 14. exf3
{ Hostilities are over and White seemingly has a pawn for nothing - it's Black's turn to be active. }
14... d4
{ Otherwise White will play d4 himself and start to press Black in earnest. From here the game is not forced but Black's plan is simple - castle long and activate his rook to press the weak white pawns. }
15. Rb1
{ If White will try to go past with c4, Black has the very annoying ...d3 resource. }
15... O-O-O
{ Black had a sufficient compensation for the pawn in the game Ding,L @@StartBracket@@2811@@EndBracket@@ -Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2758@@EndBracket@@ FIDE World Cup 2019, and with some active rook maneuvers should be able to win back the sacrificed pawn. You can find the full game annotation in the Model games. }
