[Round "?"]
[White "21. Four Knights: 4.g3 Sidelines"]
[Black "5.cxd5, 6.Bg2, 7.O-O: #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3
{ Now that White has forced Black to play ...Nc6 to protect the e5 pawn, he can fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2 and meet the otherwise traditional  4...Bb4  with  5.Nd5  It's a different branch with a big theory which I'm not going to explore. Instead, I offer to use the opportunity to play actively in the center. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5
{ This continuation has seen a big boom of popularity which started with the game between Pavel Eljanov against Alexander Grischuk in the 2017 FIDE Grand Prix in Geneva. It wasn't a novelty at the time and had been played prior multiple times at an amateur level, but with this game, the variation got the attention of pretty much everyone. Ever since the leading players of the world have been exploring this line, culminating as one of the hot topics in the World Championship match between Magnus Carlsen and Fabiano Caruana in 2018, where the challenger twice repelled the champion's ambitions and held the games to a draw. Black's main idea is with tactical motifs keep the knight on d5 so that it doesn't have to retreat to the traditional b6 square, and the bishop on c5 is pretty active itself. }
7. O-O { The main move - White keeps all options open. } 7... O-O
{ The threat of Nxe5 is still in the air but nothing has changed - it's not dangerous but it definitely will keep an unprepared player busy to consider it. }
8. Nxd5
{ Capturing the knights on d5 early for White is possible but it gives Black more options to choose from, should the game transpose to the mainline with 9.d3. }
8... Qxd5 9. Ng5
{ A tricky move that has been around for a while now. Again, White's  9.d3  would transpose to the mainline of the next chapter. }
9... Qd8 10. Nxh7
{ An original idea, first played by Levon Aronian. I don't think he's ever going to revisit this line as I think that White is simply worse now and the element of surprise is gone. }
10... Re8 { Suddenly the white knight is in trouble. } 11. Ng5
{ White might try to escape with  11.d4  but then after  11...Nxd4  12.e3  Nf5  Black has regained the pawn and is better. }
11... Qxg5 { Now White has a little choice here. } 12. d4
{ This is the best choice. } 12... Qh5 13. dxc5
{ This was played in Rajdeep,S @@StartBracket@@2364@@EndBracket@@-Pranav,A @@StartBracket@@2361@@EndBracket@@ Western Asia U-20 championship 2019, and here Black should have included a very important intermezzo move. }
13... Rd8
{ Suddenly White has no satisfactory defense against the incoming ...Nd4. } 14.
Bd2 { Or  14.Bf3  Bg4  . } 14... Nd4
{ Black is pressing and has excellent compensation for the pawn. } 15. f3
{ This was played in a high-level correspondence game which ended with a dynamic draw. }
15... e4 16. Be3 { 16.Rc1  Be6  doesn't look to be an improvement for White. }
16... Qxc5 17. fxe4 Be6
{ Black has got excellent compensation for the pawn with very active pieces and the absence of the pawn seems to be insignificant. }
18. Kf2 Qe5 19. Qc1 Qh5 20. Re1
{ White is on the defensive and must be careful. } 20... Bh3 21. Bf3 Bg4 22.
Bxd4 { Probably Black has nothing better than to repeat the position. } 22...
Qxh2+ 23. Ke3 { After  23.Bg2  Black is pressing with  23...Bh3 } 23... Qh6+
{ Players soon agreed to a draw in Kribben,M @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@ -Hall,M @@StartBracket@@2602@@EndBracket@@ NED MT-Van Oosterom email 2017. }
