1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3
{ Now that White has forced Black to play ...Nc6 to protect the e5 pawn, he can fianchetto the light-squared bishop to g2 and meet the otherwise traditional  4...Bb4  with  5.Nd5  It's a different branch with a big theory which I'm not going to explore. Instead, I offer to use the opportunity to play actively in the center. }
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5
{ This continuation has seen a big boom of popularity which started with the game between Pavel Eljanov against Alexander Grischuk in the 2017 FIDE Grand Prix in Geneva. It wasn't a novelty at the time and had been played prior multiple times at an amateur level, but with this game, the variation got the attention of pretty much everyone. Ever since the leading players of the world have been exploring this line, culminating as one of the hot topics in the World Championship match between Magnus Carlsen and Fabiano Caruana in 2018, where the challenger twice repelled the champion's ambitions and held the games to a draw. Black's main idea is with tactical motifs keep the knight on d5 so that it doesn't have to retreat to the traditional b6 square, and the bishop on c5 is pretty active itself. }
7. O-O { The main move - White keeps all options open. } 7... O-O
{ The threat of Nxe5 is still in the air but nothing has changed - it's not dangerous but it definitely will keep an unprepared player busy to consider it. }
8. d3
{ The main move - if White is very slow with his decisions, Black can already consider to trade the knights on c3 or play something else active. Here Black is at the crossroads - in the original game Grischuk against Eljanov played  8...Bb6  but the theory since 2017 has evolved.   Today the two most popular continuations here are  8...h6  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n5/2bnp3/8/2NP1NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Re8  and I believe that it's a matter of taste because the difference between them is not big. The rook move seemingly is more active but it allows White additional Bg5 provocative moves which are particularly popular at the highest level.   Thus I decided to go for @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n5/2bnp3/8/2NP1NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...h6  which seems to be the simplest. }
8... h6
{ The latest word in the line - Black prepares to play either ...Be6 to protect the knight on d5 which immediately is impossible because of the annoying Ng5 threat and Black doesn't want to give up his light-squared bishop just like that. Another idea is that if nothing dramatic will happen, Black can retreat with the knight to f6, and the pawn on h6 stops White from pinning the knight with Bg5. With the knight on f6 Black is typically continuing with ...Re8 and preparing to play ...Nd4, then closing the power of White's light-squared bishop with ...c6 and a good game. }
9. Nxe5 { Here we go again! Black's approach remains the same. } 9... Nxc3 10.
Nxc6
{ This doesn't lose but White will be balancing between a worse and an equal position. }
10... Nxd1 11. Nxd8 Bxf2+ 12. Kh1
{ Kluge,L @@StartBracket@@1249@@EndBracket@@-Triantafillidis,K @@StartBracket@@1239@@EndBracket@@ German Team championships G-14 2010, this loses similarly, and the maneuver you should already know from one of the previous sidelines. }
12... Bg4
{ We already had this position without White's d3 and Black's h6 included - nothing changes. }
13. Rxd1 Raxd8
{ White is considerably worse. An interesting continuation could be if White would decide to trap black bishops. }
14. Bxb7 Bxe2 15. Rd2 Rfe8 16. Be4 { Tactically this doesn't work. } 16... Rxe4
17. dxe4 Bf3# { That's a nice mate. } *

