9. a3
{ The two critical continuations  9.Bd2  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pp1/2n4p/2bnp3/8/2NP1NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nxd5  will be analyzed in the final chapter of the course. If White allows Black to choose between ... Nf6 or ...Be6, go for it. Here retreating with the knight to f6 looks a little strange due to b4. }
9... Be6 10. Na4
{ White might try to play b4 and first remove the knight from the c3 square. }
10... Bd6
{ Again, there should be a very good reason to allow to trade off the dark-squared bishop thus the retreat to b6 is not recommended if White can trade it off for the knight. }
11. b4
{ This was played in Sukta, S-Orlowski, M @@StartBracket@@1611@@EndBracket@@ Ogolnopolski championship 2013. Instead, White could have included the more reasonable  11.Qc2  first to prepare b4 but then Black can just play  11...a5  to stop the pawn push altogether. Now after the inaccurate  12.Nc5  Bxc5!  13.Qxc5  Black has gained something from the trade - the b3 square, and can continue with  13...a4  but also  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1pp2pp1/2n1b2p/p1Qnp3/8/P2P1NP1/1P2PPBP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qd6  looks good.   If White doesn't do it and plays something normal as  12.Bd2  ,  then Black just continues the development with  12...Qd7  and a solid grip of the center. }
11... b5
{ A rare occasion when Black can counter-strike back with such an odd move, thus important to know. }
12. Nc5 { 12.Nb2  a5  looks just terrible for White. } 12... Bxc5 13. bxc5 Qe8
{ Black controls what's happening in the center and has a future passed pawn on the queenside. }
