9. a3
{ The two critical continuations  9.Bd2  and  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2pp1/2n4p/2bnp3/8/2NP1NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nxd5  will be analyzed in the final chapter of the course. If White allows Black to choose between ... Nf6 or ...Be6, go for it. Here retreating with the knight to f6 looks a little strange due to b4. }
9... Be6 10. Nxe5
{ One more final attempt but this time the knight on d5 is protected and Black can safely go for the trade without any tricks. }
10... Nxe5 11. d4
{ Theoretically White could consider including  11.Bxd5  before playing d4 but I see no gain. Instead, after  11...Bxf2+  12.Rxf2  Bxd5  Black simply seems to be better and White's  13.Rf5  can be met with  13...f6  and the light-squared bishop can always retreat to e6, attacking the white rook. }
11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bd6 13. dxe5 Bxe5
{ This is a forced line and something similar you should have already encountered in some of the previous sidelines. Here the only difference is that the light-squared bishop has already been developed on e6, thus the black pawn on b7 is under attack. }
14. Bxb7
{ If White won't take the pawn, Black can just play ...c6 to protect it. }
14... Rb8 15. Rb1
{ It's very tempting to protect the bishop on b7 as after Black's  15...Bxc3  White suddenly gets an advantage with  16.Be3  ,  attacking the a7 pawn and the rook as well. However, Black has a nice intermezzo move at his disposal. }
15... Bf5
{ The idea is to force the white rook to leave the first rank before playing ...Bh3 and then winning a critical tempo against the rook on b5. }
16. Rb5
{ After  16.Rb3  White unexpectedly drops a rook with  16...Qxd1  and ...Bc2 to follow,   but  16.Rb4  allows  16...a5  with a tempo.   White's  16.e4  is also no good as it disconnects the kingside from the light-squared bishop and Black can continue with  16...Bh3  and then grab the pawn on c3. }
16... Bh3 { Only now the black bishop goes to h3. } 17. Be3
{ 17.Re1  doesn't seem to be an option due to  17...Bxc3 } 17... Bxf1 18. Qxd8
{ The point is revealed in line -  18.Qxf1  Black plays  18...Qd7  and attacks the white rook, continuing with ...c6. With the white rook on b1, this would be impossible. }
18... Rfxd8 19. Kxf1 a6
{ Black simplifies the position as White can't retreat  20.Rb3  due to  20...c5  and ...Rd7 next. White will be forced to lead a long defense for a draw. }
