{ After   9.bxc3  Nxe5  10.d4  Bd6  the position is just equal, but what happens here? }
9... Nxd1 10. Nxd8 Bxf2+ { Much more presise than taking with the knight. } 11.
Kh1
{ 11.Rxf2  This is objectively the best, albeit the arising position for White is not fun.  11...Nxf2  12.Nxb7  Nh3+  13.Kf1  Bg4  Black has exchange for a pawn and is better developed. }
11... Bg4
{ After this precise move, Black's advantage becomes obvious - the threat of ...Bxe2 must be dealt with. }
12. Bf3 Bxf3+ 13. exf3 Raxd8 14. Rxd1 Rfe8
{ Black is ahead in development and has a better pawn structure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Four Knights: 4.g3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Chapter 21 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/ppp2pp1/2nbb2p/3np3/N7/P2P1NP1/1P2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11. b4
{ White found a way how to stop Black's traditional .. .a5 and is about to play Bb2 and pressure the black pawn on e5. How can Black claim an advantage? }
11... b5
{ The circumstances when this will work are quite rare, but here it works! }
12. Nc5
{ 12.Nb2  a5  This looks like a disaster for White - the knight on b2 has nothing to do. }
12... Bxc5 13. bxc5 Qe8
{ After the trade Black has established a strong passed pawn at the queenside and has good control over the central squares. }
