[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Four Knights: 4.g3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Chapter 21 Exercise: #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1br2k1/ppp2pp1/8/2P1p2q/3n4/6P1/PP1BPPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

15. e3
{ Black has a strong compensation for the pawn so White is ready to give up the extra pawn to simplify the position. Will you accept it or maybe there's something more? }
15... Ne2+
{ There is more!   15...Bg4  This would allow Black to win back the pawn. Normally Black should be quite happy about it if only there wasn't more!  16.f3  Nxf3+  17.Bxf3  Bxf3  18.Rxf3  Rxd2  19.Qxd2  Qxf3  Black has a minor advantage due to exposed white king but nothing serious. }
16. Kh1 e4
{ Black fixes the control over the light squares and the incoming ...Bg4-f3 threat is too strong. }
17. Bxe4
{ 17.Qc2  Bg4  White can't take on e4 with the queen as the bishop on d2 is still hanging.  18.Bc3  Bf3  19.Rad1  It's difficult to suggest something better.  19...Bxg2+  20.Kxg2  Qf3+  21.Kh3  Nxc3  22.bxc3  Kh7  Black delivers a simple mate. }
17... Bg4 { White suffers big material losses. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Four Knights: 4.g3 Mainlines"]
[Black "9.Bd2: #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5
{ All of the potential sidelines, including White's countless options to take on e5, you can examine in the previous chapter. In the final chapter of the entire course we will examine the two most popular continuations, where White is still seeking to create some practical problems for Black. You will see the world champion Magnus Carlsen playing these lines from both sides! }
7. O-O O-O 8. d3 h6 9. Bd2
{ White finishes the development and resumes the threat of Nxe5, now that ...Nxc3 can be answered with Bxc3 and the knight on e5 will be protected by the bishop. It is possible to protect the knight on d5 with ... Be6, but I like the text move a lot more. }
9... Nf6
{ Sometimes it's alright to retreat and regroup! The knight on d5 was standing just fine but it's a subject of many of White's ideas. The black knight on f6 stands perfectly for numerous reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ Mostly Black's threat is to play ...Re8, prepare to play ...Nd4 to trade off the knights, typically recapture with ...exd4 and close White's light-squared bishop's gaze with ...c6 and target the weak pawn on e2. On this occasion, the dark-squared bishop will be well placed either on b6 or usually on f8 where it's waiting for further instructions. The knight on d5 makes this plan almost impossible to achieve.   2@@EndBracket@@ The knight on f6 also makes feel White's pieces a little clumsy on the queenside as they are lacking space. The white knight on c3 doesn't do much and two of its potential maneuvers to d5 or e4 are now covered by the black knight on f6. White probably would like to trade the c3 knight for the dark-squared bishop and at least get a two-bishop advantage.   3@@EndBracket@@ With the knight on f6 now a potential idea of pushing forward the e-pawn might appear on some occasions, should the white knight on c3 leave its post. Notice that this knight's retreat is possible thanks to the previously included ...h6 so that White can't pin the knight with Bg5. }
10. Na4
{ This move takes away Black's option to position the dark-squared bishop on f8 and avoid it being traded. Black could consider keeping the dark-squared bishop with ...Bd6 but the arising positions feel a little awkward. }
10... Bb6
{ The simplest retreat which looks solid - Black doesn't mind giving up the dark-squared bishop and is ready to recapture it with ... axb6, immediately pressuring the white pawn on a2. }
11. Rc1
{ White not only has finished the development but is also threatening with Rxc6 and Nxe5 next. }
11... Re8
{ Depending on White's response, Black wants to play one of the two ideas - go for ...Nd4 or push ...e4. I hope that with some of the selected continuations you will have a pretty good idea, when to choose which continuation. }
12. a3
{ A multi-purpose move, mostly directed against  12...e4  If Black does it, then after  13.dxe4  Nxe4  14.Nxb6  axb6  the white a-pawn suddenly is protected and White can continue with  15.Be3  with some edge. }
12... Nd4
{ Given the circumstances, now this plan looks best - Black wants to continue with ...c6 }
13. Bc3
{ This would be tricky, White again going for the bishop trade on d4. It's best to trade the knight for a knight. }
13... Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 c6 15. Nxb6 axb6
{ The arising position is about equal. If White would try to open the center with d4, then Black can close it with ...e4. }
*

