[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5
{ All of the potential sidelines, including White's countless options to take on e5, you can examine in the previous chapter. In the final chapter of the entire course we will examine the two most popular continuations, where White is still seeking to create some practical problems for Black. You will see the world champion Magnus Carlsen playing these lines from both sides! }
7. O-O O-O 8. d3 h6 9. Bd2
{ White finishes the development and resumes the threat of Nxe5, now that ...Nxc3 can be answered with Bxc3 and the knight on e5 will be protected by the bishop. It is possible to protect the knight on d5 with ... Be6, but I like the text move a lot more. }
9... Nf6
{ Sometimes it's alright to retreat and regroup! The knight on d5 was standing just fine but it's a subject of many of White's ideas. The black knight on f6 stands perfectly for numerous reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ Mostly Black's threat is to play ...Re8, prepare to play ...Nd4 to trade off the knights, typically recapture with ...exd4 and close White's light-squared bishop's gaze with ...c6 and target the weak pawn on e2. On this occasion, the dark-squared bishop will be well placed either on b6 or usually on f8 where it's waiting for further instructions. The knight on d5 makes this plan almost impossible to achieve.   2@@EndBracket@@ The knight on f6 also makes feel White's pieces a little clumsy on the queenside as they are lacking space. The white knight on c3 doesn't do much and two of its potential maneuvers to d5 or e4 are now covered by the black knight on f6. White probably would like to trade the c3 knight for the dark-squared bishop and at least get a two-bishop advantage.   3@@EndBracket@@ With the knight on f6 now a potential idea of pushing forward the e-pawn might appear on some occasions, should the white knight on c3 leave its post. Notice that this knight's retreat is possible thanks to the previously included ...h6 so that White can't pin the knight with Bg5. }
10. Be3
{ White might consider including the bishop trade which makes perfect sense as it takes care of the center, offers to open the f-file for the white rook, and stops both of Black's plans to act in the center. However, this also seriously weakens White's pawn structure, and most notably the e3 square. }
10... Bxe3 11. fxe3 a5
{ The most active move - Black takes more space and has ideas to meet Qb3 with ...a4 and ...Ng4 to follow. Suddenly the e3 pawn is impossible to defend as White is overloaded with the knight on a4. }
12. a3 Re8
{ Black plans to reroute the queenside knight to e7 and then either f5 or g6, and continue with the traditional ...c6 to limit the activity of White's light-squared bishop. }
13. Rc1 { This logical move, however, is a mistake! } 13... Ng4 14. Qd2 e4
{ Black suddely takes over. Now after  15.Nxe4  Black will continue with  15...f5  and recapture on e3 with the knight, but after   15.dxe4  Black can just trade the queens and continue with  ...Nxe3  and a better position. }
