10. Rc1
{ The standard move - White is developing the queenside rook and is threatening with a discovered attack. This also gives Black enough time to play ...Re8 so that the dark-squared bishop can be hidden on f8 and prepare to play ...Nd4 next. }
10... Re8
{ Black already wants to play ...Nd4 next and recapture with the e-pawn. } 11.
Nh4
{ This very original move was played in Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2772@@EndBracket@@-Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2776@@EndBracket@@ Tata Steel India blitz 2019, and probably with an idea to parry both Black's ideas of ...e4 and ...Nd4, as the latter can be met with e3 and the black knight has to retreat without trading the knights. However, the white knight on h4 has pretty much nothing to do. Another idea might be White threatening with Bxc6 and double the c-pawns but that's not something that should make Black deeply concerned. }
11... Bb6
{ If White wants to take on c6, don't stop him - you will get good attacking chances at the kingside. The text move is a multi-purpose move to solidify the position. }
12. Na4 Qd6
{ Black can make many good moves before switching back to the ...Nd4 or ...e4 plans. The white knight on h4 is not going to stay forever and the only way back is via the f3 square. }
