{ I'm convinced that this is the critical choice for White who takes the knight on  d5  before Black has the opportunity either to protect it with ...Be6 or retreat to f6,  which will be the case with the alternative  9.Bd2 }
9... Qxd5
{ The black queen isn't always well placed on a central square - without the light-squared bishop on g2 it would be a perfect spot but the bishop is still there, thus the black queen will be a subject for White to win some tempos. Black will step back with the queen to avoid any surprises with a discovered attack and as far as I understand the position, there are two reasonable squares - on d6 and d8.   Some high-level games from a few setups have seen ...Qe6 but I think it's quite awkward. In general, it should be fairly easy to remember - if White is continuing a normal development with Bd2 with or without including a3, then ...Qd6 is good enough but if the white knight is early rerouted to d2, then obviously it's d8 to avoid any immediate Ne4 forks. }
10. Nd2
{ This move was twice played by Ding Liren against Teimour Radjabov in the 2019 FIDE World Cup final match, in two tie-break games. The idea must have been threatening with the odd  Bxc6  and ruining Black's pawn structure but we will never know it for sure as Radjabov opted for  10...Qe6  retreat in both games. }
10... Qd8
{ I suggest going the ambitious approach and not being afraid of the Bxc6 threat as it should lead to some very double-edged games. It's a novelty but one can say that about every second line in modern variations. }
11. b3 { White continues the development and keeps all options open. } 11...
Bg4
{ Not only is Black threatening  ...Nd4 but the idea is to provoke White's h3 so that White is pretty much never considering to take on c6, now that the kingside is weakened. }
12. h3 { Black is happy. } 12... Be6
{ Since White can't even consider playing Bxc6. Black is to continue with ...Bd5. }
13. Bb2 Bd5
{ With the light-squared bishop trade Black has successfully finished the opening phase. }
14. Nf3 { The final trick in White's arsenal to win the pawn on e5. } 14... f6
{ The temporary weaknesses of the light squares at the kingside don't play a big role - White can't exploit it. }
