[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Four Knights: 4.g3 Mainlines"]
[Black "9.Nxd5 and 10.Nd2: #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5
{ All of the potential sidelines, including White's countless options to take on e5, you can examine in the previous chapter. In the final chapter of the entire course we will examine the two most popular continuations, where White is still seeking to create some practical problems for Black. You will see the world champion Magnus Carlsen playing these lines from both sides! }
7. O-O O-O 8. d3 h6 9. Nxd5
{ I'm convinced that this is the critical choice for White who takes the knight on  d5  before Black has the opportunity either to protect it with ...Be6 or retreat to f6,  which will be the case with the alternative  9.Bd2 }
9... Qxd5
{ The black queen isn't always well placed on a central square - without the light-squared bishop on g2 it would be a perfect spot but the bishop is still there, thus the black queen will be a subject for White to win some tempos. Black will step back with the queen to avoid any surprises with a discovered attack and as far as I understand the position, there are two reasonable squares - on d6 and d8.   Some high-level games from a few setups have seen ...Qe6 but I think it's quite awkward. In general, it should be fairly easy to remember - if White is continuing a normal development with Bd2 with or without including a3, then ...Qd6 is good enough but if the white knight is early rerouted to d2, then obviously it's d8 to avoid any immediate Ne4 forks. }
10. Nd2
{ This move was twice played by Ding Liren against Teimour Radjabov in the 2019 FIDE World Cup final match, in two tie-break games. The idea must have been threatening with the odd  Bxc6  and ruining Black's pawn structure but we will never know it for sure as Radjabov opted for  10...Qe6  retreat in both games. }
10... Qd8
{ I suggest going the ambitious approach and not being afraid of the Bxc6 threat as it should lead to some very double-edged games. It's a novelty but one can say that about every second line in modern variations. }
11. b3 { White continues the development and keeps all options open. } 11...
Bg4
{ Not only is Black threatening  ...Nd4 but the idea is to provoke White's h3 so that White is pretty much never considering to take on c6, now that the kingside is weakened. }
12. Nc4
{ This must be the most critical response, that is available to White, immediately applying some pressure against the pawn on e5. Black needs to be careful here. }
12... Re8
{ First, Black should protect the pawn on e5 and continue the development. The threat of ...Nd4 is in the air but White can always meet it with Re1. }
13. Ba3
{ A very tricky response! The immediate  13.Bb2  would allow Black to play the desired  13...Nd4  and now  14.Re1  meets  14...Bb4 }
13... Bb6
{ Black dodges a little positional trap, which happens after  13...Bxa3  as White could include  14.Bxc6  first and only then capture on a3. This position might be perfectly playable for Black but with fewer and fewer pieces on the board, the weaknesses of the c-pawns might start to tell at some point. }
14. Bb2
{ Now White positions the bishop on the desired square and yet again is pressuring the e5 pawn. Now Black can't play  14...Nd4  as after  15.Re1  Black has no access to the a5-e1 diagonal to bother the white rook and after  15...c6  White suddenly comes ahead with  16.h3  ,  and after g4 follows e3 and the black pawn on e5 is lost. }
14... Qd7
{ Black finishes the development and indirectly defends the pawn on e5 but the consequences are not obvious at all! }
15. Bxc6 { This doesn't work for White. } 15... Qxc6 16. Nxe5 Rxe5 17. Bxe5
{ Now instead of the anticipated  17...Bh3  after which White just plays  18.e4  and gives back the exchange, Black suddenly uncorks a beautiful combination. }
17... Re8 { Black has some decisive threats. } 18. Rc1 Qd5 19. Bxc7 Rxe2
{ Black is threatening with ...Bh3 and a mate on g2. } 20. Bxb6 Qf3
{ White's extra rook is meaningless as Black is about to mate White who already has nothing better than to give up the queen on e2 and enter a strategically lost position as the white king is too weak. }
*

