{ I suggest going the ambitious approach and not being afraid of the Bxc6 threat as it should lead to some very double-edged games. It's a novelty but one can say that about every second line in modern variations. }
11. Qc2
{ White might include the early queen development and go for the pawn. } 11...
Bb6 12. Nc4
{ This jump might be a more pragmatic choice - although the black knight will get to d4 with a tempo, it won't manage to stay there for long. }
12... Nd4 13. Qd1 Re8 14. Re1
{ This is a standard waiting move in the English opening, overprotecting the e2 pawn - very often White shows some enduring patience against the black knight on d4. }
14... c6
{ Since Black is already about to play ...Bc7 and protect the e5 pawn, White can try to push the knight back. }
15. e3 Nb5
{ While there's a potential gambit with  15...Ne6  to sacrifice the pawn on e5, followed with ...Ng5 later, this feels to be good enough. }
16. a4 Nd6 17. b4 Nxc4 { Black simplifies the position. } 18. dxc4 Qf6
{ Black should be feeling pretty safe. White has some advanced pawns at the queenside but that's it. }
