Bb6 12. Nc4
{ This jump might be a more pragmatic choice - although the black knight will get to d4 with a tempo, it won't manage to stay there for long. }
12... Nd4 13. Qd1 Re8 14. a4
{ White being overly patient with the black knight on d4 can backfire. } 14...
Bg4 15. Re1 e4 { A nice tactical motif to know. } 16. h3
{ After  16.Bxe4  Black can continue with  16...Nxe2+  17.Rxe2  Rxe4  with a double pin and some material gain. }
16... Bh5 17. Nxb6 axb6 18. g4 exd3
{ This appears to be much stronger than the peaceful  18...Bg6  ,  which also keeps some advantage. }
19. gxh5 Rxe2
{ Black is attacking with huge forces but the absence of a piece isn't even felt. }
20. Bd2 Qh4 21. Rf1 Nc2 22. Rc1 Rae8
{ A dominating sight - White has his piece but is almost paralyzed. Every single Black's piece is participating in the attack. }
23. Bc3 Qg5
{ The final precise move - now the ...Ne3 threat is impossible to parry. } 24.
h4 Qg4 25. Qxd3 Ne3
{ The game is over - Black is about to checkmate the white king so White must drop his queen. }
