Bb6 12. Nc4
{ This jump might be a more pragmatic choice - although the black knight will get to d4 with a tempo, it won't manage to stay there for long. }
12... Nd4 13. Qd1 Re8 14. e3 Nc6 15. Be4
{ This motif is common from some Sicilian Dragon positions - the white bishop is feeling pretty active on e4 and also protects the d3 pawn. With the clumsy bishop on b6 Black should act quickly. }
15... Be6 16. a3 Bd5 17. b4
{ Now I wouldn't rush with trading on e4 but develop pieces first. } 17... Qd7
18. Bb2 Rad8
{ Black can always include ...a6 and give the dark-squared bishop a little air. At the right moment ...Bxe4 will have to be played. Additionally,  19.b5  doesn't win a pawn because after  19...Na5  ,  there is no time for  20.Nxe5  because the b-pawn hangs. }
