11... Qd8 12. b3
{ White can continue the development without including the a-pawn movements but Black's plan remains the same. }
12... Bg4
{ Black is trying to provoke White to play h3 so that the bishop can return to e6-d5. }
13. Nc4 Re8
{ The difference of including a3 and ...a5 quickly becomes visible. } 14. Bb2
{ White can play this now since after  14...Nd4  15.Re1  Black doesn't have access to  15...Bb4 }
14... Qd7
{ Despite the little change, Black feels pretty fine. Now White can try to take on the pawn on e5 which should result in an equal endgame. }
15. Bxc6 Qxc6 16. Nxe5 Rxe5 { This motif you should already remember. } 17.
Bxe5 Re8 { White has to defend with the only moves. } 18. d4
{ The difference with the previous line is that here the black bishop is under attack. }
18... Bh3 19. f3
{ Now follow a couple of trades and the position inevitably reaches an equal heavy piece endgame. }
19... Rxe5 20. dxc5 Bxf1 21. Kxf1 Rxc5
{ Visually Black looks even slightly better. } *

