10... a5 11. Bd2
{ The same rule from the mainline applies also here - with the white bishop on d2 the black queen can retreat to d6. }
11... Qe6
{ This is one of the most famous predecessors of the line. It draws some parallels to the 2019 FIDE World Cup final tiebreak games between Ding Liren and Teimour Radjabov where Black went for the same maneuver, albeit under different circumstances. To me, the maneuver feels a little too slow as Black spends whole two tempos to rearrange the queen thus I decided not to pursue it. I do believe that with a precise play Black is doing fine there as well but I like the text move even more. }
12. Rc1 Qe7 { Black's idea was to go for the immediate ...Nd4 } 13. Bc3 Nd4 14.
e3 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3
{ White ended up having some pressure but with a precise game Black should be able to neutralize it. }
15... Bd6 16. Qh5 c6 17. f4
{ White sacrificed a pawn for an attack, which Black accepted. } 17... exf4 18.
gxf4 Qxe3+
{ Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2845@@EndBracket@@-Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2797@@EndBracket@@ Gashimov memorial 2019, Black soon regretted it and quickly went down in flames. }
