1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5
{ All of the potential sidelines, including White's countless options to take on e5, you can examine in the previous chapter. In the final chapter of the entire course we will examine the two most popular continuations, where White is still seeking to create some practical problems for Black. You will see the world champion Magnus Carlsen playing these lines from both sides! }
7. O-O O-O 8. d3 h6 9. Nxd5
{ I'm convinced that this is the critical choice for White who takes the knight on  d5  before Black has the opportunity either to protect it with ...Be6 or retreat to f6,  which will be the case with the alternative  9.Bd2 }
9... Qxd5
{ The black queen isn't always well placed on a central square - without the light-squared bishop on g2 it would be a perfect spot but the bishop is still there, thus the black queen will be a subject for White to win some tempos. Black will step back with the queen to avoid any surprises with a discovered attack and as far as I understand the position, there are two reasonable squares - on d6 and d8.   Some high-level games from a few setups have seen ...Qe6 but I think it's quite awkward. In general, it should be fairly easy to remember - if White is continuing a normal development with Bd2 with or without including a3, then ...Qd6 is good enough but if the white knight is early rerouted to d2, then obviously it's d8 to avoid any immediate Ne4 forks. }
10. Bd2
{ White has completed the development and is ready to reroute the bishop to c3 - let's treat this as the mainline. With the white bishop on d2 and the particular square blocked for the knight, now the black queen doesn't have to retreat as far as d8 - d6 will do just fine. }
10... Qd6
{ If at any moment White will include a3, Black is ready to respond with ...a5, unless there's something better. }
11. Bc3
{ White is threatening with Nxe5 and d4 next - a motif of which you should already be well familiar with. }
11... Rd8
{ Black takes under the control the d4 square and thus stops White's intentions, and at the same time also develops a piece. With the last move Black sets a nasty trap as well. }
12. Nd2
{ White is threatening with the fork on e2 but having spent two tempos for Bd2-c3 this already is not so dangerous. }
12... Be6
{ Black has finished the development and wants to play ...Bd5 next. Again, White can't play the very tempting  13.Nc4  due to  13...Bxf2+  threat, followed by ...Bxc4 and ... Qc5+, if necessary. I think for White it's very easy to miss it. }
13. Ne4 { This is tempting but not dangerous for Black. } 13... Qe7 14. Nxc5
{ Forced, otherwise the black bishop will simply retreat to b6 and the entire idea of Nd2-e4 loses its purpose. }
14... Qxc5
{ Black is back to the idea to play ...Bd5 next and trade-off the light-squared bishops. }
15. Rc1
{ One final attempt to get something out of the position and threaten with a discovered attack. I should mention that White couldn't have played  15.Bxc6  Qxc6  16.Bxe5  due to the same  16...Bh3  threat. }
15... Bxa2
{ Brave and good - White can't imprison the bishop with b3 as Black will continue with ...Qb6 and after capturing the pawn on b3 is ready to support the bishop with ...a5-a4, if necessary. }
16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Qa4
{ White could be seeking ways to attack the weak black pawns at the queenside. It's best to give up the extra pawn immediately. }
17... Bd5 18. Bxe5 Qe7
{ White’s dark-squared bishop can’t leave the e5 square because the pawn on e2 will be lost, which could be catastrophic for White, due to the weak light squares around the king. Thus after the logical  19.e4  Qxe5  20.exd5  Qxd5  all of the queenside pawns should disappear after mass trades, leading to an equal endgame of heavy pieces. }
