[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Four Knights: 4.g3 Mainlines"]
[Black "Chapter 22 Exercise: #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/ppp2pp1/1bq4p/4p3/2N3b1/1P1P2P1/PB2PP1P/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]

16. Nxe5
{ White has just won a pawn and with a fork is threatening to simplify the position. What will you do? }
16... Rxe5 { Solve your positional problems with a tactical solution! } 17.
Bxe5 Re8 18. Rc1
{ 18.d4  This move doesn't work.  18...Bh3  19.f3  Rxe5  Black collects the second bishop and now has a strategically winning position. }
18... Qd5 19. Bxc7
{ White is ready to give up the extra exchange. Will you take it or look for more instead? }
19... Rxe2
{ Always go for more, if you can! Black is threatening with ...Bh3 and a mate to follow. }
20. Bxb6 { Now what? } 20... Qf3
{ The dark-squared bishop on b6 is meaningless! Black improves the threat and will play ...Bh3 next. White is powerless - the best option here is to give up the queen on e2 immediately. Because of the weakened light squares around the white king, Black should be winning. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Four Knights: 4.g3 Mainlines"]
[Black "Chapter 22 Exercise: #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqr1k1/ppp2pp1/1b5p/4p3/2Nn4/3P2P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. a4
{ White has allowed the black knight on d4 to stand unchallenged. How can Black use this to his advantage? }
14... Bg4 15. Re1 e4
{ A great shot! Black uses the opportunity to rip White's position apart. } 16.
h3
{ 16.Bxe4  This would allow Black to execute a nice idea.  16...Nxe2+!  17.Rxe2  Rxe4!  That's a double pin! }
16... Bh5 17. Nxb6 axb6 18. g4
{ The danger for White is over, or so it seems. Will you retreat with the bishop to g6 for a nice position or seek a strong attack instead? }
18... exd3
{ Black still has enough pieces to conduct a very dangerous attack. } 19. gxh5
Rxe2 { Black has many threats here and is dominating the board. } 20. Bd2 Qh4
21. Rf1 Nc2 22. Rc1 Rae8
{ Including the final piece in the attack. White is running out of moves. } 23.
Bc3 Qg5 { Suddenly White has no defense against the ...Ne3 threat. } 24. h4 Qg4
25. Qxd3 Ne3 { Black finally crashes through. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Four Knights: 4.g3 Mainlines"]
[Black "Chapter 22 Exercise: #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2r2k1/ppp2pp1/2nqb2p/2b1p3/8/2BP2P1/PP1NPPBP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

13. Nc4
{ This tempting move actually is a terrible mistake - do you know why? } 13...
Bxf2+ { Thanks to this trick White loses a pawn for no compensation. } 14. Rxf2
{ 14.Kxf2  Capturing with the king White keeps the d1 square well defended, but this also opens the white king for checks.  14...Bxc4  15.dxc4  Qc5+  White loses the queen. }
14... Bxc4
{ The queen on d1 is not well defended thus the black bishop on c4 can't be taken. }
