[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ding, L. vs. Radjabov, T. FIDE World Cup, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. Nxe5
{ The details of this variation are already explained in Chapter 21. Normally this tactical trick is not dangerous for Black but you should be aware of it at all times. I think this is the best moment for White when to go for it, because of the following line. }
7... Nxc3 8. Bxc6+
{ If Black has already castled short, obviously White won't have this intermezzo move anymore, as the queen is under attack. }
8... bxc6 9. bxc3 Qd5 10. Nf3 Bh3 11. Qb3
{ This must have been Ding Liren's preparation for just one game. This was the fourth and final classical game of the World Cup final match, the score was a tie, and in case of a draw, there would be tiebreaks. An experienced GM in this situation would choose something safe that can be played for a win without any risk. That's a very popular strategy among professionals - now Black will need to show an accurate defense. }
11... Bg2
{ Perhaps Black could have gambled and declined the queen trade but with the stakes so high, this move is an easy decision. Black needs to draw to move the match to the tiebreaks. }
12. Qxd5 { This is a start of a forced sequence. } 12... cxd5 13. Rg1 Bxf3 14.
exf3
{ This must have been Ding's idea all along - have some minor practical chances to play for the win. White has the extra pawn after all. If Black will play precisely, fine - it's a draw and proceed to the tiebreaks. White is threatening with d4 which must be stopped. }
14... d4
{ An important accuracy - White can't be allowed to play d4 himself as Black would run out of active moves. }
15. Rb1
{ 15.c4  This would be a risky choice that can backfire. White would like to play d3 afterward but Black is a little faster.  15...d3!  Suddenly White is experiencing some practical problems. }
15... O-O-O
{ Very strong - the relative weakness of the black king doesn't matter. Black brings into the game the queenside rook. }
16. Rb5 Rhe8+ 17. Kd1
{ 17.Kf1  Doesn't quite work for White thanks to a simple tactic.  17...dxc3  18.Rxc5  cxd2  Black temporarily has sacrificed a piece but is about to win it back with some interest. }
17... Bb6 18. cxd4
{ 18.c4  White might consider again to play c4-d3 to close the center but this again looks like a risky decision.  18...d3  19.c5?  c6!  White loses the pawn on c5. }
18... Bxd4 19. Rf1
{ White's only hope to win this game is to hold on to the pawn, try to trade the bishops, one pair of rooks, and then perhaps somehow capitalize on the extra pawn in the rook or pawn endgame. One advantage of having the extra pawn is that the opponent still needs to spend a tempo to capture it back! }
19... Re6
{ Black can't just sit and wait until White will improve his position. The pawn on a2 makes a fine target. }
20. Bb2
{ This allows Black to win back the pawn by force.   20.Ra5  This might have been a little more stubborn but this would also mean that White can't trade the dark-squared bishops anymore.  20...Kb7  21.f4  c5  Black looks very active and the absence of the pawn doesn't even feel.  22.f3  22...f5  23.Re1  Rxe1+  24.Kxe1  Rd6  White already needs to be careful here. Holding to the extra pawns is good, as long as everything else doesn't suffer from it. }
20... Ra6 21. Bxd4 Rxd4 22. Rb2 Rda4
{ The pawn on a2 is lost. This now gives White some time to activate the other rook. }
23. Re1 Kd7 24. Rb8
{ The last practical chance - White gives up the a2 pawn and instead seeks some targets with the rooks, penetrating Black's back rank. }
24... Rxa2 25. Ree8 Ra1+
{ One final accuracy - Black trades off pair of rooks to eliminate any danger from the white rooks causing some serious problems at the kingside. }
26. Ke2 Re6+ 27. Rxe6 Kxe6
{ Black already has a better pawn structure. White needs to end the game as quickly as possible in order not to get into trouble. }
28. Re8+ Kf6 29. Rc8 { Invitation for a draw with a perpetual attack. } 29...
Rc1 30. Ra8 Ra1 31. Rc8
{ None of the players can improve the position. I like Ding's chosen strategy for such an important game of the match but Radjabov showed a textbook defense, easily holding the game to a draw. In the tiebreaks Radjabov scored a win, thus winning the World Cup. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Wang, Y. vs. Narayanan S. Belt and Road Hunan Open, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O 8.
d3 h6 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Bd2 Qd6 11. Bc3 Rd8 12. Nd2 Be6 13. Qa4 Nd4 14. Bxd4
{ I don't think that White can pose any problems for Black after this move, as I already explained in Chapter 22.   14.Rfe1  This was the critical try but Black manages to proceed with his plan.  14...Bd5  15.Ne4  Qe7  Black is about to reposition its bishop on b6 and the trades in the center do not necessarily favor White. }
14... Qxd4 15. Qc2 Bd6
{ 15...c6  This was already fine here but I can imagine that Black wanted to keep the option alive to play for the win, or at least give White an opportunity to make a mistake. With opposite-color bishops on the board, it could be very difficult to achieve.  16.Nb3  Bxb3  17.Qxb3  The position is equal. }
16. Nc4
{ This is where White unexpectedly starts to get into trouble.   16.Bxb7  This feels to be principled as it ruins Black's pawn structure.  16...Rab8  17.e3  This is a necessary intermezzo move, otherwise ...Rxb2 will be a very unpleasant threat to deal with.  17...Qb6  18.Bc6  Qxb2  19.Qxb2  Rxb2  20.Nc4  The arising position should be just equal and perhaps Black already has to take on c4. }
16... c6
{ Black is threatening to escape the bishop trade with ... Bc7 and play for a two-bishop advantage. }
17. Nxd6 Rxd6
{ Not a very obvious inaccuracy!   17...Qxd6!  This was necessary, mainly with the idea that now White can't play 18.b4 as Black takes the pawn and has access to the e7 square to protect the pawn on b7! White won't get another chance because Black is about to play ...a5. }
18. Qc3
{ This is too passive.   18.b4  White had to play this, given the opportunity. Now Black can't take the pawn as the b7 pawn will fall and the black rook on d6 blocks the e7 square to protect the pawn.  18...a5  19.bxa5  Rxa5  20.Rfb1  Rd8!  Black can still press this a little but because of White's counterplay at the b-file, the position should be about balanced. }
18... a5
{ Black is clearly on top after the opening as he can organize something at the queenside while it's not very clear what should White do. }
19. Rfc1 Ra6 20. Qxd4 Rxd4 21. a3 Rb6
{ White's in trouble and forced to defend passively. White must have thought that it's not a big deal as the pawn on b2 can be easily defended. }
22. Rc2
{ 22.Rc5?  This looks more active but is a mistake - Black is about to organize a passed pawn at the queenside which will be supported by the bishop.  22...Rxb2  23.Rxe5  Ra4  White might lose the a3 pawn very quickly and once the black a-pawn will start rolling forward, it will be difficult to stop. }
22... f6
{ The next three moves are directed to limit White's counter-chances with Rc5, should White change it's mind. There's no need to hurry. }
23. Kf1 Rd8 24. Ke1 Rb5 25. Kd2
{ White has brought the king closer to the action but he's still missing a counterplay. }
25... f5
{ According to Nimzowitch, if your opponent has one weakness, what should you do? Create another! }
26. Ke1 Kf7 27. a4
{ Finally White understands that sitting passively will ultimately end badly thus he's looking for some counterplay with Rc5. }
27... Rb4 28. Rc5 Kf6
{ 28...Ra8  29.Rxe5  Rxb2  This looked great as well and I'm sure that Black was comparing the results and in the end, chose what he played in the game. }
29. Rxa5 Rxb2
{ Now Black is threatening with ...e4 and double the rooks on the second rank - White must hurry back. }
30. Rc5 Ra8 { Now the a-pawn is a weakness that will keep White busy. } 31. a5
Ra6 32. Rc3
{ White's been leading difficult defense and is holding so far. From here everything went South very quickly as soon as Black started to march towards the weak a-pawn. }
32... Ke7 33. Rca3
{ White is back to the passive defense - it was better to keep the rook on c5 where it's active. }
33... Kd6 34. Bf3 g5 { Black could had played 34...Bb3 right away. } 35. e3 Bb3
{ The black king is coming to b4 with a devastating effect. It's a piece after all! All White can do is silently sit and watch the position to collapse. }
36. Be2 Ra7
{ If the a-pawn will move forward, Black will just shoot past with ...b5 and then take care of the a-pawn which is well blocked. }
37. Bf3 g4 38. Be2 Kc5 39. e4 { White is out of ideas. } 39... fxe4 40. dxe4 h5
{ There's no need to hurry. } 41. Bd1 Bxd1 42. Rxd1 Kb4 43. Rda1 Ra6
{ Black wants to play ...b6 next and win the pawn. White can't take it because Black would win the rook and Rb2 defends the runner. }
44. R3a2 Rxa2 { One final attempt. } 45. Rxa2 Kb3
{ The a-pawn inevitably falls and with it - the entire game. Now after   46.Ra1  Black can dominate the rook with  46...Kb2  and after  47.Ra4  b5  is decisive. }
46. Rd2 Rxa5 { Black quickly wrapped up the game. } 47. Rd7 b5 48. Rc7 Ra6 49.
Re7 b4
{ The e-pawn doesn't matter as Black is about to promote the b-pawn. A powerful position display by Black! }
*

