[Black "Suninen, J. vs. Kazantsev, R. FIN jub50 Correspondence, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2 Bxc3 6. bxc3 d6
{ All of the theoretical details about this line are explained in Chapter 19. }
7. e4 O-O 8. g3 a6 9. Rb1 Na5 10. d3 Bd7 11. Bg2 b5 12. O-O Re8 13. cxb5 axb5
14. Nh4 h6 15. f4 Ra6 16. Nf5
{ This is the most tempting move which one could expect at the board as well. White could have included   16.fxe5  move first but it wouldn't change anything from Black's perspective. }
16... c5
{ Suddenly Black has a very annoying positional threat of ...c4 and White's center is now more vulnerable than ever. There's no real attack at the kingside, except a menacing-looking white knight on f5. }
17. Ne3 c4 { The white pawn on e4 loses its main support. } 18. fxe5
{ 18.d4  This was a decent attempt, however...  18...Bc6!  The position should lead to the same pawn structure as in the game.  19.fxe5  dxe5  20.d5  Bd7  The knight is heading to d6 for a perfect blockade. }
18... dxe5 19. d4 Nc6 20. d5
{ 20.Nd5  Might have been a better option from the human's perspective but in correspondence chess, it's probably meaningless.  20...exd4!  21.Nxf6+  gxf6  Black king's position is shattered but the positional gains are greater.  22.Rxb5  d3  23.Qf2  Ne5  24.Rb7  Bg4  Black should just sacrifice the pawn on h6, instead of on focusing - how to protect it. The strong d-pawn and aggressive continuations should decide the game in favor of Black. }
20... Na7 { Great maneuver! Black starts by rerouting the knight to d6. } 21.
Qe2 Nc8 22. Ra1 Nd6
{ Phase one is finished - Black has an excellent blockade. Now all he needs to do is pay some attention to White's weaknesses. }
23. Nc2 Bg4 { The bishop is heading to g6. } 24. Qe3 Ra4 25. Nb4
{ White has some ideas of his own that Black needs to take care of first. }
25... Nd7 26. Qf2 Qc7 27. Be3 Bh5 28. Nc6
{ I find it quite amazing how useless is the white knight on c6, comparing to its colleague on d6! }
28... Nf6 29. Qc2 Ng4
{ A great positional concept - Black trades off the most active White's piece! }
30. Bc5 Nb7 31. Bf2 Nxf2 32. Qxf2 Nd6
{ Phase two completed - the knight can go back. } 33. Bf3 Bg6 34. Rfe1 f6
{ Phase three - Black continues to improve the position which starts by getting rid of the white knight on c6. }
35. Rac1 Rea8 36. Rc2 Be8 37. Nb4
{ Mission accomplished - now Black starts to increase pressure against White's weaknesses. }
37... Qa7 38. Re3 Bd7 39. Kg2 Nb7
{ Phase four - since the white knight is holding together everything, most notably the pawn on a2, Black wants to trade it off. }
40. Bd1 Ra3 41. Qd2 Nc5 42. Rb2 Qa5 43. Bc2 Na6 44. Bb1 Nxb4 45. Rxb4 Qb6
{ Phase five - Black creates a passed pawn at the queenside. } 46. Re2 R8a4 47.
Rxa4 Rxa4 48. Qe3 Qa5 49. Qc1 b4 50. cxb4 Qxb4
{ Black has established a strong passed pawn which is inevitably moving forward. Combining with the already existing two weaknesses on e4 and a2, Black has a strategically winning position. }
51. Rb2 Qc5 52. Qc3 Kh7
{ The c-pawn will inevitably roll forward thus White just resigned. } *

