1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 Bxc3+ 8.
bxc3 Ne5 9. c5 Qe7 10. Nb3 Rb8 11. O-O b6 12. Re1 bxc5 13. f4 Nc4 14. e4 d6
{ Link to trainable variation } 15. Qe2
{ White's idea is to get rid of the knight so that the e5 threat becomes real and White can recapture with the queen, thus attacking the c5 pawn. }
15... Ba6
{ Obviously, Black is not interested! The knight looks just fine on c4. } 16.
Na5 Qe6 { Black parries White's threats and is about to play ...d5 next. } 17.
f5
{ White doesn't have a choice and tries to complicate the matters.   17.Bf1  This would be very tempting, if not for Black's next move.  17...d5!  18.exd5  Qxe2  19.Bxe2  Rfe8  White already has to seek an escape with the only moves.  20.Be3!  Nxe3  21.Bxa6  Rb2  Black has a large advantage due to more active pieces while White's knight and bishop seem to be completely disconnected from the action. }
17... Qe5 18. Nc6 { 18.Nxc4  Qxc3  This looks even worse for White. } 18...
Qxc3 19. Nxb8 Rxb8
{ The complications have ended, Black has two pawns for the exchange and a great outpost on e5 for one of the knights. }
20. Bf4 Nd7 21. Bf1 Rb2 22. Qd3 Qa5
{ Black is incredibly active and on top of the minor material advantage is threatening with ...Ne5. }
23. Qd5
{ 23.Rac1?  This would allow Black to execute the following idea.  23...Nce5!  24.Qxa6??  Nf3+  25.Kh1  Rxh2 }
23... Ncb6 24. Qd1 Bxf1 25. Rxf1 c4
{ Minor material advantage, better pieces, weakened white king and the strong passed pawn - Factoring all these in the evaluation, Black is winning. }
26. Qd4 c3 27. Rf3 Na4 28. Re1 Qb6
{ Simplifying the game and increasing the power of the passed pawn. } 29. Qxb6
axb6 30. e5
{ It's difficult to suggest something better - White is seeking at least some active counterplay. }
30... Nxe5 31. Bxe5 dxe5 32. Rxe5 h5
{ Around this point I'm sure that Black already thought that the game is officially over - the c-pawn is unstoppable. }
33. Re4 Rxa2
{ Unnecessary greed - the a-pawn plays no role here! Black might have been in time trouble here.   33...c2!  34.Rc4  b5  35.Rxc7  b4  Black will just play either ...Nc3 or ...Rb1 first and then ...Nc3, winning a rook for the passed pawn. This would have been a logical outcome of a great game. }
34. Rf2 Ra1+
{ They do say that mistakes come in pairs.   34...Rxf2  35.Kxf2  b5  This still should be easily winning. Better keep the rooks on the board and all options open, right? }
35. Kg2
{ Suddenly White is back in the game as the Black king is left undefended and the c-pawn isn't moving anymore. }
35... Nc5
{ Black hurries back to help the monarch but this drops the passed pawn.   35...b5  36.Re8+  Kh7  37.Rf8!  Things can turn nasty very quickly.  37...f6?  38.Re2 }
36. Rc4 Rc1
{ Triple mistake?   36...Nd3  This was a better try.  37.Re2  c2!  38.Re8+  Kh7  39.Rxc2  Ne1+  40.Rxe1  Rxe1  41.Rxc7  However, despite the fact that Black is up a pawn, the endgame looks quite drawish, as the king is disconnected from the game to help the passed pawn. }
37. Rf3
{ White now wins back by force the most dangerous passed pawn and I can imagine, that around here was fierce time trouble as the players still had 3 moves to play before reaching second time control. }
37... Rc2+ 38. Kh3 Re2 39. Rfxc3 Ne4
{ Black was still playing for the mate and just missed the next move. } 40. Rc2
{ Incidentally this move also protects the h2 pawn. } 40... Rxc2 41. Rxc2
{ After the second time control had kicked in and time trouble was no longer a factor, White was suddenly ahead. The game continued with mutual mistakes and then already in a drawn position Black suddenly blundered. }
41... c5 42. Rb2 Nd6 43. f6 b5 44. Rd2 Ne4 45. Rd8+ Kh7 46. fxg7 Kxg7 47. Re8
f5 48. Rb8 b4 49. Kh4 Kf6 50. Kxh5 Nd2 51. h3 Ne4 52. g4 fxg4 53. Kxg4 Nf2+ 54.
Kg3 Nxh3
{ Must have been a hallucination - Black is too slow to advance the pawns.   54...Nd3  55.Kf3  c4  56.Ke3  Kg5  57.Kd4  Nf2  Should be quite simple from here - rook vs knight is an easy theoretical draw. }
55. Kxh3 Ke5 56. Kg2 Kd4 57. Kf2 Kc3 58. Ke1 b3 59. Kd1 Kb2 60. Rc8 Ka1 61.
Rxc5 b2 62. Ra5+ Kb1 63. Rb5 { Black threw away a great game. } *

