[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Timofeev, A. vs. Karjakin, S. World Rapid Championship, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. e3 Nc6 4. d3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Be7 7. Be2 O-O 8.
O-O Be6 9. a3 a5 10. Qc2 f5 11. Re1 Kh8 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. e4
{ This line is covered in the Chapter 15 - Reversed Sicilian, part 2. White's last move is one of the common ideas of the Sicilian Scheveningen. }
13... Qd6 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Be3 Rad8 16. Rad1 Qg6 17. Qb3
{ The idea to bother the b-pawn is a known annoyance in the Sicilian Scheveningen setup, but here it backfires tactically.   17.Kh1  It was necessary to remove the king from the pin first.  17...Be6  Black takes care of the b3 square and reroutes the bishop to d5.  18.Nd2  Bd5  19.Ne4  b6  At some point, Black is ready to play ...Nd4. White's natural Bf3 comes with a potential exchange sacrifice on f3 and an easy attacking game for Black. }
17... Be6 { Black quickly spots that White can't take on b7. } 18. Qa4
{ Better to acknowledge the mistake than be stubborn.   18.Qxb7?  This loses in a stunning fashion.  18...Bh3  The more natural 18...Bd5 works great as well, but with different ideas.  19.g3  Rb8!  The white queen doesn't have good retreat squares.  20.Qa6   20.Qxc7  This feels like climbing into a lion's cage with hopes to stay alive.  20...Rfc8  21.Nxe5  Qe8!  White has to give up a piece to save the queen.  Rxf3!  The point of the entire sequence - Black is about to continue with ... Nd4 and capture on f3 with an intermezzo check.  21.Bxf3  Nd4  22.Bb7  Last trick - White saves the bishop and protects the queen.  22...Nf3+!  Black's attack is still unstoppable - the knight can't be taken.  23.Kh1  Qh5  The white king is about to be mated - either the light-squared bishop will retreat with a devastating effect, or ...Nxh2 will come through. }
18... Bd5 19. Kh1 h6
{ In a dominating position Black is too careful - this was the moment to charge forward.   19...Nd4!  20.Bxd4  exd4  Once Black will position his second bishop on d6, the attack at the kingside looks overwhelming.  21.Qxa5  Qh5  Black protects the bishop on d5 first and is about to play ...Bd6.  22.Qa4  Bd6  I don't see White surviving this attack. }
20. Rg1 b6 21. Rc1 e4
{ Another inaccuracy - Black understandably wants to open the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop but misses White's defensive setup. It was better to increase the pressure with   21...Qf6  ,  preparing to play ...Nd4 next. }
22. dxe4 Bxe4 23. Rc4
{ White should have played   23.h3  with an idea to reroute the knight to h2 and prepare to play Bf3 next - the worst would be over for him. }
23... Bd5 24. Rcc1 { White has lost two tempi for nothing. } 24... Rd6 25. Nd2
Bg5 26. Nf3 { Two more tempi... } 26... Bxe3 27. fxe3 Rdf6
{ Black is threatening with a sacrifice on f3. } 28. h3 Qg3 29. Qg4 Qf2 30. Bc4
Bxc4
{ Black wins a pawn but now White will have decent drawing chances.   30...Rxf3!  31.Bxd5  Ne5  This was much better which probably would have resulted in an extra pawn as well, but Black's pieces feel more active. Now after  32.Qh5  Black can either take the pawn on e3 or continue to press for more with  32...R3f5  ,  followed with ...Qg3. }
31. Rxc4 Qxe3 32. Qg3 { 32.Re1  felt more active. } 32... Qd3 33. Rc3 Qd6
{ Black consolidated the position and went on to win the game. The weak c7 pawn gives White good chances to save the game. }
34. Kh2 Qxg3+ 35. Kxg3 Rg6+ 36. Kh2 Re8 37. Rc2 Ree6 38. Rb1 Kg8 39. b4 axb4
40. axb4 b5 41. Rbb2 Re4 42. Rc5 Nxb4 43. Rxc7 Rb6 44. Nd2
{ Now   44.Rd2  to activate both rooks and bother the black king should be enough to draw the game. In the worst-case scenario, White can put the rook behind the passed black pawn. }
44... Rf4 45. Rb3 Nc6 46. Rg3 Rf7 47. Rc8+ Kh7
{ Now it's not so simple for White. } 48. Ne4 Ne5 49. Rc5 Ng6 50. Rb3 b4 51.
Rc4 Rfb7 52. Rd4 Ne5 53. Nc5 Rc7 54. Na4 Rg6 55. Rb2 b3
{ Probably White flagged here. The outcome could have been really nice -   56.Rxb3  Rc2  57.Rg3  Nf3+!  and White gets mated. }
