1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3 Re8 6. O-O e4 7. Nd4 Nc6 8. Nc2
Bxc3 9. bxc3 d5 10. cxd5 Qxd5
{ The nuances of this variation are covered in Chapter 14 - this is mainline. Black captures the pawn with the queen so that it can be rerouted to h5 and ...Bh3 to follow. }
11. Ne3 Qh5 12. h4
{ This, however, is not the main move! White avoids the light-squared bishop trade but at a high cost. White ventures into a position with no active plan.   12.f3  The modern continuation.  12...exf3  Now White will capture with the e-pawn and try to make good use of the center and the two bishops. Black is very solid. }
12... Be6 13. d4 Na5
{ An excellent positional move - Black takes good care of the weakened light squares. }
14. Qc2 Nc4 15. Re1 Qg6
{ The queen on h5 has nothing to do anymore. Black prepares to simplify the position by trading the most active White's piece. }
16. Rb1 Nxe3 17. Bxe3 Ng4
{ A great square for the knight - Black is threatening to take on e3 and thus win the g3 pawn in the process. To make matters worse, the white bishop can't leave - then the ...e3 move will come through with a disastrous effect. }
18. Qd2
{ What else? The pawn on e4 can't be taken -   18.Bxe4  meets  18...f5  and ...Nxe3 to follow   While after  18.Qxe4  Black will collect a lot of things with  18...Bf5 }
18... b6 19. Bf4 c6
{ Black slowly improves the position and prepares to occupy the c4 and d5 squares as outposts. Thanks to 12. h4, White has no counterplay as playing f3 here would weaken the king's position even more. }
20. Rb2 Bc4 21. Qc2 h6
{ In dominating positions prophylactic moves feel particularly good. } 22. Bh3
Nf6 { Black reroutes the knight to d5. } 23. Be5
{ White would love to trade off that knight. } 23... Nd5 24. Bg2 f5
{ Black's light pieces on c4 and d5 are there to stay - the white bishop on e5 does not do much and Black will just ignore it. }
25. e3 b5 26. a4 Nb6
{ Using the sudden opportunity, Black forces a favorable pawn trade. Now Black will have a strong passed pawn at the queenside and can also apply some pressure against the c3 pawn. }
27. axb5 cxb5 28. Bc7
{ White must have realized that the c3 pawn is now a weakness thus reroutes the bishop on a much more passive square. }
28... Nd5 29. Ba5 a6 { Another prophylactic move - Black need not hurry. } 30.
Ra1 Qf7
{ Black is ready to launch a kingside attack and either go for the f-pawn push or just checkmate on the h-file. White in silent horror watches the unfolding attack. }
31. Qd2 g5 32. hxg5 hxg5 33. Qd1 Qh7
{ Some very direct threats start to appear. } 34. f3
{ This drops a pawn but White's position is already on a freefall. } 34... Nxe3
35. Qc1 f4
{ Black secures the knight's outpost on e3 and the rest of the moves don't require an annotation. }
36. Bh1 Re6 37. Rh2 Rh6 38. Rxh6 Qxh6 39. Qd2 fxg3 40. Bc7 Qh3 41. d5 exf3 42.
Bxf3 Rf8 43. Rxa6 Qf1# { A wonderful dominating display by Black! } *

