1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. e4 Bxc3 6. dxc3 d6 7. Qe2 Nbd7 8.
Nf3 Nc5 9. Nh4 a6 10. f3 Be6 11. Be3 Qd7 12. O-O b5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Qf2 Qc6
{ The details of the opening phase are covered in Chapter 12. Typically for this pawn structure, Black is seeking a counterplay at the queenside. }
15. Nf5 Rfe8
{ A fine multi-purpose move, first avoiding the obvious fork on e7 and keeping all options open but I think it was better to clarify the situation immediately.   15...Bxf5  Black could have taken the knight while White hasn't played g4 yet.  16.exf5  Rfe8  17.a3  White protects the a2 pawn so that the queenside rook can join the game. Now  17.g4  looks like a positional mistake as Black can proceed with  17...Nd3  and position it on f4, even if means sacrificing a pawn. White's light-squared bishop looks terrible.   @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/2p2ppp/2qp1n2/1pn1pP2/8/P1P1BPP1/1P3QBP/R4RK1 b - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17...Nb3  18.Rad1  d5  Black appears to be calling the shots in the center but should be a little careful with White's incoming h4-g4-g5 threats. Keep a cool head! }
16. g4 Bxf5 17. gxf5
{ There's the difference - White can now recapture with the g-pawn and organize an attack at the g-file. }
17... Ra4 18. Rfd1
{ White is concerned about the ...Nd3-f4 idea and just in case positions the rook at the d-file if White will fire up the center with ...d5. This is also very defensive and gives Black some freedom.   18.Kh1  This continuation was more to the point - if the g-file is open, it makes sense to use it.  18...Ncd7  Black prepares to push ...d5.  19.Rg1  d5  20.Bf1!  Suddenly White's bishops become very active - the e4 pawn can be sacrificed.  20...dxe4  21.Qg2  g6  Now after  22.fxe4  and the pawn sacrifice there's an unclear position on the board but White at least has a clear plan - either go for the black king or activate the bishops. }
18... Ncd7
{ Black might want to play ...d5 in one go but the knight on c5 is under attack. }
19. b3 Ra3 20. Bf1
{ White improves the light-squared bishop, indirectly defends the c3 pawn and has prepared a surprise against the ...d5 push. }
20... Rea8
{ Black has found a weakness to pressure.   20...d5  This was an interesting way to spice things up.  21.exd5  Nxd5  22.Bxb5!  This must have been White's idea.  22...Qxb5  23.c4  Qa6  Black has lost a pawn but has the initiative. }
21. c4
{ A strange positional mistake - White must have thought that things are quite bad already.   21.Bc1  This drops the pawn on b3 but it still was a better choice.  21...Rxb3  If the black rook will retreat with   21...R3a5  ,  White can consider sacrificing a pawn with  22.a4  bxa4  23.b4  ,  blocking the queenside with the following Ra3, and slowly activating the bishops.  If   @@StartFEN@@r5k1/2pn1ppp/2qp1n2/1p2pP2/4P3/1rP2P2/P4Q1P/R1BR1BK1 w - - 0 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Bb2!  Rba3  23.Bxa3  Rxa3  Black has obvious compensation for the exchange @@StartBracket@@I would pick Black without hesitation@@EndBracket@@ but probably not more than that. }
21... b4
{ Black fixes an outpost on c5. White's light-squared bishop is terrible and the pawn on a2 won't hold for long. }
22. Qd2 Nc5 23. Rab1
{ White suddenly collapses while it was still possible to hold. Mistakes come in pairs.   23.Qxb4  This was a much better try.  23...Nxb3!  24.Rab1  Nd4  25.Bxd4  exd4  White's position is positionally ugly but after  26.Qb5  he might try to hold it. }
23... Rxa2 24. Qxb4 Ncxe4
{ White must have seen this shot but misevaluated the consequences - Black starts a deadly attack. }
25. fxe4 Qxe4 26. Qe1 Ng4
{ Now after   27.Bg5  Black can just collect the pawn on f5 and after the incoming . ..e4 and ...Qc5+ threats the dangerous attack continues. White suddenly resigned but the position objectively is already lost. }
