1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. g3 Bb4 4. e4 Bxc3 5. bxc3 O-O 6. f3
{ The reasoning for this extravagant move is explained in Chapter 11 - forget what you already knew and welcome to the new world! }
6... Re8 7. Nh3 c6 8. Nf2 d5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Bg2 b6
{ I would have preferred to play something more classical with   10...Nc6  11.O-O  Be6  and Black has easy targets at the queenside. The light-squared bishop on e6 also appears to be more ready against any White's lash-outs in the center. }
11. O-O Ba6
{ A slight inaccuracy - the bishop has not much to do on a6 -   11...Bb7  was more logical. }
12. Re1 Nc6 13. d3
{ Magnus misses his first opportunity.   13.exd5!  Odd but this strange-looking move actually is a great move. The point is that if Black will recapture with  13...Nxd5  then after  14.f4  Black can't take trade the pawns as after the rook trade on e8 the black knight on d5 hangs.   @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/p4ppp/bpn2n2/3Pp3/8/2P2PP1/P2P1NBP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qxd5  14.f4  e4  Here White has two interesting continuations - either temporarily sacrifice a pawn with  15.d3  and win it back a few moves later with two strong bishops, or continue with an extravagant-looking  @@StartFEN@@r3r1k1/p4ppp/bpn2n2/3q4/4pP2/2P3P1/P2P1NBP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.g4  to go after the e4 pawn with the g5 threat. I like the latter idea more. }
13... h6
{ Too slow, missing White's next reply. Black had to continue with   13...dxe4  14.fxe4  Rc8  and an excellent position after the opening. White's queenside pawns make an easy target. }
14. exd5 { This time White doesn't miss it. } 14... Nxd5 15. f4
{ An unnecessary inaccuracy - both opponents @@StartBracket@@probably characteristically for a rapid game@@EndBracket@@ must have assumed that the pawn on c3 can't be taken, but it can!   15.c4!  This was the right order of the moves, dodging the unnecessary complications and eventually leading to what happened in the game.  15...Nf6  16.f4  Rc8  We transpose to the game. }
15... Rc8
{ Levon avoids the complications when he shouldn't have.   15...Nxc3!  Black gives up two light pieces for a rook and a pawn.  16.Qc2  Rc8  17.Qxc3  Nd4  18.Qb2  Nc2  Black wins back an exchange with about a material equality. The position is pretty open for the rooks so Black should have nothing to complain about. }
16. c4 { Here   16.Bb2  was much stronger, improving the c4 threat. } 16... Nf6
17. fxe5 Rxe5 18. Rxe5 Nxe5 19. Bb2
{ The opening phase is over and White stands better - he has two powerful bishops. }
19... Ned7 20. Qa4 Nc5 21. Qa3 Bb7
{ Activity above all - it's important to get rid of the bishops, even if it will cost a pawn. Black will have some counterplay against White's d3 pawn. }
22. Bxb7 Nxb7 23. Qxa7 Nc5 24. Qa3
{ Black is threatening with ...Ra8 so the queen's retreat looks logical. However, it's a little passive, probably losing any chances to win the game. Here   24.Rb1  was a lot more energetic, threatening with Bxf6 and the pawn on b6 is under attack. }
24... h5
{ Down a pawn, Black seeks counterplay against the weakened white king or the weak d3 pawn. }
25. Re1 Ng4 26. Nxg4 hxg4 27. Qc3 f6
{ The complications have ended - Black has managed to eliminate the power of the strong White's bishops and has a sufficient counterplay. White's weak king doesn't allow him to hope for success. }
28. Re3 Qd7 29. Qd4
{ With the queens on the board, White can't move forward the pawns without looking behind his shoulder at the weakened king. Thus White trades the queens but this costs him a pawn. }
29... Rd8 30. Qxd7 Rxd7 31. d4 Na4 32. Ba1 Rc7
{ Black wins back the pawn. The rest of the game doesn't require an annotation - both sides played a very high level chess without mistakes and the game ended with a logical draw. }
33. c5 bxc5 34. Ra3 cxd4 35. Bxd4 Rc4 36. Be3 Nc3 37. Kf1 Kh7 38. Ke1 Kg6 39.
Ra7 Rb4 40. Kd2 Nd5 41. Bc5 Rb2+ 42. Kd3 Rxh2 43. Rd7 Rh5 44. Bf8 Re5 45. Kd4
Nb6 46. Rxg7+ Kf5 47. Ra7 Re4+ 48. Kd3 Nc4 49. Bh6 Ne5+ 50. Kc3 Rc4+ 51. Kb3
Rd4 52. Rc7 Ke4 53. a4 Rd3+ 54. Rc3 Rxc3+ 55. Kxc3 Kd5 56. Bg7 Nf3 57. Bxf6 Nh2
{ Know your endgames - White has the wrong corner! } 58. Kb4 Kc6 59. Bd4 Kb7
60. Bg1 Nf3 { Levon is having a little fun -   60...Nf1  obviously draws. } 61.
Bf2 Nh2 62. Kb5 Ka8 63. a5 Kb7 64. a6+ Ka8 65. Kc6 Nf1 66. Kd5 Nxg3 67. Bxg3
