1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3 e4 4. Nd4 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. Nc2 Nf6 7. Nc3 Qe5 8. Bg2
Na6 9. O-O Be7 10. Ne3 h5
{ The opening nuances of this variation are explained in Chapter 9. Black can castle short as well but this continuation is more fun. }
11. d4 exd3 12. exd3 Qd4
{ It's important to stop White from playing d4-d5, thus opening the light-squared bishop on g2. }
13. Nc2 Qg4
{ Black should be ready to stop d4-d5 in time with either ...Be6 or ...Nac7. }
14. Bf4 Qxd1 15. Raxd1 Bg4 16. Rd2 O-O-O
{ At some point, Black wants to play ...Be6 and after ...Nac7 block everything at the d5 square. However, after the immediate   16...Be6  with the white pawn still on d3 White has access to the annoying  17.Nd4 }
17. d4 Nc7 18. Ne3 Be6 19. d5
{ White forces a lot of trades - if Black will be allowed to play ...Ncd5 and trade off many light pieces, White will be left with a weak d-pawn.   19.Be5  Anish could have played a little more tricky with 19. Be5 to improve the d5 threat.  19...h4  Black includes in the game the kingside rook. Most likely White will be back to the d5 push, initiating a lot of trades. }
19... Ncxd5
{ It's important to take with the pieces first - White's idea is to penetrate Black's position with Rc1-c7. }
20. Ncxd5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Rxd5 Rxd5 23. Bxd5 cxd5 24. Rc1+ Kd7 25. Rc7+
Ke6 26. Rxb7
{ This was White's idea - the rook is active, the black pawn on a7 is weak. }
26... Rc8
{ The final accuracy - Black sacrifices the a-pawn to activate his rook. For strong players this is an easy move. }
27. Rxa7 Rc2 28. Be3 Bf6 29. Ra4 Bxb2
{ Black has won back the pawn and has a minor edge due to the more advanced passed pawn. }
30. Kg2 d4 { Grischuk decides not to pursue it and fixes a draw. } 31. Bxd4
Bxd4 32. Rxd4 Rxa2
{ Normally the game should end already here with a quick 'elbow knock' instead of the traditional handshake, but the Sofia rules in the Candidates tournament state - no draw until the 40th move. }
33. Re4+ Kf6 34. Rf4+ Ke6 35. Re4+ Kf6 36. Rf4+ Ke6 37. Re4+ Kf6 38. Rf4+ Ke6
{ I'm pretty sure that the threefold repetition was already there. } 39. h4 g6
40. Re4+ Kf6
{ Now there's no need to call an arbiter to prove the repetition on another board. }
