1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Qb3 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nc6 7. Nxd5 Nxd5 8.
Qxd5 Bd6 { This variation is covered in detail in Chapter 7. } 9. Nf3 Nb4 10.
Qe4 f5 11. Qb1 Qc7 12. O-O Nc2 13. d3 Nxa1 14. Qxa1 O-O 15. b3 Re8
{ Black in advance defends the e5 pawn.   15...Bd7  I find this continuation being more human, although there's nothing wrong with what was played in the game. The idea is to quickly transfer the light-squared bishop on c6. }
16. Bb2 Qe7
{ If White won't do anything immediately, Black is about to bring out his light-squared bishop. As soon as the white knight will leave its outpost on f3, Black is ready to trade off the dark-squared bishops to simplify the position. More trades favor Black. }
17. Nd2 Ba3 18. Bc3 Bb4 { White can't dodge the trade. } 19. Bxb4 Qxb4 20. Nc4
Qe7 { The black queen is back to defend the e5 pawn. } 21. Rd1 Rb8
{ Black wants to trade off the light-squared bishops as well but not on c6 as after ...bxc6 the white knight on c4 will remain forever. }
22. d4
{ White seeks counter-chances in the center but this opens the position. }
22... exd4 23. Qxd4 Be6
{ Positional gains over material! Black gives up the second pawn for the exchange but simplifies the position and activates his pieces. Not an easy decision over the board. }
24. Qxa7 b5 { Black forces the queen trade. } 25. Qxe7 Rxe7 26. Ne3 Rd7
{ Black consistently is trading off the most active White's pieces. } 27. Rxd7
Bxd7 28. Kf1
{ Start of the wrong plan - White activates his king but it was important to switch on the schematic thinking.   28.Bd5+  A strong player should recognize that as soon as Black will activate his rook, only he will be playing for the win. Thus it's best to trade the only thing which keeps Black's chances alive - the b-pawn at the queenside, even if it costs a pawn.  28...Kf8  29.a4!  bxa4  I don't think Black can really consider to push forward the b-pawn and get to the b3 pawn.  30.bxa4  Rb1+  31.Kg2  Ra1  Black will win the pawn on a4 but four pawns vs three at the kingside down an exchange should be a draw. Since the bishops are still on the board, the draw might not be so trivial. Ideally White is looking for ways to trade all three Black's pawns. }
28... Rc8 29. Ke1 Rc1+ 30. Kd2 Ra1 31. Bd5+
{ Perhaps   31.a4  was still working but the white king now is slightly misplaced and the kingside pawns - vulnerable. }
31... Kf8 32. b4
{ White saves the pawn on a2 but keeps the black pawn on b5 alive. } 32... Ke7
{ The only mistake that Black made in the game - he had to include   32...g5  to take away from White the option to push h4. }
33. Nc2 { It was necessary to stop Black from playing ...g5 with   33.h4 }
33... Rf1 34. Ke3 g5
{ Now White will start to experience some problems with the h-pawn and then there's the ...f4+ threat. Black's only chance to win the game is to create a passed pawn and at the right moment - trade the bishops. }
35. f4 g4 { White's position is deteriorating rapidly. } 36. Kd2 h5 37. Ke3 Kd6
38. Bg2 Rg1 39. Bb7 Rb1 40. Kd2 Bc6
{ Now Black is happy to trade the bishops - eventually the weakness of White's h-pawn should decide the game in favor for Black. }
41. Bc8
{ 41.Bxc6  This was a decent try but White should lose anyway.  41...Kxc6  42.Nd4+  Kd5  Black centralizes the king.  43.Nxb5  Rxb4  44.a4  h4!  With an idea to push the h-pawn to h3 and then either winning the h-pawn or capturing with the rook on g3 should make the black h-pawn unstoppable. }
41... Be4 42. Nd4 Rxb4
{ Black gives up the f-pawn and creates what's he's been striving for - a passed pawn, unexpectedly at the queenside. }
43. Nxf5+ Bxf5 44. Bxf5
{ White seeks some counter-chances at the kingside but it's too late. } 44...
Rb2+ 45. Ke1 Rxa2 46. Bg6 h4
{ A nice way to save a pawn - the doubled h-pawns play no role. } 47. gxh4 Ke7
48. Bf5 b4 49. Bxg4
{ 49.Kd1  This also loses.  49...b3  50.Kc1  Rxe2  51.Bxg4  Rxh2  The black king will come to help the passed pawn. }
49... b3
{ Black's b-pawn is about to promote and it doesn't even need the assistance of the black monarch. }
50. Bf5 Ra1+ 51. Kf2 Kf6 52. Bd3 b2
{ Black will promote the b-pawn and then collect all four white pawns. } *

