1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. d4 e4 4. d5 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Qe7 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. Nh3
cxd5 9. cxd5 d6 10. O-O Bf5 11. f3 Na6 12. g4 Bg6 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6
{ This comes with an idea to sacrifice a pawn on c3 to shut out black's bishop. The problem with the plan is - it's temporary.   14.Bh4  It was interesting to keep the pin alive.  14...exf3  15.exf3  Bxc3  16.bxc3  Qe3+  Black is doing here just fine but needs to be a little accurate in the next few moves, which is analyzed in Chapter 6. Immediately grabbing the pawn on c3 can result in shutting out the light-squared bishop from the game forever with f4-f5. }
14... Qxf6 15. f4
{ 15.fxe4?  This would be a big strategic mistake - White wins a pawn but the cost is too great. Black has much more active pieces.  15...Qe5  It's entirely possible that Black can win back the pawn on e4 but it shouldn't be a priority. }
15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 Qxc3 17. f5 Bh7
{ This sequence is forced - now it's not clear how White should proceed. The black bishop eventually will find its way out of the cage. }
18. Rc1 Qe3+ 19. Kh1 Nc5
{ The black knight is heading to f6 to secure the king. } 20. Qe1 Rac8
{ Black would like to trade as many pieces as he can to ease a potential attack. }
21. Qh4
{ Feeling that the game has taken the wrong turn, White decides to launch a desparate attack at the kingside.   21.Nf4  The attack could have been prepared a little.  21...Nd7  22.Rb1  White wants to keep on the board as many pieces as he can.  22...b6  23.Qh4  Nf6  I can imagine that here playing 23...f6 to stop the attack could be a difficult decision for Black as it weakens many light-squares around the black king.  24.g5  hxg5  25.Qxg5  Qd4  26.Rg1  e3!  Despite Black's resourcefulness, White's game is easier as he's attacking. }
21... Nd7 22. Rb1 Nf6
{ Black is overly defensive and misses a chance to punish White.   22...Qxe2!  White's attack is scary but the best defense is a counter-attack!  23.g5  Rc2  24.Nf4  hxg5  25.Qxg5  Qd2  26.Rxb7  Nf6  Black has kept a cool head and defended against the attack, still enjoying the extra pawn. }
23. g5 hxg5 24. Nxg5 Rc2 { Now the counter-attack comes a little late. } 25.
Nxh7
{ This can't be good - the knight on g5 is so much stronger piece than the black bishop on h7. Trades like this can be done only if something specific follows after it thus I can only assume that White miscalculated something.   25.Rg1  This was much more energetic, also preparing a rook lift with Rb3-h3 if given an opportunity.  25...Bxf5  26.Bh3  Bg6   26...Bxh3  It doesn't look like a practical decision from Black's perspective to open the g-file.  27.Nxh3  27...Nh7  28.Rxg7+!  Nice trick!  28...Kxg7  29.Rg1+  Qxg1+  This is necessary, because alternative  29...Kh8  30.Ng5  ends with greater losses. Although Black has two rooks for the queen, he can't hope for success as the king is exposed for a perpetual check.  27.Nxf7!!  This shot from afar can be easily missed, especially in calculations.  ...Kxf7  Or   @@StartFEN@@5rk1/pp3Np1/3p1nb1/3P4/4p2Q/4q2B/P1r1P2P/1R4RK b - - 0 27@@EndFEN@@  27...Rxf7  28.Rxg6  and  Be6  to follow.  @@StartFEN@@5r2/pp3kp1/3p1nb1/3P4/4p2Q/4q2B/P1r1P2P/1R4RK w - - 0 28@@EndFEN@@  28.Rxb7+  Ke8  Black loses after  28...Kg8  due to  29.Be6  check - switch on your tactical skills!   @@StartFEN@@4kr2/pR4p1/3p1nb1/3P4/4p2Q/4q2B/P1r1P2P/6RK w - - 1 29@@EndFEN@@  29.Rb8+  Ke7  30.Rb7+  Ke8  Both sides should agree a draw. }
25... Nxh7 26. f6 g6 27. Rb3
{ White's idea is to transfer the rook to h3 but Black has enough resources here to fend-off the attack. }
27... Qxe2
{ 27...Rc3  was more precise, with an idea to meet  28.Rxb7  with  28...Rc1  ,  effectively winning the f6 pawn.  Even   27...Qg5  looks good. }
28. Rg3 Qd2 29. Bxe4
{ This is a very tempting move to sacrifice something on g6 but effectively it's a blunder, ignoring Black's idea - it was necessary to take the pawn with   29.Qxe4  but after  29...Kh8  the black king feels pretty safe. }
29... Rc1
{ Black trades off the white rook on f1 to get to the f6 pawn and not only White's attack collapses, but the entire position. }
30. Rxc1 Qxc1+ 31. Rg1 Qc4
{ The attack is over - White is left with a lot of weaknesses and an exposed king. Once Black will collect the pawn on f6, it's a matter of time until he'll convert it to a win. }
32. Re1 Re8 33. Bxg6 { Last trick. } 33... Qxh4 34. Rxe8+ Nf8
{ There's no mate. } *

